{"id": "MECHANICS/101", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "The problem discusses a stick figure model. The stick figure's head is a uniform sphere with a radius of $r$ and a mass of $m$, while the rest of the body consists of uniform rods with negligible thickness and a mass per unit length of $\\lambda$. All parts are connected by hinges. Specifically, the torso and both arms have a length of $l$, while the legs have a length of $1.2l$. $\\theta$ represents the angle between the arms and the torso, and $\\varphi$ represents the angle between the legs and the extended torso line (not an obtuse angle). The stick figure is composed of a head, a torso, two arms, and two legs. Initially, the stick figure is in a state where $\\theta=\\textstyle{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}$ and $\\varphi={\\frac{\\pi}{4}}$. The head has a mass of $m=0.6\\lambda l$, with the result expressed in terms of $\\lambda$. \n\nThe stick figure is a simulation of a real biological body, so if necessary, the connections between the torso and the arms/legs, in addition to providing interaction forces, can also exert a couple (i.e., a torque), even if there is no interaction force between them. This net torque is independent of the choice of reference point. In the following discussion, this will be referred to simply as a \"couple.\"\n\nDuring a certain free-fall motion, the stick figure, overwhelmed with panic, forgets to bring its legs together and swings its arms and torso with an amplitude of $\\theta_{0}$ (small angle) and an angular frequency of $\\omega$. As a result, its legs passively oscillate near $\\varphi={\\frac{\\pi}{4}}$. Find the amplitude of resonance for the legs (seek the steady-state solution starting from the initial position). Assume that the stick figure can actively generate a couple for the arms but not for the legs.", "solutions": "\n\n(1) The forces are already marked on the diagram. List Newton's laws and rotational equations, assuming the displacement of the driven object is $\\pmb{x}$, positive upwards.\n\nVertical direction of the leg\n\n$$\nT_{3}=1.2\\lambda l\\times\\left(0.6l\\times{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left({\\mathrm{cos}}\\varphi\\right)-{\\ddot{x}}\\right)\n$$\n\nVertical direction of the arm\n\n$$\nT_{1}=\\lambda l\\left(\\ddot{x}-0.5l\\times\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\right)\\right)\n$$\n\nVertical direction of the torso (head)\n\n$$\n2\\left(T_{3}-T_{1}\\right)=(m+\\lambda l)\\ddot{x}\n$$\n\nHorizontal direction of the leg\n\n$$\n-T_{4}=1.2\\lambda l\\times0.6l\\times\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}\\left(\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi\\right)\n$$\n\nHorizontal direction of the arm\n\n$$\n-T_{2}=\\lambda l\\times0.5l\\times{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left(\\mathrm{sin}\\theta\\right)\n$$\n\nAngular momentum theorem for the leg\n\n$$\nT_{3}\\times0.6l\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi+T_{4}\\times0.6l\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi-M=\\frac{1}{12}\\times1.2\\lambda l\\times(1.2l)^{2}\\ddot{\\varphi}\n$$\n\nAngular momentum theorem for the arm\n\n$$\nT_{2}\\times0.5l\\mathrm{cos}\\theta-T_{1}\\times0.5l\\mathrm{sin}\\theta=\\frac{1}{12}\\times\\lambda l\\times l^{2}\\ddot{\\theta}\n$$\n\nSubstitute in, we have\n\n$$\n\\frac{1}{12}l^{2}{\\ddot{\\theta}}+0.25l^{2}{\\mathrm{cos}}\\theta\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}{\\mathrm{sin}}\\theta+\\frac{T_{1}}{\\lambda}\\times0.5{\\mathrm{sin}}\\theta=0\n$$\n\nBy combining the previous equations, we get\n\n$$\nT_{1}=\\left({\\frac{6}{25}}{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi\\right)-{\\frac{1}{3}}{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\right)\\right)\\lambda l^{2}\n$$\n\nBy substituting, we obtain the final expression\n\n$$\n\\left(\\frac{1}{3}-\\frac{1}{12}\\mathrm{sin}^{2}\\theta\\right)\\ddot{\\theta}-\\frac{1}{12}\\mathrm{sin}\\theta\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\dot{\\theta}^{2}=\\frac{3}{25}\\omega^{2}\\mathrm{sin}\\theta\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi\n$$\n\nTherefore,\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{c}{{A(\\theta)=\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{3}-\\frac{1}{12}\\mathrm{sin}^{2}\\theta}}\\ {{{}}}\\ {{B(\\theta)=-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{12}\\mathrm{sin}\\theta\\mathrm{cos}\\theta}}\\ {{{}}}\\ {{C(\\theta)=\\displaystyle\\frac{3}{25}\\omega^{2}\\mathrm{sin}\\theta}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nSubstituting back into the previous angular momentum theorem, we have\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{r l r}{M=\\frac{9}{25}\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi\\lambda l^{3}\\left(\\frac{12}{25}\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi\\omega^{2}+\\frac{1}{3}\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\dot{\\theta}^{2}+\\frac{1}{3}\\mathrm{sin}\\theta\\ddot{\\theta}\\right)}&{{}=\\frac{12}{25}\\frac{\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi}{\\mathrm{sin}\\theta}\\ddot{\\theta}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nThere still remain the first five equations from the first question and the modified angular momentum theorem\n\n$$\nT_{3}\\times0.6l\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi+T_{4}\\times0.6l\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi=\\frac{1}{12}\\times1.2\\lambda l\\times(1.2l)^{2}\\ddot{\\varphi}\n$$\n\nSubstitute and combine, we get\n\n$$\nT_{3}\\times0.6l\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi-1.2\\times0.6\\lambda l^{2}{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}(\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi)\\times0.6l\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi={\\frac{1}{12}}\\times1.2\\lambda l\\times(1.2l)^{2}\\ddot{\\varphi}\n$$\n\n$$\nT_{3}=\\lambda l\\left(\\ddot{x}-0.5l\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\right)\\right)+\\frac{1}{2}(m+\\lambda l)\\ddot{x}\n$$\n\nCombining, we get\n\n$$\nT_{3}=-\\frac{1}{5}\\lambda l^{2}\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\right)+\\frac{54}{125}\\lambda l^{2}\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi\\right)\n$$\n\nSubstituting the above equation, we obtain the final expression\n\n$$\n\\left({\\frac{54}{125}}{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi\\right)-{\\frac{1}{5}}{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left(\\mathrm{cos}\\theta\\right)\\right)\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi-{\\frac{18}{25}}{\\frac{d^{2}}{d t^{2}}}\\left(\\mathrm{sin}\\varphi\\right)\\mathrm{cos}\\varphi={\\frac{6}{25}}{\\ddot{\\varphi}}\n$$\n\nLet = +, then retain terms up to the first order of and θ, we get\n\n$$\n\\ddot{\\delta}=-\\frac{25\\sqrt{2}}{204}\\omega^{2}\\theta_{0}\\mathrm{cos}\\omega t\n$$\n\nThat is\n\n$$\nA={\\frac{25{\\sqrt{2}}}{204}}\\theta_{0}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nA = \\frac{25 \\sqrt{2}}{204} \\theta_0\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem analyzes the motion of a stick figure model during free-fall. The figure consists of a head, a torso, two arms, and two legs, connected by hinges. The arms are actively driven to oscillate, which induces a passive oscillation in the legs. The objective is to find the amplitude of the steady-state oscillation of the legs.\n\nThe physical parameters of the stick figure are as follows:\n*   **Head**: A uniform sphere of mass `m` and radius `r`. The mass is given by the relation `m = 0.6\\lambda l`. We assume its radius `r` is negligible and its center of mass is located at the upper hinge, `H_A`.\n*   **Torso**: A uniform rod of length `l` and mass per unit length `\\lambda`. Its mass is `m_T = \\lambda l`.\n*   **Arms**: Two identical uniform rods, each of length `l` and mass `m_A = \\lambda l`.\n*   **Legs**: Two identical uniform rods, each of length `1.2l` and mass `m_L = 1.2\\lambda l`.\n\nThe configuration and motion are described by two angles:\n*   `\\theta(t)`: The angle between each arm and the vertical torso. The arms are actively driven to oscillate around the horizontal position (`\\theta = \\pi/2`) with a small amplitude `\\theta_0` and angular frequency `\\omega`. The motion is described by `\\theta(t) = \\pi/2 + \\theta_0 \\cos(\\omega t)`.\n*   `\\varphi(t)`: The angle between each leg and the downward vertical extension of the torso. The legs oscillate passively around the equilibrium angle `\\varphi_{eq} = \\pi/4`. We describe this small oscillation by `\\delta(t)`, such that `\\varphi(t) = \\pi/4 + \\delta(t)`.\n\nThe entire stick figure is in free-fall in a uniform gravitational field with acceleration `g`. Due to the symmetric construction and motion of the arms and legs, the torso only undergoes vertical translation. We establish an inertial frame of reference with the y-axis pointing upwards. Let `y(t)` be the vertical coordinate of the lower hinge `H_L` (connecting torso and legs). The problem states that the couple exerted by the torso on the legs is zero, as the legs are passive. We aim to find the amplitude `A` of the steady-state leg oscillation `\\delta(t)`.\n\n### Step 1: System Masses and Center of Mass Kinematics\nFirst, we define the masses of the components and the vertical positions of their centers of mass (CM) in terms of the generalized coordinates `y(t)`, `\\varphi(t)`, and `\\theta(t)`.\n\nThe masses of the components are:\n*   Torso: `m_T = \\lambda l`\n*   Each Arm: `m_A = \\lambda l`\n*   Each Leg: `m_L = 1.2\\lambda l`\n*   Head: `m_{head} = m = 0.6\\lambda l`\n\nThe total mass of the system is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nM_{\\text{tot}} = m_{head} + m_T + 2m_A + 2m_L = (0.6 + 1 + 2 \\cdot 1 + 2 \\cdot 1.2)\\lambda l = 6\\lambda l\n\\label{eq:total_mass} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nLet the lower hinge `H_L` be at `\\mathbf{r}_{H_L} = (0, y)`. The upper hinge `H_A` is at `\\mathbf{r}_{H_A} = (0, y+l)`. The vertical positions of the CMs of the various parts are:\n*   **Legs**: The CM of each leg is at a distance of `1.2l/2 = 0.6l` from `H_L`. Its vertical position is `y_{CM,L} = y - 0.6l \\cos\\varphi`.\n*   **Arms**: The CM of each arm is at a distance of `l/2 = 0.5l` from `H_A`. Its vertical position is `y_{CM,A} = y_{H_A} - 0.5l \\cos\\theta = y + l - 0.5l \\cos\\theta`.\n*   **Torso-Head Assembly**: The CM of the torso is at `y+l/2`. The CM of the head is at `y+l`. The combined mass is `M_{TH} = m_T + m_{head} = 1.6\\lambda l`. The vertical position of their combined CM is:\n    `y_{CM,TH} = \\frac{m_T(y+l/2) + m_{head}(y+l)}{M_{TH}} = y + \\frac{\\lambda l(l/2) + 0.6\\lambda l(l)}{1.6\\lambda l} = y + \\frac{1.1}{1.6}l`.\n\nThe vertical position of the total center of mass of the stick figure, `Y_{CM,tot}`, is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nM_{\\text{tot}} Y_{CM,tot} &= M_{TH} y_{CM,TH} + 2m_A y_{CM,A} + 2m_L y_{CM,L} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (1.6\\lambda l)(y + \\frac{1.1}{1.6}l) + 2(\\lambda l)(y + l - 0.5l \\cos\\theta) + 2(1.2\\lambda l)(y - 0.6l \\cos\\varphi) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (1.6+2+2.4)\\lambda l y + (1.1 + 2 - 1\\cos\\theta - 1.44\\cos\\varphi)\\lambda l^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= M_{\\text{tot}} y + (3.1 - \\cos\\theta - 1.44\\cos\\varphi)\\lambda l^2\n\\label{eq:Y_cm} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Global Equation of Motion and Hinge Acceleration\nSince the entire stick figure is in free-fall, its total center of mass must accelerate downwards with acceleration `g`. We use this fact to find the acceleration of the hinge `H_L`.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe motion of the center of mass of a system is governed by the net external force. For a system in a uniform gravitational field, this is:\n\\[\\boxed{M_{\\text{tot}} \\ddot{\\mathbf{r}}_{CM,tot} = \\mathbf{F}_{\\text{ext, net}} = M_{\\text{tot}}\\mathbf{g}}\\]\nIn our coordinate system (`y` upwards), this gives for the vertical component:\n\\[\\boxed{\\ddot{Y}_{CM,tot} = -g}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nWe differentiate Eq. \\eqref{eq:Y_cm} twice with respect to time:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nM_{\\text{tot}} \\ddot{Y}_{CM,tot} = M_{\\text{tot}} \\ddot{y} + \\lambda l^2 \\frac{d^2}{dt^2}(3.1 - \\cos\\theta - 1.44\\cos\\varphi) \\nonumber \\\\\nM_{\\text{tot}} \\ddot{Y}_{CM,tot} = M_{\\text{tot}} \\ddot{y} - \\lambda l^2 (\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 1.44\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)})\n\\label{eq:Y_cm_ddot} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting `\\ddot{Y}_{CM,tot} = -g` and `M_{\\text{tot}} = 6\\lambda l` into Eq. \\eqref{eq:Y_cm_ddot}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nM_{\\text{tot}}(-g) &= M_{\\text{tot}} \\ddot{y} - \\lambda l^2 (\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 1.44\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)}) \\nonumber \\\\\nM_{\\text{tot}}(\\ddot{y} + g) &= \\lambda l^2 (\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 1.44\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)}) \\nonumber \\\\\n6\\lambda l (\\ddot{y} + g) &= \\lambda l^2 (\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 1.44\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)}) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\ddot{y} + g &= \\frac{l}{6} (\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 1.44\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)}) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\ddot{y} + g &= l \\left(\\frac{1}{6}\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 0.24\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)}\\right)\n\\label{eq:y_accel} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Rotational Dynamics of a Leg\nWe derive the equation of motion for the leg's angle `\\varphi` by considering torques about the accelerating hinge `H_L`. Since the leg is passive, the net couple from the hinge is zero.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe equation for the net external torque `\\boldsymbol{\\tau}_A^{\\text{ext}}` about a possibly accelerating point `A` is:\n\\[\\boxed{\\boldsymbol{\\tau}_A^{\\text{ext}} = I_A \\boldsymbol{\\alpha} + m (\\mathbf{r}_{CM} - \\mathbf{r}_A) \\times \\mathbf{a}_A}\\]\nwhere `I_A` is the moment of inertia about `A`, `\\boldsymbol{\\alpha}` is the angular acceleration, `m` is the mass of the body, `\\mathbf{r}_{CM}` and `\\mathbf{r}_A` are position vectors, and `\\mathbf{a}_A` is the acceleration of point `A`.\n\n**Derivation**:\nWe apply this to a leg, with point `A` being the hinge `H_L`.\n*   **External Torque**: The only external force creating a torque about `H_L` is gravity. The position of the leg's CM relative to `H_L` is `\\mathbf{r}_{H_L,CM} = (0.6l\\sin\\varphi, -0.6l\\cos\\varphi, 0)`. The gravitational force is `m_L\\mathbf{g} = (0, -m_L g, 0)`.\n    \\[\\begin{align} \\boldsymbol{\\tau}_{H_L}^{\\text{ext}} = \\mathbf{r}_{H_L,CM} \\times m_L\\mathbf{g} = (-0.6l m_L g \\sin\\varphi)\\hat{\\mathbf{k}} = (-0.72\\lambda l^2 g \\sin\\varphi)\\hat{\\mathbf{k}} \\end{align}\\]\n*   **Inertial Term**: The moment of inertia of the leg (a rod of length `1.2l`) about its end `H_L` is `I_{H_L} = \\frac{1}{3}m_L(1.2l)^2 = \\frac{1}{3}(1.2\\lambda l)(1.44l^2) = 0.576 \\lambda l^3`. The angular acceleration is `\\boldsymbol{\\alpha} = \\ddot{\\varphi}\\hat{\\mathbf{k}}`.\n    \\[\\begin{align} I_{H_L} \\boldsymbol{\\alpha} = (0.576 \\lambda l^3 \\ddot{\\varphi})\\hat{\\mathbf{k}} \\end{align}\\]\n*   **Fictitious Torque Term**: This term arises from the acceleration of the reference point `H_L`, which is `\\mathbf{a}_{H_L} = \\ddot{y}\\hat{\\mathbf{j}}`.\n    \\[\\begin{align} m_L(\\mathbf{r}_{CM,L} - \\mathbf{r}_{H_L}) \\times \\mathbf{a}_{H_L} &= m_L \\mathbf{r}_{H_L,CM} \\times \\mathbf{a}_{H_L} = (1.2\\lambda l) (0.6l\\sin\\varphi \\ddot{y})\\hat{\\mathbf{k}} = (0.72\\lambda l^2 \\ddot{y} \\sin\\varphi)\\hat{\\mathbf{k}} \\end{align}\\]\nEquating the z-components of the torque equation:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n-0.72\\lambda l^2 g \\sin\\varphi &= 0.576 \\lambda l^3 \\ddot{\\varphi} + 0.72\\lambda l^2 \\ddot{y} \\sin\\varphi \\nonumber \\\\\n0 &= 0.576 l \\ddot{\\varphi} + 0.72 \\sin\\varphi (\\ddot{y} + g) \\label{eq:leg_eom_prelim}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSubstituting the expression for `\\ddot{y}+g` from Eq. \\eqref{eq:y_accel}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n0 &= 0.576 l \\ddot{\\varphi} + 0.72 \\sin\\varphi \\left[ l \\left(\\frac{1}{6}\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} + 0.24\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n0 &= 0.576 \\ddot{\\varphi} + 0.72 \\sin\\varphi \\left(0.24 \\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)} + \\frac{1}{6} \\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)}\\right) \\label{eq:leg_eom_full}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 4: Linearization of the Equation of Motion\nWe linearize the equation of motion \\eqref{eq:leg_eom_full} for small oscillations `\\delta(t)` around `\\varphi = \\pi/4` and for the small driving amplitude `\\theta_0`. Let `\\varepsilon(t) = \\theta_0 \\cos(\\omega t)`.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nFor small `\\delta` and `\\varepsilon`:\n\\[\\boxed{\\varphi(t) = \\pi/4 + \\delta(t), \\quad \\theta(t) = \\pi/2 + \\varepsilon(t)}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\sin(\\pi/4+\\delta) \\approx \\sin(\\pi/4) = 1/\\sqrt{2}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\cos(\\pi/4+\\delta) \\approx \\cos(\\pi/4) - \\delta\\sin(\\pi/4) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}(1-\\delta)}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\cos(\\pi/2+\\varepsilon) = -\\sin\\varepsilon \\approx -\\varepsilon}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nWe find the second time derivatives of the cosine terms, keeping only first-order terms in `\\delta` and `\\varepsilon`.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\ddot{\\varphi} &= \\ddot{\\delta} \\\\\n\\ddot{(\\cos\\varphi)} &= \\frac{d^2}{dt^2}\\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}(1-\\delta)\\right) = -\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\ddot{\\delta} \\\\\n\\ddot{(\\cos\\theta)} &= \\frac{d^2}{dt^2}(-\\varepsilon) = -\\ddot{\\varepsilon} = -(-\\omega^2 \\varepsilon) = \\omega^2\\varepsilon = \\omega^2\\theta_0\\cos(\\omega t)\n\\end{align}\\]\nWe substitute these into the equation of motion \\eqref{eq:leg_eom_full}. The term in parentheses is of first order, so we can use the zeroth-order approximation for the `\\sin\\varphi` factor multiplying it.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n0 &\\approx 0.576 \\ddot{\\delta} + 0.72 \\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\right) \\left[ 0.24 \\left(-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\ddot{\\delta}\\right) + \\frac{1}{6} \\omega^2\\theta_0\\cos(\\omega t) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n0 &\\approx 0.576 \\ddot{\\delta} - \\frac{0.72 \\times 0.24}{2} \\ddot{\\delta} + \\frac{0.72}{6\\sqrt{2}} \\omega^2\\theta_0\\cos(\\omega t) \\nonumber \\\\\n0 &\\approx (0.576 - 0.0864) \\ddot{\\delta} + \\frac{0.12}{\\sqrt{2}} \\omega^2\\theta_0\\cos(\\omega t) \\nonumber \\\\\n0.4896 \\ddot{\\delta} &\\approx - \\frac{0.12}{\\sqrt{2}} \\omega^2\\theta_0\\cos(\\omega t) \\label{eq:linear_eom_final}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 5: Steady-State Solution and Amplitude\nThe linearized equation describes a simple forced oscillation. We seek the steady-state solution, which oscillates at the driving frequency `\\omega`.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nWe assume a steady-state solution of the form:\n\\[\\boxed{\\delta(t) = A \\cos(\\omega t)}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe second time derivative of the assumed solution is `\\ddot{\\delta}(t) = -A \\omega^2 \\cos(\\omega t)`. Substituting this into the linearized equation \\eqref{eq:linear_eom_final}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n0.4896(-A \\omega^2 \\cos(\\omega t)) &= - \\frac{0.12}{\\sqrt{2}} \\omega^2\\theta_0\\cos(\\omega t) \\nonumber \\\\\n0.4896 A &= \\frac{0.12}{\\sqrt{2}}\\theta_0 \\nonumber \\\\\nA &= \\frac{0.12}{0.4896\\sqrt{2}} \\theta_0\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo simplify the fraction, we can use `0.12/0.4896 = 1200/4896 = 25/102`.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nA &= \\frac{25}{102\\sqrt{2}} \\theta_0 \\nonumber \\\\\nA &= \\frac{25\\sqrt{2}}{102 \\cdot 2} \\theta_0 = \\frac{25\\sqrt{2}}{204} \\theta_0\n\\label{eq:final_amplitude} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe amplitude `A` is dimensionless and proportional to the driving amplitude `\\theta_0`. Notably, the result is independent of the mass parameter `\\lambda`, length `l`, gravitational acceleration `g`, and the driving frequency `\\omega`. This occurs because the driving term, which originates from the arm's motion, and the leg's inertial response are both proportional to `\\omega^2`, causing the frequency to cancel out. The term \"resonance\" in the problem statement refers to this steady-state driven response, not a frequency-dependent peak in amplitude.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe amplitude of resonance for the legs is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{A = \\frac{25\\sqrt{2}}{204}\\theta_{0}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/630", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "In this problem, we study a simple \\\"gas-fueled rocket.\\\" The main body of the rocket is a plastic bottle, which can take off after adding a certain amount of fuel gas and igniting it. It is known that the external atmospheric pressure is $P_{0}$, and the initial pressure of the gas in the bottle is $P_{0}$, with a temperature of $T_{0}$. The proportion of the molar amount of fuel gas is $\\alpha$, and the rest is air. Alcohol is chosen as the fuel, with the reaction equation in air as: $C_{2}H_{5}OH(g) + 3O_{2}(g) \\rightarrow 3H_{2}O(g) + 2CO_{2}(g)$. Assume that the air contains only $N_{2}$ and $O_{2}$, all gases are considered as ideal gases, and none of the vibrational degrees of freedom are excited. It is known that under conditions of pressure $P_{0}$ and temperature $T_{0}$, the reaction heat is $-\\lambda$ (enthalpy change for $1\\mathrm{mol}$ of ethanol reacting under isothermal and isobaric conditions). Ignore heat loss, assume the reaction is complete, and that there is air remaining, with the gas volume remaining constant throughout. Find the pressure $P_{1}$ of the gas inside the bottle after the gas has completely reacted upon ignition.", "solutions": "Let the initial moles of air be $n_{0}$, and the moles of alcohol be  $$ n_{x}=\\frac{\\alpha n_{0}}{1-\\alpha} $$ The ideal gas equation of state is $$ {P_{0}V_{0}=\\left(n_{x}+n_{0}\\right)R T_{0}} \\\\ {P_{0}V_{1}=\\left(2n_{x}+n_{0}\\right)R T_{0}} $$ According to the definition of enthalpy change, we have $$ \\Delta{{H}_{0}}=\\Delta{{U}_{0}}+\\Delta\\left(P V\\right)=\\Delta{{U}_{0}}+{{P}_{0}}\\left({{V}_{1}}-{{V}_{0}}\\right) $$ It follows that $$ \\Delta U_{0}=-n_{x}\\lambda-n_{x}RT_{0} $$ Since heat loss is neglected and no gas escapes from the bottle, the reaction is adiabatic and the volume does not change, giving us $$ \\Delta U=\\Delta U_{\\mathrm{0}}+\\Big[\\frac{5}{2}R\\cdot\\big(n_{0}-n_{x}\\big)+3R\\cdot 3n_{x}\\Big]\\big(T_{1}-T_{0}\\big)=0 $$ We obtain $$ T_{1}=T_{0}+\\frac{2n_{x}\\left(\\lambda+R T_{0}\\right)}{R\\left(5n_{0}+13n_{x}\\right)}=T_{0}+\\frac{2\\alpha\\left(\\lambda+R T_{0}\\right)}{R\\left(5+8\\alpha\\right)} $$ The ideal gas equation of state is $$ {P_{0}V_{0}=\\left(n_{x}+n_{0}\\right)R T_{0}} \\\\ {P_{1}V_{0}=\\left(2n_{x}+n_{0}\\right)R T_{1}} $$ We find $$ P_{1}=P_{0}\\frac{(1+\\alpha)(5+10\\alpha+2\\alpha(\\frac{\\lambda}{R T_{0}}))}{5+8\\alpha} $$", "final_answers": "$$P_0 \\frac{(1+\\alpha)(5+10\\alpha+2\\alpha \\frac{\\lambda}{R T_0})}{5+8\\alpha}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the final pressure, $P_1$, inside a sealed bottle of constant volume after a fuel-air mixture is ignited and combusts completely.\n\n**System and State Variables:**\n*   The system is the gas mixture inside a bottle of constant volume $V$.\n*   **Initial State (State 0):**\n    *   Pressure: $P_0$\n    *   Temperature: $T_0$\n    *   The gas is a mixture of fuel (gaseous ethanol, $C_2H_5OH$) and air. Let $n_x$ be the initial moles of fuel and $n_0$ be the initial moles of air.\n    *   The total initial moles of gas are $n_{tot,0} = n_x + n_0$.\n    *   The molar proportion of fuel is given as $\\alpha = \\frac{n_x}{n_{tot,0}}$.\n*   **Final State (State 1):**\n    *   Pressure: $P_1$ (to be determined)\n    *   Temperature: $T_1$\n    *   The gas is a mixture of reaction products ($H_2O, CO_2$) and unreacted components of air ($N_2$ and excess $O_2$).\n    *   Total final moles of gas: $n_{tot,1}$.\n\n**Process and Key Information:**\n*   **Chemical Reaction:** The combustion of ethanol in air is given by the equation:\n    $C_{2}H_{5}OH(g) + 3O_{2}(g) \\rightarrow 3H_{2}O(g) + 2CO_{2}(g)$.\n*   **Thermodynamic Process:** The reaction occurs in a sealed, insulated bottle. This means the process is adiabatic (no heat exchange with the surroundings, $Q=0$) and isochoric (constant volume, so work done is $W=0$).\n*   **Reaction Enthalpy:** The molar enthalpy of reaction at constant pressure $P_0$ and temperature $T_0$ is given as $\\Delta_r H_m = -\\lambda$. For the reaction of $n_x$ moles of fuel, the total enthalpy change under these conditions is $\\Delta H = -n_x \\lambda$.\n\n**Assumptions:**\n1.  All gases (reactants and products) behave as ideal gases.\n2.  Air consists only of diatomic nitrogen ($N_2$) and oxygen ($O_2$).\n3.  The reaction is complete, with ethanol being the limiting reactant, meaning there is excess air (specifically, excess oxygen).\n4.  Vibrational degrees of freedom of all gas molecules are not excited. This determines their molar heat capacities at constant volume ($C_{V,m}$):\n    *   Diatomic gases ($N_2, O_2$) and linear polyatomic gases ($CO_2$): Have 3 translational and 2 rotational degrees of freedom, so $f=5$. $C_{V,m} = \\frac{5}{2}R$.\n    *   Non-linear polyatomic gases ($C_2H_5OH, H_2O$): Have 3 translational and 3 rotational degrees of freedom, so $f=6$. $C_{V,m} = 3R$.\n\n### Step 1: Relate Initial Moles of Fuel and Air\nFirst, we use the definition of the molar proportion $\\alpha$ to establish a relationship between the initial moles of fuel, $n_x$, and air, $n_0$.\n\\[\n\\boxed{ \\alpha = \\frac{n_x}{n_{tot,0}} = \\frac{n_x}{n_x + n_0} }\n\\]\nFrom this definition, we can express $n_x$ in terms of $n_0$ and $\\alpha$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\alpha (n_x + n_0) &= n_x \\nonumber \\\\\n\\alpha n_0 &= n_x - \\alpha n_x \\nonumber \\\\\n\\alpha n_0 &= n_x(1-\\alpha) \\nonumber \\\\\nn_x &= \\frac{\\alpha}{1-\\alpha} n_0\n\\label{eq:nx_vs_n0} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis relationship will be used to express results in terms of the given proportion $\\alpha$.\n\n### Step 2: Determine the Final Molar Composition\nNext, we determine the total number of moles of gas, $n_{tot,1}$, after the combustion is complete, using the stoichiometry of the reaction.\n\\[\n\\boxed{ C_{2}H_{5}OH(g) + 3O_{2}(g) \\rightarrow 3H_{2}O(g) + 2CO_{2}(g) }\n\\]\nThe reaction consumes $n_x$ moles of ethanol and $3n_x$ moles of oxygen, while producing $3n_x$ moles of water vapor and $2n_x$ moles of carbon dioxide. The change in the total number of moles of gas, $\\Delta n_{tot}$, is the moles of gaseous products formed minus the moles of gaseous reactants consumed.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta n_{tot} &= n_{products} - n_{reactants\\_consumed} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (n_{H_2O} + n_{CO_2}) - (n_{C_2H_5OH} + n_{O_2}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (3n_x + 2n_x) - (n_x + 3n_x) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 5n_x - 4n_x = n_x\n\\label{eq:delta_n_tot} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe total number of moles of gas increases by $n_x$. The final total moles, $n_{tot,1}$, can be found by adding this change to the initial total moles, $n_{tot,0}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn_{tot,1} &= n_{tot,0} + \\Delta n_{tot} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (n_0 + n_x) + n_x \\nonumber \\\\\n&= n_0 + 2n_x\n\\label{eq:n_final} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Apply the First Law of Thermodynamics\nThe process occurs in a sealed, insulated container, meaning it is adiabatic ($Q=0$) and isochoric ($W=0$). The First Law of Thermodynamics dictates the change in the system's internal energy, $\\Delta U$.\n\\[\n\\boxed{ \\Delta U = Q - W }\n\\]\nFor this specific process, the total change in internal energy is zero.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta U = 0 - 0 = 0\n\\label{eq:deltaU_zero} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo analyze this, we can conceptualize the overall process as a two-step thermodynamic path from the initial state (reactants at $T_0$) to the final state (products at $T_1$):\n1.  An isothermal, isochoric chemical reaction at the initial temperature $T_0$. The change in internal energy for this step is $\\Delta U_{reaction, T_0}$.\n2.  An isochoric heating of the product mixture from $T_0$ to the final temperature $T_1$. The change in internal energy for this step is $\\Delta U_{heating}$.\nThe total change in internal energy is the sum of these two conceptual steps:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta U = \\Delta U_{reaction, T_0} + \\Delta U_{heating} = 0\n\\label{eq:U_decomp} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the Chemical Internal Energy Change ($\\Delta U_{reaction, T_0}$)\nWe calculate the internal energy change for the isothermal reaction at $T_0$ using the given reaction enthalpy.\n\\[\n\\boxed{ \\Delta H = \\Delta U + \\Delta(PV) }\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{ PV = nRT \\quad (\\text{Ideal Gas Law}) }\n\\]\nThe given reaction enthalpy for $n_x$ moles of fuel is $\\Delta H = -n_x \\lambda$. For a reaction of ideal gases at a constant temperature $T_0$, the change in the $PV$ term is $\\Delta(PV) = \\Delta(n_{gas}RT_0) = (\\Delta n_{gas})RT_0$, where $\\Delta n_{gas}$ is the change in the number of moles of gas for the stoichiometric reaction. From Eq. \\eqref{eq:delta_n_tot}, this change is $n_x$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta U_{reaction, T_0} &= \\Delta H - \\Delta(PV) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -n_x \\lambda - (\\Delta n_{gas})RT_0 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -n_x \\lambda - n_x RT_0 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -n_x (\\lambda + RT_0)\n\\label{eq:deltaU_chem} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Calculate the Thermal Internal Energy Change ($\\Delta U_{heating}$)\nThis step involves calculating the total heat capacity of the final gas mixture, $C_{V,final}$, and then expressing $\\Delta U_{heating}$.\n\\[\n\\boxed{ \\Delta U = C_V (T_f - T_i) \\quad (\\text{for isochoric heating with constant } C_V) }\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{ C_{V,m} = \\frac{f}{2}R \\quad (\\text{Molar heat capacity of an ideal gas}) }\n\\]\nThe final mixture consists of $(n_0 - 3n_x)$ moles of unreacted air ($N_2, O_2$), $2n_x$ moles of $CO_2$, and $3n_x$ moles of $H_2O$. The molar heat capacities are: $C_{V,m,air} = \\frac{5}{2}R$, $C_{V,m,CO_2} = \\frac{5}{2}R$, and $C_{V,m,H_2O} = 3R$. The total heat capacity is the sum of the heat capacities of all components.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nC_{V,final} &= (n_0 - 3n_x)C_{V,m,air} + (2n_x)C_{V,m,CO_2} + (3n_x)C_{V,m,H_2O} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (n_0 - 3n_x)\\frac{5}{2}R + (2n_x)\\frac{5}{2}R + (3n_x)(3R) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left( (n_0 - 3n_x) + 2n_x \\right)\\frac{5}{2}R + 9n_x R \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (n_0 - n_x)\\frac{5}{2}R + 9n_x R \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{5}{2}n_0 R - \\frac{5}{2}n_x R + \\frac{18}{2}n_x R \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{5}{2}n_0 R + \\frac{13}{2}n_x R = \\frac{R}{2}(5n_0 + 13n_x)\n\\label{eq:Cv_final} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe change in internal energy from heating the final gas mixture from $T_0$ to $T_1$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta U_{heating} = C_{V,final}(T_1 - T_0) = \\frac{R}{2}(5n_0 + 13n_x)(T_1 - T_0)\n\\label{eq:deltaU_heat} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 6: Determine the Final Temperature $T_1$\nUsing the energy balance equation from Step 3, $\\Delta U_{reaction, T_0} + \\Delta U_{heating} = 0$, we can now solve for the final temperature $T_1$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n-n_x (\\lambda + RT_0) + \\frac{R}{2}(5n_0 + 13n_x)(T_1 - T_0) &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{R}{2}(5n_0 + 13n_x)(T_1 - T_0) &= n_x (\\lambda + RT_0) \\nonumber \\\\\nT_1 - T_0 &= \\frac{2n_x(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R(5n_0 + 13n_x)}\n\\label{eq:T1_moles} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstitute $n_x = \\frac{\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}n_0$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:nx_vs_n0} to express the temperature change in terms of $\\alpha$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nT_1 - T_0 &= \\frac{2\\left(\\frac{\\alpha n_0}{1-\\alpha}\\right)(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R\\left(5n_0 + 13\\frac{\\alpha n_0}{1-\\alpha}\\right)} = \\frac{2\\frac{\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R\\left(5 + \\frac{13\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}\\right)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{2\\frac{\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R\\left(\\frac{5(1-\\alpha) + 13\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}\\right)} = \\frac{2\\alpha(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R(5 - 5\\alpha + 13\\alpha)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{2\\alpha(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R(5 + 8\\alpha)}\n\\label{eq:T1_delta} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSo, the final temperature is $T_1 = T_0 + \\frac{2\\alpha(\\lambda + RT_0)}{R(5 + 8\\alpha)}$.\n\n### Step 7: Calculate the Final Pressure $P_1$\nFinally, we use the ideal gas law for the initial and final states to find the final pressure $P_1$.\n\\[\n\\boxed{ PV = nRT }\n\\]\nApplying the law to the initial and final states (at constant volume $V$):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nP_0 V &= n_{tot,0} R T_0 \\label{eq:ideal_initial} \\tag{11} \\\\\nP_1 V &= n_{tot,1} R T_1 \\label{eq:ideal_final} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nDividing Eq. \\eqref{eq:ideal_final} by Eq. \\eqref{eq:ideal_initial} gives the pressure ratio:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{P_1}{P_0} = \\frac{n_{tot,1}}{n_{tot,0}} \\frac{T_1}{T_0}\n\\label{eq:P_ratio} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe express the mole ratio and temperature ratio in terms of $\\alpha$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{n_{tot,1}}{n_{tot,0}} = \\frac{n_0 + 2n_x}{n_0 + n_x} = \\frac{n_0 + 2\\frac{\\alpha n_0}{1-\\alpha}}{n_0 + \\frac{\\alpha n_0}{1-\\alpha}} = \\frac{1 + \\frac{2\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}}{1 + \\frac{\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}} = \\frac{\\frac{1-\\alpha+2\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}}{\\frac{1-\\alpha+\\alpha}{1-\\alpha}} = \\frac{1+\\alpha}{1} = 1+\\alpha\n\\label{eq:mole_ratio_alpha} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{T_1}{T_0} &= 1 + \\frac{T_1 - T_0}{T_0} = 1 + \\frac{2\\alpha(\\lambda + RT_0)}{RT_0(5 + 8\\alpha)} = \\frac{RT_0(5+8\\alpha) + 2\\alpha\\lambda + 2\\alpha RT_0}{RT_0(5+8\\alpha)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{5RT_0 + 8\\alpha RT_0 + 2\\alpha\\lambda + 2\\alpha RT_0}{RT_0(5+8\\alpha)} = \\frac{5RT_0 + 10\\alpha RT_0 + 2\\alpha\\lambda}{RT_0(5+8\\alpha)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{5 + 10\\alpha + 2\\alpha\\frac{\\lambda}{RT_0}}{5+8\\alpha}\n\\label{eq:temp_ratio_alpha} \\tag{15}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting these ratios back into Eq. \\eqref{eq:P_ratio}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nP_1 = P_0 \\left( \\frac{n_{tot,1}}{n_{tot,0}} \\right) \\left( \\frac{T_1}{T_0} \\right) = P_0 (1+\\alpha) \\left( \\frac{5 + 10\\alpha + 2\\alpha\\frac{\\lambda}{RT_0}}{5+8\\alpha} \\right)\n\\label{eq:P1_final} \\tag{16}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe pressure $P_1$ of the gas inside the bottle after the gas has completely reacted is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{P_{1}=P_{0}\\frac{(1+\\alpha)\\left(5+10\\alpha+2\\alpha\\frac{\\lambda}{R T_{0}}\\right)}{5+8\\alpha}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/134", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "A fox is escaping along a straight line $AB$ at a constant speed $v_{1}$. A hound is pursuing it at a constant speed $v_{2}$, always aimed at the fox. At a certain moment, the fox is at $F$ and the hound is at $D$. $FD \\bot AB$ and $FD = L$. Find the magnitude of the hound's acceleration at this moment.", "solutions": "To solve $\\textcircled{1}$, the hunting dog performs uniform circular motion. Thus, the tangential acceleration is zero, while the normal acceleration changes. Assume that during a very short period of time $\\mathrm{d}t$ after the given moment, the curvature radius of the trajectory of the hunting dog is $\\rho,$ then the normal acceleration is  \n\n$$\na_{n}={\\frac{v_{2}^{2}}{\\rho}}.\n$$\n\nDuring the time interval $\\mathrm{d}t$, the fox and the hunting dog respectively reach positions $F^{\\prime}$ and $D^{\\prime}$ (see Figure 1.7(a) in the problem). The angle turned by the hunting dog's direction of motion is  \n\n$$\n\\alpha={\\frac{\\widehat{D D^{\\prime}}}{\\rho}}={\\frac{v_{2}\\mathrm{d}t}{\\rho}}.\n$$\n\nHowever, the distance traveled by the fox is  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{r}{\\overline{{F F^{\\prime}}}=v_{1}\\mathrm{d}t\\approx L\\tan\\alpha\\approx\\alpha L,}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nwhich implies  \n\n$$\n\\alpha={\\frac{v_{1}\\mathrm{d}t}{L}}.\n$$\n\nThus,  \n\n$$\n\\frac{\\upsilon_{2}\\mathrm{d}t}{\\rho}=\\frac{\\upsilon_{1}\\mathrm{d}t}{L},\n$$\n\nand from this, the curvature radius can be obtained as  \n\n$$\n\\rho=\\frac{L v_{2}}{v_{1}}.\n$$\n\nTherefore, the magnitude of the acceleration is  \n\n$$\na_{n}={\\frac{v_{2}^{2}}{\\rho}}={\\frac{v_{1}v_{2}}{L}}.\n$$\n\nIt should be noted that the acceleration obtained this way corresponds only to the specific moment mentioned in the problem, not to the acceleration at any arbitrary position during the chasing process.", "final_answers": "$$\\frac{v_1 v_2}{L}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem describes a pursuit scenario. A fox moves along a straight line, which we denote as $AB$, at a constant speed $v_{1}$. A hound pursues the fox, moving at a constant speed $v_{2}$. The defining characteristic of the pursuit is that the hound's velocity vector is always directed towards the fox's instantaneous position.\n\nWe are asked to find the magnitude of the hound's acceleration at a specific moment. At this instant, the physical configuration is as follows:\n1.  The fox is at a point $F$.\n2.  The hound is at a point $D$.\n3.  The line segment connecting the hound and the fox, $FD$, is perpendicular to the fox's path $AB$.\n4.  The length of the segment $FD$ is given as $L$.\n\nTo analyze the motion, we establish a 2D Cartesian coordinate system. For simplicity, let the fox's path $AB$ be the horizontal line $y=L$. At the moment of interest, which we set as time $t=0$, the segment $FD$ is perpendicular to the line $y=L$. This means $F$ and $D$ must have the same x-coordinate. We can set this x-coordinate to zero without loss of generality due to translational symmetry.\n*   The position of the fox at $t=0$ is $\\vec{r}_F(0) = (0, L)$.\n*   The position of the hound at $t=0$ is $\\vec{r}_D(0) = (0, 0)$.\nThis setup satisfies the given conditions: the path $AB$ is the line $y=L$, the segment $FD$ lies along the y-axis (and is thus perpendicular to $AB$), and the distance is $FD = \\sqrt{(0-0)^2 + (L-0)^2} = L$.\n\nThe velocities of the fox and the hound at this instant ($t=0$) are:\n*   **Fox's velocity, $\\vec{v}_F$**: The fox moves along the line $y=L$ at a constant speed $v_1$. We can assume it moves in the positive x-direction, so its velocity vector is $\\vec{v}_F = (v_1, 0)$.\n*   **Hound's velocity, $\\vec{v}_H$**: The hound, located at the origin $(0,0)$, is always aimed at the fox, which is at $(0, L)$. Therefore, the hound's velocity vector points in the positive y-direction. Since its speed is $v_2$, its velocity vector is $\\vec{v}_H = (0, v_2)$.\n\nThe objective is to find the magnitude of the hound's acceleration, $|\\vec{a}_H|$, at this specific moment ($t=0$).\n\n### Step 1: Analyze the Nature of the Hound's Acceleration\nThe acceleration vector of any particle, $\\vec{a}$, can be decomposed into two orthogonal components: a tangential component $\\vec{a}_t$, which is parallel to the velocity and describes the change in speed, and a normal component $\\vec{a}_n$, which is perpendicular to the velocity and describes the change in direction.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{a} = \\vec{a}_t + \\vec{a}_n}\\]\nThe magnitude of the tangential component of acceleration, $a_t$, is defined as the rate of change of the particle's speed, $v=|\\vec{v}|$.\n\\[\\boxed{a_t = \\frac{d|\\vec{v}|}{dt}}\\]\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\text{In this problem, the hound moves at a constant speed } v_2. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Therefore, the magnitude of its velocity is constant: } |\\vec{v}_H| = v_2 = \\text{constant}. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{This means the tangential component of its acceleration is zero.} \\nonumber \\\\\na_t = \\frac{dv_2}{dt} = 0 \\label{eq:at_zero} \\tag{1} \\\\\n\\text{Consequently, the hound's acceleration is purely normal to its path of motion.} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{a}_H = \\vec{a}_n \\label{eq:a_is_an} \\tag{2} \\\\\n\\text{The magnitude of the total acceleration is thus equal to the magnitude of the normal acceleration, } a_H = a_n. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{This normal acceleration arises solely from the change in the direction of the hound's velocity vector.} \\nonumber\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 2: Relate Acceleration to the Rotation of the Velocity Vector\nSince the hound's acceleration is due to the change in its velocity's direction, we can express it in terms of the rotation of its velocity vector. The hound's velocity vector is always aligned with the unit vector pointing from the hound to the fox.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{v} = v \\vec{u}}\\]\nHere, $\\vec{u}$ is the unit vector in the direction of the velocity $\\vec{v}$, and $v$ is the speed. The time derivative of a unit vector $\\vec{u}$ that is rotating with an angular velocity $\\vec{\\omega}$ is given by the kinematic relation:\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{d\\vec{u}}{dt} = \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{u}}\\]\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\text{The hound's acceleration } \\vec{a}_H \\text{ is the time derivative of its velocity } \\vec{v}_H. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{a}_H &= \\frac{d\\vec{v}_H}{dt} = \\frac{d}{dt}(v_2 \\vec{u}) \\label{eq:a_def} \\tag{3} \\\\\n\\text{where } \\vec{u} \\text{ is the unit vector pointing from the hound to the fox. Since } v_2 \\text{ is constant:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{a}_H &= v_2 \\frac{d\\vec{u}}{dt} \\label{eq:a_deriv} \\tag{4} \\\\\n\\text{Substituting the expression for the derivative of a rotating unit vector:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{a}_H &= v_2 (\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{u}) \\label{eq:a_omega} \\tag{5} \\\\\n\\text{Here, } \\vec{\\omega} \\text{ is the angular velocity of the line of sight from the hound to the fox.} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The magnitude of the acceleration is } a_H = |\\vec{a}_H| = v_2 |\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{u}|. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The angular velocity vector } \\vec{\\omega} \\text{ is perpendicular to the plane of motion (the xy-plane), while } \\vec{u} \\text{ lies within this plane.} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Thus, } \\vec{\\omega} \\text{ is perpendicular to } \\vec{u}, \\text{ and the magnitude of their cross product is:} \\nonumber \\\\\n|\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{u}| &= |\\vec{\\omega}||\\vec{u}|\\sin(90^\\circ) = \\omega \\cdot 1 \\cdot 1 = \\omega. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Therefore, the magnitude of the hound's acceleration is:} \\nonumber \\\\\na_H &= v_2 \\omega \\label{eq:a_mag} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 3: Calculate the Angular Velocity of the Line of Sight\nThe angular velocity of the line connecting the hound and the fox is determined by their relative motion.\nThe relative velocity of the fox with respect to the hound is given by the principle of Galilean relativity:\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{v}_{\\text{rel}} = \\vec{v}_F - \\vec{v}_H}\\]\nThe magnitude of the angular velocity, $\\omega$, of the separation vector $\\vec{r}$ is the magnitude of the component of the relative velocity perpendicular to $\\vec{r}$, denoted $v_{\\text{rel,}\\perp}$, divided by the distance $r=|\\vec{r}|$.\n\\[\\boxed{\\omega = \\frac{v_{\\text{rel,}\\perp}}{r}}\\]\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\text{At the instant } t=0, \\text{ using the coordinate system from the problem explanation:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The separation vector from the hound to the fox is } \\vec{r} = \\vec{r}_F - \\vec{r}_H = (0, L) - (0, 0) = (0, L). \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The distance between them is } r = |\\vec{r}| = L. \\label{eq:dist} \\tag{7} \\\\\n\\text{The velocities are } \\vec{v}_F = (v_1, 0) \\text{ and } \\vec{v}_H = (0, v_2). \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The relative velocity is:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{v}_{\\text{rel}} &= \\vec{v}_F - \\vec{v}_H = (v_1, 0) - (0, v_2) = (v_1, -v_2). \\label{eq:v_rel} \\tag{8} \\\\\n\\text{The line of sight vector } \\vec{r} \\text{ is along the y-axis. The component of the relative velocity } \\vec{v}_{\\text{rel}} \\text{ that is perpendicular to the line of sight is its x-component.} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The magnitude of this perpendicular component is } v_{\\text{rel,}\\perp} = |(\\vec{v}_{\\text{rel}})_x| = |v_1| = v_1 \\text{ (since } v_1 \\text{ is a speed).} \\label{eq:v_perp} \\tag{9} \\\\\n\\text{Now, we can calculate the magnitude of the angular velocity } \\omega: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\omega &= \\frac{v_{\\text{rel,}\\perp}}{r} = \\frac{v_1}{L}. \\label{eq:omega_val} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the Hound's Acceleration\nWe now combine the results from the previous steps to find the magnitude of the hound's acceleration. This step is a direct substitution of the angular velocity found in Step 3 into the expression for acceleration derived in Step 2. No new principles are required.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\text{From Eq. \\eqref{eq:a_mag} in Step 2, the magnitude of the hound's acceleration is related to the angular velocity by:} \\nonumber \\\\\na_H &= v_2 \\omega \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{From Eq. \\eqref{eq:omega_val} in Step 3, we found the angular velocity of the line of sight at the given instant:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\omega &= \\frac{v_1}{L} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Substituting the expression for } \\omega \\text{ into the equation for } a_H: \\nonumber \\\\\na_H &= v_2 \\left(\\frac{v_1}{L}\\right) = \\frac{v_1 v_2}{L}. \\label{eq:final_a} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis is the magnitude of the hound's acceleration at the specific moment when the line connecting the hound and the fox is perpendicular to the fox's path.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe magnitude of the hound's acceleration at the given moment is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{a_H = \\frac{v_1 v_2}{L}}\n\\end{align}\\]"}
