{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/423", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "One mole of a substance is a simple $p,v,T$ system. The coefficient of body expansion in any case is\n\n$$\n\\alpha=3/T\n$$\n\nThe adiabatic equation in any case is\n\n$$\np v^{2}=C\n$$\n\nThe isobaric heat capacity of the system in the arbitrary case is exactly: $$  \n\n$$\nc_{p}\\propto \\frac{p v}{T}\n$$  \n\nThe scale factor is a state-independent dimensionless constant, and\nTo determine the entropy change $$S_D-S_A$$ of the D state compared to the A state, two states $$A,D$$ on the $$p-v$$ graph are chosen, knowing that $$p_{A}$$,$$v_{A}$$,$$T_{A}$$,$$p_{D}$$,$$v_{D}$$ and that the entropy change of the D state compared to the A state is $$S_D-S_A$$.\n", "solutions": "First of all\n\n$$\n\\alpha={\\frac{1}{v}}\\left({\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T}}\\right)_{p}={\\frac{3}{T}}\n$$\n\nThe equation of state can be obtained\n\n$$\nv=T^{3}h(p)\n$$\n\nWrite the full differential of entropy and utilize Maxwell's relation:\n\n$$\nd S={\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}}d T+{\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial p}}d p\n$$\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial p}=-\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T}=-3T^{2}h\n$$\n\nDuring adiabatic process $$ d S=0$$\n\n$$\n{\\frac{d p}{d T}}={\\frac{\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}}{3T^{2}h}}}\n$$\n\nAnd the adiabatic process is\n\n$$\np v^{2}=T^{6}p h^{2}=C\n$$\n\nThe logarithmic differentiation yields\n\n$$\n\\frac{d p}{d T}=-\\frac{6p h}{T(h+2p h^{\\prime})}\n$$\n\nComparing the two derivatives gives\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}=-\\frac{18T p h^{2}}{h+2p h^{\\prime}}}\n$$\n\nDue to the properties of full differentiation, the two partial derivatives continue to conform to\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial p}\\left(-\\frac{18T p h^{2}}{h+2p h^{\\prime}}\\right)=\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T}\\left(-3T^{2}h\\right)\n$$\n\nGet the differential equation\n\n$$\n\\left({\\frac{3p h^{2}}{h+2p h^{\\prime}}\\right)^{\\prime}=h\n$$\n\nSimplify it like this\n\n$$\nh=\\left[\\frac{3p h^{3}}{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}}\\right]^{\\prime}=-3p h^{3}\\cdot\\frac{(p h^{2})^{\\prime\\prime}}{[(p h^{2})^{\\prime}]^{2}}}+3\\ frac{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}h+p h^{2}h^{\\prime}}{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}}\n$$\n\n$$\n{\\frac{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}}{p h^{3}}}\\cdot h={\\frac{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}}{p h^{2}}}=-3{\\frac{(p h^{2})^{\\prime\\prime}}{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}}}}}+ 3{\\frac{(p h^{2})^{\\prime}}{p h^{2}}}}+3{\\frac{h^{\\prime}}{h}}}\n$$\n\nThe solution is\n\n$$\n(p h^{2})^{-2/3}(p h^{2})^{\\prime}=C h=C p^{-1/2}\\cdot(p h^{2})^{1/2}\n$$\n\nFurther moving the right-hand side $(p h^{2})^{1/2}$ to the left-hand side and integrating over $P$ finally yields\n\n$$\nh={\\frac{1}{C_{1}{\\sqrt{p}}({\\sqrt{p}}+C_{2})^{3}}}}\n$$\n\nAnd thus the final equation of state\n\n$$\nT=C_{1}^{\\frac{1}{3}}p^{\\frac{1}{6}}(\\sqrt{p}+C_{2})v^{\\frac{1}{3}}\n$$\n\nSince the isobaric heat capacity is  \n\n$$\nc_{P}=T{\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}}\n$$  \n\nSubstituting gives the result  \n\n$$\nc_{P}=-{\\frac{18T^{2}p h^{2}}{h+2p h^{\\prime}}}}={\\frac{6T^{2}}{C_{1}({\\sqrt{p}}+C_{2})^{2}}}}\n$$  \n\nSince  \n\n$$\nv=T^{3}\\cdot{\\frac{1}{C_{1}{\\sqrt{p}}({\\sqrt{p}}+C_{2})^{3}}}}\n$$  \n\nSubstituting the relationship yields  \n\n$$\n\\lambda=6\\left(1+{\\frac{C_{2}}{\\sqrt{p}}}\\right)\n$$  \n\nIn order to make $\\lambda$ constant we deduce that  \n\n$$\nC_{2}=0\n$$  \n\nThus, only  \n\nSince $$ C_{2}=0 $$ the previous conclusion reduces to  \n\n$$\n\\lambda=6\n$$  \n\nSince $C_{2}=0$ simplifies to\n\n$$\nh={\\frac{1}{C_{1}p^{2}}}\n$$\n\n$$\nT^{3}=C_{1}p^{2}v\n$$\n\n$$\nd S=\\frac{6T}{C_{1}p}d T-\\frac{3T^{2}}{C_{1}p^{2}}d p\n$$\n\nThus, according to the equation of state\n\n$$\nC_{1}=\\frac{3T_A^{3}}{p_{A}v_{A}^2}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\left({\\frac{T_{D}}{T_{A}}}\\right)^{3}=\\left({\\frac{p_{D}}{p_{A}}}\\right)^{2}\\left({\\frac{v_{D}}}{v_{A}}}\\right)\n$$\n\nGet\n\n$$\nT_{D}=T_{A}\\left(\\frac{p_D^2v_{D}}{p_A^2v_{A}}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{3}}\n$$\n\nThe entropy integral gives\n\n$$\nS={\\frac{3T^{2}}{C_{1}p}}+C^{\\prime}=3{\\sqrt{\\frac{T v}{C_{1}}}}+C^{\\prime}\n$$\n\nSince the third law of thermodynamics\n\n$$\nC^{\\prime}=0\\quad,\\quad S=\\frac{3T^{2}}{C_{1}p}\n$$\n\nThus entropy changes\n\n$$\nS_{D}-S_{A}={\\frac{3T_{D}^{2}}{C_{1}p_{D}}}-{\\frac{3T_{A}^{2}}{C_{1}p_{A}}}=\\frac{3p_Av_A}{T_A}\\left(\\left(\\frac{p_Dv_D^2}{p_Av_A^ 2}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{3}}-1\\right)\n$$\n", "final_answers": "$$\nS_{D}-S_{A}=\\frac{3p_Av_A}{T_A}\\left(\\left(\\frac{p_Dv_D^2}{p_Av_A^2}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{3}}-1\\right)\n$$\n", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem concerns a thermodynamic system consisting of one mole of a substance, which is described as a simple $p,v,T$ system. The state of the system is defined by its pressure $p$, molar volume $v$, and absolute temperature $T$. The behavior of this substance is constrained by three specific physical laws:\n\n1.  **Coefficient of Volume Expansion**: The coefficient of volume expansion, $\\alpha$, is given by the relation:\n    $$ \\alpha = \\frac{3}{T} $$\n2.  **Adiabatic Process Equation**: For any reversible adiabatic process (a process with zero heat exchange, $dS=0$), the system follows the equation:\n    $$ pv^2 = C $$\n    where $C$ is a constant specific to the particular adiabatic path.\n3.  **Isobaric Heat Capacity**: The molar heat capacity at constant pressure, $c_p$, is proportional to the term $\\frac{pv}{T}$. This can be expressed as:\n    $$ c_p = \\lambda \\frac{pv}{T} $$\n    where $\\lambda$ is a dimensionless constant that is independent of the state of the system.\n\nWe are given two equilibrium states of the system: an initial state A, characterized by known variables $(p_A, v_A, T_A)$, and a final state D, characterized by known variables $(p_D, v_D)$. The temperature of state D, $T_D$, is not explicitly given but is determined by the system's equation of state.\n\nThe objective is to calculate the change in molar entropy, $S_D - S_A$, as the system transitions from state A to state D.\n\n### Step 1: Derive the General Form of the Equation of State\nWe start by using the given expression for the coefficient of volume expansion, $\\alpha$, to determine the functional form of the system's equation of state. The definition of $\\alpha$ is:\n\\[\\boxed{ \\alpha = \\frac{1}{v}\\left(\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T}\\right)_p }\\]\nThe problem states that $\\alpha = 3/T$. Equating this with the definition gives a partial differential equation.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{1}{v}\\left(\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T}\\right)_p &= \\frac{3}{T} \\label{eq:alpha_given}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo solve for the relationship between $v$ and $T$ at constant pressure, we can treat this as an ordinary differential equation by holding $p$ constant and separating the variables.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{1}{v} dv &= \\frac{3}{T} dT \\quad (\\text{for constant } p) \\label{eq:sep_var}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe integrate this equation. The constant of integration for the temperature integral will, in general, be a function of pressure, which we denote as $\\ln(h(p))$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int \\frac{1}{v} dv &= \\int \\frac{3}{T} dT \\nonumber \\\\\n\\ln(v) &= 3\\ln(T) + \\ln(h(p)) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\ln(v) &= \\ln(T^3 h(p)) \\nonumber \\\\\nv &= T^3 h(p) \\label{eq:eos_general}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis equation represents the general form of the equation of state that is consistent with the given coefficient of volume expansion. The specific form of the function $h(p)$ is yet to be determined.\n\n### Step 2: Formulate the Entropy Differential dS\nThe differential of molar entropy, $dS$, for a simple $p,v,T$ system can be expressed as a function of temperature $T$ and pressure $p$.\n\\[\\boxed{ dS = \\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}\\right)_p dT + \\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial p}\\right)_T dp }\\]\nThe partial derivatives of entropy can be related to other thermodynamic properties using standard identities.\n\\[\\boxed{ \\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}\\right)_p = \\frac{c_p}{T} }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial p}\\right)_T = -\\left(\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T}\\right)_p \\quad (\\text{Maxwell's Relation}) }\\]\nWe use the information given in the problem to find expressions for these partial derivatives. From the given isobaric heat capacity, $c_p = \\lambda \\frac{pv}{T}$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}\\right)_p = \\frac{1}{T} \\left(\\lambda \\frac{pv}{T}\\right) = \\lambda \\frac{pv}{T^2} \\label{eq:dSdT}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFrom the definition of $\\alpha$ and the given relation $\\alpha=3/T$, we have $(\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T})_p = v\\alpha = 3v/T$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial p}\\right)_T = -\\left(\\frac{\\partial v}{\\partial T}\\right)_p = -\\frac{3v}{T} \\label{eq:dSdp}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting these expressions back into the total differential for entropy gives:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ndS = \\lambda \\frac{pv}{T^2} dT - \\frac{3v}{T} dp \\label{eq:dS_general}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Determine the Proportionality Constant $\\lambda$\nSince entropy $S$ is a state function, its differential $dS$ must be an exact differential. This implies that the mixed second partial derivatives of $S$ must be equal (Clairaut's theorem).\n\\[\\boxed{ \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial p}\\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial T}\\right)_p = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T}\\left(\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial p}\\right)_T }\\]\nWe apply this condition to the coefficients of $dT$ and $dp$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:dS_general}.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial p}\\left(\\lambda \\frac{pv}{T^2}\\right)_T &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T}\\left(-\\frac{3v}{T}\\right)_p \\label{eq:schwartz_apply}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo evaluate these partial derivatives, we substitute the general equation of state $v = T^3 h(p)$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:eos_general}.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{LHS: } \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial p}\\left(\\lambda \\frac{p(T^3 h(p))}{T^2}\\right)_T &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial p}\\left(\\lambda T p h(p)\\right)_T = \\lambda T \\left(h(p) + p h'(p)\\right) \\label{eq:lhs} \\\\\n\\text{RHS: } \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T}\\left(-\\frac{3(T^3 h(p))}{T}\\right)_p &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T}\\left(-3 T^2 h(p)\\right)_p = -6 T h(p) \\label{eq:rhs}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nEquating the left-hand side (LHS) and right-hand side (RHS) yields a differential equation for $h(p)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\lambda T (h(p) + p h'(p)) &= -6 T h(p) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda (h(p) + p h'(p)) &= -6 h(p) \\label{eq:h_de}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo solve for $\\lambda$, we need to determine the form of $h(p)$. We use the given adiabatic condition. For an adiabatic process:\n\\[\\boxed{ dS = 0 }\\]\nApplying this to Eq. \\eqref{eq:dS_general}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n0 &= \\lambda \\frac{pv}{T^2} dT - \\frac{3v}{T} dp \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda \\frac{p}{T} dT &= 3 dp \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{\\lambda}{3} \\frac{dT}{T} &= \\frac{dp}{p} \\label{eq:ad_rel_1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nIntegrating this gives the temperature-pressure relationship for an adiabatic process: $T^{\\lambda/3} = (\\text{const}) \\cdot p$. We must reconcile this with the given adiabatic law $pv^2=C$. We use the general equation of state $v=T^3h(p)$, which implies $T=(v/h(p))^{1/3}$. Substituting this into our derived T-p relation:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left( \\frac{v}{h(p)} \\right)^{\\lambda/9} = (\\text{const}) \\cdot p \\implies v^{\\lambda/9} = (\\text{const}) \\cdot p \\cdot (h(p))^{\\lambda/9} \\label{eq:ad_rel_2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFrom the given law $pv^2=C$, we have $v^2 \\propto p^{-1}$, so $v \\propto p^{-1/2}$. Raising this to the power of $\\lambda/9$ gives $v^{\\lambda/9} \\propto (p^{-1/2})^{\\lambda/9} = p^{-\\lambda/18}$. Comparing this with Eq. \\eqref{eq:ad_rel_2}, the dependence on $p$ must be the same:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\np \\cdot (h(p))^{\\lambda/9} &\\propto p^{-\\lambda/18} \\nonumber \\\\\n(h(p))^{\\lambda/9} &\\propto p^{-1-\\lambda/18} = p^{-(\\lambda+18)/18} \\nonumber \\\\\nh(p) &\\propto \\left(p^{-(\\lambda+18)/18}\\right)^{9/\\lambda} = p^{-(\\lambda+18)/(2\\lambda)} \\label{eq:h_form}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow we substitute this functional form, $h(p) \\propto p^n$ with $n = -(\\lambda+18)/(2\\lambda)$, into Eq. \\eqref{eq:h_de}. For $h(p) \\propto p^n$, we have $ph'(p) = n h(p)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\lambda (h(p) + n h(p)) &= -6 h(p) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda (1+n) &= -6 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda \\left(1 - \\frac{\\lambda+18}{2\\lambda}\\right) &= -6 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda \\left(\\frac{2\\lambda - (\\lambda+18)}{2\\lambda}\\right) &= -6 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{\\lambda-18}{2} &= -6 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda - 18 &= -12 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\lambda &= 6 \\label{eq:lambda_val}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe consistency of the three given physical laws uniquely determines the value of the proportionality constant to be $\\lambda=6$.\n\n### Step 4: Derive the Specific Equation of State\nWith $\\lambda=6$, we can find the specific form of the function $h(p)$ and thus the equation of state for the substance. We use the functional form derived in the previous step:\n\\[\\boxed{ h(p) = K p^n \\quad \\text{with} \\quad n = -(\\lambda+18)/(2\\lambda) }\\]\nSubstituting $\\lambda=6$ into the expression for the exponent $n$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn = -\\frac{6+18}{2 \\cdot 6} = -\\frac{24}{12} = -2\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSo, $h(p) = K p^{-2}$, where $K$ is a constant. Substituting this into the general equation of state, Eq. \\eqref{eq:eos_general}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv = T^3 (K p^{-2}) \\implies p^2 v = K T^3 \\label{eq:eos_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is the specific equation of state for the substance. The constant $K$ can be determined by applying the equation to the known state A $(p_A, v_A, T_A)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\np_A^2 v_A = K T_A^3 \\implies K = \\frac{p_A^2 v_A}{T_A^3} \\label{eq:K_const}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Calculate the Entropy Change\nWe can now calculate the entropy change $S_D - S_A$ by integrating the entropy differential $dS$.\n\\[\\boxed{ S_D - S_A = \\int_A^D dS }\\]\nUsing the expression for $dS$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:dS_general} with $\\lambda=6$ and substituting the specific equation of state $v = K T^3 p^{-2}$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ndS &= 6 \\frac{pv}{T^2} dT - \\frac{3v}{T} dp \\nonumber \\\\\ndS &= 6 \\frac{p(K T^3 p^{-2})}{T^2} dT - \\frac{3(K T^3 p^{-2})}{T} dp \\nonumber \\\\\ndS &= 6 K T p^{-1} dT - 3 K T^2 p^{-2} dp \\label{eq:dS_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is an exact differential. We can find the entropy function $S(T, p)$ by integration. We can recognize that $d(T^2 p^{-1}) = 2T p^{-1} dT - T^2 p^{-2} dp$, so $dS = 3K d(T^2 p^{-1})$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nS(T, p) = 3K \\frac{T^2}{p} + S_0 \\label{eq:S_final}\n\\end{align}\nwhere $S_0$ is a constant of integration representing the reference entropy. The entropy change $S_D - S_A$ is the difference in this function between states D and A.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nS_D - S_A = \\left(3K \\frac{T_D^2}{p_D} + S_0\\right) - \\left(3K \\frac{T_A^2}{p_A} + S_0\\right) = 3K \\left(\\frac{T_D^2}{p_D} - \\frac{T_A^2}{p_A}\\right) \\label{eq:deltaS_intermediate}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo get the final answer in terms of the given variables, we eliminate $K$ and $T_D$. From the equation of state, Eq. \\eqref{eq:eos_final}, we have $\\frac{p^2 v}{T^3} = K$. Thus, for states A and D:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{p_D^2 v_D}{T_D^3} = K = \\frac{p_A^2 v_A}{T_A^3} \\implies T_D^3 = T_A^3 \\frac{p_D^2 v_D}{p_A^2 v_A} \\implies T_D^2 = T_A^2 \\left(\\frac{p_D^2 v_D}{p_A^2 v_A}\\right)^{2/3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow substitute $K$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:K_const} and the expression for $T_D^2$ into Eq. \\eqref{eq:deltaS_intermediate}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nS_D - S_A &= 3 \\left(\\frac{p_A^2 v_A}{T_A^3}\\right) \\left(\\frac{T_D^2}{p_D} - \\frac{T_A^2}{p_A}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A^2 v_A}{T_A^3} \\cdot T_A^2 \\left(\\frac{1}{p_D}\\frac{T_D^2}{T_A^2} - \\frac{1}{p_A}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A^2 v_A}{T_A} \\left(\\frac{1}{p_D}\\left(\\frac{p_D^2 v_D}{p_A^2 v_A}\\right)^{2/3} - \\frac{1}{p_A}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A v_A}{T_A} \\left(\\frac{p_A}{p_D}\\left(\\frac{p_D^2 v_D}{p_A^2 v_A}\\right)^{2/3} - 1\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A v_A}{T_A} \\left(p_A p_D^{-1} p_D^{4/3} p_A^{-4/3} v_D^{2/3} v_A^{-2/3} - 1\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A v_A}{T_A} \\left(p_A^{-1/3} p_D^{1/3} v_A^{-2/3} v_D^{2/3} - 1\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A v_A}{T_A} \\left(\\left(\\frac{p_D}{p_A}\\right)^{1/3} \\left(\\frac{v_D^2}{v_A^2}\\right)^{1/3} - 1\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 3 \\frac{p_A v_A}{T_A} \\left(\\left(\\frac{p_D v_D^2}{p_A v_A^2}\\right)^{1/3} - 1\\right) \\label{eq:deltaS_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe entropy change of state D compared to state A is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{S_D - S_A = 3 \\frac{p_A v_A}{T_A} \\left[ \\left(\\frac{p_D v_D^2}{p_A v_A^2}\\right)^{1/3} - 1 \\right]}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/36", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "Assume that the Earth is initially a solid sphere with a uniform density of $\\rho$ and a volume of $V={\\frac{4}{3}}\\pi R^{3}$, and is incompressible. The gravitational constant $G$ is known.\n\nFirst, consider the effect of Earth's rotation. Earth rotates around its polar axis with a constant angular velocity $\\omega$, forming an oblate spheroid under the action of inertial centrifugal forces.\n\nAlso consider the tidal forces exerted by Earth's satellite—the Moon. For simplicity, we establish the following simplified model: consider the Moon as a homogeneous ring with mass line density $\\textstyle{\\lambda={\\frac{m}{2\\pi r}}}$, located in the Earth's equatorial plane and centered at the Earth's center with a radius of $r$ ($r\\gg R$). Find the eccentricity of the Earth when stable $\\begin{array}{r}{e=\\frac{\\sqrt{a^{2}-b^{2}}}{a}}\\end{array}$, where $a$ is the semi-major axis and $b$ is the semi-minor axis.", "solutions": "The incompressibility condition is given as  \n\n$$\n{\\frac{4\\pi a^{2}b}{3}}={\\frac{4\\pi R^{3}}{3}}\n$$  \n\nThus,  \n\n$$\na={\\frac{R}{(1-e^{2})^{\\frac{1}{6}}}}\n$$  \n\nA uniformly dense ellipsoid can be divided into many thin ellipsoid shells with the same eccentricity. It can be proven that the surface mass density distribution of each ellipsoid shell is identical to the surface charge density distribution of ellipsoid conductors in electrostatics. The gravitational potential inside an ellipsoid shell is zero, so the self-energy of each ellipsoid shell can be calculated and summed. The total gravitational self-energy is  \n\n$$\nV_{g}=\\int_{0}^{a}-{\\frac{4\\pi}{3}}{\\sqrt{1-e^{2}}}a^{3}{\\frac{4\\pi G\\rho a{\\sqrt{1-e^{2}}}}{e}}\\mathrm{sin}^{-1}e d a\n$$  \n\nAfter integration,  \n\n$$\nV_{g}=-{\\frac{16\\pi^{2}}{15}}G\\rho^{2}R^{5}{\\frac{(1-e^{2})^{\\frac{1}{6}}}{e}}\\sin^{-1}e\n$$  \n\nThe total centrifugal potential energy is  \n\n$$\nV_{i}=\\iiint-{\\frac{1}{2}}\\rho\\omega^{2}(x^{2}+y^{2})d V\n$$  \n\nAfter integration,  \n\n$$\nV_{g}=-\\frac{4\\pi}{15}\\rho\\omega^{2}R^{5}\\frac{1}{(1-e^{2})^{\\frac{1}{3}}}\n$$  \n\nThe tidal potential energy per unit mass is  \n\n$$\nv_{t}=\\int_{0}^{2\\pi}-\\frac{G\\lambda r d\\varphi}{[(x-r\\cos\\varphi)^{2}+(y-r\\sin\\varphi)^{2}+z^{2}]^{\\frac{1}{2}}}\n$$  \n\nAfter approximation,  \n\n$$\nv_{t}=-{\\frac{G m}{r}}+{\\frac{G m}{4r^{3}}}(2z^{2}-x^{2}-y^{2})\n$$  \n\nThe total tidal potential energy is  \n\n$$\nV_{t}=\\iiint[-{\\frac{G m\\rho}{r}}+{\\frac{G m\\rho}{4r^{3}}}(2z^{2}-x^{2}-y^{2})]d V=-{\\frac{4\\pi G m\\rho R^{3}}{3}}-{\\frac{2\\pi G m\\rho R^{5}}{15}}{\\frac{e^{2}}{r^{3}(1-e^2)^{1/6}}}\n$$  \n\nThe total potential function is the sum of gravitational self-energy, centrifugal potential energy, and tidal potential energy. After approximation,  \n\n$$\nV=-\\frac{16\\pi^{2}}{15}G\\rho^{2}R^{5}-\\frac{4\\pi}{15}\\rho\\omega^{2}R^{5}-\\frac{4\\pi}{3}\\frac{G m\\rho R^{3}}{r}-\\frac{4\\pi}{45}\\rho\\omega^{2}R^{5}e^{2}-\\frac{2\\pi}{15}\\frac{G m\\rho R^{5}}{r^{3}}e^{2}+\\frac{16\\pi^{2}}{675}G\\rho^{2}R^{5}e^{4}\n$$  \n\nWhen stable, the potential function reaches a minimum,  \n\n$$\ne={\\sqrt{\\frac{30\\omega^{2}+45{\\frac{G m}{r^{3}}}}{16\\pi\\rho G}}}\n$$  \n\n**[Solution Method 2] (Alternative Method: Surface Equipotential Approach)**  \n\nThe surface equation for a rotational ellipsoid with a short axis in spherical coordinates is  \n\n$$\nr^{\\prime}(\\theta)^{2}=\\frac{a^{2}b^{2}}{a^{2}\\cos\\theta^{2}+b^{2}\\sin\\theta^{2}}\n$$  \n\nFrom equation $\\textcircled{2}$,  \n\n$$\nr^{\\prime}(\\theta)\\approx R+\\frac{R}{6}(1-3\\cos\\theta^{2})\n$$  \n\nUsing the multipole expansion method in electrostatics and expanding to the quadrupole moment of a rotational ellipsoid, the gravitational potential per unit mass is  \n\n$$\nv_{g}=-{\\frac{4\\pi G\\rho R^{3}}{3r^{\\prime}}}-{\\frac{2\\pi G\\rho R^{5}}{15{r^{\\prime}}^{5}}}{\\frac{e^{2}}{(1-e^{2})^{\\frac{1}{3}}}}{({x^{\\prime}}^{2}+{y^{\\prime}}^{2}-2{z^{\\prime}}^{2})}\n$$  \n\nThe centrifugal potential per unit mass is  \n\n$$\nv_{i}=-\\frac{1}{2}\\omega^{2}({x^{\\prime}}^{2}+{y^{\\prime}}^{2})\n$$  \n\nThe tidal potential per unit mass is  \n\n$$\nv_{t}=-{\\frac{G m}{r}}+{\\frac{G m}{4r^{3}}}(2{z^{\\prime}}^{2}-{x^{\\prime}}^{2}-{y^{\\prime}}^{2})\n$$  \n\nThe total surface potential per unit mass, which is the sum of the three potentials, is approximated as  \n\n$$\nv(\\theta)=-\\frac{4\\pi G\\rho R^{2}e^{2}}{45}(3\\cos\\theta^{2}-1)-\\frac{1}{2}\\omega^{2}R^{2}\\sin\\theta^{2}-\\frac{G m}{r}+\\frac{G m R^{2}}{4r^{3}}(3\\cos\\theta^{2}-1)\n$$  \n\nThe surface equipotential condition requires $v$ to be independent of $\\theta$, yielding  \n\n$$\ne={\\sqrt{\\frac{30\\omega^{2}+45{\\frac{G m}{r^{3}}}}{16\\pi\\rho G}}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\sqrt{\\frac{30\\omega^2 + \\frac{45Gm}{r^3}}{16\\pi\\rho G}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the equilibrium eccentricity, $e$, of the Earth, which deforms from an initial spherical shape into an oblate spheroid. The Earth is modeled as a solid, incompressible body with a uniform density $\\rho$. Its initial spherical state is characterized by a radius $R$ and volume $V = \\frac{4}{3}\\pi R^3$. The gravitational constant is $G$.\n\nThe deformation is caused by two effects:\n1.  **Earth's Rotation:** The Earth rotates with a constant angular velocity $\\omega$ about its polar axis.\n2.  **Tidal Forces:** The Moon is modeled as a homogeneous ring with total mass $m$ and radius $r$, located in the Earth's equatorial plane and centered at the Earth's center. It is assumed that the Moon's orbit is much larger than the Earth's size, i.e., $r \\gg R$.\n\nWe establish a coordinate system with the origin at the Earth's center. The z-axis is aligned with the polar axis of rotation, and the xy-plane is the equatorial plane, which also contains the Moon ring. The resulting oblate spheroid has a semi-major axis $a$ (in the equatorial plane) and a semi-minor axis $b$ (along the polar axis).\n\nThe relevant variables are:\n*   $e = \\frac{\\sqrt{a^2 - b^2}}{a}$: The eccentricity of the oblate spheroid.\n*   $a$: The semi-major axis (equatorial radius).\n*   $b$: The semi-minor axis (polar radius).\n*   $M = \\rho V = \\frac{4}{3}\\pi\\rho R^3$: The total mass of the Earth.\n*   $(\\tilde{r}, \\theta, \\phi)$: Spherical coordinates, where $\\theta$ is the polar angle from the z-axis.\n\nThe stable shape is achieved when the Earth is in hydrostatic equilibrium, meaning its surface is an equipotential surface for the combined potential fields. We assume the deformation is small, which implies that the eccentricity is small ($e \\ll 1$).\n\n### Step 1: Geometry of the Oblate Spheroid\nWe relate the semi-axes $a$ and $b$ of the oblate spheroid to the initial radius $R$ using the incompressibility condition (constant volume) and the definition of eccentricity.\n\\[\\boxed{V = \\frac{4}{3}\\pi a^2 b = \\frac{4}{3}\\pi R^3}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{b^2 = a^2(1-e^2)}\\]\nFrom the incompressibility condition, we have $a^2 b = R^3$. Using the definition of eccentricity, we can express $b$ in terms of $a$ and $e$ as $b = a\\sqrt{1-e^2}$. Substituting this into the volume relation gives:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\na^2 (a\\sqrt{1-e^2}) &= R^3 \\nonumber \\\\\na^3 (1-e^2)^{1/2} &= R^3 \\nonumber \\\\\na &= R (1-e^2)^{-1/6} \\label{eq:a_exact} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor a small eccentricity ($e \\ll 1$), we use the binomial approximation $(1+x)^n \\approx 1+nx$ to find the semi-axes to second order in $e$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\na &\\approx R \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{6}e^2\\right) \\label{eq:a_approx} \\tag{2} \\\\\nb &= a\\sqrt{1-e^2} \\approx R \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{6}e^2\\right) \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{2}e^2\\right) \\approx R \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{6}e^2 - \\frac{1}{2}e^2\\right) = R \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{3}e^2\\right) \\label{eq:b_approx} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe surface of the oblate spheroid is described by $\\frac{x^2+y^2}{a^2} + \\frac{z^2}{b^2} = 1$. In spherical coordinates, the radius of the surface, $r'(\\theta)$, as a function of the polar angle $\\theta$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nr'(\\theta)^2 &= \\frac{a^2 b^2}{b^2\\sin^2\\theta + a^2\\cos^2\\theta} = \\frac{a^2 b^2}{a^2(1-e^2)\\sin^2\\theta + a^2\\cos^2\\theta} = \\frac{b^2}{1-e^2\\sin^2\\theta} \\nonumber \\\\\nr'(\\theta) &= b(1-e^2\\sin^2\\theta)^{-1/2} \\approx b\\left(1+\\frac{1}{2}e^2\\sin^2\\theta\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx R\\left(1-\\frac{1}{3}e^2\\right)\\left(1+\\frac{1}{2}e^2\\sin^2\\theta\\right) \\approx R\\left(1-\\frac{1}{3}e^2+\\frac{1}{2}e^2\\sin^2\\theta\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= R\\left[1+e^2\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\sin^2\\theta-\\frac{1}{3}\\right)\\right] = R\\left[1+e^2\\left(\\frac{1}{2}(1-\\cos^2\\theta)-\\frac{1}{3}\\right)\\right] = R\\left[1+e^2\\left(\\frac{1}{6}-\\frac{1}{2}\\cos^2\\theta\\right)\\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= R\\left[1 - \\frac{e^2}{3}\\left(\\frac{3\\cos^2\\theta-1}{2}\\right)\\right] = R\\left(1 - \\frac{e^2}{3}P_2(\\cos\\theta)\\right) \\label{eq:r_prime} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nwhere $P_2(\\cos\\theta) = \\frac{1}{2}(3\\cos^2\\theta-1)$ is the Legendre polynomial of degree 2.\n\n### Step 2: Principle of Hydrostatic Equilibrium\nFor a fluid body to be in a stable equilibrium configuration, its surface must be an equipotential surface. The total effective potential per unit mass, $U$, is the sum of the gravitational self-potential ($v_g$), the centrifugal potential due to rotation ($v_i$), and the tidal potential from the Moon ($v_t$).\n\\[\\boxed{U = v_g + v_i + v_t}\\]\nThe condition for hydrostatic equilibrium is that the total potential $U$ is constant on the surface of the spheroid.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU(r'(\\theta), \\theta) = \\text{constant} \\quad (\\text{for all } \\theta) \\label{eq:equipotential} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis implies that the sum of all terms in the expression for $U$ on the surface that depend on the angle $\\theta$ must be zero.\n\n### Step 3: Gravitational Potential on the Surface\nThe external gravitational potential of an axially symmetric body can be described by a multipole expansion in terms of Legendre polynomials. To sufficient accuracy for this problem (order $e^2$), we truncate at the quadrupole term.\n\\[\\boxed{v_g(\\tilde{r}, \\theta) = -\\frac{GM}{\\tilde{r}} + \\frac{G(I_z - I_x)}{\\tilde{r}^3}P_2(\\cos\\theta)}\\]\nwhere $I_z$ and $I_x$ are the principal moments of inertia about the polar (z) and an equatorial (x) axis, respectively. For a uniform oblate spheroid:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nI_z = \\frac{2}{5}Ma^2, \\quad I_x = \\frac{1}{5}M(a^2+b^2) \\implies I_z - I_x = \\frac{1}{5}M(a^2-b^2) = \\frac{1}{5}Ma^2e^2 \\label{eq:mom_inertia_diff} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe evaluate the potential on the surface $\\tilde{r} = r'(\\theta)$. In the quadrupole term, which is already of order $e^2$, we can approximate $a \\approx R$ and $\\tilde{r} \\approx R$. In the monopole term, we expand $1/r'(\\theta)$ to first order in $e^2$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_g(r'(\\theta), \\theta) &\\approx -\\frac{GM}{R(1 - \\frac{e^2}{3}P_2(\\cos\\theta))} + \\frac{G(\\frac{1}{5}MR^2e^2)}{R^3}P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx -\\frac{GM}{R}\\left(1 + \\frac{e^2}{3}P_2(\\cos\\theta)\\right) + \\frac{GMe^2}{5R}P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{GM}{R} - \\left(\\frac{GMe^2}{3R} - \\frac{GMe^2}{5R}\\right)P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{GM}{R} - \\frac{2}{15}\\frac{GMe^2}{R}P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:vg_surface} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe $\\theta$-dependent part of the gravitational potential on the surface is $v_{g,\\theta} = -\\frac{2}{15}\\frac{GMe^2}{R}P_2(\\cos\\theta)$.\n\n### Step 4: Centrifugal Potential on the Surface\nThe centrifugal potential per unit mass for rotation with angular velocity $\\omega$ about the z-axis is given by:\n\\[\\boxed{v_i = -\\frac{1}{2}\\omega^2(x^2+y^2) = -\\frac{1}{2}\\omega^2 \\tilde{r}^2\\sin^2\\theta}\\]\nWe evaluate this potential on the surface $\\tilde{r} = r'(\\theta)$. Since the centrifugal potential is a small perturbation, we can approximate the surface radius by the initial radius, $r'(\\theta) \\approx R$. Any corrections would be of higher order and can be neglected.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_i(r'(\\theta), \\theta) \\approx -\\frac{1}{2}\\omega^2 R^2 \\sin^2\\theta \\label{eq:vi_approx} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo isolate the angular dependence in the form of $P_2(\\cos\\theta)$, we use the identity $\\sin^2\\theta = \\frac{2}{3} - \\frac{2}{3}P_2(\\cos\\theta)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_i(r'(\\theta), \\theta) &\\approx -\\frac{1}{2}\\omega^2 R^2 \\left(\\frac{2}{3} - \\frac{2}{3}P_2(\\cos\\theta)\\right) = -\\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 + \\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:vi_surface} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe $\\theta$-dependent part of the centrifugal potential on the surface is $v_{i,\\theta} = +\\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 P_2(\\cos\\theta)$.\n\n### Step 5: Tidal Potential on the Surface\nThe gravitational potential per unit mass created by the external ring-shaped Moon can be expressed using a multipole expansion. For a point $(\\tilde{r}, \\theta)$ inside the ring's orbit ($\\tilde{r} \\ll r$), the potential is given by:\n\\[\\boxed{v_t(\\tilde{r}, \\theta) = -\\frac{Gm}{r} \\sum_{l=0}^{\\infty} P_{2l}(0) P_{2l}(\\cos\\theta) \\left(\\frac{\\tilde{r}}{r}\\right)^{2l}}\\]\nWe keep terms up to $l=1$ (the quadrupole term). Using $P_0(x)=1$ and $P_2(x)=\\frac{1}{2}(3x^2-1)$, which gives $P_2(0)=-1/2$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_t(\\tilde{r}, \\theta) &\\approx -\\frac{Gm}{r}\\left[P_0(0)P_0(\\cos\\theta)\\left(\\frac{\\tilde{r}}{r}\\right)^0 + P_2(0)P_2(\\cos\\theta)\\left(\\frac{\\tilde{r}}{r}\\right)^2\\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{Gm}{r}\\left[1 - \\frac{1}{2}P_2(\\cos\\theta)\\left(\\frac{\\tilde{r}}{r}\\right)^2\\right] = -\\frac{Gm}{r} + \\frac{Gm\\tilde{r}^2}{2r^3}P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:vt_general} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe evaluate this on the surface $\\tilde{r} = r'(\\theta)$. As with the centrifugal potential, we can approximate $\\tilde{r} \\approx R$ in the small quadrupole term, as corrections are of higher order.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_t(r'(\\theta), \\theta) \\approx -\\frac{Gm}{r} + \\frac{GmR^2}{2r^3}P_2(\\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:vt_surface} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe $\\theta$-dependent part of the tidal potential on the surface is $v_{t,\\theta} = +\\frac{GmR^2}{2r^3}P_2(\\cos\\theta)$.\n\n### Step 6: Applying the Equipotential Condition\nFor the total potential $U$ to be constant on the surface, the sum of all $\\theta$-dependent terms must be zero.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_{g,\\theta} + v_{i,\\theta} + v_{t,\\theta} &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n-\\frac{2}{15}\\frac{GMe^2}{R}P_2(\\cos\\theta) + \\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 P_2(\\cos\\theta) + \\frac{GmR^2}{2r^3}P_2(\\cos\\theta) &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(-\\frac{2}{15}\\frac{GMe^2}{R} + \\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 + \\frac{GmR^2}{2r^3}\\right)P_2(\\cos\\theta) &= 0 \\label{eq:potential_balance} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSince this equation must hold for all angles $\\theta$, the coefficient of $P_2(\\cos\\theta)$ must be zero.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{2}{15}\\frac{GMe^2}{R} &= \\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 + \\frac{GmR^2}{2r^3} \\nonumber \\\\\ne^2 &= \\frac{15R}{2GM}\\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\omega^2 R^2 + \\frac{GmR^2}{2r^3}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\ne^2 &= \\frac{R^3}{GM}\\left(\\frac{15}{2 \\cdot 3}\\omega^2 + \\frac{15}{2 \\cdot 2}\\frac{Gm}{r^3}\\right) = \\frac{R^3}{GM}\\left(\\frac{5}{2}\\omega^2 + \\frac{15}{4}\\frac{Gm}{r^3}\\right) \\label{eq:e2_intermediate} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we substitute $M = \\rho \\frac{4}{3}\\pi R^3$, which gives $\\frac{R^3}{GM} = \\frac{R^3}{G(\\frac{4}{3}\\pi\\rho R^3)} = \\frac{3}{4\\pi G\\rho}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ne^2 &= \\frac{3}{4\\pi G\\rho}\\left(\\frac{5}{2}\\omega^2 + \\frac{15}{4}\\frac{Gm}{r^3}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{4\\pi G\\rho}\\left(\\frac{15}{2}\\omega^2 + \\frac{45}{4}\\frac{Gm}{r^3}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{16\\pi G\\rho}\\left(30\\omega^2 + 45\\frac{Gm}{r^3}\\right) \\label{eq:e2_final} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTaking the square root gives the eccentricity $e$.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe eccentricity of the Earth when stable is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{e = \\sqrt{\\frac{30\\omega^2 + 45\\frac{Gm}{r^3}}{16\\pi G\\rho}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/333", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "A dielectric cylinder with a radius $R$, mass $m$, and uniform length $L \\gg R$ is permanently polarized, where the magnitude of the polarization intensity vector at any point a distance $r$ from the center is $P_{0}e^{k r}$, directed radially outward. Initially, the cylinder is at rest, and a constant external torque $M$ is applied to the cylinder. Find the angular acceleration $\\beta$ of the cylinder. The final result is expressed in terms of $M, m, k, R, L, P_0, \\mu_0$.", "solutions": "When the angular velocity of the cylinder is $\\omega$, the surface current density is  \n\n$$\ni=\\sigma\\omega R=P_{0}\\omega R e^{k R}\n$$\n\nThe volume current density in region C is  \n\n$$\nj_{2}=\\rho r\\omega=-(1+k r)P_{0}\\omega e^{k r}\n$$\n\nFrom Ampère's circuital theorem:  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{l}{{\\displaystyle{\\cal B}=\\int_{r}^{R}\\mu_{\\scriptscriptstyle0}j d r+\\mu_{\\scriptscriptstyle0}i}}\\ {{\\mathrm{}}}\\ {{\\displaystyle{\\cal B}=\\mu_{\\scriptscriptstyle0}P_{0}\\omega r e^{k r}}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nMagnetic flux  \n\n$$\n\\Phi=\\int_{0}^{r}\\boldsymbol{B}\\cdot2\\pi r d r\n$$\n\n$$\n\\Phi=2\\pi\\mu_{\\scriptscriptstyle0}\\omega P_{\\scriptscriptstyle0}(\\frac{r^{\\prime}{}^{2}}k e^{k r}-\\frac r{k^{2}}e^{k r}+\\frac2{k^{3}}e^{k r})\n$$\n\nElectromagnetic induction  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{l}{E=-\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{2\\pi r}\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t}\\Phi}\\ {E=-\\displaystyle\\mu_{0}\\beta P_{0}e^{\\displaystyle k r}(\\frac{r}{k}{-}\\frac{2}{k^{2}}{+}\\frac{2}{k^{3}r})}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nElectromagnetic torque  \n\n$$\nM_{c}=\\int_{0}^{R}E\\cdot\\rho L\\cdot2\\pi r^{2}d r+E R\\sigma\\cdot2\\pi R L_{\\mathrm{~/~}}\n$$\n\nAfter integrating  \n\nFrom the momentum theorem:  \n\n$$\nM+M_{e}=\\frac{1}{2}m R^{2}\\beta\\stackrel{\\_}{\\_}.\n$$\n\nSolving for $\\beta$  \n\n$$\n\\beta = \\frac{2M}{mR^2+4\\mu_0P_0^2\\pi L[\\frac 3{8k^4}+(\\frac{R^3}{2k}-\\frac{3R^2}{4k^2}+\\frac{3R}{4k^3}-\\frac 3 {8k^4})e ^{2kR}}]\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\beta = \\frac{2M}{mR^2 + 4\\mu_0 P_0^2 \\pi L \\left(\\frac{3}{8k^4} + \\left(\\frac{R^3}{2k} - \\frac{3R^2}{4k^2} + \\frac{3R}{4k^3} - \\frac{3}{8k^4}\\right)e^{2kR}\\right)}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem analyzes the rotational dynamics of a special dielectric cylinder. We are given the following information:\n*   **Object**: A solid dielectric cylinder.\n*   **Geometric and Physical Properties**:\n    *   Radius: $R$\n    *   Mass: $m$\n    *   Length: $L$\n    *   It is a long cylinder, which implies the approximation $L \\gg R$ can be used to neglect fringe effects at the ends.\n*   **Electromagnetic Properties**:\n    *   The cylinder has a permanent, \"frozen-in\" polarization $\\vec{P}$.\n    *   The polarization vector at a radial distance $r$ from the axis is given by $\\vec{P}(r) = P_0 e^{kr} \\hat{r}$, where $P_0$ and $k$ are constants. The vector is directed radially outward.\n*   **Initial Conditions**: The cylinder is initially at rest, so its initial angular velocity is zero.\n*   **Process**: A constant external torque, with magnitude $M$, is applied to the cylinder, causing it to rotate about its central axis. The angular velocity is $\\vec{\\omega} = \\omega(t) \\hat{z}$, and the angular acceleration is $\\vec{\\beta} = \\beta(t) \\hat{z}$, where $\\beta = d\\omega/dt$.\n*   **Goal**: We need to find the expression for the angular acceleration $\\beta$. The final result should be expressed in terms of the given parameters: $M, m, k, R, L, P_0$, and the permeability of free space, $\\mu_0$.\n\nThe physical process involves a coupling between mechanics and electromagnetism. The applied torque causes rotation. The rotation of the polarized material creates bound electric currents. These currents generate a magnetic field. As the cylinder accelerates, this magnetic field changes in time, which, by Faraday's Law of induction, induces an electric field. This induced electric field exerts a counter-torque (a back-torque) on the polarized material, opposing the acceleration. The net torque determines the final angular acceleration.\n\n### Step 1: Analysis of the Polarization Field and Bound Charges\nFirst, we determine the bound charge distribution arising from the permanent polarization. The term \"permanently polarized\" implies the polarization is \"frozen-in\" the material of the cylinder.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe bound volume charge density $\\rho_b$ and bound surface charge density $\\sigma_b$ are related to the polarization vector $\\vec{P}$ by:\n\\[\\boxed{\\rho_b = -\\nabla \\cdot \\vec{P}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\sigma_b = \\vec{P} \\cdot \\hat{n}}\\]\nThe divergence operator in cylindrical coordinates for a radial vector field $\\vec{A} = A_r(r) \\hat{r}$ is:\n\\[\\boxed{\\nabla \\cdot \\vec{A} = \\frac{1}{r}\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r}(r A_r)}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe polarization is given as $\\vec{P}(r) = P_0 e^{kr} \\hat{r}$. This describes a polarization field that is fixed relative to the cylinder's material. Due to the axial symmetry, the polarization field is static in the lab frame, i.e., $\\vec{P}(r, \\phi, z, t) = P_0 e^{kr} \\hat{r}$.\n\nWe calculate the bound volume charge density $\\rho_b$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\rho_b &= -\\nabla \\cdot (P_0 e^{kr} \\hat{r}) = -\\frac{1}{r}\\frac{\\partial}{\\partial r}(r P_0 e^{kr}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{P_0}{r}(e^{kr} + rke^{kr}) = -P_0 e^{kr} \\left(\\frac{1}{r} + k\\right) \\label{eq:rho_b} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nOn the cylindrical surface at $r=R$, the outward unit normal vector is $\\hat{n} = \\hat{r}$. The bound surface charge density $\\sigma_b$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\sigma_b = \\vec{P}(R) \\cdot \\hat{r} = (P_0 e^{kR} \\hat{r}) \\cdot \\hat{r} = P_0 e^{kR} \\label{eq:sigma_b} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Bound Current Calculation\nThe rotation of the cylinder causes the bound charges to move, creating bound currents. The total bound current is the sum of the convection current (from moving charges) and the polarization current (from the time variation of $\\vec{P}$).\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe velocity of a point at position $\\vec{r}$ in a body rotating with angular velocity $\\vec{\\omega}$ is:\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{v} = \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}}\\]\nThe total bound volume current density $\\vec{j}_b$ and surface current density $\\vec{K}_b$ are given by:\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{j}_b = \\rho_b \\vec{v} + \\frac{\\partial \\vec{P}}{\\partial t}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{K}_b = \\sigma_b \\vec{v}}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nAs established in Step 1, the polarization field $\\vec{P}(r) = P_0 e^{kr} \\hat{r}$ is static in the laboratory frame. Therefore, its partial time derivative is zero.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{\\partial \\vec{P}}{\\partial t} = 0 \\label{eq:dPdt_zero} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis means the polarization current is zero. The bound currents are purely convective. The velocity of a point at radius $r$ rotating with angular velocity $\\vec{\\omega} = \\omega \\hat{z}$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{v} = (\\omega \\hat{z}) \\times (r\\hat{r}) = \\omega r (\\hat{z} \\times \\hat{r}) = \\omega r \\hat{\\phi} \\label{eq:velocity} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe bound volume current density is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{j}_b = \\rho_b \\vec{v} = \\left[-P_0 e^{kr} \\left(\\frac{1}{r} + k\\right)\\right] (\\omega r \\hat{\\phi}) = -P_0 \\omega (1+kr) e^{kr} \\hat{\\phi} \\label{eq:j_b} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe bound surface current density at $r=R$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{K}_b = \\sigma_b \\vec{v}|_{r=R} = (P_0 e^{kR}) (\\omega R \\hat{\\phi}) = P_0 \\omega R e^{kR} \\hat{\\phi} \\label{eq:K_b} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Magnetic Field Calculation\nThe bound currents generate a magnetic field $\\vec{B}$. We use Ampere's law and the corresponding boundary condition to find it. For a long cylinder ($L \\gg R$), we can neglect fringe effects and assume the magnetic field is axial.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nAmpere's law in differential form relates the magnetic field to the current density:\n\\[\\boxed{\\nabla \\times \\vec{B} = \\mu_0 \\vec{j}}\\]\nThe boundary condition for the magnetic field at a surface with current $\\vec{K}$ is:\n\\[\\boxed{\\hat{n} \\times (\\vec{B}_{2} - \\vec{B}_{1}) = \\mu_0 \\vec{K}}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nGiven the cylindrical symmetry and that the currents are purely azimuthal ($\\hat{\\phi}$ direction), the magnetic field inside the long cylinder must be of the form $\\vec{B} = B_z(r) \\hat{z}$. In cylindrical coordinates, the curl of such a field is $\\nabla \\times \\vec{B} = -\\frac{dB_z}{dr}\\hat{\\phi}$. Applying Ampere's law with $\\vec{j} = \\vec{j}_b$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n-\\frac{dB_z}{dr}\\hat{\\phi} &= \\mu_0 \\vec{j}_b = \\mu_0 (-P_0 \\omega (1+kr) e^{kr} \\hat{\\phi}) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{dB_z}{dr} &= \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega (1+kr) e^{kr} \\label{eq:dBdr} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nIntegrating with respect to $r$ (using integration by parts or recognizing that $\\frac{d}{dr}(re^{kr}) = (1+kr)e^{kr}$):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nB_z(r) = \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega \\int (1+kr)e^{kr} dr = \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega (r e^{kr}) + C \\label{eq:B_int} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nwhere $C$ is an integration constant. To find $C$, we apply the boundary condition at $r=R$. Let region 1 be inside ($r<R$) and region 2 be outside ($r>R$). The normal vector is $\\hat{n}=\\hat{r}$. For a very long cylinder, the external magnetic field is negligible, so we approximate $\\vec{B}_{2}=\\vec{B}_{\\text{out}}=0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\hat{r} \\times (0 - \\vec{B}_{\\text{in}}(R)) &= \\mu_0 \\vec{K}_b \\nonumber \\\\\n-\\hat{r} \\times (B_z(R)\\hat{z}) &= \\mu_0 (P_0 \\omega R e^{kR} \\hat{\\phi}) \\nonumber \\\\\n-B_z(R) (-\\hat{\\phi}) &= \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega R e^{kR} \\hat{\\phi} \\nonumber \\\\\nB_z(R) &= \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega R e^{kR} \\label{eq:B_boundary} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nComparing this with Eq. \\eqref{eq:B_int} evaluated at $r=R$, we have $B_z(R) = \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega R e^{kR} + C$. This implies that the constant $C=0$. Thus, the magnetic field inside the cylinder is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{B}(r,t) = \\mu_0 P_0 \\omega(t) r e^{kr} \\hat{z} \\quad (\\text{for } r \\le R) \\label{eq:B_final} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Electromagnetic Back-Torque Calculation\nThe angular acceleration $\\beta = d\\omega/dt$ causes $\\vec{B}$ to change, which induces an electric field $\\vec{E}$ via Faraday's Law. This $\\vec{E}$ field exerts a torque $\\vec{M}_e$ on the polarized material.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nFaraday's law of induction in differential form is:\n\\[\\boxed{\\nabla \\times \\vec{E} = -\\frac{\\partial \\vec{B}}{\\partial t}}\\]\nThe torque on the bound charges is given by the volume and surface integrals of the torque density:\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{M}_e = \\int_V \\vec{r} \\times (\\rho_b \\vec{E}) dV + \\oint_S \\vec{r} \\times (\\sigma_b \\vec{E}) dS}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nDue to symmetry, the induced electric field is azimuthal: $\\vec{E} = E_\\phi(r)\\hat{\\phi}$. The torque element $d\\vec{M}_e = \\vec{r} \\times d\\vec{F}_e$ is in the $\\hat{z}$ direction.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nM_{e,z} &= \\int_V (\\vec{r} \\times (\\rho_b \\vec{E}))_z dV + \\oint_S (\\vec{r} \\times (\\sigma_b \\vec{E}))_z dS \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{With } &\\vec{r} = r\\hat{r} \\text{ and } \\vec{E} = E_\\phi(r)\\hat{\\phi}, \\text{ we have } \\vec{r} \\times \\vec{E} = rE_\\phi \\hat{z}. \\text{ For a cylinder of length L:} \\nonumber \\\\\nM_{e,z} &= \\int_0^L \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\int_0^R \\rho_b(r) (r E_\\phi(r)) r dr d\\phi dz + \\int_0^L \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\sigma_b (R E_\\phi(R)) R d\\phi dz \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2\\pi L \\left( \\int_0^R r^2 \\rho_b(r) E_\\phi(r) dr + R^2 \\sigma_b E_\\phi(R) \\right) \\label{eq:torque_start} \\tag{11} \\\\\n\\text{Substituting } &\\rho_b = -\\frac{1}{r}\\frac{d}{dr}(rP_r) \\text{ and } \\sigma_b = P_r(R), \\text{ where } P_r = P_0 e^{kr}: \\nonumber \\\\\nM_{e,z} &= 2\\pi L \\left( -\\int_0^R r E_\\phi(r) \\frac{d(rP_r)}{dr} dr + R^2 P_r(R) E_\\phi(R) \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{We integrate } &\\text{the first term by parts with } u = rE_\\phi \\text{ and } dv = \\frac{d(rP_r)}{dr}dr: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\int_0^R r E_\\phi \\frac{d(rP_r)}{dr} dr &= \\left[ (rE_\\phi)(rP_r) \\right]_0^R - \\int_0^R (rP_r) \\frac{d(rE_\\phi)}{dr} dr = R^2 E_\\phi(R) P_r(R) - \\int_0^R r P_r(r) \\frac{d(rE_\\phi)}{dr} dr \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Substituting this } &\\text{back into the expression for torque simplifies it:} \\nonumber \\\\\nM_{e,z} &= 2\\pi L \\left( - \\left( R^2 E_\\phi(R) P_r(R) - \\int_0^R r P_r \\frac{d(rE_\\phi)}{dr} dr \\right) + R^2 P_r(R) E_\\phi(R) \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2\\pi L \\int_0^R r P_r(r) \\frac{d(rE_\\phi)}{dr} dr \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{From Faraday's law, } &\\nabla \\times \\vec{E} = \\frac{1}{r}\\frac{d}{dr}(rE_\\phi)\\hat{z} = -\\frac{\\partial \\vec{B}}{\\partial t} = -\\frac{\\partial B_z}{\\partial t}\\hat{z}, \\text{ so } \\frac{d(rE_\\phi)}{dr} = -r\\frac{\\partial B_z}{\\partial t}. \\nonumber \\\\\nM_{e,z} &= 2\\pi L \\int_0^R r P_r(r) \\left(-r \\frac{\\partial B_z}{\\partial t}\\right) dr = -2\\pi L \\int_0^R r^2 P_r(r) \\frac{\\partial B_z}{\\partial t} dr \\label{eq:torque_simplified} \\tag{12} \\\\\n\\text{Using } P_r(r) &= P_0 e^{kr} \\text{ and } \\frac{\\partial B_z}{\\partial t} = \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial t}(\\mu_0 P_0 \\omega r e^{kr}) = \\mu_0 P_0 \\beta r e^{kr}: \\nonumber \\\\\nM_e &= -2\\pi L \\int_0^R r^2 (P_0 e^{kr}) (\\mu_0 P_0 \\beta r e^{kr}) dr = -2\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\beta \\int_0^R r^3 e^{2kr} dr \\label{eq:Me_final} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe negative sign confirms this is a back-torque, opposing the acceleration $\\beta$.\n\n### Step 5: Calculation of the Torque Integral\nWe evaluate the definite integral from Eq. \\eqref{eq:Me_final} using integration by parts.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe standard formula for repeated integration by parts is:\n\\[\\boxed{\\int r^n e^{ar} dr = e^{ar} \\left(\\frac{r^n}{a} - \\frac{n r^{n-1}}{a^2} + \\frac{n(n-1)r^{n-2}}{a^3} - \\dots + (-1)^n \\frac{n!}{a^{n+1}}\\right)}\\]\nFor $n=3$, this gives:\n\\[\\boxed{\\int r^3 e^{ar} dr = e^{ar} \\left(\\frac{r^3}{a} - \\frac{3r^2}{a^2} + \\frac{6r}{a^3} - \\frac{6}{a^4}\\right)}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nWe evaluate the definite integral from $0$ to $R$ with $a=2k$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^R r^3 e^{ar} dr &= \\left[ e^{ar} \\left(\\frac{r^3}{a} - \\frac{3r^2}{a^2} + \\frac{6r}{a^3} - \\frac{6}{a^4}\\right) \\right]_0^R \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left( e^{aR} \\left(\\frac{R^3}{a} - \\frac{3R^2}{a^2} + \\frac{6R}{a^3} - \\frac{6}{a^4}\\right) \\right) - \\left( e^0 \\left(0 - 0 + 0 - \\frac{6}{a^4}\\right) \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= e^{aR} \\left(\\frac{R^3}{a} - \\frac{3R^2}{a^2} + \\frac{6R}{a^3} - \\frac{6}{a^4}\\right) + \\frac{6}{a^4} \\label{eq:integral_def} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting $a=2k$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^R r^3 e^{2kr} dr &= e^{2kR} \\left(\\frac{R^3}{2k} - \\frac{3R^2}{(2k)^2} + \\frac{6R}{(2k)^3} - \\frac{6}{(2k)^4}\\right) + \\frac{6}{(2k)^4} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= e^{2kR} \\left(\\frac{R^3}{2k} - \\frac{3R^2}{4k^2} + \\frac{3R}{4k^3} - \\frac{3}{8k^4}\\right) + \\frac{3}{8k^4} \\label{eq:integral_final} \\tag{15}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 6: Rotational Dynamics and Final Solution\nThe net torque on the cylinder is the sum of the external torque $M$ and the electromagnetic back-torque $M_e$. We apply Newton's second law for rotation to find the angular acceleration $\\beta$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nNewton's second law for rotation states that the net torque equals the moment of inertia times the angular acceleration:\n\\[\\boxed{M_{\\text{net}} = I \\beta}\\]\nThe moment of inertia of a solid cylinder of mass $m$ and radius $R$ about its central axis is:\n\\[\\boxed{I = \\frac{1}{2}mR^2}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe net torque is $M_{\\text{net}} = M + M_e$. The equation of motion is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nI \\beta &= M + M_e \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{1}{2}mR^2 \\beta &= M + \\left(-2\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\beta \\int_0^R r^3 e^{2kr} dr\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{1}{2}mR^2 \\beta &= M - \\left(2\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\int_0^R r^3 e^{2kr} dr\\right) \\beta \\label{eq:newton_rot} \\tag{16}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSolving for $\\beta$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{1}{2}mR^2 + 2\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\int_0^R r^3 e^{2kr} dr\\right) \\beta &= M \\nonumber \\\\\n\\beta &= \\frac{M}{\\frac{1}{2}mR^2 + 2\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\int_0^R r^3 e^{2kr} dr} \\label{eq:beta_almost} \\tag{17}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstitute the result of the integral from Eq. \\eqref{eq:integral_final}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\beta &= \\frac{M}{\\frac{1}{2}mR^2 + 2\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\left[e^{2kR} \\left(\\frac{R^3}{2k} - \\frac{3R^2}{4k^2} + \\frac{3R}{4k^3} - \\frac{3}{8k^4}\\right) + \\frac{3}{8k^4}\\right]} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\beta &= \\frac{2M}{mR^2 + 4\\pi L \\mu_0 P_0^2 \\left[\\frac{3}{8k^4} + \\left(\\frac{R^3}{2k} - \\frac{3R^2}{4k^2} + \\frac{3R}{4k^3} - \\frac{3}{8k^4}\\right)e^{2kR}\\right]} \\label{eq:beta_final} \\tag{18}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe angular acceleration $\\beta$ of the cylinder is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\beta = \\frac{2M}{mR^2+4\\pi \\mu_0 P_0^2 L\\left[\\frac{3}{8k^4}+\\left(\\frac{R^3}{2k}-\\frac{3R^2}{4k^2}+\\frac{3R}{4k^3}-\\frac{3}{8k^4}\\right)e^{2kR}\\right]}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/50", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "A cylindrical container with a cross-sectional area $S$ is fixed on the ground. The container walls are thermally insulated, and the top is sealed with a thermally insulated piston of mass $p_{0}S/g$ (where $g$ is the gravitational acceleration). The lower surface of the piston is parallel to the bottom surface of the container. The exterior of the container is a vacuum, and the interior contains a diatomic ideal gas with the mass of a single molecule being $m$ and the total number of molecules $N$. The temperature of the gas throughout the container is uniform at $T_{0}$. \n\nSlowly sprinkle a total mass of powder $(p_{1}-p_{0})S/g$ onto the piston. Neglect all friction, and consider the effect of gravity on the distribution of gas molecules. Find the final temperature of the gas inside the container, $T_{1}$.", "solutions": "In equilibrium in a gravitational field, the molecular number density at temperature $T$ follows the Boltzmann distribution:\n\n$$\nn(z) = n_{0} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g z}{k T}\\right)\n$$\n\nIn the formula, $n_{0}$ is the molecular number density at $z=0$ (the bottom of the container), which is an unknown to be determined; $k$ is the Boltzmann constant. The total number of molecules in the container remains constant, always equal to $N$:\n\n$$\nN = \\int_{0}^{H} S n(z) \\operatorname{d}z = S n_{0} \\int_{0}^{H} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g z}{k T}\\right) \\operatorname{d}z = \\frac{S n_{0} k T}{m g} \\left[1 - \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g H}{k T}\\right)\\right]\n$$\n\nSince the system is adiabatic and the powder is spread slowly, it can be assumed that the gas inside the container undergoes a quasi-static adiabatic process. At any moment during the process, let the temperature of the gas inside the container be $T$, the pressure at the lower surface of the piston inside the container be $p$, and the height from the lower surface of the piston to the bottom of the container be $H$. According to the first law of thermodynamics, for the gas inside the container, we have\n\n$$\n-p S \\mathrm{d}H = \\frac{5}{2}N k \\mathrm{d}T + \\mathrm{d}E_{p}\n$$\n\nIn this formula, $\\frac{5}{2}N k \\mathrm{d}T$ represents the increase in internal energy of a diatomic ideal gas, and $\\mathrm{d}E_{p}$ is the increase in gravitational potential energy of the gas in the container. Taking $z=0$ as the zero point of gravitational potential energy, we have\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{l}{E_{p} = \\int_{0}^{H} m g z S n(z) \\mathrm{d}z = m g S n_{0} \\int_{0}^{H} z \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g z}{k T}\\right) \\mathrm{d}z } \\\\ { = -k T S H n_{0} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g H}{k T}\\right) + k T S n_{0} \\cdot \\frac{k T}{m g} - k T S n_{0} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g H}{k T}\\right) \\cdot \\frac{k T}{m g}} \\end{array}\n$$\n\nAt the lower surface of the piston, according to the ideal gas pressure formula, we have\n\n$$\np = n(H) \\cdot k T = n_{0} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{m g H}{k T}\\right) k T\n$$\n\nSubstituting into equation $\\textcircled{4}$ gives\n\n$$\nE_{p} = -p S H + (p S + N m g) \\frac{k T}{m g} - p S \\frac{k T}{m g} = -p S H + N k T\n$$\n\nHere, $p + \\frac{N m g}{S} = n_{0} k T$ is the pressure at the bottom of the container. Taking the differential of the above equation gives $\\mathrm{d}E_{p} = -p S \\mathrm{d}H - S H \\mathrm{d}p + N k \\mathrm{d}T$, substituting into equation $\\textcircled{3}$ gives\n\n$$\nS H \\mathrm{d}p = \\frac{7}{2} N k \\mathrm{d}T\n$$\n\nCombining equations $\\textcircled{2}$ and $\\textcircled{5}$ gives\n\n$$\nH = \\frac{k T}{m g} \\ln\\frac{p S + N m g}{p S}\n$$\n\nSubstituting into equation $\\textcircled{7}$ gives\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{c}{{\\displaystyle{\\frac{S}{m g}}\\ln\\frac{p S + N m g}{p S} \\mathrm{d}p = \\frac{7}{2} N \\frac{\\mathrm{d}T}{T}}} \\\\ {\\mathrm{}} \\\\ {\\displaystyle{\\ln(p S + N m g) \\mathrm{d}(p S) - \\ln(p S) \\mathrm{d}(p S) = \\frac{7}{2} N m g \\frac{\\mathrm{d}T}{T}}} \\end{array}\n$$\n\nAccording to piston equilibrium, initial state $T = T_{0}$, $p = p_{0}$, final state $T = T_{1}$, $p = p_{1}$, integrating the above equation gives\n\n$$\n\\frac{p_{1} S}{N m g} \\ln\\left(1 + \\frac{N m g}{p_{1} S}\\right) - \\frac{p_{0} S}{N m g} \\ln\\left(1 + \\frac{N m g}{p_{0} S}\\right) + \\ln\\frac{p_{1} S + N m g}{p_{0} S + N m g} = \\frac{7}{2} \\ln\\frac{T_{1}}{T_{0}}\n$$\n\nTherefore, the temperature we seek is\n\n$$\nT_{1} = T_{0} \\frac{\\left(1 + \\frac{N m g}{p_{1} S}\\right)^{\\frac{2 p_{1} S}{7 N m g}}}{\\left(1 + \\frac{N m g}{p_{0} S}\\right)^{\\frac{2 p_{0} S}{7 N m g}}} \\left(\\frac{p_{1} S + N m g}{p_{0} S + N m g}\\right)^{\\frac{2}{7}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nT_0 \\frac{\\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_1 S}\\right)^{\\frac{2p_1 S}{7Nmg}}}{\\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_0 S}\\right)^{\\frac{2p_0 S}{7Nmg}}} \\left(\\frac{p_1 S+Nmg}{p_0 S+Nmg}\\right)^{\\frac{2}{7}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThe problem describes the quasi-static, adiabatic compression of a diatomic ideal gas within a thermally insulated cylinder. The compression is caused by slowly adding powder to a thermally insulated piston. A key aspect of this problem is that the effect of gravity on the gas molecules is considered, which results in a non-uniform density and pressure distribution along the height of the cylinder.\n\nThe given parameters are:\n*   `S`: The cross-sectional area of the cylindrical container.\n*   `p_0`: A parameter with units of pressure, related to the initial mass of the piston, `m_{p,0} = p_0 S / g`.\n*   `p_1`: A parameter with units of pressure, related to the final mass of the piston plus powder, `m_{p,1} = p_1 S / g`.\n*   `g`: The acceleration due to gravity.\n*   `m`: The mass of a single gas molecule.\n*   `N`: The total number of molecules of the gas.\n*   `T_0`: The initial uniform temperature of the gas.\n\nWe make the following assumptions based on the problem description:\n*   The gas is an ideal diatomic gas.\n*   The process is quasi-static (slow) and adiabatic (thermally insulated).\n*   The exterior of the container is a vacuum.\n*   All friction is negligible.\n\nWe define the following variables to describe the state of the system:\n*   `z`: The vertical coordinate, with `z=0` at the bottom of the container.\n*   `H`: The height of the piston from the bottom of the container.\n*   `T`: The uniform temperature of the gas at any instant.\n*   `n(z)`: The number density of gas molecules at height `z`.\n*   `p(z)`: The pressure of the gas at height `z`.\n*   `p`: The pressure exerted by the gas on the piston's lower surface, i.e., `p = p(H)`.\n*   `k`: The Boltzmann constant.\n\nThe goal is to determine the final temperature of the gas, `T_1`, after the compression process is complete.\n\n### Step 1: Equilibrium State and Piston Height\nIn thermal equilibrium at a uniform temperature `T`, the gas molecules are distributed in the gravitational field according to the Boltzmann distribution. We use this, along with the ideal gas law and the mechanical equilibrium of the piston, to relate the piston height `H` to the gas temperature `T` and the pressure `p` at the piston.\n\n\\[\\boxed{n(z) = n(0) \\exp\\left(-\\frac{mgz}{kT}\\right)}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{p(z) = n(z)kT}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{N = \\int_V n(z) dV = \\int_0^H S n(z) dz}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{pS = M_{\\text{total}}g}\\]\n\nHere, `n(0)` is the number density at the bottom of the container (`z=0`), and `M_total` is the total mass of the piston and powder. The pressure at the piston, `p=p(H)`, is determined by the mechanical equilibrium condition.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\np(z) &= n(z)kT = \\left(n(0) e^{-mgz/kT}\\right)kT = p(0) e^{-mgz/kT} \\label{eq:pressure_dist} \\\\\np &= p(H) = p(0) e^{-mgH/kT} \\label{eq:piston_pressure}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe total number of molecules `N` is found by integrating the number density over the cylinder's volume:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nN &= \\int_0^H S n(z) dz = S n(0) \\int_0^H e^{-mgz/kT} dz \\\\\n&= S n(0) \\left[-\\frac{kT}{mg} e^{-mgz/kT}\\right]_0^H \\\\\n&= S n(0) \\frac{kT}{mg} \\left(1 - e^{-mgH/kT}\\right) \\label{eq:total_molecules}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFrom eq. \\eqref{eq:total_molecules}, we have `Nmg = S n(0) kT (1 - e^{-mgH/kT})`. Using `p(0) = n(0) kT` and `p = p(H)` from eq. \\eqref{eq:piston_pressure}, we find `Nmg = S(p(0) - p)`. This gives `p(0) = p + Nmg/S`. Substituting this into eq. \\eqref{eq:piston_pressure}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\np &= \\left(p + \\frac{Nmg}{S}\\right) e^{-mgH/kT} \\\\\n\\frac{pS}{pS + Nmg} &= e^{-mgH/kT} \\\\\n\\ln\\left(\\frac{pS + Nmg}{pS}\\right) &= \\frac{mgH}{kT} \\\\\nH &= \\frac{kT}{mg} \\ln\\left(1 + \\frac{Nmg}{pS}\\right) \\label{eq:height}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis equation relates the state variables `H`, `T`, and `p`.\n\n### Step 2: The First Law of Thermodynamics\nThe process is quasi-static and adiabatic. The first law of thermodynamics states that the change in the total internal energy of the gas, `dU`, equals the work done on the gas, `dW`, as the heat exchange `dQ` is zero. The total internal energy `U` is the sum of the total kinetic energy `E_k` and the total gravitational potential energy `E_p` of the gas molecules.\n\n\\[\\boxed{dU = dQ + dW}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{U = E_k + E_p}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{E_k = \\frac{5}{2}NkT}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{dW = -p dV = -pS dH}\\]\n\nFor an adiabatic process, `dQ=0`. For a diatomic ideal gas, the total kinetic energy is `E_k = (5/2)NkT`. The work done on the gas by the piston is `dW = -pS dH`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ndU &= dE_k + dE_p \\label{eq:dU} \\\\\ndE_k &= \\frac{5}{2}Nk dT \\label{eq:dEk} \\\\\ndU &= 0 + dW = -pS dH \\label{eq:first_law_applied}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nCombining these equations gives the differential form of the energy conservation for this process:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{5}{2}Nk dT + dE_p = -pS dH \\label{eq:first_law_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Gravitational Potential Energy of the Gas\nTo proceed with the first law, we need an expression for the change in the total potential energy of the gas, `dE_p`. We first calculate `E_p` by integrating the potential energy of molecules over the volume.\n\n\\[\\boxed{E_p = \\int_V (mgz) n(z) dV}\\]\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nE_p &= \\int_0^H (mgz) S n(z) dz = mgS n(0) \\int_0^H z e^{-mgz/kT} dz \\label{eq:Ep_integral}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nUsing integration by parts (`∫ u dv = uv - ∫ v du`) with `u=z` and `dv = e^{-az}dz` where `a=mg/kT`, the integral evaluates to:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^H z e^{-az} dz = \\frac{1}{a^2}(1 - e^{-aH}) - \\frac{H}{a}e^{-aH} \\label{eq:integral_result}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting this result and `a=mg/kT` back into the expression for `E_p`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nE_p &= mgS n(0) \\left[ \\left(\\frac{kT}{mg}\\right)^2 (1 - e^{-mgH/kT}) - H\\frac{kT}{mg}e^{-mgH/kT} \\right] \\\\\n&= S n(0) kT \\frac{kT}{mg} (1 - e^{-mgH/kT}) - S H n(0) kT e^{-mgH/kT} \\label{eq:Ep_sub1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nUsing `N = S n(0) \\frac{kT}{mg} (1 - e^{-mgH/kT})` from eq. \\eqref{eq:total_molecules} and `p = p(H) = p(0) e^{-mgH/kT} = n(0)kT e^{-mgH/kT}`, we simplify `E_p`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nE_p &= NkT - pSH \\label{eq:Ep_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow we find the differential `dE_p` by differentiating this expression, treating `T`, `p`, and `H` as variables:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ndE_p = d(NkT - pSH) = Nk dT - d(pSH) = Nk dT - (pS dH + SH dp) \\label{eq:dEp}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Deriving the Differential Equation for the Process\nWe now substitute the expression for `dE_p` from eq. \\eqref{eq:dEp} into the first law equation, eq. \\eqref{eq:first_law_final}.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{5}{2}Nk dT + (Nk dT - pS dH - SH dp) &= -pS dH \\\\\n\\frac{7}{2}Nk dT - pS dH - SH dp &= -pS dH \\\\\n\\frac{7}{2}Nk dT - SH dp &= 0 \\label{eq:diff_eq_simple}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis gives a simple relation between the differentials. We now use the expression for `H` from eq. \\eqref{eq:height} to obtain a differential equation relating the state variables `p` and `T`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{7}{2}Nk dT &= SH dp \\\\\n\\frac{7}{2}Nk dT &= S \\left(\\frac{kT}{mg} \\ln\\left(1 + \\frac{Nmg}{pS}\\right)\\right) dp \\\\\n\\frac{7}{2}Nmg \\frac{dT}{T} &= S \\ln\\left(\\frac{pS + Nmg}{pS}\\right) dp \\label{eq:diff_eq_almost_sep}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo prepare for integration, we can express this in terms of the variable `x = pS`, for which `dx = S dp`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{7}{2}Nmg \\frac{dT}{T} &= \\left[\\ln(pS+Nmg) - \\ln(pS)\\right] S dp \\\\\n\\frac{7}{2}Nmg \\frac{dT}{T} &= \\left[\\ln(x+Nmg) - \\ln(x)\\right] dx \\label{eq:diff_eq_to_integrate}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Integration and Final Result\nWe integrate the differential equation, eq. \\eqref{eq:diff_eq_to_integrate}, between the initial and final states of the process.\n*   Initial state (0): Temperature is `T_0`. The piston mass is `m_{p,0} = p_0 S/g`. Mechanical equilibrium `p_{gas}(H_0) S = m_{p,0} g` implies the initial gas pressure at the piston is `p=p_0`. Thus, `x_0 = p_0 S`.\n*   Final state (1): Temperature is `T_1`. The total mass is `m_{p,1} = p_1 S/g`. Mechanical equilibrium `p_{gas}(H_1) S = m_{p,1} g` implies the final gas pressure at the piston is `p=p_1`. Thus, `x_1 = p_1 S`.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\int \\ln(u)du = u\\ln(u) - u}\\]\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_{T_0}^{T_1} \\frac{7}{2}Nmg \\frac{dT}{T} &= \\int_{p_0 S}^{p_1 S} \\left[\\ln(x+Nmg) - \\ln(x)\\right] dx \\label{eq:integration_setup}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe left-hand side (LHS) integrates to:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{LHS} = \\frac{7}{2}Nmg \\ln\\left(\\frac{T_1}{T_0}\\right) \\label{eq:lhs_integrated_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor the right-hand side (RHS), we use the standard integral of the natural logarithm:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int \\left[\\ln(x+Nmg) - \\ln(x)\\right] dx &= \\left[(x+Nmg)\\ln(x+Nmg) - (x+Nmg)\\right] - \\left[x\\ln(x) - x\\right] \\\\\n&= (x+Nmg)\\ln(x+Nmg) - x\\ln(x) - Nmg\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nEvaluating the definite integral for the RHS from `x_0 = p_0 S` to `x_1 = p_1 S`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{RHS} &= \\left[(p_1 S+Nmg)\\ln(p_1 S+Nmg) - p_1 S\\ln(p_1 S) - Nmg\\right] \\\\\n&- \\left[(p_0 S+Nmg)\\ln(p_0 S+Nmg) - p_0 S\\ln(p_0 S) - Nmg\\right] \\\\\n&= (p_1 S+Nmg)\\ln(p_1 S+Nmg) - p_1 S\\ln(p_1 S) - (p_0 S+Nmg)\\ln(p_0 S+Nmg) + p_0 S\\ln(p_0 S) \\label{eq:rhs_integrated}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nEquating LHS and RHS and dividing by `Nmg`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{7}{2}\\ln\\left(\\frac{T_1}{T_0}\\right) &= \\frac{1}{Nmg} \\left[ (p_1 S+Nmg)\\ln(p_1 S+Nmg) - p_1 S\\ln(p_1 S) \\right] \\\\\n&- \\frac{1}{Nmg} \\left[ (p_0 S+Nmg)\\ln(p_0 S+Nmg) - p_0 S\\ln(p_0 S) \\right] \\\\\n&= \\left[ \\left(\\frac{p_1 S}{Nmg}+1\\right)\\ln(p_1 S+Nmg) - \\frac{p_1 S}{Nmg}\\ln(p_1 S) \\right] \\\\\n&- \\left[ \\left(\\frac{p_0 S}{Nmg}+1\\right)\\ln(p_0 S+Nmg) - \\frac{p_0 S}{Nmg}\\ln(p_0 S) \\right] \\\\\n&= \\left[ \\frac{p_1 S}{Nmg}\\ln\\left(\\frac{p_1 S+Nmg}{p_1 S}\\right) + \\ln(p_1 S+Nmg) \\right] \\\\\n&- \\left[ \\frac{p_0 S}{Nmg}\\ln\\left(\\frac{p_0 S+Nmg}{p_0 S}\\right) + \\ln(p_0 S+Nmg) \\right] \\\\\n&= \\frac{p_1 S}{Nmg}\\ln\\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_1 S}\\right) - \\frac{p_0 S}{Nmg}\\ln\\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_0 S}\\right) + \\ln\\left(\\frac{p_1 S+Nmg}{p_0 S+Nmg}\\right) \\label{eq:log_equation}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSolving for `T_1/T_0` by multiplying by `2/7` and exponentiating:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{T_1}{T_0} &= \\exp\\left\\{\\frac{2}{7}\\left[ \\frac{p_1 S}{Nmg}\\ln\\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_1 S}\\right) - \\frac{p_0 S}{Nmg}\\ln\\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_0 S}\\right) + \\ln\\left(\\frac{p_1 S+Nmg}{p_0 S+Nmg}\\right) \\right]\\right\\} \\\\\n&= \\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_1 S}\\right)^{\\frac{2p_1 S}{7Nmg}} \\left(1+\\frac{Nmg}{p_0 S}\\right)^{-\\frac{2p_0 S}{7Nmg}} \\left(\\frac{p_1 S+Nmg}{p_0 S+Nmg}\\right)^{\\frac{2}{7}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe final temperature of the gas inside the container, $T_{1}$, is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{T_{1} = T_{0} \\frac{\\left(1 + \\frac{N m g}{p_{1} S}\\right)^{\\frac{2 p_{1} S}{7 N m g}}}{\\left(1 + \\frac{N m g}{p_{0} S}\\right)^{\\frac{2 p_{0} S}{7 N m g}}} \\left(\\frac{p_{1} S + N m g}{p_{0} S + N m g}\\right)^{\\frac{2}{7}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MODERN/221", "tag": "MODERN", "questions": "A three-dimensional relativistic oscillator moves in a space filled with uniform \"dust.\" During motion, \"dust\" continuously adheres to the oscillator, which is assumed to increase the rest mass of the sphere without altering its size. The collision is adiabatic, and the \"dust\" quickly replenishes the region the sphere just passed. The original length of the spring is vanishing, and the potential energy $V$ can be expressed as $V=\\frac{1}{2}k x^2$, where $k$ is a known constant. The cross-sectional area of the sphere is $A$, the density of the \"dust\" is $\\rho$, the initial rest mass of the sphere is $m_{0}$, and the speed of light in vacuum is $c$. Initially, the sphere performs uniform circular motion with a radius $R_{0}$. Find the time $t$ required when the circular motion radius changes to $R$. Assume $R^2 \\gg A$ and $m_{0} \\gg \\rho A R$.", "solutions": "From the problem statement, it can be assumed that the sphere is constantly maintaining uniform circular motion  \n\n$$\nv=\\omega r\n$$  \n\n$$\n\\omega={\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{\\gamma m}}}\n$$  \n\nAlso, angular momentum conservation  \n\n$$\n\\gamma m v r=c o n s t\n$$  \n\nWhere $\\gamma = \\begin{array}{r}{\\gamma=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}}}}\\end{array}$  \n\n$$\n\\gamma m r^{4}=c o n s t=B\n$$  \n\nNext, solve for the initial $B$. From  \n\n$$\n{\\frac{1}{\\gamma^{2}}}=1-{\\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}}=1-{\\frac{k r^{2}}{\\gamma m c^{2}}}\n$$  \n\nSimplify to obtain  \n\n$$\n\\gamma^{2}-{\\frac{k r^{2}}{m c^{2}}}\\gamma-1=0\n$$  \n\nTherefore  \n\n$$\n\\gamma=\\frac{\\frac{k r^{2}}{m c^{2}}+\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{k r^{2}}{m c^{2}}\\right)^{2}+4}}{2}\n$$  \n\nSubstitute initial conditions, we have  \n\n$$\n\\gamma_{0}=\\frac{\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}+\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}\\right)^{2}+4}}{2}\n$$  \n\n$$\nB=\\frac{\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}+\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}\\right)^{2}+4}}{2}m R_{0}^{4}\n$$  \n\nAdiabatic process implies total energy conservation, and mass changes with time  \n\n$$\n{\\frac{d}{d t}}\\gamma m=\\rho A v-{\\frac{k r}{c^{2}}}{\\frac{d r}{d t}}\n$$  \n\nSubstitute angular momentum conservation  \n\n$$\nd(\\frac{B}{r^{4}})=\\rho A\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{B}}r^{3}d t-d(\\frac{k r^{2}}{2c^{2}})\n$$  \n\nResulting in  \n\n$$\n\\Delta(-\\frac{k}{c^{2}r}+\\frac{4B}{7r^{7}})=\\rho A\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{B}}t\n$$  \n\nSimplify to get  \n\n$$\nt=\\frac{1}{\\rho A}\\sqrt{\\frac{B}{k}}(\\frac{k}{c^{2}}(-\\frac{1}{R}+\\frac{1}{R_{0}})+\\frac{4}{7}B(\\frac{1}{R^{7}}-\\frac{1}{R_{0}^{7}}))\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nt=\\frac{1}{\\rho A}\\sqrt{\\frac{\\left(\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}+\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}\\right)^{2}+4}\\right)m R_{0}^{4}}{2k}}\\left(\\frac{k}{c^{2}}\\left(-\\frac{1}{R}+\\frac{1}{R_{0}}\\right)+\\frac{4}{7}\\frac{\\left(\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}+\\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{k R_{0}^{2}}{m_{0}c^{2}}\\right)^{2}+4}\\right)m R_{0}^{4}}{2}\\left(\\frac{1}{R^{7}}-\\frac{1}{R_{0}^{7}}\\right)\\right)\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem describes a three-dimensional relativistic oscillator, modeled as a sphere, moving through a uniform, stationary medium of \"dust\". The sphere's rest mass increases as it accretes dust, which in turn affects its trajectory.\n\n*   **Physical System**: A sphere is attached to an ideal spring with a spring constant `k` and a vanishing natural length. The potential energy of the spring is given by `V = \\frac{1}{2}kx^2`, where `x` is the displacement from the origin. Since the motion is a slow spiral, we can use the radial distance `r` for the displacement, so `V = \\frac{1}{2}kr^2`. The force exerted by the spring is a central force, `\\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}} = -k\\vec{r}`.\n*   **Relativistic Motion**: The sphere's speed is potentially comparable to the speed of light, requiring a relativistic treatment. Its momentum is `\\vec{p} = \\gamma m \\vec{v}` and its energy is `E_{\\text{particle}} = \\gamma m c^2`, where `m` is its rest mass and `\\gamma = (1 - v^2/c^2)^{-1/2}` is the Lorentz factor.\n*   **Mass Accretion**: The sphere moves through a stationary dust cloud of uniform density `\\rho`. As it moves, it sweeps up dust in a perfectly inelastic collision, causing its rest mass `m(t)` to increase over time. The sphere has a constant cross-sectional area `A`. The collision is described as \"adiabatic,\" which we interpret as a perfectly inelastic collision where the total 4-momentum of the oscillator-dust system is conserved at the instant of collision, with no energy radiated away as heat or sound.\n*   **Initial Conditions**: At time `t=0`, the sphere has an initial rest mass `m_0` and is in a uniform circular motion of radius `R_0`.\n*   **Goal**: We need to find the expression for the time `t` it takes for the radius of the motion to change from its initial value `R_0` to a final value `R`.\n*   **Variables**:\n    *   `m(t)`: The rest mass of the sphere at time `t`.\n    *   `m_0`: The initial rest mass of the sphere at `t=0`.\n    *   `k`: The spring constant.\n    *   `r(t)`: The radius of the path at time `t`.\n    *   `R_0`, `R`: The initial and final radii of the motion.\n    *   `v(t)`: The speed of the sphere at time `t`.\n    *   `\\rho`: The density of the dust.\n    *   `A`: The cross-sectional area of the sphere.\n    *   `c`: The speed of light in a vacuum.\n    *   `t`: The time elapsed.\n*   **Assumptions**:\n    1.  `R^2 \\gg A`: The radius of motion is much larger than the physical size of the sphere, allowing us to treat it as a point mass for trajectory calculations.\n    2.  `m_0 \\gg \\rho A R`: The initial mass of the sphere is much larger than the mass of dust accreted in a typical revolution. This implies that the properties of the motion, such as mass and radius, change very slowly. This justifies treating the motion as a \"quasi-circular orbit\" or a \"slow spiral,\" where the radial velocity `v_r = dr/dt` is much smaller than the tangential velocity `v_\\theta`, and the radial component of momentum change `dp_r/dt` can be neglected.\n\n### Step 1: Conservation of Angular Momentum\nThe equation of motion for a relativistic particle with variable rest mass `m` accreting mass that is initially at rest is given by the relativistic form of Newton's second law. The only external force is the central spring force `\\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}} = -k\\vec{r}`.\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{d\\vec{p}}{dt} = \\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}}}\\]\nThe time evolution of the angular momentum `\\vec{L} = \\vec{r} \\times \\vec{p}` is determined by the net external torque `\\vec{\\tau}_{\\text{ext}}`.\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{d\\vec{L}}{dt} = \\vec{\\tau}_{\\text{ext}} = \\vec{r} \\times \\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}}}\\]\n**Derivation**\nThe external torque on the sphere is calculated as follows:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\vec{\\tau}_{\\text{ext}} &= \\vec{r} \\times (-k\\vec{r}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -k (\\vec{r} \\times \\vec{r}) = 0 \\label{eq:torque_zero}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSince the torque is zero, the angular momentum vector `\\vec{L}` is a constant of motion. This confines the motion to a plane perpendicular to the constant vector `\\vec{L}`. We can therefore analyze the motion in terms of its constant magnitude, `L = |\\vec{L}| = L_0`.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nL = |\\vec{r} \\times \\vec{p}| = r p_\\theta = r (\\gamma m v_\\theta) = L_0 = \\text{constant} \\label{eq:L_const} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\\]\nHere, `v_\\theta` is the tangential component of the velocity `\\vec{v}`.\n\n### Step 2: Radial Dynamics for Quasi-Circular Motion\nWe analyze the radial component of the relativistic equation of motion. In polar coordinates, the radial component of `d\\vec{p}/dt` is `dp_r/dt - p_\\theta v_\\theta / r`.\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{dp_r}{dt} - \\frac{p_\\theta v_\\theta}{r} = F_r}\\]\nThe assumption `m_0 \\gg \\rho A R` implies that the radius `r` changes very slowly. This means the radial velocity `v_r = dr/dt` is very small compared to the tangential velocity `v_\\theta`, and its time derivative (related to radial acceleration) is negligible. This is the quasi-circular approximation.\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{dp_r}{dt} = \\frac{d(\\gamma m v_r)}{dt} \\approx 0}\\]\n**Derivation**\nFor our system, `p_r = \\gamma m v_r`, `p_\\theta = \\gamma m v_\\theta`, and the radial force is `F_r = -kr`. The radial equation of motion is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d(\\gamma m v_r)}{dt} - \\frac{\\gamma m v_\\theta^2}{r} = -kr\n\\end{align}\\]\nUnder the quasi-circular approximation, the first term is negligible. We also have that the total speed `v = \\sqrt{v_r^2 + v_\\theta^2} \\approx v_\\theta`. The radial equation simplifies to:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n-\\frac{\\gamma m v^2}{r} &\\approx -kr \\nonumber \\\\\nkr^2 &\\approx \\gamma m v^2 \\label{eq:centripetal} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis equation relates the radius, speed, and the product `\\gamma m` at any point in the slow spiral.\n\n### Step 3: Energy Evolution of the System\nThe system's total energy `E_{\\text{system}}` (particle kinetic energy + potential energy) changes due to the accretion of dust. We derive an expression for the rate of change of this energy.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\n1.  The relativistic equation of motion for a particle with variable rest mass `m(t)` accreting stationary mass:\n    \\[\\boxed{\\frac{d\\vec{p}}{dt} = \\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}}}\\]\n2.  The total energy of the oscillator-spring system:\n    \\[\\boxed{E_{\\text{system}} = E_{\\text{particle}} + V = \\gamma m c^2 + \\frac{1}{2}kr^2}\\]\n3.  The relationship between a particle's energy, momentum, and rest mass:\n    \\[\\boxed{E_{\\text{particle}}^2 = (pc)^2 + (mc^2)^2}\\]\n4.  The rate of change of potential energy is related to the external force by:\n    \\[\\boxed{\\frac{dV}{dt} = \\nabla V \\cdot \\frac{d\\vec{r}}{dt} = -\\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}} \\cdot \\vec{v}}\\]\n5.  The rate at which the oscillator sweeps up dust rest mass `dm_{\\text{dust}}` is:\n    \\[\\boxed{\\frac{dm_{\\text{dust}}}{dt} = \\rho A v}\\]\n6.  In a perfectly inelastic collision, the total 4-momentum of the colliding system is conserved. The invariant mass of the system before and after the collision is the same.\n\n**Derivation**\nFirst, we find the rate of change of the particle's energy, `E_{\\text{particle}}`. Differentiating the energy-momentum relation with respect to time:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d}{dt}(E_{\\text{particle}}^2) &= \\frac{d}{dt}((pc)^2 + (mc^2)^2) \\nonumber \\\\\n2E_{\\text{particle}}\\frac{dE_{\\text{particle}}}{dt} &= 2c^2\\left(\\vec{p} \\cdot \\frac{d\\vec{p}}{dt}\\right) + 2m c^4 \\frac{dm}{dt} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{dE_{\\text{particle}}}{dt} &= \\frac{c^2\\vec{p}}{E_{\\text{particle}}} \\cdot \\frac{d\\vec{p}}{dt} + \\frac{mc^4}{E_{\\text{particle}}} \\frac{dm}{dt} \\label{eq:dE_dt_general}\n\\end{align}\\]\nUsing `\\vec{p} = \\gamma m \\vec{v}` and `E_{\\text{particle}} = \\gamma m c^2`, we get `\\frac{c^2\\vec{p}}{E_{\\text{particle}}} = \\vec{v}` and `\\frac{mc^4}{E_{\\text{particle}}} = \\frac{c^2}{\\gamma}`. Substituting these:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dE_{\\text{particle}}}{dt} = \\vec{v} \\cdot \\frac{d\\vec{p}}{dt} + \\frac{c^2}{\\gamma}\\frac{dm}{dt} \\label{eq:dE_particle_dt}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe rate of change of the total system energy `E_{system}` is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dE_{\\text{system}}}{dt} &= \\frac{dE_{\\text{particle}}}{dt} + \\frac{dV}{dt} = \\left(\\vec{v} \\cdot \\frac{d\\vec{p}}{dt} + \\frac{c^2}{\\gamma}\\frac{dm}{dt}\\right) + (-\\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}} \\cdot \\vec{v}) \\label{eq:dE_sys_intermediate}\n\\end{align}\\]\nUsing the equation of motion `d\\vec{p}/dt = \\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}}`, we find:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dE_{\\text{system}}}{dt} &= \\left(\\vec{v} \\cdot \\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}} + \\frac{c^2}{\\gamma}\\frac{dm}{dt}\\right) - (\\vec{F}_{\\text{ext}} \\cdot \\vec{v}) = \\frac{c^2}{\\gamma}\\frac{dm}{dt} \\label{eq:energy_evo_general}\n\\end{align}\\]\nNext, we determine `dm/dt`. The change in the oscillator's rest mass `dm` results from absorbing a dust particle of rest mass `dm_{dust}`. We use conservation of the system's invariant mass. The 4-momentum of the oscillator is `P_{osc} = (\\gamma m c, \\gamma m \\vec{v})` and for the stationary dust is `P_{dust} = (dm_{dust} c, \\vec{0})`. The invariant mass `M_{sys}` of the combined system is given by `(M_{sys}c)^2 = (P_{osc} + P_{dust})^2`. After the collision, the new particle has rest mass `m' = m+dm`, so `M_{sys} = m'`.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n(m+dm)^2 c^2 &= (P_{osc} + P_{dust}) \\cdot (P_{osc} + P_{dust}) = P_{osc}^2 + P_{dust}^2 + 2 P_{osc} \\cdot P_{dust} \\nonumber \\\\\n(m+dm)^2 c^2 &= (mc)^2 + (dm_{dust}c)^2 + 2(\\gamma m c)(dm_{dust}c) \\nonumber \\\\\nm^2+2m\\,dm + (dm)^2 &= m^2 + (dm_{dust})^2 + 2\\gamma m\\,dm_{dust} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\end{align}\\]\nIgnoring infinitesimal terms of second order (`(dm)^2`, `(dm_{dust})^2`):\n\\[\\begin{align}\n2m\\,dm &\\approx 2\\gamma m\\,dm_{dust} \\nonumber \\\\\ndm &= \\gamma\\,dm_{dust} \\label{eq:mass_increase}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe rate of change of rest mass is thus `dm/dt = \\gamma (dm_{dust}/dt) = \\gamma \\rho A v`. Substituting this into Eq. \\eqref{eq:energy_evo_general}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dE_{\\text{system}}}{dt} &= \\frac{c^2}{\\gamma} (\\gamma \\rho A v) = \\rho A v c^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{d}{dt} \\left( \\gamma m c^2 + \\frac{1}{2}kr^2 \\right) &= \\rho A v c^2 \\label{eq:energy_evo_final} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 4: Deriving the Differential Equation for the Radius\nWe now combine the conserved angular momentum `L_0` and the dynamical equations to find a differential equation for the radius `r`.\n\\[\\boxed{L_0 = r(\\gamma m v) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad kr^2 = \\gamma m v^2}\\]\n**Derivation**\nFrom the two equations above (using Eq. \\eqref{eq:L_const} with `v_\\theta \\approx v` and Eq. \\eqref{eq:centripetal}), we can express `v` and `\\gamma m` in terms of `r` and constants.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nL_0 &= r(\\gamma m v) \\label{eq:L_def_re} \\\\\nkr^2 &= (\\gamma m) v^2 \\label{eq:kr2_gammamv_re}\n\\end{align}\\]\nFrom Eq. \\eqref{eq:kr2_gammamv_re}, we express `\\gamma m` as `kr^2/v^2`. Substituting this into Eq. \\eqref{eq:L_def_re}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nL_0 = r \\left(\\frac{kr^2}{v^2}\\right) v = \\frac{kr^3}{v} \\implies v = \\frac{kr^3}{L_0} \\label{eq:v_of_r} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\\]\nNow we express the product `\\gamma m` in terms of `r` using Eq. \\eqref{eq:L_def_re} and Eq. \\eqref{eq:v_of_r}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\gamma m = \\frac{L_0}{rv} = \\frac{L_0}{r(kr^3/L_0)} = \\frac{L_0^2}{kr^4} \\label{eq:gammam_of_r} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSubstitute these expressions for `v` and `\\gamma m` into the energy evolution equation (Eq. \\eqref{eq:energy_evo_final}):\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d}{dt} \\left( \\frac{L_0^2}{kr^4} c^2 + \\frac{1}{2}kr^2 \\right) &= \\rho A \\left(\\frac{kr^3}{L_0}\\right) c^2 \\label{eq:pre_diff}\n\\end{align}\\]\nUsing the chain rule on the left side, `\\frac{d}{dt} = \\frac{dr}{dt}\\frac{d}{dr}`:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d}{dr} \\left( \\frac{L_0^2 c^2}{k}r^{-4} + \\frac{k}{2}r^2 \\right) \\frac{dr}{dt} &= \\frac{\\rho A k c^2 r^3}{L_0} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left( \\frac{L_0^2 c^2}{k}(-4r^{-5}) + kr \\right) \\frac{dr}{dt} &= \\frac{\\rho A k c^2 r^3}{L_0} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left( kr - \\frac{4L_0^2 c^2}{kr^5} \\right) \\frac{dr}{dt} &= \\frac{\\rho A k c^2 r^3}{L_0} \\nonumber\n\\end{align}\\]\nIsolating `dt` gives the differential element of time as a function of the change in radius `dr`:\n\\[\\begin{align}\ndt &= \\frac{kr - \\frac{4L_0^2 c^2}{kr^5}}{\\frac{\\rho A k c^2 r^3}{L_0}} dr = \\frac{L_0}{\\rho A k c^2 r^3} \\left( kr - \\frac{4L_0^2 c^2}{kr^5} \\right) dr \\nonumber \\\\\ndt &= \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\left( \\frac{L_0}{c^2 r^2} - \\frac{4L_0^3}{k^2 r^8} \\right) dr \\label{eq:dt_dr} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 5: Integration to Find the Elapsed Time\nTo find the total time `t` for the radius to change from `R_0` to `R`, we integrate Eq. \\eqref{eq:dt_dr}. First, we determine the sign of `dr`.\n\\[\\boxed{t = \\int_0^t dt' = \\int_{R_0}^R \\left[ \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\left( \\frac{L_0}{c^2 r^2} - \\frac{4L_0^3}{k^2 r^8} \\right) \\right] dr}\\]\n**Derivation**\nThe differential time `dt` must be positive. Let's analyze the sign of the right-hand side of Eq. \\eqref{eq:dt_dr}. The term in the parenthesis can be rewritten as:\n\\[ \\frac{L_0}{c^2 r^2} - \\frac{4L_0^3}{k^2 r^8} = \\frac{L_0}{c^2 r^2} \\left( 1 - \\frac{4L_0^2 c^2}{k^2 r^6} \\right) \\]\nUsing `v = kr^3/L_0` from Eq. \\eqref{eq:v_of_r}, we have `L_0^2 = k^2 r^6 / v^2`. Substituting this into the parenthesis gives:\n\\[ 1 - \\frac{4(k^2 r^6 / v^2) c^2}{k^2 r^6} = 1 - \\frac{4c^2}{v^2} \\]\nSince the particle is relativistic and has mass, its speed `v` must be less than the speed of light `c`. Thus, `v^2 < c^2`, which implies `c^2/v^2 > 1`, and `4c^2/v^2 > 4`. Therefore, the term `(1 - 4c^2/v^2)` is negative.\nThe entire coefficient of `dr` in Eq. \\eqref{eq:dt_dr} is negative. Since `dt` must be positive, `dr` must be negative (`dt = (\\text{negative}) \\times dr \\implies dr < 0`). This means the radius of the motion decreases over time. The integration will be from the initial radius `R_0` to a smaller final radius `R`.\n\nPerforming the integration:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nt &= \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\int_{R_0}^R \\left( \\frac{L_0}{c^2} r^{-2} - \\frac{4L_0^3}{k^2} r^{-8} \\right) dr \\nonumber \\\\\nt &= \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\left[ \\frac{L_0}{c^2} \\frac{r^{-1}}{-1} - \\frac{4L_0^3}{k^2} \\frac{r^{-7}}{-7} \\right]_{R_0}^R \\nonumber \\\\\nt &= \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\left[ -\\frac{L_0}{c^2 r} + \\frac{4L_0^3}{7k^2 r^7} \\right]_{R_0}^R \\nonumber \\\\\nt &= \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\left[ \\left(-\\frac{L_0}{c^2 R} + \\frac{4L_0^3}{7k^2 R^7}\\right) - \\left(-\\frac{L_0}{c^2 R_0} + \\frac{4L_0^3}{7k^2 R_0^7}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\nt &= \\frac{1}{\\rho A} \\left[ \\frac{L_0}{c^2}\\left(\\frac{1}{R_0} - \\frac{1}{R}\\right) + \\frac{4L_0^3}{7k^2}\\left(\\frac{1}{R^7} - \\frac{1}{R_0^7}\\right) \\right] \\label{eq:time_integrated}\n\\end{align}\\]\nFactoring out `L_0` and rearranging terms gives the final expression for the time `t`:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nt = \\frac{L_0}{\\rho A} \\left[ \\frac{4L_0^2}{7k^2} \\left(\\frac{1}{R^7} - \\frac{1}{R_0^7}\\right) - \\frac{1}{c^2} \\left(\\frac{1}{R} - \\frac{1}{R_0}\\right) \\right] \\label{eq:time_final} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 6: Determining the Constant of Motion `L_0`\nThe constant `L_0` is determined by the initial conditions at `t=0`, where `r=R_0`, `m=m_0`, and the speed is `v_0`. The Lorentz factor is `\\gamma_0 = (1-v_0^2/c^2)^{-1/2}`.\n\\[\\boxed{L_0 = R_0 \\gamma_0 m_0 v_0}\\]\nFrom the radial dynamics equation, Eq. \\eqref{eq:centripetal}, applied at `t=0`: `kR_0^2 = \\gamma_0 m_0 v_0^2`. We can find an expression for `L_0^2`:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nL_0^2 &= (R_0 \\gamma_0 m_0 v_0)^2 = R_0^2 (\\gamma_0 m_0)^2 v_0^2 = R_0^2 (\\gamma_0 m_0) (\\gamma_0 m_0 v_0^2) \\nonumber \\\\\nL_0^2 &= R_0^2 (\\gamma_0 m_0) (kR_0^2) = \\gamma_0 m_0 k R_0^4 \\label{eq:L0_squared} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo find `\\gamma_0`, we eliminate `v_0` using the definition of the Lorentz factor and the centripetal force equation.\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{1}{\\gamma^2} = 1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}}\\]\n**Derivation**\nSubstituting `v^2 = kr^2/(\\gamma m)` from Eq. \\eqref{eq:centripetal}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{1}{\\gamma^2} &= 1 - \\frac{kr^2}{\\gamma m c^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n1 &= \\gamma^2 - \\frac{kr^2}{mc^2}\\gamma \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma^2 - \\left(\\frac{kr^2}{mc^2}\\right)\\gamma - 1 &= 0 \\label{eq:gamma_quad}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis is a quadratic equation for `\\gamma`. We solve it for the initial conditions (`r=R_0, m=m_0`) to find `\\gamma_0`. Since `\\gamma_0 \\ge 1`, we must take the positive root of the quadratic formula:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\gamma_0 &= \\frac{ \\left(\\frac{kR_0^2}{m_0c^2}\\right) + \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{kR_0^2}{m_0c^2}\\right)^2 - 4(1)(-1)} }{2(1)} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma_0 &= \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{kR_0^2}{m_0c^2} + \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{kR_0^2}{m_0c^2}\\right)^2 + 4} \\right) \\label{eq:gamma0} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe constant of motion `L_0` is now fully determined by the initial parameters of the problem via Eq. \\eqref{eq:L0_squared} and Eq. \\eqref{eq:gamma0}.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe time `t` required for the circular motion radius to change from `R_0` to `R` (where `R < R_0`) is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{t = \\frac{L_0}{\\rho A} \\left[ \\frac{4L_0^2}{7k^2} \\left(\\frac{1}{R^7} - \\frac{1}{R_0^7}\\right) - \\frac{1}{c^2} \\left(\\frac{1}{R} - \\frac{1}{R_0}\\right) \\right]}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nwhere the constant of motion `L_0` is determined by the initial conditions via `L_0^2 = \\gamma_0 m_0 k R_0^4`, and the initial Lorentz factor `\\gamma_0` is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\gamma_0 = \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{kR_0^2}{m_0c^2} + \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{kR_0^2}{m_0c^2}\\right)^2 + 4} \\right)}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/120", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "Consider an ideal gas with a known fixed constant $\\gamma$ undergoing a rectangular cycle on a $p-V$ diagram, which consists of two isochoric processes and two isobaric processes forming a positive cycle. It is known that the area of this cycle is fixed as $W$ (where $W$ is sufficiently small, negating the possibility of negative pressure or volume). The rectangle must contain the point $(p_0,V_0)$. Find the maximum efficiency of this cycle.", "solutions": "If the center shifts to $\\mathcal{p}^{\\prime}, V^{\\prime}$, then the heat absorbed is:  \n\n$$\nQ={\\frac{W}{2}}+{\\frac{\\Delta p V^{\\prime}+\\gamma p^{\\prime}\\Delta V}{\\gamma-1}}\n$$\n\nLet us first consider the translation of a fixed rectangular shape with ${\\Delta p,\\Delta V=W/\\Delta p}$ in the $\\mathcal{P}V$ diagram. Clearly, minimizing the heat absorbed requires minimizing the values of the center's $p,V$.Thus, it becomes optimal only when the rectangle is translated so that the $(p_0, V_0)$ point is at the upper-right corner of the rectangle:  \n\n$$\np^{\\prime}=p_0-{\\frac{\\Delta p}{2}}\\quad,\\quad V^{\\prime}=V_0-{\\frac{\\Delta V}{2}}\n$$\n\nSubstituting back, the heat absorbed becomes:  \n\n$$\nQ={\\frac{\\Delta p V+\\gamma p\\Delta V}{\\gamma-1}}-{\\frac{W}{\\gamma-1}}\n$$\n\nFrom the same inequality, the maximum efficiency is:  \n\n$$\n\\eta=\\frac{\\gamma-1}{2\\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0/W}-1}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\eta=\\frac{\\gamma-1}{2\\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0/W}-1}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the maximum efficiency, $\\eta_{max}$, of a heat engine. The working substance is an ideal gas with a fixed adiabatic index $\\gamma = C_p/C_V$. The engine operates on a rectangular thermodynamic cycle on a pressure-volume ($p-V$) diagram.\n\nThe cycle consists of four processes connecting four states. Let the pressures be $p_1$ and $p_2$ and the volumes be $V_1$ and $V_2$, with $p_1 < p_2$ and $V_1 < V_2$. The four corner states of the rectangular cycle are:\n-   State A: $(V_1, p_1)$\n-   State B: $(V_1, p_2)$\n-   State C: $(V_2, p_2)$\n-   State D: $(V_2, p_1)$\n\nThe cycle is positive (clockwise), meaning net work is done by the gas. The processes are:\n1.  A $\\to$ B: Isochoric heating (constant volume $V_1$).\n2.  B $\\to$ C: Isobaric expansion (constant pressure $p_2$).\n3.  C $\\to$ D: Isochoric cooling (constant volume $V_2$).\n4.  D $\\to$ A: Isobaric compression (constant pressure $p_1$).\n\nThe following constraints are given:\n1.  **Net Work**: The net work done per cycle, $W$, is the area of the rectangle on the $p-V$ diagram. It is a fixed positive value. We define $\\Delta p = p_2 - p_1$ and $\\Delta V = V_2 - V_1$. Then, $W = \\Delta p \\Delta V$.\n2.  **Containment Constraint**: The rectangular cycle must contain a specific point $(p_0, V_0)$. This implies the following inequalities must hold: $p_1 \\le p_0 \\le p_2$ and $V_1 \\le V_0 \\le V_2$.\n3.  **Physicality Assumption**: The work $W$ is stated to be \"sufficiently small\". This ensures that for the optimal cycle, the pressure and volume remain positive, i.e., $p_1 > 0$ and $V_1 > 0$.\n\nThe goal is to find the maximum possible efficiency, $\\eta_{max}$, by choosing the optimal cycle parameters ($p_1, p_2, V_1, V_2$) that satisfy these constraints.\n\n### Step 1: General Expression for Cycle Efficiency\nThe efficiency of any heat engine is defined as the ratio of the net work done by the engine, $W_{net}$, to the total heat absorbed from the hot reservoir, $Q_{in}$.\n\\[\\boxed{\\eta = \\frac{W_{net}}{Q_{in}}}\\]\n**Derivation:**\nFor this cycle, the net work done is the area of the rectangle, which is given as a fixed value $W$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nW_{net} = W\n\\label{eq:work} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo maximize the efficiency $\\eta$ for a fixed work output $W$, we must minimize the total heat absorbed, $Q_{in}$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\eta = \\frac{W}{Q_{in}} \\implies \\eta_{max} = \\frac{W}{Q_{in, min}}\n\\label{eq:eta_max_general} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Calculating the Heat Absorbed ($Q_{in}$)\nHeat is absorbed by the ideal gas when its temperature increases. According to the ideal gas law, $T \\propto pV$. Temperature increases during the isochoric heating process (A $\\to$ B, where pressure increases at constant volume) and the isobaric expansion process (B $\\to$ C, where volume increases at constant pressure).\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe heat transfer and internal energy change are governed by the following principles for an ideal gas:\n\\[\\boxed{Q = \\Delta U + W_{by} \\quad (\\text{First Law of Thermodynamics})}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\Delta U = n C_V \\Delta T \\quad (\\text{Internal energy of an ideal gas})}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{pV = nRT \\quad (\\text{Ideal Gas Law})}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{C_p - C_V = R \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\gamma = C_p/C_V \\quad (\\text{Properties of an ideal gas})}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{W_{by} = \\int p \\, dV \\quad (\\text{Work done by the gas})}\\]\n**Derivation:**\nFirst, we derive a more convenient expression for the change in internal energy. From the ideal gas relations, we find $C_V = R/(\\gamma-1)$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\Delta U = n C_V \\Delta T = n \\left(\\frac{R}{\\gamma-1}\\right) \\Delta T = \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\Delta(nRT) = \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1}\\Delta(pV)\n\\label{eq:delta_U_pV} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow we calculate the heat absorbed in the two relevant processes:\n\n1.  **Isochoric heating (A $\\to$ B)**: Volume is constant at $V_1$, so $dV=0$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nW_{by, A \\to B} &= 0 \\\\\nQ_1 = Q_{A \\to B} &= \\Delta U_{A \\to B} = \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1}(p_2V_1 - p_1V_1) = \\frac{V_1(p_2-p_1)}{\\gamma-1} = \\frac{V_1 \\Delta p}{\\gamma-1}\n\\label{eq:Q1} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n2.  **Isobaric expansion (B $\\to$ C)**: Pressure is constant at $p_2$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nW_{by, B \\to C} &= \\int_{V_1}^{V_2} p_2 \\, dV = p_2(V_2-V_1) = p_2 \\Delta V \\\\\n\\Delta U_{B \\to C} &= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1}(p_2V_2 - p_2V_1) = \\frac{p_2(V_2-V_1)}{\\gamma-1} = \\frac{p_2 \\Delta V}{\\gamma-1} \\\\\nQ_2 = Q_{B \\to C} &= \\Delta U_{B \\to C} + W_{by, B \\to C} = \\frac{p_2 \\Delta V}{\\gamma-1} + p_2 \\Delta V = \\frac{\\gamma p_2 \\Delta V}{\\gamma-1}\n\\label{eq:Q2} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe total heat absorbed, $Q_{in}$, is the sum of $Q_1$ and $Q_2$, as both are positive (since $p_2>p_1$ and $V_2>V_1$).\n\\[\\begin{align}\nQ_{in} = Q_1 + Q_2 = \\frac{V_1 \\Delta p}{\\gamma-1} + \\frac{\\gamma p_2 \\Delta V}{\\gamma-1} = \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1}(V_1 \\Delta p + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V)\n\\label{eq:Qin_total} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Optimizing the Cycle's Position\nTo minimize $Q_{in}$, we must minimize the function $f(p_1, p_2, V_1, V_2) = V_1 \\Delta p + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V$ subject to the given constraints. We perform this minimization in two sequential steps.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe optimization is subject to the constraints:\n\\[\\boxed{(p_2-p_1)(V_2-V_1) = W}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{p_1 \\le p_0 \\le p_2}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{V_1 \\le V_0 \\le V_2}\\]\n**Derivation:**\n**Part A: Optimizing volume placement for fixed pressures.**\nLet's fix the pressures $p_1$ and $p_2$. This fixes $\\Delta p = p_2-p_1$ and consequently $\\Delta V = W/\\Delta p$. We want to minimize $Q_{in}$, which is proportional to $f(V_1) = V_1 \\Delta p + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V$. Since the second term is constant for fixed pressures, we only need to minimize $V_1 \\Delta p$. As $\\Delta p > 0$, this is equivalent to minimizing $V_1$.\nThe constraints on $V_1$ are $V_1 \\le V_0$ and $V_2 \\ge V_0$. Since $V_2 = V_1 + \\Delta V$, the second constraint becomes $V_1 + \\Delta V \\ge V_0$, which implies $V_1 \\ge V_0 - \\Delta V$.\nThus, the allowed range for $V_1$ is $[V_0 - \\Delta V, V_0]$. The minimum value is $V_1 = V_0 - \\Delta V$. This choice sets $V_2 = V_1 + \\Delta V = V_0$.\nThis means that for any given pressure range, the heat input is minimized when the right side of the rectangle passes through $V_0$.\n\n**Part B: Optimizing pressure placement.**\nBased on Part A, the optimal configuration must have $V_2 = V_0$. Now we optimize the pressure placement. Let's fix the shape of the rectangle, i.e., fix $\\Delta p$ and $\\Delta V$. We want to find the optimal values of $p_1$ and $p_2$. With $V_2=V_0$ and $V_1=V_0-\\Delta V$, the function to minimize is $Q_{in} \\propto V_1 \\Delta p + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V = (V_0-\\Delta V)\\Delta p + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V = V_0\\Delta p - W + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V$.\nLet's consider this as a function of $p_2$: $g(p_2) = (V_0\\Delta p - W) + (\\gamma \\Delta V) p_2$. Since $\\gamma > 0$ and $\\Delta V > 0$, the slope with respect to $p_2$ is positive. Thus, $g(p_2)$ is minimized by choosing the smallest possible value for $p_2$.\nThe constraints on $p_2$ are $p_2 \\ge p_0$ and $p_1 \\le p_0$. The second constraint is $p_2 - \\Delta p \\le p_0$, or $p_2 \\le p_0 + \\Delta p$.\nThe allowed range for $p_2$ is $[p_0, p_0 + \\Delta p]$. The minimum value is $p_2 = p_0$.\n\n**Conclusion:** Combining the results from Part A and B, $Q_{in}$ is minimized when the cycle is positioned such that $(p_0, V_0)$ is the corner with the highest pressure and volume.\n\\[\\begin{align}\np_2 = p_0 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad V_2 = V_0\n\\label{eq:optimal_placement} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Optimizing the Cycle's Shape\nWith the optimal placement fixed by Eq. \\eqref{eq:optimal_placement}, the cycle's four parameters can be expressed in terms of a single variable that defines the shape of the rectangle, for instance, the pressure difference $\\Delta p$.\nThe parameters are:\n$p_2 = p_0$, $V_2 = V_0$\n$\\Delta V = W/\\Delta p$\n$p_1 = p_2 - \\Delta p = p_0 - \\Delta p$\n$V_1 = V_2 - \\Delta V = V_0 - W/\\Delta p$\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nTo find the minimum of a function, we find the point where its first derivative is zero.\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{d f(x)}{dx} = 0 \\quad (\\text{Condition for finding an extremum})}\\]\n**Derivation:**\nWe substitute the optimal placement parameters into the expression for $Q_{in}$ (Eq. \\eqref{eq:Qin_total}) to get $Q_{in}$ as a function of $\\Delta p$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nQ_{in}(\\Delta p) &= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\left[ V_1 \\Delta p + \\gamma p_2 \\Delta V \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\left[ \\left(V_0 - \\frac{W}{\\Delta p}\\right) \\Delta p + \\gamma p_0 \\left(\\frac{W}{\\Delta p}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\left[ V_0 \\Delta p - W + \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{\\Delta p} \\right]\n\\label{eq:Qin_vs_dp} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo find the minimum value of $Q_{in}$, we find the extremum of the term in the brackets with respect to $\\Delta p$. Let $g(\\Delta p) = V_0 \\Delta p - W + \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{\\Delta p}$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d g}{d(\\Delta p)} &= V_0 - \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{(\\Delta p)^2} \\label{eq:derivative} \\tag{9} \\\\\n\\text{Setting } \\frac{d g}{d(\\Delta p)} &= 0 \\implies V_0 = \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{(\\Delta p)^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n(\\Delta p_{opt})^2 &= \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{V_0} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\Delta p_{opt} &= \\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{V_0}}\n\\label{eq:dp_opt} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe second derivative, $\\frac{d^2 g}{d(\\Delta p)^2} = \\frac{2\\gamma p_0 W}{(\\Delta p)^3}$, is positive for $\\Delta p > 0$, confirming this value of $\\Delta p$ minimizes $Q_{in}$. The problem statement's assumption that $W$ is \"sufficiently small\" ensures that $p_1 = p_0 - \\Delta p_{opt} > 0$ and $V_1 = V_0 - W/\\Delta p_{opt} > 0$, which requires $p_0 V_0 > \\gamma W$.\n\n### Step 5: Calculating the Maximum Efficiency\nWe substitute the optimal value $\\Delta p_{opt}$ back into the expression for $Q_{in}$ (Eq. \\eqref{eq:Qin_vs_dp}) to find the minimum possible heat input, $Q_{in, min}$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe maximum efficiency is calculated using the minimized heat input.\n\\[\\boxed{\\eta_{max} = \\frac{W}{Q_{in, min}}}\\]\n**Derivation:**\n\\[\\begin{align}\nQ_{in, min} &= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\left[ V_0 \\Delta p_{opt} - W + \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{\\Delta p_{opt}} \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\left[ V_0 \\left(\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{V_0}}\\right) - W + \\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma p_0 W}{V_0}}} \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\left[ \\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W} - W + \\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W} \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{2\\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W} - W}{\\gamma-1}\n\\label{eq:Qin_min} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFinally, we calculate the maximum efficiency, $\\eta_{max}$, using the fixed work $W$ and this minimum heat input $Q_{in, min}$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\eta_{max} &= \\frac{W}{Q_{in, min}} = \\frac{W}{\\frac{2\\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W} - W}{\\gamma-1}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{(\\gamma-1)W}{2\\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W} - W} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Dividing numerator and denominator by } W: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\eta_{max} &= \\frac{\\gamma-1}{\\frac{2\\sqrt{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W}}{W} - 1} = \\frac{\\gamma-1}{2\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma p_0 V_0 W}{W^2}} - 1} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\gamma-1}{2\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma p_0 V_0}{W}} - 1}\n\\label{eq:eta_max_final} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe maximum efficiency of the cycle is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\eta_{max} = \\frac{\\gamma-1}{2\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma p_0 V_0}{W}} - 1}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MODERN/121", "tag": "MODERN", "questions": "Two spacecraft are traveling in a space medium that is flowing uniformly at a constant velocity $u$ with respect to an inertial frame $S$. The spacecraft are moving through the medium with equal relative velocities $v$ with respect to the medium. Neither of the velocities is known. Ultimately, the velocities of the two spacecraft with respect to the inertial frame $S$ are $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$, and the angle between the directions of these velocities is an acute angle $\\alpha$. These three quantities are given. The speed of light is $c$. Considering relativistic effects, determine the minimum possible value of $u$.", "solutions": "First, let's derive a byproduct of velocity transformation. The velocity transformation is:\n\n$$\n v_{x}^{\\prime}={\\frac{v_{x}-u}{1-u v_{x}/c^{2}}}\n$$\n\n$$\nv_{y,z}^{\\prime}=v_{y,z}\\cdot\\frac{\\sqrt{1-u^{2}/c^{2}}}{1-u v_{x}/c^{2}}\n$$\n\nHence, we can calculate:\n\n$$\n  \\begin{array}{l}{\\gamma=\\cfrac{1}{\\sqrt{1-(v_{x}^{2}+v_{y}^{2}+v_{z}^{2})/c^{2}}}}\\ {=\\cfrac{1}{\\sqrt{1-(v_{x}^{\\prime2}+v_{y}^{\\prime2}+v_{z}^{\\prime2})/c^{2}}}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nObtain the transformation:\n\n$$\n  \\gamma^{\\prime}=\\gamma\\cdot\\frac{1-{u v_{x}}/{c^{2}}}{\\sqrt{1-{u^{2}}/{c^{2}}}}\n$$\n\nThe minimum value of $v$ can be calculated by first determining the relative velocity of two planes:\n\n$$\n  \\gamma_{12}=\\frac{1-\\beta_{1}\\beta_{2}\\cos\\alpha}{\\sqrt{(1-\\beta_{1}^{2})(1-\\beta_{2}^{2})}}\n$$\n\nConsider a system where two spaceships have equal but opposite velocities, this velocity $v=\\beta c$ is what we seek. At this moment, the relative velocity of the two planes can be obtained:\n\nThus, jointly obtain:\n\n$$\n  \\gamma_{12}=\\frac{1+\\beta^{2}}{\\sqrt{(1-\\beta^{2})(1-\\beta^{2})}}=\\frac{1+\\beta^{2}}{1-\\beta^{2}}\n$$\n\n$$\nv=c{\\sqrt{\\frac{c^{2}-v_{1}v_{2}\\cos\\alpha-{\\sqrt{(c^{2}-v_{1}^{2})(c^{2}-v_{2}^{2})}}}{c^{2}-v_{1}v_{2}\\cos\\alpha+{\\sqrt{(c^{2}-v_{1}^{2})(c^{2}-v_{2}^{2})}}}}}\n$$\n\nThe minimum value of $u=\\beta_{\\mathsf{u}}c$ can be set such that its magnitude and direction in the original reference system are between angles $\\varphi_{1},\\varphi_{2}$ of both velocities. Therefore, after transformation, shared velocity:\n\n$$\n  =\\gamma_{i}\\frac{1-\\beta_{u}\\beta_{\\mathrm{{i}c o s\\varphi_{i}}}}{\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{u}^{2}}}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\gamma_{1}^{\\prime}=\\gamma_{2}^{\\prime}\n$$\n\nObtain velocity:\n\n$$\n  \\beta_{u}=\\frac{\\gamma_{1}-\\gamma_{2}}{\\gamma_{1}\\beta_{1}\\cos\\varphi_{1}-\\gamma_{2}\\beta_{2}\\cos\\varphi_{2}}\n$$\n\nThe denominator can be expanded using the auxiliary angle formula to find extremes:\n\n$$\n\\cdots=(\\gamma_{1}\\beta_{1}-\\gamma_{2}\\beta_{2}\\cos\\alpha)\\cos\\varphi_{1}-\\gamma_{2}\\beta_{2}\\sin\\alpha\\sin\\varphi_{1}\\leq{\\sqrt{(\\gamma_{1}\\beta_{1}-\\gamma_{2}\\beta_{2}\\cos\\alpha)^{2}+(\\gamma_{2}\\beta_{2}\\sin\\alpha)^{2}}}\n$$\nSubstitute to find the extreme value:\n\n$$\nu=c^{2}{\\frac{\\left|{\\sqrt{c^{2}-v_{1}^{2}}}-{\\sqrt{c^{2}-v_{1}^{2}}}\\right|}{{\\sqrt{c^{2}\\left(v_{1}^{2}+v_{2}^{2}\\right)-2v_{1}^{2}v_{2}^{2}-2v_{1}v_{2}\\cos\\alpha{\\sqrt{(c^{2}-v_{1}^{2})(c^{2}-v_{2}^{2})}}}}}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nu = c^2 \\frac{\\left| \\sqrt{c^2 - v_1^2} - \\sqrt{c^2 - v_1^2} \\right|}{\\sqrt{c^2 (v_1^2 + v_2^2) - 2 v_1^2 v_2^2 - 2 v_1 v_2 \\cos \\alpha \\sqrt{(c^2 - v_1^2)(c^2 - v_2^2)}}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the minimum possible speed `u` of a uniformly flowing space medium, relative to an inertial frame `S`. Two spacecraft are moving through this medium. Their velocities as measured in the inertial frame `S` are given by the vectors $\\mathbf{v}_1$ and $\\mathbf{v}_2$. The magnitudes of these velocities are $v_1 = |\\mathbf{v}_1|$ and $v_2 = |\\mathbf{v}_2|$, and the angle between their directions is an acute angle $\\alpha$. The crucial condition is that the speeds of the two spacecraft relative to the medium are equal. We must consider relativistic effects, and the speed of light is $c$.\n\nWe define the following frames of reference and variables:\n*   $S$: The primary inertial frame of reference, where the velocities $\\mathbf{v}_1$ and $\\mathbf{v}_2$ are measured.\n*   $S'$: The rest frame of the space medium. This frame moves with a constant velocity $\\mathbf{u}$ with respect to $S$. Our goal is to find the minimum possible magnitude of this velocity, $u_{min} = |\\mathbf{u}|_{min}$.\n*   $\\mathbf{v}_1, \\mathbf{v}_2$: The velocity vectors of the two spacecraft in frame $S$. Their magnitudes are $v_1$ and $v_2$, and the angle between them is $\\alpha$, so $\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{v}_2 = v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha$.\n*   $\\mathbf{v}'_1, \\mathbf{v}'_2$: The velocity vectors of the two spacecraft in the medium's rest frame $S'$.\n*   The core condition of the problem is that the speeds in the medium's frame are equal: $|\\mathbf{v}'_1| = |\\mathbf{v}'_2|$.\n*   $c$: The speed of light in vacuum.\n*   $\\gamma(v) = 1/\\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}$ is the Lorentz factor for a speed $v$. We will use the notations $\\gamma_1 = \\gamma(v_1)$, $\\gamma_2 = \\gamma(v_2)$, and $\\gamma_u = \\gamma(u)$.\n\nTo solve this problem, we will use the formalism of 4-vectors, as it provides a concise way to handle Lorentz transformations.\n\n### Step 1: Relativistic Transformation of the Lorentz Factor\nThe condition of equal speeds in frame $S'$ implies equal Lorentz factors in $S'$. We need to relate the Lorentz factors of the spacecraft in frame $S'$ ($\\gamma'_1, \\gamma'_2$) to the known quantities in frame $S$. This can be achieved using the Lorentz-invariant scalar product of 4-velocities.\n\n\\[\\boxed{U = \\gamma(v)(c, \\mathbf{v})}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{A \\cdot B = A_0 B_0 - \\mathbf{A} \\cdot \\mathbf{B}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\gamma'_p = \\frac{U_p \\cdot U_f}{c^2}}\\]\n\nThe Lorentz factor $\\gamma'_p$ of a particle (4-velocity $U_p$) as measured in a frame $F$ (4-velocity $U_f$) is given by the Lorentz-invariant scalar product $\\gamma'_p = (U_p \\cdot U_f) / c^2$. We apply this to our spacecraft. Let $U_1, U_2$ be the 4-velocities of the spacecraft and $U_u$ be the 4-velocity of the medium, all expressed in frame $S$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU_1 &= \\gamma_1(c, \\mathbf{v}_1) \\\\\nU_2 &= \\gamma_2(c, \\mathbf{v}_2) \\\\\nU_u &= \\gamma_u(c, \\mathbf{u})\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe Lorentz factors of the spacecraft in the medium's frame $S'$ are $\\gamma'_1$ and $\\gamma'_2$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\gamma'_1 &= \\frac{U_1 \\cdot U_u}{c^2} = \\frac{\\gamma_1(c, \\mathbf{v}_1) \\cdot \\gamma_u(c, \\mathbf{u})}{c^2} = \\frac{\\gamma_1 \\gamma_u (c^2 - \\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{u})}{c^2} = \\gamma_1 \\gamma_u \\left(1 - \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}}{c^2}\\right) \\label{eq:gamma_trans1} \\tag{1} \\\\\n\\gamma'_2 &= \\frac{U_2 \\cdot U_u}{c^2} = \\frac{\\gamma_2(c, \\mathbf{v}_2) \\cdot \\gamma_u(c, \\mathbf{u})}{c^2} = \\frac{\\gamma_2 \\gamma_u (c^2 - \\mathbf{v}_2 \\cdot \\mathbf{u})}{c^2} = \\gamma_2 \\gamma_u \\left(1 - \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_2 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}}{c^2}\\right) \\label{eq:gamma_trans2} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Establishing the Condition for the Medium's Velocity u\nThe problem states that the speeds of the spacecraft relative to the medium are equal. This condition allows us to establish a constraint on the medium's velocity $\\mathbf{u}$.\n\n\\[\\boxed{|\\mathbf{v}'_1| = |\\mathbf{v}'_2|}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\gamma(v) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-v^2/c^2}}}\\]\n\nThe Lorentz factor $\\gamma(v)$ is a monotonically increasing function of speed $v$ for $v \\in [0, c)$, since its derivative $d\\gamma/dv = (v/c^2)(1-v^2/c^2)^{-3/2}$ is positive. Therefore, the condition $|\\mathbf{v}'_1| = |\\mathbf{v}'_2|$ is equivalent to the condition that their corresponding Lorentz factors in frame $S'$ are equal, i.e., $\\gamma'_1 = \\gamma'_2$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\gamma'_1 &= \\gamma'_2 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma_1 \\gamma_u \\left(1 - \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}}{c^2}\\right) &= \\gamma_2 \\gamma_u \\left(1 - \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_2 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}}{c^2}\\right) \\quad (\\text{using eqs. \\ref{eq:gamma_trans1}, \\ref{eq:gamma_trans2}}) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma_1 \\left(1 - \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}}{c^2}\\right) &= \\gamma_2 \\left(1 - \\frac{\\mathbf{v}_2 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}}{c^2}\\right) \\quad (\\text{since } u < c, \\gamma_u \\neq 0) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma_1 - \\frac{\\gamma_1}{c^2}(\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}) &= \\gamma_2 - \\frac{\\gamma_2}{c^2}(\\mathbf{v}_2 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2 &= \\frac{1}{c^2} (\\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{u} - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2 \\cdot \\mathbf{u}) \\nonumber \\\\\nc^2(\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2) &= \\mathbf{u} \\cdot (\\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2) \\label{eq:u_condition} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Minimizing the Speed of the Medium u\nEquation \\eqref{eq:u_condition} is a linear equation for the unknown velocity $\\mathbf{u}$. We want to find the minimum possible magnitude $u = |\\mathbf{u}|$ that satisfies this equation.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\mathbf{A} \\cdot \\mathbf{B} = |\\mathbf{A}| |\\mathbf{B}| \\cos\\theta}\\]\n\nLet's define a constant vector $\\mathbf{K}$ using the given quantities: $\\mathbf{K} = \\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2$. Equation \\eqref{eq:u_condition} becomes $c^2(\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2) = \\mathbf{u} \\cdot \\mathbf{K}$.\nLet $u = |\\mathbf{u}|$ and let $\\theta$ be the angle between the vectors $\\mathbf{u}$ and $\\mathbf{K}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nc^2(\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2) &= u |\\mathbf{K}| \\cos\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\nu &= \\frac{c^2(\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2)}{|\\mathbf{K}| \\cos\\theta} \\label{eq:u_magnitude} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe are looking for the minimum positive value of $u$. The value of $u$ depends on the angle $\\theta$. To minimize $u$, we must maximize the magnitude of the denominator, $|\\mathbf{K}| |\\cos\\theta|$. Since $|\\mathbf{K}|$ is a fixed value determined by the given parameters, we must maximize $|\\cos\\theta|$. The maximum value of $|\\cos\\theta|$ is 1, which occurs when $\\theta = 0$ or $\\theta = \\pi$. This means that for the minimum speed $u$, the velocity vector $\\mathbf{u}$ must be collinear with the vector $\\mathbf{K}$.\nThe minimum speed $u_{min}$ is therefore:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nu_{min} = \\left| \\frac{c^2(\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2)}{|\\mathbf{K}|} \\right| = \\frac{c^2|\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2|}{|\\mathbf{K}|} = \\frac{c^2|\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2|}{|\\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2|} \\label{eq:u_min_intermediate} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculating the Final Expression for u_min\nTo obtain the final expression for $u_{min}$, we calculate the magnitude of the vector $\\mathbf{K} = \\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2$ and substitute it into Equation \\eqref{eq:u_min_intermediate}.\n\n\\[\\boxed{|\\mathbf{A}|^2 = \\mathbf{A} \\cdot \\mathbf{A}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{v}_2 = v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\gamma^2(v) v^2 = c^2(\\gamma^2(v) - 1)}\\]\n\nWe compute the square of the magnitude, $|\\mathbf{K}|^2$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n|\\mathbf{K}|^2 &= (\\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2) \\cdot (\\gamma_1 \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\gamma_2 \\mathbf{v}_2) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\gamma_1^2 |\\mathbf{v}_1|^2 + \\gamma_2^2 |\\mathbf{v}_2|^2 - 2\\gamma_1\\gamma_2(\\mathbf{v}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{v}_2) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\gamma_1^2 v_1^2 + \\gamma_2^2 v_2^2 - 2\\gamma_1\\gamma_2 v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha \\nonumber \\\\\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nUsing the identity $\\gamma^2(v) v^2 = c^2(\\gamma^2(v) - 1)$, we can rewrite the first two terms to simplify the expression:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n|\\mathbf{K}|^2 &= c^2(\\gamma_1^2 - 1) + c^2(\\gamma_2^2 - 1) - 2\\gamma_1\\gamma_2 v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha \\nonumber \\\\\n&= c^2(\\gamma_1^2 + \\gamma_2^2 - 2) - 2\\gamma_1\\gamma_2 v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha \\label{eq:K_squared_final} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow we substitute this into the expression for $u_{min}$ from Equation \\eqref{eq:u_min_intermediate}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nu_{min} &= \\frac{c^2|\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2|}{|\\mathbf{K}|} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{c^2|\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2|}{\\sqrt{c^2(\\gamma_1^2 + \\gamma_2^2 - 2) - 2\\gamma_1\\gamma_2 v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{c|\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2|}{\\sqrt{\\gamma_1^2 + \\gamma_2^2 - 2 - \\frac{2}{c^2}\\gamma_1\\gamma_2 v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha}} \\label{eq:final_u_min} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis expression gives the minimum speed $u_{min}$ in terms of the Lorentz factors $\\gamma_1, \\gamma_2$ and the given speeds and angle.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe minimum possible value of the speed $u$ of the medium is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nu_{min} = \\frac{c|\\gamma_1 - \\gamma_2|}{\\sqrt{\\gamma_1^2 + \\gamma_2^2 - 2 - \\frac{2}{c^2}\\gamma_1\\gamma_2 v_1 v_2 \\cos\\alpha}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nwhere $\\gamma_1 = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - v_1^2/c^2}}$ and $\\gamma_2 = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - v_2^2/c^2}}$."}
{"id": "MECHANICS/648", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "In a vacuum, there are concentric spherical shells made of insulating material with radii $R$ and $2R$. The inner shell is uniformly charged with a total charge of $Q(Q>0)$, while the outer shell is uncharged. There is also a small insulating sphere with a charge of $+q(q>0)$ and a mass $m$, which can be launched from a point on the inner shell with a certain velocity. The direction can be adjusted, and its motion is confined between the inner and outer shells. Collisions with the inner and outer shells are perfectly elastic, and the charges do not change during collisions. It is known that the sphere can return to its starting point after making one full orbit around the center. If the sphere is launched from point $A$ on the inner shell and it collides with the inner shell a total of $n$ times (counting the final return to the starting point as one collision), determine the minimum launch speed $v$, ignoring gravity.\n", "solutions": "Let the distance from the center of the sphere to the position of the ball at the extreme point be $r_{1}$, and the speed be $ u_{\\mathrm{_I}}$. According to the conservation of angular momentum and energy: $$ m u_{0}R\\sin\\theta = m u_{1}r_{1} = L $$ $$ {\\frac{1}{2}}{m{ u_{0}}^{2}}+{\\frac{k Q q}{R}} = {\\frac{1}{2}}{m{ u_{1}}^{2}}+{\\frac{k Q q}{r_{1}}} = E = {\\frac{k Q q}{2a}} $$ In an appropriate polar coordinate system, we have: $$ p = \\frac{L^{2}}{kQq m}, \\quad e = \\sqrt{1+\\frac{2E}{m}\\frac{L^{2}}{k^{2}{Q}^{2}q^{2}}} $$ When $Q>0$, the charged ball undergoes hyperbolic motion. Each time it collides with the inner sphere shell, it also collides with the outer sphere shell, and returns to point $A$. The angular displacement around the center during inner and outer sphere collisions is: $$ \\alpha = {\\frac{2\\pi}{2n}} = {\\frac{\\pi}{n}} $$ The curve $AB$ is its trajectory, with point $O$ as one focus of the hyperbola, and $C$ as the other focus. According to conic section knowledge, the trajectory of the hyperbola to focus $O$ is: $$ r = \\frac{p}{e\\cos\\theta^{\\prime}-1} $$ where $\\theta^{\\prime}$ is the angle between the trajectory of the ball and its polar axis. Considering that: $$ 2a = {\\overline{{A O}}} - {\\overline{{A C}}} = R - {\\overline{{A C}}} = {\\overline{{B O}}} - {\\overline{{B C}}} = 2R - {\\overline{{B C}}} $$ $$ {\\overline{B C}} - {\\overline{{A C}}} = R $$ Thus the possible trajectory of point $C$ is a hyperbola, and since $r$ continuously increases from $A$ to $\\boldsymbol{B}$, the polar axis of the hyperbola must not pass through the trajectory $AB$. To minimize the launch speed $ u_{0}$, and thus minimize energy $E$, $2a$ should be maximized, making $AC$ minimal, satisfying the condition when focus $C$ is at the extended line $OA$ and intersects the asymptote of the hyperbola at point $D$. At this point: $$ \\theta = \\frac{\\pi}{2} $$ The speed is minimal, and according to geometric relations: $$ a+c = R $$ Additionally, according to previous equations: $$ \\theta^{\\prime} = 0,\\quad r = {\\frac{p}{e\\cos0-1}} = R $$ $$ \\begin{array}{c c}{{\\theta^{\\prime}=\\alpha,}}&{{r=\\displaystyle\\frac{p}{e\\cos{\\alpha}-1}}=2R} {{}}&{{}} \\end{array} $$ $$ {{\\displaystyle a=\\frac{2\\cos{\\alpha}-1}{2\\cos{\\alpha}}R}} $$ Substituting into previous equations: $$  u_{0} = \\sqrt{\\frac{2k Q q}{m R}\\frac{1-\\cos\\frac{\\pi}{n}}{2\\cos\\frac{\\pi}{n}-1}} $$\n", "final_answers": "$$\n\\sqrt{\\frac{2kQq}{mR} \\cdot \\frac{1-\\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{n}\\right)}{2\\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{n}\\right)-1}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nWe are analyzing the motion of a small insulating sphere with mass $m$ and positive charge $+q$. This sphere moves in the electric field generated by two concentric, insulating spherical shells, all within a vacuum. The inner shell has a radius $R$ and is uniformly charged with a total positive charge $Q$. The outer shell has a radius of $2R$ and is uncharged. Gravitational effects are to be ignored.\n\nThe sphere is launched from a point $A$ on the surface of the inner shell. Its motion is confined to the region between the two shells, meaning its radial distance $r$ from the center $O$ is always in the range $R \\le r \\le 2R$. Any collision the sphere makes with either shell is perfectly elastic.\n\nThe problem states that a specific type of periodic orbit is possible: the sphere can return to its starting point $A$ after completing one full orbit (an angular displacement of $2\\pi$ around the center $O$). In the course of this orbit, the sphere collides with the inner shell a total of $n$ times. The final return to the starting point $A$ is counted as the $n$-th collision. Our goal is to determine the minimum possible launch speed, $v$, for such a motion to occur.\n\nThe relevant physical quantities and variables are:\n*   $R$: Radius of the inner spherical shell.\n*   $2R$: Radius of the outer spherical shell.\n*   $Q$: Total charge on the inner shell ($Q>0$).\n*   $q$: Charge of the small sphere ($q>0$).\n*   $m$: Mass of the small sphere.\n*   $n$: The number of collisions with the inner shell during one full orbit.\n*   $v$: The launch speed of the sphere from the inner shell.\n*   $k$: The Coulomb constant, $k = 1/(4\\pi\\epsilon_0)$.\n\nWe assume the spherical shells are fixed in position. The electric field from the uniformly charged inner shell is calculated using the shell theorem.\n\n### Step 1: Analyze Forces and Conserved Quantities\nFirst, we determine the force acting on the sphere and identify the conserved quantities governing its motion.\n\n*   **Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n    The electric field $\\vec{E}$ produced by a uniformly charged spherical shell of charge $Q$ and radius $R_{shell}$ at a distance $r$ from its center is given by the shell theorem:\n    \\[\\boxed{\n    \\vec{E} = \n    \\begin{cases} \n    \\frac{kQ}{r^2}\\hat{r} & \\text{for } r > R_{shell} \\\\\n    0 & \\text{for } r < R_{shell} \n    \\end{cases}\n    }\\]\n    The electric force $\\vec{F}$ on a charge $q$ in an electric field $\\vec{E}$ is:\n    \\[\\boxed{\\vec{F} = q\\vec{E}}\\]\n    For a central force (a force always directed towards or away from a fixed center), the angular momentum $\\vec{L}$ about that center is conserved.\n    \\[\\boxed{\\vec{L} = \\vec{r} \\times \\vec{p} = \\text{constant}}\\]\n    For a conservative force, the total mechanical energy $E$ is conserved. The potential energy $U$ is related to the force by $\\vec{F} = -\\nabla U$.\n    \\[\\boxed{E = K + U = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + U(r) = \\text{constant}}\\]\n\n*   **Derivation**:\n    The uncharged outer shell ($r=2R$) produces no electric field. The inner shell (radius $R$, charge $Q$) produces an electric field in the region of motion ($R \\le r \\le 2R$). According to the shell theorem, for $r \\ge R$, the field is:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    \\vec{E}(r) = \\frac{kQ}{r^2}\\hat{r}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    The force on the sphere with charge $q$ is therefore:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    \\vec{F}(r) = q\\vec{E}(r) = \\frac{kQq}{r^2}\\hat{r} \\label{eq:force} \\tag{1}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    Since $Q>0$ and $q>0$, the force is repulsive. This force is a central force, as it always points radially away from the center $O$. Consequently, the angular momentum $\\vec{L}$ of the sphere about $O$ is conserved.\n    The force is also conservative, as it depends only on the radial distance $r$. The associated electrostatic potential energy $U(r)$ is:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    U(r) = -\\int_{\\infty}^{r} \\vec{F}(r') \\cdot d\\vec{r'} = -\\int_{\\infty}^{r} \\frac{kQq}{r'^2} dr' = \\left[\\frac{kQq}{r'}\\right]_{\\infty}^{r} = \\frac{kQq}{r}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    Thus, the total mechanical energy $E$ of the sphere is also conserved:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    E = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + \\frac{kQq}{r} = \\text{constant} \\label{eq:energy} \\tag{2}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 2: The Equation of the Trajectory\nThe trajectory of a particle under an inverse-square central force is a conic section.\n\n*   **Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n    For a particle moving under a repulsive inverse-square central force $F = K/r^2$ (with $K=kQq>0$), the trajectory is a hyperbola. The general polar equation of this hyperbola, with the force center at the external focus, is:\n    \\[\\boxed{r(\\phi) = \\frac{p}{e\\cos(\\phi - \\phi_0) - 1}}\\]\n    where $p$ is the semi-latus rectum, $e > 1$ is the eccentricity, and $\\phi_0$ is the angle of the axis of symmetry. The parameters $p$ and $e$ are related to the energy $E$ and angular momentum magnitude $L$ by:\n    \\[\\boxed{p = \\frac{L^2}{mK} = \\frac{L^2}{mkQq}}\\]\n    \\[\\boxed{e = \\sqrt{1 + \\frac{2EL^2}{mK^2}} = \\sqrt{1 + \\frac{2EL^2}{m(kQq)^2}}}\\]\n\n*   **Derivation**:\n    The motion of the sphere between any two collisions is governed by the repulsive inverse-square force given by Eq. \\eqref{eq:force}. Since the total energy $E = K+U$ must be positive ($K \\ge 0$ and $U=kQq/r > 0$), the eccentricity $e$ is always greater than 1. Therefore, the path of the sphere between collisions is a segment of a hyperbola, with the center of the shells $O$ being the repulsive focus.\n\n### Step 3: Geometric Analysis of the Periodic Orbit\nWe analyze the geometry of the complete orbit to relate it to the number of collisions $n$.\n\n*   **Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n    In a perfectly elastic collision with a fixed, massive, spherical surface that is concentric with the center of force, the impulse delivered to the particle is purely radial.\n    \\[\\boxed{\\text{Tangential velocity is unchanged, radial velocity reverses sign: } (v_t, v_r) \\to (v_t, -v_r)}\\]\n\n*   **Derivation**:\n    The problem states that the sphere returns to its starting point $A$ after a total angular displacement of $2\\pi$ and after $n$ collisions with the inner shell. Let the points of collision with the inner shell be $A_0, A_1, \\dots, A_{n-1}$, where $A_0=A$ is the launch point and the final return is to $A_n=A_0$.\n    The path from any collision point $A_i$ to the next $A_{i+1}$ forms one segment of the total orbit. Due to the rotational symmetry of the system, all $n$ segments must be identical. Therefore, the angular displacement for each segment is the same: $\\Delta\\phi_{\\text{segment}} = 2\\pi/n$.\n    Each of these segments consists of an outward path (from the inner shell at $A_i$ to the outer shell at some point $B_i$) and an inward path (from $B_i$ back to the inner shell at $A_{i+1}$).\n    The collision at the outer shell at point $B_i$ is elastic. Because the shell is spherical and centered at $O$, the collision reverses the radial component of the sphere's velocity while leaving the tangential component unchanged. This means the subsequent trajectory ($B_i \\to A_{i+1}$) is a mirror image of the preceding trajectory ($A_i \\to B_i$) with respect to the line $OB_i$.\n    Consequently, the angular displacement of the outward path, $\\Delta\\phi(A_i \\to B_i)$, is equal to the angular displacement of the inward path, $\\Delta\\phi(B_i \\to A_{i+1})$. Let's denote this angle by $\\alpha$.\n    The total angular displacement for one full segment is the sum of these two: $\\Delta\\phi_{\\text{segment}} = \\alpha + \\alpha = 2\\alpha$.\n    By combining our findings, we get $2\\alpha = 2\\pi/n$, which simplifies to:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    \\alpha = \\frac{\\pi}{n} \\label{eq:angle} \\tag{3}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    This is the angle subtended at the center $O$ by the hyperbolic arc connecting a point on the inner shell to a point on the outer shell.\n\n### Step 4: Condition for Minimum Launch Speed\nTo find the minimum launch speed, we must find the trajectory that requires the minimum total energy.\n\n*   **Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n    The total energy is related to the launch speed $v$ at the inner shell ($r=R$) by:\n    \\[\\boxed{E = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + \\frac{kQq}{R}}\\]\n    For a transfer orbit between two radii $r_1$ and $r_2$ over a fixed angle $\\Delta\\phi < \\pi$, the trajectory with the minimum possible total energy $E$ is the one that is tangential to the circular path at either $r_1$ or $r_2$.\n\n*   **Derivation**:\n    From the energy equation, minimizing the launch speed $v$ at a fixed radius $R$ is equivalent to minimizing the total mechanical energy $E$ of the sphere.\n    The trajectory segment connects the inner shell ($r=R$) to the outer shell ($r=2R$) over an angle $\\alpha = \\pi/n$. For a physically meaningful orbit with at least one bounce on the outer shell, we must have $n \\ge 2$, which implies $\\alpha \\le \\pi/2$. This satisfies the condition $\\alpha < \\pi$ for the minimum energy principle.\n    This principle states that the orbit with the lowest energy will have a velocity that is purely tangential at one of the endpoints ($r=R$ or $r=2R$). A point where the velocity is purely tangential is an apsis (a turning point in radial motion). For a repulsive central force, the only possible apsis is the pericenter (point of closest approach).\n    Since the motion occurs for $r \\ge R$, the pericenter distance $r_p$ must be $r_p \\le R$. For the trajectory to have an apsis at either $R$ or $2R$, it must be the pericenter, which must be at the smaller radius, $R$.\n    Therefore, the minimum energy trajectory occurs when the pericenter distance is $r_p=R$. This means the sphere is launched tangentially from the inner shell.\n\n### Step 5: Calculating Trajectory Parameters for the Minimum Speed Case\nWe now use the condition for minimum speed to determine the specific parameters of the hyperbolic trajectory.\n\n*   **Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n    The equation for a hyperbolic orbit with its pericenter (point of closest approach) oriented at angle $\\phi=0$ is:\n    \\[\\boxed{r(\\phi) = \\frac{p}{e\\cos\\phi - 1}}\\]\n\n*   **Derivation**:\n    We set up a polar coordinate system where the launch point $A$ (the pericenter) is at $\\phi=0$.\n    At point $A$: $r=R$ at $\\phi=0$. Substituting into the orbit equation:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    R = \\frac{p}{e\\cos(0) - 1} = \\frac{p}{e-1} \\label{eq:cond1} \\tag{4}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    The sphere then travels to a point $B$ on the outer shell, where $r=2R$, after an angular displacement of $\\alpha = \\pi/n$.\n    At point $B$: $r=2R$ at $\\phi=\\alpha$.\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    2R = \\frac{p}{e\\cos\\alpha - 1} \\label{eq:cond2} \\tag{5}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    We solve the system of equations \\eqref{eq:cond1} and \\eqref{eq:cond2} for $e$. From \\eqref{eq:cond1}, $p = R(e-1)$. Substituting this into \\eqref{eq:cond2}:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    2R &= \\frac{R(e-1)}{e\\cos\\alpha - 1} \\\\\n    2(e\\cos\\alpha - 1) &= e-1 \\\\\n    2e\\cos\\alpha - 2 &= e - 1 \\\\\n    e(2\\cos\\alpha - 1) &= 1 \\\\\n    e &= \\frac{1}{2\\cos\\alpha - 1} \\label{eq:eccentricity} \\tag{6}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    For the trajectory to be a hyperbola, the eccentricity must be $e > 1$. This requires the denominator to be positive and less than 1: $0 < 2\\cos\\alpha - 1 < 1$.\n    The condition $2\\cos\\alpha - 1 > 0$ implies $\\cos\\alpha > 1/2$. Substituting $\\alpha = \\pi/n$, we get $\\cos(\\pi/n) > 1/2$. Since $\\cos(x)$ is a decreasing function for $x \\in [0, \\pi]$, this means $\\pi/n < \\pi/3$, which gives $n > 3$.\n    Thus, a periodic orbit of the type described is only possible for an integer $n > 3$. For $n=3$, $e$ would be infinite, requiring infinite launch speed. For $n<3$, a tangential launch from $r=R$ cannot connect to $r=2R$ over the angle $\\pi/n$. The problem statement implies such an orbit exists, so we proceed assuming $n$ is an integer greater than 3.\n\n### Step 6: Calculating the Minimum Launch Speed\nFinally, we relate the trajectory parameters back to the energy and solve for the speed $v$.\n\n*   **Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n    The energy of a hyperbolic orbit under a repulsive force $kQq/r^2$ is related to its semi-major axis $a$:\n    \\[\\boxed{E = \\frac{kQq}{2a}}\\]\n    The semi-major axis $a$, semi-latus rectum $p$, and eccentricity $e$ are related by:\n    \\[\\boxed{p = a(e^2-1)}\\]\n    The energy is related to the launch speed by the conservation of energy equation:\n    \\[\\boxed{E = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + \\frac{kQq}{R}}\\]\n\n*   **Derivation**:\n    First, we find the semi-major axis $a$. From Eq. \\eqref{eq:cond1}, $p=R(e-1)$.\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    a = \\frac{p}{e^2-1} = \\frac{R(e-1)}{(e-1)(e+1)} = \\frac{R}{e+1}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    Substituting the expression for $e$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:eccentricity} with $\\alpha=\\pi/n$:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    a = \\frac{R}{\\frac{1}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1} + 1} = \\frac{R}{\\frac{1 + (2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1}} = \\frac{R(2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n)} \\label{eq:semiaxis} \\tag{7}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    Now, we calculate the total energy $E$:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    E = \\frac{kQq}{2a} = \\frac{kQq}{2R \\frac{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1}{2\\cos(\\pi/n)}} = \\frac{kQq}{R} \\frac{\\cos(\\pi/n)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1} \\label{eq:final_energy} \\tag{8}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    Using the conservation of energy at the launch point, we find the kinetic energy and then the speed $v$:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 &= E - \\frac{kQq}{R} \\\\\n    &= \\frac{kQq}{R} \\frac{\\cos(\\pi/n)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1} - \\frac{kQq}{R} \\\\\n    &= \\frac{kQq}{R} \\left( \\frac{\\cos(\\pi/n) - (2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1} \\right) \\\\\n    &= \\frac{kQq}{R} \\frac{1 - \\cos(\\pi/n)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1} \\label{eq:kinetic_energy} \\tag{9}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n    Solving for the minimum launch speed $v$:\n    \\[\\begin{align}\n    v^2 &= \\frac{2kQq}{mR} \\frac{1 - \\cos(\\pi/n)}{2\\cos(\\pi/n) - 1} \\\\\n    v &= \\sqrt{\\frac{2kQq}{mR} \\frac{1 - \\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{n}\\right)}{2\\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{n}\\right) - 1}} \\label{eq:final_speed} \\tag{10}\n    \\end{align}\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe minimum launch speed $v$ required for the described periodic motion is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{v = \\sqrt{\\frac{2kQq}{mR} \\frac{1 - \\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{n}\\right)}{2\\cos\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{n}\\right) - 1}}}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis solution is valid for integers $n>3$, as this condition is required for the existence of a real, hyperbolic trajectory that satisfies the problem's geometric constraints under the minimum energy condition."}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/72", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "At time $t=0$, an adiabatic cylinder with a cross-sectional area $S$ is divided into two equal parts with a volume of $V_{0}$ by an adiabatic, thin and lightweight  movable piston. On the right side, there is an ideal gas with an adiabatic index of $\\gamma=5/3$ and a pressure of $p_{0}$. On the left side of the cylinder, there is the same type of gas with a pressure of $2p_{0}$. The container wall has a selectable viscous material with negligible heat capacity and volume, characterized by providing resistance to the piston as it moves at velocity $v$ in a certain direction (rightward in the diagram), allowing the piston to move slowly. Half of the heat generated by friction is absorbed by the left side of the container, and half by the right side. The piston is released from rest; calculate the displacement $l$ after the piston stops moving (express the result as a coefficient with two significant figures), shown in the form:\n$$\nl=x \\frac{V_{0}}{S} (x \\text{ unknown, to two decimal places})\n$$ \nThis problem assumes that all processes are quasistatic processes.", "solutions": "From the proportional relationship between work done and heat absorbed:\n\n$$\n\\frac{1}{2}\\left(p_{1}\\mathrm{d}V_{1}+p_{2}\\mathrm{d}V_{2}\\right)=T_{1}\\mathrm{d}S_{1}=T_{2}\\mathrm{d}S_{2}\n$$  \n\nFrom the first law of thermodynamics:\n\n$$\n\\mathrm{d}U_{i}=T_{i}\\mathrm{d}S_{i}-p_{i}\\mathrm{d}V_{i}\n$$  \n\nAnd the equation of state:\n\n$$\nU_{i}=\\frac{3}{2}\\nu_{i}R T_{i}=\\frac{3}{2}p_{i}V_{i}\n$$  \n\nWe obtain:\n\n$$\n\\mathrm{d}U_{1}={\\frac{3}{2}}\\mathrm{d}\\left(p_{1}V_{1}\\right)=-{\\frac{1}{2}}p_{1}\\mathrm{d}V_{1}+{\\frac{1}{2}}p_{2}\\mathrm{d}V_{2}\n$$  \n\n$$\n\\mathrm{d}U_{2}={\\frac{3}{2}}\\mathrm{d}\\left(p_{2}V_{2}\\right)=-{\\frac{1}{2}}p_{2}\\mathrm{d}V_{2}+{\\frac{1}{2}}p_{1}\\mathrm{d}V_{1}\n$$  \n\nTo solve these two differential equations, we note that due to energy conservation, the total internal energy remains unchanged:\n\n$$\nU_{1}+U_{2}={\\frac{3}{2}}\\left(p_{1}V_{1}+p_{2}V_{2}\\right)={\\frac{9}{2}}p_{0}V_{0}\n$$  \n\nThus, for the above two equations, we define:\n\n$$\nV_{1}=(1+x)V_{0}\\quad,\\quad V_{2}=(1-x)V_{0}\n$$  \n\nSimplifying the first equation:\n\n$$\n\\frac{4}{3}p_{1}V_{2}\\mathrm{d}V_{1}+\\frac{1}{3}p_{1}V_{1}\\mathrm{d}V_{2}+V_{1}V_{2}\\mathrm{d}p_{1}=p_{0}V_{0}\\mathrm{d}V_{2}\n$$  \n\nMultiplying both sides by $V_{1}^{1/3}V_{2}^{-2/3}$, the left side conveniently forms a total differential:\n\n$$\n\\mathrm{d}\\left[p_{1}(1+x)^{\\frac{1}{3}}(1-x)^{\\frac{1}{3}}\\right]=-p_{0}{\\frac{(1+x)^{1/3}}{(1-x)^{2/3}}}\\mathrm{d}x\n$$  \n\nDue to conservation of internal energy, the pressure at final equilibrium is equal on both sides:\n\n$$\np\\cdot2V_{0}=3p_{0}V_{0}\\quad,\\quad p={\\frac{3}{2}}p_{0}\n$$  \n\nThus, we finally obtain the integral equation:\n\n$$\n2-\\frac{3}{2}(1+y)^{\\frac{1}{3}}(1-y)^{\\frac{1}{3}}=\\int_{0}^{y}\\frac{(1+x)^{1/3}}{(1-x)^{2/3}}\\mathrm{d}x\n$$  \n\nSolution by numerical methods:\n\n$$\ny=0.20\n$$  \n\nThat is:\n\n$$\nl=0.20\\frac{V_{0}}{S}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nl=0.20\\frac{V_0}{S}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem describes a thermodynamic process in a closed system. The system consists of an adiabatic cylinder with a uniform cross-sectional area $S$. A thin, lightweight, adiabatic, and movable piston divides the cylinder into two chambers.\n\n**Initial State (t=0):**\n*   The piston is at the center, dividing the cylinder into two equal volumes, $V_0$.\n*   **Left Chamber (Part 1):** Contains an ideal gas with initial pressure $p_{1,i} = 2p_0$ and initial volume $V_{1,i} = V_0$.\n*   **Right Chamber (Part 2):** Contains the same type of ideal gas with initial pressure $p_{2,i} = p_0$ and initial volume $V_{2,i} = V_0$.\n*   The ideal gas in both chambers has a constant adiabatic index $\\gamma = 5/3$.\n\n**Process:**\n*   The piston is released from rest. Due to the pressure difference, it moves to the right.\n*   The motion is slow, implying the process is quasistatic. This means the gas in each chamber remains in internal thermodynamic equilibrium at all times.\n*   A viscous material provides a frictional force that opposes the piston's motion, generating heat.\n*   The total heat generated by friction, $dQ_{gen}$, is distributed equally between the two chambers. The heat absorbed by the left chamber is $dQ_1$ and by the right is $dQ_2$, with $dQ_1 = dQ_2 = \\frac{1}{2} dQ_{gen}$.\n*   The cylinder walls and the piston are adiabatic, preventing any other heat exchange with the surroundings.\n\n**Final State:**\n*   The piston eventually comes to rest. At this point, the forces on it are balanced, which means the pressures in the two chambers are equal. Let this final pressure be $p_f$.\n*   The piston will have moved a distance $l$ to the right. The final volumes will be $V_{1,f} = V_0 + Sl$ and $V_{2,f} = V_0 - Sl$.\n\n**Goal:**\nThe objective is to calculate the displacement $l$ of the piston. The result must be expressed in the form $l = x \\frac{V_0}{S}$, where $x$ is a numerical coefficient determined to two significant figures.\n\n### Step 1: Energy Conservation for the Combined System\nWe begin by applying the First Law of Thermodynamics to each chamber to find a conservation law for the entire system.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe First Law of Thermodynamics for a closed system undergoing a quasistatic process is:\n\\[\\boxed{\ndU = dQ - p\\,dV\n}\\]\nThe internal energy of an ideal gas with a constant adiabatic index $\\gamma$ is given by:\n\\[\\boxed{\nU = \\frac{pV}{\\gamma-1}\n}\\]\nThe net work done by the gases on the piston over an infinitesimal displacement is converted into heat by the viscous friction.\n\\[\\boxed{\ndQ_{gen} = (p_1 - p_2)dV_1\n}\\]\nThe problem states that this generated heat is distributed equally to both chambers:\n\\[\\boxed{\ndQ_1 = dQ_2 = \\frac{1}{2} dQ_{gen}\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nFor this problem, the adiabatic index is $\\gamma = 5/3$, so the internal energy of the gas is $U = \\frac{pV}{5/3 - 1} = \\frac{3}{2}pV$. Let's consider an infinitesimal displacement of the piston to the right, causing the volume of the left chamber to increase by $dV_1$ and the right chamber to decrease by $dV_2 = -dV_1$.\n\nFor the left chamber (Part 1), the change in internal energy is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\ndU_1 &= dQ_1 - p_1 dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{2} dQ_{gen} - p_1 dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{2}(p_1 - p_2)dV_1 - p_1 dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left(\\frac{1}{2}p_1 - \\frac{1}{2}p_2 - p_1\\right)dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1 \\label{eq:dU1} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\\]\nFor the right chamber (Part 2), the change in internal energy is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\ndU_2 &= dQ_2 - p_2 dV_2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{2} dQ_{gen} - p_2(-dV_1) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{2}(p_1 - p_2)dV_1 + p_2 dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left(\\frac{1}{2}p_1 - \\frac{1}{2}p_2 + p_2\\right)dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1 \\label{eq:dU2} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe total change in internal energy of the system (the gas in both chambers) is the sum of the changes for each part:\n\\[\\begin{align}\ndU_{total} = dU_1 + dU_2 = -\\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1 + \\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1 = 0\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis result shows that the total internal energy of the system is conserved throughout the process. We can therefore equate the initial and final total internal energies.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nU_{total, initial} &= U_{1,i} + U_{2,i} = \\frac{3}{2}p_{1,i}V_{1,i} + \\frac{3}{2}p_{2,i}V_{2,i} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{3}{2}(2p_0)V_0 + \\frac{3}{2}(p_0)V_0 = \\frac{9}{2}p_0V_0 \\label{eq:U_initial} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSince $U_{total}$ is constant, for any state during the process:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nU_1 + U_2 = \\frac{3}{2}(p_1V_1 + p_2V_2) = \\frac{9}{2}p_0V_0\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis gives us a crucial energy conservation constraint that holds at all times:\n\\[\\begin{align}\np_1V_1 + p_2V_2 = 3p_0V_0 \\label{eq:energy_conservation} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 2: Deriving the Differential Equation for the Process\nWe now use the results from Step 1 to formulate a differential equation that describes the state of the gas in the left chamber as the piston moves.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nWe use the following relationships derived or defined previously:\n\\[\\boxed{\ndU_1 = -\\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1\n}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\nU_1 = \\frac{3}{2}p_1V_1\n}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\np_2 = \\frac{3p_0V_0 - p_1V_1}{V_2}\n}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\nV_1 + V_2 = 2V_0\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nBy differentiating the expression for $U_1$ and equating it to the expression for $dU_1$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nd\\left(\\frac{3}{2}p_1V_1\\right) &= -\\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{3}{2}(V_1 dp_1 + p_1 dV_1) &= -\\frac{1}{2}(p_1 + p_2)dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n3V_1 dp_1 + 3p_1 dV_1 &= -p_1 dV_1 - p_2 dV_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n3V_1 dp_1 + (4p_1 + p_2) dV_1 &= 0 \\label{eq:pre_de} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\\]\nWe eliminate $p_2$ and $V_2$ using the constraints: $p_2 = (3p_0V_0 - p_1V_1)/(2V_0 - V_1)$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n3V_1 dp_1 + \\left(4p_1 + \\frac{3p_0V_0 - p_1V_1}{2V_0 - V_1}\\right) dV_1 = 0\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo simplify, we introduce a dimensionless displacement variable $x = \\frac{Sl}{V_0}$, where $l$ is the piston's displacement to the right. The volumes and their differentials become:\n$V_1 = V_0 + Sl = V_0(1+x)$, $V_2 = V_0 - Sl = V_0(1-x)$, and $dV_1 = S\\,dl = V_0\\,dx$.\nSubstituting these into the equation:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n3V_0(1+x) dp_1 + \\left(4p_1 + \\frac{3p_0V_0 - p_1V_0(1+x)}{V_0(1-x)}\\right) V_0 dx = 0\n\\end{align}\\]\nDividing by $V_0$ and grouping terms with $dx$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n3(1+x) dp_1 + \\left[4p_1 + \\frac{3p_0 - p_1(1+x)}{1-x}\\right] dx = 0\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo clear the denominator, we multiply the entire equation by $(1-x)$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n3(1+x)(1-x) dp_1 + \\left[4p_1(1-x) + 3p_0 - p_1(1+x)\\right] dx &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n3(1-x^2) dp_1 + [4p_1 - 4p_1x + 3p_0 - p_1 - p_1x] dx &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n3(1-x^2) \\frac{dp_1}{dx} + p_1(3 - 5x) + 3p_0 &= 0 \\label{eq:final_de} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 3: Solving the Ordinary Differential Equation\nThe relation derived in Step 2 is a first-order linear ordinary differential equation for $p_1(x)$. We solve it using the method of integrating factors.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nA first-order linear ODE in the standard form $\\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)$ can be solved using an integrating factor $I(x)$:\n\\[\\boxed{\nI(x) = \\exp\\left(\\int P(x) dx\\right)\n}\\]\nThe solution is then found from the equation $\\frac{d}{dx}(I(x)y) = I(x)Q(x)$.\n\n**Derivation**:\nFirst, we rewrite Eq. \\eqref{eq:final_de} in the standard form $\\frac{dp_1}{dx} + P(x)p_1 = Q(x)$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dp_1}{dx} + p_1 \\left(\\frac{3-5x}{3(1-x^2)}\\right) = -\\frac{3p_0}{3(1-x^2)} = -\\frac{p_0}{1-x^2} \\label{eq:standard_de} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe function $P(x)$ is $P(x) = \\frac{3-5x}{3(1-x^2)}$. We integrate $P(x)$ using partial fraction decomposition:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nP(x) = \\frac{3-5x}{3(1-x)(1+x)} = \\frac{1}{3}\\left(\\frac{A}{1-x} + \\frac{B}{1+x}\\right)\n\\end{align}\\]\nMultiplying by $3(1-x)(1+x)$ gives $3-5x = A(1+x) + B(1-x)$.\n*   For $x=1$: $3-5 = A(2) \\implies -2 = 2A \\implies A = -1$.\n*   For $x=-1$: $3-5(-1) = B(2) \\implies 8 = 2B \\implies B = 4$.\nSo, $P(x) = \\frac{1}{3}\\left(\\frac{4}{1+x} - \\frac{1}{1-x}\\right)$. The integral is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\int P(x) dx = \\frac{1}{3} \\int \\left(\\frac{4}{1+x} - \\frac{1}{1-x}\\right) dx = \\frac{4}{3}\\ln(1+x) + \\frac{1}{3}\\ln(1-x) = \\frac{1}{3}\\ln\\left((1+x)^4(1-x)\\right)\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe integrating factor $I(x)$ is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nI(x) = \\exp\\left(\\frac{1}{3}\\ln\\left((1+x)^4(1-x)\\right)\\right) = (1+x)^{4/3}(1-x)^{1/3} \\label{eq:integrating_factor} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\\]\nMultiplying Eq. \\eqref{eq:standard_de} by $I(x)$ yields:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[p_1(x) (1+x)^{4/3}(1-x)^{1/3}\\right] &= Q(x)I(x) = -\\frac{p_0}{1-x^2} (1+x)^{4/3}(1-x)^{1/3} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -p_0 (1-x)^{-1}(1+x)^{-1} (1+x)^{4/3}(1-x)^{1/3} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -p_0 (1+x)^{1/3}(1-x)^{-2/3} \\label{eq:integrable_de} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 4: Applying Boundary Conditions to Find the Displacement\nWe integrate the differential relation from the initial state to the final state to find the total displacement.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nWe apply the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to the result of Step 3.\n\\[\\boxed{\n\\int_a^b F'(x) dx = F(b) - F(a)\n}\\]\n**Boundary Conditions**:\n*   Initial state (dimensionless displacement $x=0$): The pressure in the left chamber is given.\n\\[\\boxed{p_1(0) = 2p_0}\\]\n*   Final state (dimensionless displacement $x=y=Sl/V_0$): The piston stops, so pressures equalize. The final pressure $p_f$ is determined by energy conservation.\n\\[\\boxed{p_1(y) = p_f = \\frac{3}{2}p_0}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe final pressure $p_f$ is found from the energy conservation law, Eq. \\eqref{eq:energy_conservation}, applied to the final state where $p_1=p_2=p_f$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\np_f V_{1,f} + p_f V_{2,f} = 3p_0V_0 \\implies p_f(V_{1,f} + V_{2,f}) = 3p_0V_0\n\\end{align}\\]\nSince the total volume is constant, $V_{1,f} + V_{2,f} = 2V_0$, we get $p_f(2V_0) = 3p_0V_0$, which gives $p_f = \\frac{3}{2}p_0$.\n\nNow, we integrate Eq. \\eqref{eq:integrable_de} from the initial displacement $x=0$ to the final displacement $x=y$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^y \\frac{d}{dx}\\left[p_1(x) (1+x)^{4/3}(1-x)^{1/3}\\right] dx = \\int_0^y -p_0 (1+x)^{1/3}(1-x)^{-2/3} dx\n\\end{align}\\]\nApplying the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to the left side:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\left[p_1(x) (1+x)^{4/3}(1-x)^{1/3}\\right]_0^y = -p_0 \\int_0^y (1+x)^{1/3}(1-x)^{-2/3} dx\n\\end{align}\\]\nSubstituting the boundary conditions for pressure, $p_1(y) = \\frac{3}{2}p_0$ and $p_1(0) = 2p_0$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{3}{2}p_0 (1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3}\\right) - \\left(2p_0 (1+0)^{4/3}(1-0)^{1/3}\\right) = -p_0 \\int_0^y (1+x)^{1/3}(1-x)^{-2/3} dx\n\\end{align}\\]\nDividing by $p_0$ and rearranging gives the final equation for $y$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n2 - \\frac{3}{2}(1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3} = \\int_0^y \\left(\\frac{1+x}{(1-x)^2}\\right)^{1/3} dx \\label{eq:final_integral_eq} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 5: Numerical Solution\nThe final integral equation, Eq. \\eqref{eq:final_integral_eq}, is a transcendental equation for the dimensionless displacement $y$. It does not have a simple analytical solution and must be solved numerically.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nWe must find the root $y$ of the equation $f(y)=0$, where:\n\\[\\boxed{\nf(y) = 2 - \\frac{3}{2}(1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3} - \\int_0^y \\left(\\frac{1+x}{(1-x)^2}\\right)^{1/3} dx = 0\n}\\]\nThis requires numerical methods for both integration and root-finding.\n\n**Derivation**:\nWe need to find the value of $y$ that satisfies Eq. \\eqref{eq:final_integral_eq}. We can verify the solution by testing a proposed value, for instance, $y=0.20$.\nLet's evaluate the Left-Hand Side (LHS) of Eq. \\eqref{eq:final_integral_eq} for $y=0.20$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\text{LHS} &= 2 - \\frac{3}{2}(1+0.20)^{4/3}(1-0.20)^{1/3} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2 - 1.5 \\times (1.2)^{4/3} \\times (0.8)^{1/3} \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx 2 - 1.5 \\times (1.2765) \\times (0.9283) \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx 2 - 1.7778 \\approx 0.2222\n\\end{align}\\]\nNow, we evaluate the Right-Hand Side (RHS), which is a definite integral:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\text{RHS} = \\int_0^{0.20} \\left(\\frac{1+x}{(1-x)^2}\\right)^{1/3} dx\n\\end{align}\\]\nUsing a numerical integrator (e.g., Simpson's rule or a computational software package), the value of the integral is found to be approximately $0.2222$.\nSince LHS $\\approx$ RHS for $y=0.20$, we conclude this is the correct solution to two significant figures. The physical displacement $l$ is related to the dimensionless displacement $y$ by $y = lS/V_0$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nl = y \\frac{V_0}{S} = 0.20 \\frac{V_0}{S}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe displacement $l$ of the piston after it stops moving is given by:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{l = 0.20 \\frac{V_0}{S}}\n\\end{align}\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/603", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "The characteristics of a medium in an electric field are described as follows: $D=\\varepsilon E=\\varepsilon_0 E+P$ where $E$ and $D$ are the electric field intensity and electric displacement, respectively, $\\varepsilon$ is the dielectric constant of the medium, $P$ is the polarization intensity (electric dipole moment per unit volume), and $\\varepsilon_0$ is the permittivity of free space. In the absence of free charges, the boundary conditions are the continuity of the electric field tangent to the boundary and the continuity of the electric displacement perpendicular to the boundary. In oscillating electromagnetic fields, the dielectric constant of the medium (including metals) depends on the electromagnetic field frequency $\\omega$. A uniform oscillating electric field $E_0 \\sin(\\omega t)$ is applied in the metal. Assuming that the ion mass is much greater than that of the electrons and is fixed. The effective mass and charge of the electrons are denoted as $m$ and $-e$, respectively, with a number density of $n$. Within the simple framework of the extremely sparse free electron approximation, it can be assumed that the field acting on the electrons is equivalent to $E_0 \\sin(\\omega t)$. All other forces (including dissipative forces) are very small and can be neglected. The electric field drives the electrons to move collectively in the direction of the electric field $r(t)$. Calculate the AC dielectric constant $\\varepsilon(\\omega)$ of the metal based on the electric dipole moment caused by this collective movement.", "solutions": "Write the Newton's second law for the motion of the electron:  \\[ m\\frac{d^2x}{dt^2}=eE_0 \\sin(\\omega t) \\]  We obtain  \\[ r=\\frac{eE_0}{m\\omega^2}\\sin(\\omega t) \\]  Since the motion of ions is not considered, they do not contribute to the total polarizability. The electric dipole moment of the electron and the total polarizability are  \\[ p=ex \\]  \\[ P=np=-\\frac{ne^2E_0}{m\\omega^2}\\sin(\\omega t) \\]  The formula for calculating the dielectric constant is  \\[ \\varepsilon \\varepsilon_0 E=\\varepsilon_0 E+P \\]  We obtain the dielectric constant  \\[ \\varepsilon =1-\\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m\\omega^2} \\]", "final_answers": "$$\\varepsilon = 1 - \\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m \\omega^2}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem requires the derivation of the AC dielectric constant, denoted as $\\varepsilon(\\omega)$, for a metal. The metal is modeled as a collection of free electrons and fixed positive ions, subjected to a uniform, oscillating external electric field $\\vec{E}(t) = \\vec{E}_0 \\sin(\\omega t)$.\n\nThe key physical quantities and constants are:\n*   **External Electric Field**: $\\vec{E}(t) = \\vec{E}_0 \\sin(\\omega t)$, where $\\vec{E}_0$ is the constant amplitude vector and $\\omega$ is the angular frequency.\n*   **Electron Properties**:\n    *   Effective mass: $m$.\n    *   Charge: $-e$.\n    *   Number density (number of free electrons per unit volume): $n$.\n*   **Electromagnetic Properties of the Medium**:\n    *   Permittivity of free space: $\\varepsilon_0$.\n    *   Polarization intensity (electric dipole moment per unit volume): $\\vec{P}$.\n    *   Electric displacement: $\\vec{D}$.\n    *   AC dielectric constant: $\\varepsilon(\\omega)$.\n\nThe fundamental relationship between these quantities is given by the constitutive relation: $\\vec{D} = \\varepsilon \\vec{E} = \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} + \\vec{P}$. This implies that $\\varepsilon \\vec{E} = \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} + \\vec{P}$. The term $\\varepsilon$ in this context represents the absolute permittivity. However, the \"dielectric constant\" often refers to the dimensionless relative permittivity, $\\varepsilon_r = \\varepsilon / \\varepsilon_0$. We will derive this standard quantity, $\\varepsilon_r(\\omega)$, and following common convention, denote it as $\\varepsilon(\\omega)$.\n\nThe main assumptions of the model are:\n1.  The positive ions are massive and considered fixed.\n2.  The free electrons are treated as a sparse gas, meaning electron-electron interactions are ignored.\n3.  The electric field acting on each electron is the external applied field $\\vec{E}(t)$.\n4.  All dissipative forces (e.g., due to collisions) are negligible.\n\nTo simplify the analysis of the oscillatory system, we will use complex notation. The physical electric field $\\vec{E}(t) = \\vec{E}_0 \\sin(\\omega t)$ can be represented as the imaginary part of a complex phasor: $\\vec{E}(t) = \\text{Im}[\\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t)]$, where $\\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) = \\vec{E}_0 e^{i\\omega t}$. We will solve the problem using these complex quantities, as all governing equations are linear.\n\n### Step 1: Equation of Motion for a Free Electron\nWe apply Newton's second law to a single free electron. The only force considered is the electric force from the applied field.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{F}_{\\text{net}} = m\\vec{a}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{F}_{\\text{elec}} = q\\vec{E}}\\]\nThe net force on the electron is $\\vec{F}_{\\text{net}} = \\vec{F}_{\\text{elec}}$. Using the electron's charge $q=-e$ and its acceleration $\\vec{a} = d^2\\vec{r}/dt^2$, we write the equation of motion for the complex displacement phasor $\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)$ driven by the complex electric field $\\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm \\frac{d^2\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)}{dt^2} = -e \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) \\label{eq:eom_complex} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the complex form of the electric field, $\\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) = \\vec{E}_0 e^{i\\omega t}$, we get:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm \\frac{d^2\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)}{dt^2} = -e \\vec{E}_0 e^{i\\omega t} \\label{eq:eom_specific} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Solve for the Steady-State Electron Displacement\nWe seek the steady-state oscillatory solution for the electron's displacement, which will have the same frequency as the driving field. We propose a solution of the form:\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Ansatz for steady-state solution: } \\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t) = \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t}}\\]\nwhere $\\vec{r}_0$ is the complex amplitude of the displacement.\n\nTo substitute this ansatz into the equation of motion (eq. \\ref{eq:eom_specific}), we first need its second time derivative.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)}{dt} &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\left( \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t} \\right) = i\\omega \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t} \\label{eq:velocity} \\tag{3} \\\\\n\\frac{d^2\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)}{dt^2} &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\left( i\\omega \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t} \\right) = (i\\omega)^2 \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t} = -\\omega^2 \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t} \\label{eq:acceleration} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we substitute this expression for the acceleration into the equation of motion (eq. \\ref{eq:eom_specific}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm(-\\omega^2 \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t}) &= -e \\vec{E}_0 e^{i\\omega t} \\label{eq:eom_substituted} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe term $e^{i\\omega t}$ is non-zero and can be cancelled from both sides, leaving an equation for the amplitude $\\vec{r}_0$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n-m\\omega^2 \\vec{r}_0 &= -e \\vec{E}_0 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{r}_0 &= \\frac{e\\vec{E}_0}{m\\omega^2} \\label{eq:r0_solution} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThus, the complex displacement vector is related to the complex electric field vector by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t) = \\vec{r}_0 e^{i\\omega t} = \\left(\\frac{e\\vec{E}_0}{m\\omega^2}\\right) e^{i\\omega t} = \\frac{e}{m\\omega^2} \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) \\label{eq:r_vs_E} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Calculate the Polarization and Electric Susceptibility\nThe displacement of electrons creates a net electric dipole moment per unit volume, which is the polarization intensity $\\vec{P}$.\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Dipole moment of one electron-ion pair: } \\tilde{\\vec{p}}(t) = -e\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Polarization Intensity: } \\tilde{\\vec{P}}(t) = n \\tilde{\\vec{p}}(t)}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Electric Susceptibility Definition: } \\tilde{\\vec{P}}(t) = \\varepsilon_0 \\chi_e(\\omega) \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t)}\\]\nFirst, we find the complex polarization $\\tilde{\\vec{P}}(t)$ by combining the first two principles and using the result from Step 2 (eq. \\ref{eq:r_vs_E}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\tilde{\\vec{P}}(t) = n(-e\\tilde{\\vec{r}}(t)) = -ne \\left( \\frac{e}{m\\omega^2} \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) \\right) = -\\frac{ne^2}{m\\omega^2} \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) \\label{eq:polarization} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNext, we compare this result with the definition of the electric susceptibility, $\\chi_e(\\omega)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\varepsilon_0 \\chi_e(\\omega) \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) &= -\\frac{ne^2}{m\\omega^2} \\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t) \\label{eq:compare_P} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nBy cancelling $\\tilde{\\vec{E}}(t)$, we find the expression for the electric susceptibility:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\chi_e(\\omega) = -\\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m\\omega^2} \\label{eq:susceptibility} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Determine the AC Dielectric Constant\nThe relative dielectric constant $\\varepsilon_r(\\omega)$ is related to the electric susceptibility $\\chi_e(\\omega)$. We derive this relationship from the fundamental constitutive relations.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{D} = \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} + \\vec{P}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{D} = \\varepsilon_r \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{P} = \\varepsilon_0 \\chi_e \\vec{E}}\\]\nFirst, we derive the general relationship between relative permittivity $\\varepsilon_r$ and electric susceptibility $\\chi_e$. We equate the two expressions for the electric displacement vector $\\vec{D}$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\varepsilon_r \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} = \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} + \\vec{P} \\label{eq:D_equated} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the definition of susceptibility, $\\vec{P} = \\varepsilon_0 \\chi_e \\vec{E}$, into eq. \\ref{eq:D_equated}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\varepsilon_r \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} &= \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} + \\varepsilon_0 \\chi_e \\vec{E} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\varepsilon_r \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} &= \\varepsilon_0 (1 + \\chi_e) \\vec{E} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Dividing by } \\varepsilon_0 \\vec{E} \\text{ (assuming } \\vec{E} \\neq 0): \\nonumber \\\\\n\\varepsilon_r(\\omega) &= 1 + \\chi_e(\\omega) \\label{eq:er_chi_relation} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis relationship holds generally for linear, isotropic media. Now, we use the specific expression for the susceptibility of the free electron gas derived in Step 3 (eq. \\ref{eq:susceptibility}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\varepsilon_r(\\omega) = 1 + \\left( -\\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m\\omega^2} \\right) = 1 - \\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m\\omega^2} \\label{eq:er_final} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nAs established in the problem explanation, we identify the requested AC dielectric constant $\\varepsilon(\\omega)$ with the relative permittivity $\\varepsilon_r(\\omega)$. The term $\\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m}$ is the square of the electron plasma frequency, $\\omega_p^2$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\varepsilon(\\omega) = 1 - \\frac{\\omega_p^2}{\\omega^2}, \\quad \\text{where} \\quad \\omega_p^2 = \\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m} \\label{eq:final_with_wp} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe AC dielectric constant $\\varepsilon(\\omega)$ of the metal is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\varepsilon(\\omega) = 1 - \\frac{ne^2}{\\varepsilon_0 m\\omega^2}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/670", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "Consider a plasma system composed of protons and electrons, where the equilibrium number density of positive and negative charges is \\( n_0 \\). A point charge \\( q \\) is placed in this plasma. Due to the Coulomb interaction, the point charge will attract opposite charges and repel like charges, causing a change in the charge distribution within the plasma: within a certain spatial range around the point charge, the densities of positive and negative charges are no longer equal, thereby weakening the electric field of the point charge. This phenomenon is known as Debye shielding.  It is known that in spherical coordinates, the Poisson equation for the electrostatic field is: \\[ \\nabla^2 \\varphi = \\frac{1}{r^2} \\frac{d}{dr} \\left( r^2 \\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\varphi}{\\mathrm{d}r} \\right) = -\\frac{\\rho(r)}{\\varepsilon_0}, \\] where \\( \\varphi(r) \\) is the electric potential distribution. Hint: try assuming a trial solution of the form \\( \\varphi(r) = \\frac{u(r)}{r} \\).  Assume the plasma satisfies the following conditions: At equilibrium, the number density \\( n(\\varphi) \\) of protons and electrons follows the Boltzmann distribution; The plasma is overall electrically neutral; \\( e\\varphi \\ll kT \\) (\\( e \\) is the elementary charge, \\( k \\) is the Boltzmann constant, \\( T \\) is the plasma temperature).  The Debye radius \\( \\lambda_D \\) is defined as the distance at which the potential decays to \\( \\frac{1}{e} \\) of the vacuum point charge potential. Derive the expression for \\( \\lambda_D \\).", "solutions": "The number density of positive and negative ions are respectively:   $$ n_{i}(\\varphi)=n_{i0}e^{-\\frac{e\\varphi}{k T}} $$  $$ n_{e}(\\varphi)=n_{e0}e^{\\frac{e\\varphi}{k T}} $$  Charge density:   $$ \\rho=n_{i}q+n_{e}(-q)=n_{i0}e\\cdot e^{-{\\frac{e\\varphi}{k T}}}-n_{e0}e\\cdot e^{\\frac{e\\varphi}{k T}} $$ The plasma is electrically neutral, i.e.,   $$ n_{i0}=n_{e0}=n_{0} $$ Thus, we can get:   $$ \\rho=-2\\frac{e^{2}\\varphi}{k T}n_{0} $$ Then the Poisson's equation becomes:   $$ \\frac{1}{r^{2}}\\frac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}r}(r^{2}\\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\varphi}{\\mathrm{d}r})=\\frac{2e^{2}\\varphi n_{0}}{k T\\varepsilon_{0}} $$ Let $\\varphi={\\frac{u}{r}}$, substitute and simplify to obtain:   $$ \\frac{\\mathrm{d}^{2}u}{\\mathrm{d}r^{2}}=\\frac{2e^{2}u n_{0}}{k T\\varepsilon_{0}} $$ $\\lambda_{D}=\\sqrt{\\frac{k T\\varepsilon_{0}}{2e^{2}n_{0}}}$ From the original equation, it is easy to get:   $$ u=C_{1}e^{\\frac{r}{\\lambda_{D}}}+C_{2}e^{-\\frac{r}{\\lambda_{D}}} $$ Considering the actual situation, the plasma is electrically neutral at infinity, so the potential must converge, thus $C_{1}=0$, and the potential tends towards that of a point charge at infinitesimal distances, hence   $$ \\varphi(r)={\\frac{u}{r}}={\\frac{q}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_{0}r}}e^{-{\\frac{r}{\\lambda_{D}}}} $$ According to the problem statement, the characteristic scale of the Debye shielding is given directly as:   $$ \\lambda_{_D}=\\sqrt{\\frac{k T\\varepsilon_{0}}{2e^{2}n_{0}}} $$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\lambda_D = \\sqrt{\\frac{k T \\varepsilon_0}{2 e^2 n_0}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the derivation of the expression for the Debye radius, \\( \\lambda_D \\), in a plasma. The plasma consists of protons and electrons and is in thermal equilibrium at a temperature \\( T \\). A point charge \\( q \\) is introduced, creating a spherically symmetric electrostatic potential \\( \\varphi(r) \\). This potential perturbs the charge distribution, leading to a screening effect.\n\nThe problem provides the following information, variables, and assumptions:\n1.  **Physical System**: A plasma composed of protons (charge \\(+e\\)) and electrons (charge \\(-e\\)).\n2.  **Variables and Constants**:\n    *   \\( n_0 \\): The equilibrium number density of both protons and electrons far from the point charge.\n    *   \\( q \\): The magnitude of the point charge introduced into the plasma.\n    *   \\( \\varphi(r) \\): The electrostatic potential at a distance \\( r \\) from the charge \\( q \\).\n    *   \\( \\rho(r) \\): The net charge density at a distance \\( r \\).\n    *   \\( e \\): The elementary charge.\n    *   \\( k \\): The Boltzmann constant.\n    *   \\( T \\): The absolute temperature of the plasma.\n    *   \\( \\varepsilon_0 \\): The vacuum permittivity.\n    *   \\( \\lambda_D \\): The Debye radius, the quantity to be derived.\n3.  **Governing Equation**: The electrostatic potential is governed by Poisson's equation, which in spherical coordinates is given as:\n    \\[ \\nabla^2 \\varphi = \\frac{1}{r^2} \\frac{d}{dr} \\left( r^2 \\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\varphi}{\\mathrm{d}r} \\right) = -\\frac{\\rho(r)}{\\varepsilon_0} \\]\n4.  **Assumptions and Conditions**:\n    *   The number densities of protons (\\(n_p\\)) and electrons (\\(n_e\\)) follow the Boltzmann distribution.\n    *   The plasma is electrically neutral far from the point charge \\( q \\). This implies the boundary condition \\( \\varphi(r) \\to 0 \\) as \\( r \\to \\infty \\).\n    *   The potential energy of the charges is much smaller than their thermal energy, leading to the weak potential approximation: \\( |e\\varphi| \\ll kT \\).\n5.  **Hint**: A trial solution of the form \\( \\varphi(r) = \\frac{u(r)}{r} \\) can simplify the Laplacian operator in Poisson's equation.\n6.  **Definition**: The Debye radius \\( \\lambda_D \\) is physically described as the distance at which the potential decays to \\( \\frac{1}{e} \\) of the vacuum point charge potential.\n\nThe goal is to derive the mathematical expression for \\( \\lambda_D \\) using these principles.\n\n### Step 1: Determine the Net Charge Density from Boltzmann Statistics\nFirst, we express the number densities of protons and electrons as a function of the electrostatic potential \\( \\varphi \\). The Boltzmann distribution gives the number density of a species in thermal equilibrium.\n\\[\\boxed{ n = C e^{-U/kT} }\\]\nHere, \\( U \\) is the potential energy of a particle and \\( C \\) is a normalization constant. The potential energy of a charge \\( q' \\) in an electrostatic potential \\( \\varphi \\) is:\n\\[\\boxed{ U = q' \\varphi }\\]\nFor protons (charge \\(+e\\)) and electrons (charge \\(-e\\)), the potential energies are \\( U_p = +e\\varphi \\) and \\( U_e = -e\\varphi \\), respectively. The constant \\( C \\) is determined by the boundary condition at \\( r \\to \\infty \\), where \\( \\varphi \\to 0 \\) and the densities of both species are \\( n_0 \\). This gives \\( n_0 = C e^0 \\), so \\( C = n_0 \\).\n\nThe number densities are therefore:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn_p(\\varphi) &= n_0 e^{-e\\varphi/kT} \\label{eq:np} \\tag{1} \\\\\nn_e(\\varphi) &= n_0 e^{-(-e\\varphi)/kT} = n_0 e^{+e\\varphi/kT} \\label{eq:ne} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe net charge density \\( \\rho \\) is the sum of charge densities from all species.\n\\[\\boxed{ \\rho = \\sum_i n_i q'_i }\\]\nApplying this to our plasma:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\rho(\\varphi) &= (+e)n_p(\\varphi) + (-e)n_e(\\varphi) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= e(n_p(\\varphi) - n_e(\\varphi)) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= e n_0 \\left( e^{-e\\varphi/kT} - e^{+e\\varphi/kT} \\right) \\label{eq:rho_exact} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Linearize the Charge Density Expression\nWe use the weak potential approximation, \\( |e\\varphi| \\ll kT \\), to simplify the expression for the charge density. This condition allows us to linearize the exponential terms using a first-order Taylor expansion.\n\\[\\boxed{ e^x \\approx 1 + x \\quad \\text{for } |x| \\ll 1 }\\]\nLet \\( x = \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT} \\). The assumption \\( |e\\varphi| \\ll kT \\) implies \\( |x| \\ll 1 \\). The expansions are:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ne^{-e\\varphi/kT} &\\approx 1 - \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT} \\label{eq:taylor_minus} \\tag{4} \\\\\ne^{+e\\varphi/kT} &\\approx 1 + \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT} \\label{eq:taylor_plus} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting these approximations into the charge density equation (\\ref{eq:rho_exact}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\rho(\\varphi) &\\approx e n_0 \\left[ \\left(1 - \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT}\\right) - \\left(1 + \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= e n_0 \\left( 1 - \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT} - 1 - \\frac{e\\varphi}{kT} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= e n_0 \\left( -\\frac{2e\\varphi}{kT} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{2n_0 e^2}{kT} \\varphi \\label{eq:rho_linear} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis linearized relation shows that the net charge density induced by the potential is directly proportional to the potential itself.\n\n### Step 3: Formulate the Screened Poisson Equation\nNext, we substitute the linearized expression for the charge density \\( \\rho(\\varphi) \\) into Poisson's equation.\n\\[\\boxed{ \\nabla^2 \\varphi = -\\frac{\\rho}{\\varepsilon_0} }\\]\nUsing the result from equation (\\ref{eq:rho_linear}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\nabla^2 \\varphi &= -\\frac{1}{\\varepsilon_0} \\left( -\\frac{2n_0 e^2}{kT} \\varphi \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\nabla^2 \\varphi &= \\left( \\frac{2n_0 e^2}{\\varepsilon_0 kT} \\right) \\varphi \\label{eq:screened_poisson} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is the linearized Poisson-Boltzmann equation, also known as the screened Poisson equation. It describes how the electrostatic potential behaves in a medium that screens the charge.\n\n### Step 4: Solve the Screened Poisson Equation to Find the Potential's Form\nTo understand the physical meaning of the constant term in equation (\\ref{eq:screened_poisson}) and to verify the screening behavior, we solve this differential equation. We define a characteristic length \\( \\lambda_D \\) such that the equation takes a standard form.\n\\[\\boxed{ \\frac{1}{\\lambda_D^2} \\equiv \\frac{2n_0 e^2}{\\varepsilon_0 kT} }\\]\nThe differential equation becomes \\( \\nabla^2 \\varphi = \\frac{1}{\\lambda_D^2} \\varphi \\). We solve this using the hint and boundary conditions.\n\\[\\boxed{ \\nabla^2 \\varphi = \\frac{1}{r^2} \\frac{d}{dr} \\left( r^2 \\frac{d\\varphi}{dr} \\right) }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\varphi(r) = \\frac{u(r)}{r} }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\text{Boundary Condition: } \\lim_{r\\to\\infty} \\varphi(r) = 0 }\\]\nFirst, we apply the substitution \\( \\varphi(r) = u(r)/r \\) to the Laplacian operator:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\nabla^2 \\varphi = \\nabla^2 \\left(\\frac{u}{r}\\right) = \\frac{1}{r^2} \\frac{d}{dr} \\left( r^2 \\frac{d}{dr} \\left(\\frac{u}{r}\\right) \\right) = \\frac{1}{r^2} \\frac{d}{dr} \\left( r^2 \\left(\\frac{u'}{r} - \\frac{u}{r^2}\\right) \\right) = \\frac{1}{r^2} \\frac{d}{dr} \\left( r u' - u \\right) = \\frac{1}{r^2} (u' + ru'' - u') = \\frac{u''}{r} \\label{eq:laplacian_u} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting this into the screened Poisson equation \\( \\nabla^2 \\varphi = \\varphi / \\lambda_D^2 \\):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{u''}{r} &= \\frac{1}{\\lambda_D^2} \\frac{u}{r} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{d^2u}{dr^2} - \\frac{1}{\\lambda_D^2} u &= 0 \\label{eq:ode_u} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is a standard second-order homogeneous linear ODE. Its general solution is \\( u(r) = C_1 e^{-r/\\lambda_D} + C_2 e^{r/\\lambda_D} \\). The potential is then \\( \\varphi(r) = \\frac{1}{r} (C_1 e^{-r/\\lambda_D} + C_2 e^{r/\\lambda_D}) \\). Applying the boundary condition that \\( \\varphi(r) \\to 0 \\) as \\( r \\to \\infty \\) requires \\( C_2 = 0 \\), since the \\( e^{r/\\lambda_D} \\) term would otherwise diverge. The physical solution is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\varphi(r) = \\frac{C_1}{r} e^{-r/\\lambda_D} \\label{eq:debye_potential} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis result, the Debye-Hückel potential, shows that the potential is a Coulomb-like potential (\\( \\propto 1/r \\)) multiplied by an exponential decay factor. The characteristic length of this decay is \\( \\lambda_D \\), confirming its role as the screening length.\n\n### Step 5: Derive the Expression for the Debye Radius\nIn Step 4, we defined the Debye radius \\( \\lambda_D \\) in terms of the physical constants of the plasma. We now write down this relationship and solve for \\( \\lambda_D \\).\n\\[\\boxed{ \\frac{1}{\\lambda_D^2} = \\frac{2n_0 e^2}{\\varepsilon_0 kT} }\\]\nBy taking the reciprocal of both sides, we obtain an expression for \\( \\lambda_D^2 \\).\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\lambda_D^2 &= \\frac{\\varepsilon_0 kT}{2n_0 e^2} \\label{eq:lambda_sq} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTaking the square root of both sides gives the final expression for the Debye radius.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\lambda_D &= \\sqrt{\\frac{\\varepsilon_0 kT}{2n_0 e^2}} \\label{eq:lambda_D_final} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe derived expression for the Debye radius \\( \\lambda_D \\) is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\lambda_D = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\varepsilon_0 kT}{2n_0 e^2}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/140", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "Three identical homogeneous balls are placed on a smooth horizontal surface, touching each other and are close enough to each other. A rope is wrapped around the spheres at the height of their centers, tying them together. A fourth identical sphere is placed on top of the three spheres. Find the tension $T$ in the rope. It is given that the weight of each sphere is $P$.", "solutions": "In the text, $P$ represents the gravity on sphere $O$.\n\nSince the spheres are completely identical, the string forms part of an equilateral triangle, so the tension $T$ along the direction $CG$ for sphere $C$ should equal the component of $N$ in that direction, i.e.,\n\n$$\n2T\\cos{\\frac{\\pi}{6}} = N\\cos\\theta.\n$$\n\nFrom equation (1) and equation (2), we have\n\n$$\nT = {\\frac{P}{3{\\sqrt{3}}}}\\cot\\theta.\n$$\n\nSince $G$ is the center of the equilateral triangle $ABC$ formed by the centers of spheres $A$, $B$, and $C$ (Figure 1.11(c)), from geometric relationships, we know\n\n$$\nCG = \\frac{2}{3}(2R)\\cos{\\frac{\\pi}{6}} = \\frac{2R}{\\sqrt{3}},\n$$\n\nthus,\n\n$$\n\\cos\\theta = {\\frac{CG}{CO}} = {\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}}, \\quad \\cot\\theta = {\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}}.\n$$\n\nSubstituting equation (4) into equation (3), we get\n\n$$\nT = {\\frac{\\sqrt{6}}{18}}P.\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\\frac{\\sqrt{6}}{18}P$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem describes a system of four identical, homogeneous spheres in static equilibrium. Three spheres (let's call them A, B, and C) are placed on a smooth horizontal surface, arranged symmetrically such that they are in contact with each other. A rope is wrapped around the equators of these three spheres. A fourth sphere (O) is placed on top, resting in the hollow formed by the three bottom spheres. The system is held together by the tension in the rope. We are asked to find this tension.\n\nThe given information is:\n*   There are four identical, homogeneous spheres.\n*   The weight of each sphere is $P$.\n*   The horizontal surface is smooth, implying it is frictionless.\n*   The system is in static equilibrium.\n\nLet's define the variables and geometric points:\n*   $P$: The weight of each sphere.\n*   $R$: The radius of each sphere.\n*   $T$: The tension in the rope.\n*   A, B, C: The centers of the three spheres on the horizontal plane. These points form an equilateral triangle.\n*   O: The center of the fourth sphere placed on top.\n*   G: The centroid of the equilateral triangle ABC. Due to symmetry, O is located directly above G.\n*   $N$: The magnitude of the normal force exerted by any of the bottom spheres on the top sphere.\n\nAssumptions:\n1.  The system is in static equilibrium, so the net force on each sphere is zero.\n2.  The rope is inextensible and massless. It is wrapped horizontally at the height of the centers of the bottom spheres.\n3.  The three bottom spheres are identical and arranged symmetrically. Thus, the forces they exert on the top sphere are identical in magnitude, and the forces exerted on them by the top sphere are also identical.\n4.  The rope provides the necessary inward force to counteract the outward push from the top sphere. This implies that the normal forces between the bottom spheres themselves (e.g., between sphere A and sphere B) are zero. The tension in the rope is precisely what is needed to maintain the configuration.\n\nThe goal is to find the tension $T$ in terms of the given weight $P$.\n\n### Step 1: Geometric Analysis of the Sphere Arrangement\nTo analyze the forces, we first need to determine the geometry of the sphere configuration. Specifically, we need the angle between the line connecting the center of the top sphere to a bottom sphere and the vertical axis. The centers of the three bottom spheres (A, B, C) form an equilateral triangle on the horizontal plane. The center of the top sphere (O) is located directly above the centroid (G) of this triangle.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Distance between centers of two touching spheres} = 2R}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{For an equilateral triangle with side length } a \\text{, the distance from a vertex to the centroid is } d = \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{3}}}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Definition of sine: } \\sin\\theta = \\frac{\\text{opposite}}{\\text{hypotenuse}}}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Definition of cosine: } \\cos\\theta = \\frac{\\text{adjacent}}{\\text{hypotenuse}}}\n\\]\nThe derivation of the key angle is as follows:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n& \\text{The centers A, B, C form an equilateral triangle with side length } a = 2R, \\text{ as the spheres are touching.} \\label{eq:side_length} \\\\\n& \\text{The distance from any vertex (e.g., C) to the centroid G is given by the formula for an equilateral triangle:} \\nonumber \\\\\n& CG = \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{2R}{\\sqrt{3}}. \\label{eq:centroid_dist} \\\\\n& \\text{The top sphere O touches the bottom sphere C, so the distance between their centers is the sum of their radii:} \\nonumber \\\\\n& OC = R + R = 2R. \\label{eq:center_dist} \\\\\n& \\text{The line segment OG is vertical, and CG is horizontal. Thus, } \\triangle OGC \\text{ is a right-angled triangle with the right angle at G.} \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{Let } \\theta \\text{ be the angle between the line of centers OC and the vertical axis OG. Thus, } \\theta = \\angle COG. \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{In the right-angled } \\triangle OGC, \\text{ we can find } \\sin\\theta \\text{ and } \\cos\\theta. \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\sin\\theta = \\frac{\\text{opposite}}{\\text{hypotenuse}} = \\frac{CG}{OC} = \\frac{2R/\\sqrt{3}}{2R} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}. \\label{eq:sin_theta} \\\\\n& \\text{Using the Pythagorean identity } \\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta = 1, \\text{ we find } \\cos\\theta: \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\cos\\theta = \\sqrt{1 - \\sin^2\\theta} = \\sqrt{1 - \\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right)^2} = \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{1}{3}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{2}{3}}. \\label{eq:cos_theta}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Force Equilibrium of the Top Sphere\nWe apply the condition for static equilibrium to the top sphere (center O). The vector sum of all forces acting on this sphere must be zero.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\sum \\vec{F} = 0}\n\\]\nThe forces acting on the top sphere are its weight $\\vec{P}$ (acting vertically downwards through O) and the three normal forces from the bottom spheres, $\\vec{N}_{A}$, $\\vec{N}_{B}$, and $\\vec{N}_{C}$. By symmetry, the magnitudes of these normal forces are equal, i.e., $|\\vec{N}_{A}| = |\\vec{N}_{B}| = |\\vec{N}_{C}| = N$. Each normal force acts along the line connecting the centers of the respective spheres (e.g., along CO for sphere C).\n\nWe consider the equilibrium of forces in the vertical direction. The horizontal components of the three normal forces cancel each other out due to the symmetric arrangement.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\sum F_{\\text{vertical}} &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{The vertical component of each normal force is directed upwards and has magnitude } N_{\\text{vertical}} = N \\cos\\theta. \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{The total upward force from the three normal forces must balance the downward weight P.} \\nonumber \\\\\n3 (N \\cos\\theta) - P &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\nN &= \\frac{P}{3\\cos\\theta}. \\label{eq:normal_force}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Force Equilibrium of a Bottom Sphere\nNext, we analyze the forces acting on one of the bottom spheres, for example, the sphere with center C. We consider the equilibrium of forces in the horizontal plane.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\sum \\vec{F} = 0}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Newton's Third Law: } \\vec{F}_{12} = -\\vec{F}_{21}}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\text{Resultant of two equal forces: For two forces of magnitude } F \\text{ with an angle } \\phi \\text{ between them, the magnitude of their resultant is } R = 2F \\cos(\\phi/2).}\n\\]\nThe horizontal forces acting on sphere C are:\n1.  The horizontal component of the reaction force from the top sphere O. By Newton's third law, the force exerted by sphere O on sphere C is equal and opposite to the force exerted by C on O. This reaction force has magnitude $N$ and is directed from O to C. Its horizontal component, $N_h$, acts radially outwards from the center of the system (along the line GC).\n2.  The tension forces from the rope. The rope segments connecting to spheres A and B pull on sphere C. Each force has magnitude $T$. These forces act along the lines CA and CB.\n\nWe apply the equilibrium condition in the horizontal plane:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\sum F_{\\text{horizontal}} &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{The outward horizontal force from the top sphere has magnitude } N_h = N\\sin\\theta. \\label{eq:nh} \\\\\n& \\text{The two tension forces } \\vec{T}_{CA} \\text{ and } \\vec{T}_{CB} \\text{ act along the sides of the equilateral triangle ABC. The angle between them is } 60^\\circ. \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{Their resultant, } \\vec{F}_T = \\vec{T}_{CA} + \\vec{T}_{CB}, \\text{ acts inwards along the line of symmetry GC.} \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{Using the principle for the resultant of two equal forces, with } F=T \\text{ and } \\phi=60^\\circ: \\nonumber \\\\\n& F_T = 2T\\cos\\left(\\frac{60^\\circ}{2}\\right) = 2T\\cos(30^\\circ) = 2T\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} = T\\sqrt{3}. \\label{eq:ft} \\\\\n& \\text{For equilibrium, the inward resultant tension force must balance the outward horizontal force from the top sphere.} \\nonumber \\\\\nF_T &= N_h \\nonumber \\\\\nT\\sqrt{3} &= N\\sin\\theta. \\label{eq:tension_balance}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculation of the Tension T\nFinally, we combine the equations derived in the previous steps to solve for the tension $T$. We substitute the expression for the normal force $N$ from Step 2 into the force balance equation from Step 3.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n& \\text{From Step 3, we have the relation: } T\\sqrt{3} = N\\sin\\theta. \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{From Step 2, we have the expression for N: } N = \\frac{P}{3\\cos\\theta}. \\quad (\\text{from eq. \\ref{eq:normal_force}}) \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{Substituting N into the first equation:} \\nonumber \\\\\nT\\sqrt{3} &= \\left(\\frac{P}{3\\cos\\theta}\\right) \\sin\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\nT\\sqrt{3} &= \\frac{P}{3} \\frac{\\sin\\theta}{\\cos\\theta} = \\frac{P}{3} \\tan\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\nT &= \\frac{P}{3\\sqrt{3}} \\tan\\theta. \\label{eq:tension_formula} \\\\\n& \\text{From Step 1, we have the values for } \\sin\\theta \\text{ and } \\cos\\theta: \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\sin\\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\quad (\\text{from eq. \\ref{eq:sin_theta}}) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\cos\\theta = \\sqrt{\\frac{2}{3}} \\quad (\\text{from eq. \\ref{eq:cos_theta}}). \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\text{Therefore, the tangent of the angle is:} \\nonumber \\\\\n& \\tan\\theta = \\frac{\\sin\\theta}{\\cos\\theta} = \\frac{1/\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{2/3}} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{2}} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}. \\label{eq:tan_theta} \\\\\n& \\text{Substituting this value into the expression for T (eq. \\ref{eq:tension_formula}):} \\nonumber \\\\\nT &= \\frac{P}{3\\sqrt{3}} \\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\right) = \\frac{P}{3\\sqrt{6}}. \\label{eq:tension_unrationalized} \\\\\n& \\text{To rationalize the denominator, we multiply the numerator and denominator by } \\sqrt{6}: \\nonumber \\\\\nT &= \\frac{P}{3\\sqrt{6}} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{6}}{\\sqrt{6}} = \\frac{P\\sqrt{6}}{3 \\times 6} = \\frac{\\sqrt{6}}{18}P. \\label{eq:tension_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe tension $T$ in the rope is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{T = \\frac{\\sqrt{6}}{18}P}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/653", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "A massless insulating string of length $\\alpha$ is fixed at one end, with a conductor ring of mass $m$ and radius $r$ ($r \\ll \\alpha$) suspended on the other end, forming a simple pendulum. Initially, the pendulum string is vertical, and the ring is just inside a sector of a uniform magnetic field. The center of the sector is at the suspension point, with its edges just tangent to the ring. The magnetic field is perpendicular to the plane of the ring and directed inward, with a magnetic flux density of $B$. If the ring is given an initial horizontal velocity (perpendicular to the magnetic field) with a magnitude of $v$, what is the minimum initial velocity $v_{0}$ required for the pendulum string to reach the horizontal direction? The gravitational acceleration is $g$, the magnetic field is sufficiently strong, and the torque due to the Ampere force is much greater than the torque due to gravity when the ring moves within the magnetic field. The ring is a superconducting ring with a self-inductance coefficient $L$.", "solutions": "If the ring is a superconducting ring, when it moves in a magnetic field, due to the properties of the superconductor, the magnetic flux in the ring remains unchanged, i.e.:  $$ L I + B S = B \\cdot \\pi r^2 $$  Thus, the current in the ring is:  $$ \\begin{array}{l}{I = \\displaystyle\\frac{B}{L}(\\pi r^{2} - S)}\\ = \\displaystyle\\frac{B}{L}\\left\\{r^{2}\\arcsin\\left[\\frac{a(\\theta_{0}-\\theta)}{r}\\right] - \\sqrt{2r a\\theta-a^{2}\\theta^{2}} \\cdot a(\\theta_{0}-\\theta)\\right\\}\\end{array} $$  $$ \\phi = \\operatorname{arccos}\\left[\\frac{a(\\theta_{0}-\\theta)}{r}\\right] $$  We have:  $$ \\cos\\phi = \\frac{a(\\theta_{0}-\\theta)}{r}, \\sin\\phi = \\sqrt{1-\\cos^{2}\\phi} = \\sqrt{1-\\frac{a^{2}(\\theta_{0}-\\theta)^{2}}{r^{2}}} $$  Thus:  $$ I = \\frac{B}{L}(r^{2}\\phi - r^{2}\\sin\\phi\\cos\\phi), l = 2r\\sin\\phi $$  The torque about the suspension point due to the Ampère force acting on the part of the ring within the magnetic field is approximately:  $$ \\tau = I B l a = \\frac{2B^{2}r a}{L}(r^{2}\\phi - r^{2}\\sin\\phi\\cos\\phi)\\sin\\phi $$  The dynamic equation of the ring is:  $$ m a^{2}\\frac{d\\omega}{dt} = -\\frac{2B^{2}r a}{L}(r^{2}\\phi - r^{2}\\sin\\phi\\cos\\phi)\\sin\\phi $$  Since $\\frac{d\\omega}{dt} = \\omega\\frac{d\\omega}{d\\theta}$, we have:  $$ d\\theta = \\frac{r}{a} \\sin (\\phi) d\\phi $$  Thus:  Integrating both sides, given that initially when $\\theta = 0$, $\\phi = 0$, and $\\omega \\approx \\frac{v_{0}}{a}$, we have:  $$ m a^{2}\\int_{\\frac{v_{0}}{a}}^{\\omega}\\omega d\\omega = -\\frac{2B^{2}r^{4}}{L}\\int_{0}^{\\phi}\\left(\\phi - \\sin\\phi\\cos\\phi\\right)\\sin^{2}\\phi d\\phi $$  We obtain:  $$ \\frac{1}{2}m a^{2}\\left(\\omega^{2}-\\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{a^{2}}\\right) = -\\frac{B^{2}r^{4}}{2L}\\left[\\phi^{2} - \\phi\\sin2\\phi - \\frac{1}{2}(\\cos2\\phi - 1) - \\sin^{4}\\phi\\right] $$  Thus:  $$ \\omega^{2} = \\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{a^{2}} - \\frac{B^{2}r^{4}}{m a^{2}L}\\left[\\phi^{2} - \\phi\\sin2\\phi - \\frac{1}{2}(\\cos2\\phi - 1) - \\sin^{4}\\phi\\right] $$  When the ring has just completely left the magnetic field area, $\\theta = 2\\theta_{0}$, corresponding to $\\phi = \\pi$, substituting into the above equation, we get:  $$ \\omega_{2}^{2} = \\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{a^{2}} - \\frac{\\pi^{2}B^{2}r^{4}}{m a^{2}L} $$  To make the pendulum reach the horizontal direction, it should satisfy:  $$ v_{0} = \\sqrt{2g a + \\frac{\\pi^{2}B^{2}r^{4}}{m L}} $$", "final_answers": "$$\\sqrt{2g \\alpha+\\frac{\\pi^2 B^2 r^4}{m L}}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem describes a simple pendulum composed of a massless insulating string of length $\\alpha$ and a bob, which is a superconducting conductor ring. The ring has a mass $m$, radius $r$, and self-inductance $L$. The pendulum is pivoted at one end of the string.\n\nThe physical process unfolds as follows:\n1.  **Initial State**: The pendulum is at its lowest point, with the string vertical (angle $\\theta=0$ with respect to the vertical). The ring is situated within a sector-shaped region of a uniform magnetic field of magnitude $B$. The field is perpendicular to the plane of the pendulum's swing. The problem states \"the ring is just inside a sector... with its edges just tangent to the ring,\" which we interpret to mean the magnetic field fully encompasses the ring at its initial $\\theta=0$ position. The ring is then given an initial horizontal velocity $v_0$.\n2.  **Motion**: As the pendulum swings upwards, the ring exits the magnetic field. Because the ring is a superconductor (zero electrical resistance), an electrical current is induced to maintain a constant total magnetic flux through the ring. This induced current interacts with the external magnetic field, creating a magnetic (Ampere) force that opposes the motion.\n3.  **Final State**: We are asked to find the minimum initial velocity $v_0$ required for the pendulum to just reach the horizontal position, where the string makes an angle $\\theta = \\pi/2$ with the vertical. At this highest point of its trajectory, the ring's velocity is momentarily zero.\n\nThe variables are defined as:\n*   `α`: Length of the massless insulating string.\n*   `m`: Mass of the conductor ring.\n*   `r`: Radius of the ring.\n*   `L`: Self-inductance of the superconducting ring.\n*   `B`: Magnetic flux density of the uniform magnetic field.\n*   `g`: Acceleration due to gravity.\n*   `v_0`: The minimum initial horizontal velocity, which is the quantity to be determined.\n\nKey assumptions and conditions:\n1.  **Point Mass Approximation**: We are given `r ≪ α`. This allows us to treat the ring as a point mass for calculating its gravitational potential energy and kinetic energy, with its position being at a distance `α` from the pivot.\n2.  **Superconducting Ring**: The ring has zero electrical resistance. This implies that the total magnetic flux passing through the ring must remain constant.\n3.  **Strong Magnetic Field**: The problem states that the torque from the Ampere force is much greater than the torque from gravity while the ring is exiting the field. This implies the exit process is rapid and occurs over a very small angle near $\\theta=0$.\n4.  **Isolated System**: The system consists of the ring and the electromagnetic field. We assume no other external non-conservative forces like air resistance are present. Therefore, the total energy of this system (mechanical energy + magnetic energy) is conserved.\n\nOur goal is to find $v_0$ by applying the principle of conservation of total energy between the initial and final states.\n\n### Step 1: Define the Total Energy of the System\nFor the isolated system of the ring and the magnetic field, the total energy is the sum of the ring's kinetic energy ($K$), its gravitational potential energy ($U_g$), and the magnetic energy stored in the ring's self-inductance ($U_{\\text{mag}}$). This total energy is conserved.\n\\[\\boxed{E_{\\text{total}} = K + U_g + U_{\\text{mag}} = \\text{constant}}\\]\nThe standard formulas for these energy components are:\n\\[\\boxed{K = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{U_g = mgh}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{U_{\\text{mag}} = \\frac{1}{2}LI^2}\\]\nHere, $v$ is the speed of the ring, $h$ is its vertical height above a chosen reference level, $I$ is the current in the ring, and $L$ is its self-inductance. We define the lowest point of the swing ($\\theta=0$) as the reference level for gravitational potential energy, so $h=0$ at this point. For a pendulum of length $\\alpha$ at an angle $\\theta$ from the vertical, the height is $h = \\alpha(1 - \\cos\\theta)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nE_{\\text{total}} = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + mg\\alpha(1 - \\cos\\theta) + \\frac{1}{2}LI^2\n\\label{eq:total_energy_general} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Calculate the Total Energy in the Initial State\nWe apply the general energy expression to the initial state of the system ($t=0$). At this moment, the pendulum is at its lowest position and is given the initial velocity $v_0$.\nThe initial conditions are:\n*   Initial angle: $\\theta_i = 0$\n*   Initial velocity: $v_i = v_0$\n*   Initial current: $I_i = 0$, as the magnetic flux through the ring has not yet begun to change.\n\nSubstituting these values into the energy components:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Initial Kinetic Energy: } &K_i = \\frac{1}{2}mv_0^2 \\label{eq:K_i} \\tag{2} \\\\\n\\text{Initial Gravitational Potential Energy: } &U_{g,i} = mg\\alpha(1 - \\cos 0) = 0 \\label{eq:Ug_i} \\tag{3} \\\\\n\\text{Initial Magnetic Energy: } &U_{\\text{mag},i} = \\frac{1}{2}LI_i^2 = \\frac{1}{2}L(0)^2 = 0 \\label{eq:Umag_i} \\tag{4} \\\\\n\\ \\\\\n\\text{Total Initial Energy: } &E_i = K_i + U_{g,i} + U_{\\text{mag},i} = \\frac{1}{2}mv_0^2 \\label{eq:E_i} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Calculate the Total Energy in the Final State\nNext, we evaluate the total energy when the pendulum reaches its final state. This state is defined by the string being horizontal. For the minimum required initial velocity, the ring will momentarily come to rest at this point. Before calculating the final energy, we must determine the final current $I_f$ in the ring.\n\n**Part A: Find the Final Current using Flux Conservation**\nFor a superconducting loop, the total magnetic flux through it remains constant.\n\\[\\boxed{\\Phi_{\\text{total}} = \\Phi_B + LI = \\text{constant}}\\]\nwhere $\\Phi_B$ is the flux from the external magnetic field.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Initial Flux: } &\\text{The ring is fully inside the uniform magnetic field } B \\text{. The area of the ring is } A = \\pi r^2 \\text{. The initial current is } I_i=0. \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\Phi_{\\text{initial}} = \\Phi_{B,i} + LI_i = B(\\pi r^2) + L(0) = B\\pi r^2 \\label{eq:flux_i} \\tag{6} \\\\\n\\ \\\\\n\\text{Final Flux: } &\\text{The ring is completely outside the magnetic field, so the external flux is zero. The current is } I_f. \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\Phi_{\\text{final}} = \\Phi_{B,f} + LI_f = 0 + LI_f = LI_f \\label{eq:flux_f} \\tag{7} \\\\\n\\ \\\\\n&\\text{By conservation of flux, } \\Phi_{\\text{initial}} = \\Phi_{\\text{final}}: \\nonumber \\\\\n&LI_f = B\\pi r^2 \\implies I_f = \\frac{B\\pi r^2}{L} \\label{eq:I_f} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n**Part B: Calculate the Final Total Energy**\nThe final state conditions are:\n*   Final angle: $\\theta_f = \\pi/2$\n*   Final velocity: $v_f = 0$\n*   Final current: $I_f$ is given by eq. \\ref{eq:I_f}.\n\nSubstituting these into the energy components:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Final Kinetic Energy: } &K_f = \\frac{1}{2}mv_f^2 = 0 \\label{eq:K_f} \\tag{9} \\\\\n\\text{Final Gravitational Potential Energy: } &U_{g,f} = mg\\alpha(1 - \\cos(\\pi/2)) = mg\\alpha \\label{eq:Ug_f} \\tag{10} \\\\\n\\text{Final Magnetic Energy: } &U_{\\text{mag},f} = \\frac{1}{2}LI_f^2 = \\frac{1}{2}L\\left(\\frac{B\\pi r^2}{L}\\right)^2 = \\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{2L} \\label{eq:Umag_f} \\tag{11} \\\\\n\\ \\\\\n\\text{Total Final Energy: } &E_f = K_f + U_{g,f} + U_{\\text{mag},f} = mg\\alpha + \\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{2L} \\label{eq:E_f} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Apply Energy Conservation to Find v_0\nThe principle of conservation of total energy states that the total energy in the initial state must equal the total energy in the final state.\n\\[\\boxed{E_i = E_f}\\]\nWe substitute the expressions for $E_i$ from eq. \\ref{eq:E_i} and $E_f$ from eq. \\ref{eq:E_f} to solve for $v_0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{1}{2}mv_0^2 &= mg\\alpha + \\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{2L} \\quad (\\text{using eq. \\ref{eq:E_i} and eq. \\ref{eq:E_f}}) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Multiplying by 2: } \\quad mv_0^2 &= 2mg\\alpha + \\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{L} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Dividing by m: } \\quad v_0^2 &= 2g\\alpha + \\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{mL} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Taking the square root: } \\quad v_0 &= \\sqrt{2g\\alpha + \\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{mL}} \\label{eq:v0_final} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis result shows that the initial kinetic energy must be sufficient to provide both the increase in gravitational potential energy ($mg\\alpha$) and the energy stored in the inductor's magnetic field ($\\frac{B^2\\pi^2 r^4}{2L}$) when the ring exits the external field.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe minimum initial velocity $v_0$ required for the pendulum string to reach the horizontal direction is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{v_0 = \\sqrt{2g\\alpha + \\frac{\\pi^2 B^2 r^4}{mL}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/719", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "The martian atmosphere can be considered as composed only of very thin $CO_{2}$. The molar mass of this atmosphere is denoted by $\\mu$, and the atmosphere at the same height can be considered as an ideal gas in equilibrium. The mass of Mars is $M_{m}$ (far greater than the total mass of the martian atmosphere), and its radius is $R_{m}$. Assume the relationship between the atmospheric mass density and the height $h$ above the surface of Mars is given by  $$ \\alpha(h)=\\rho_{\\mathrm{o}}(1+\\frac{h}{R_{m}})^{1-n} $$  where $\\rho_{\\mathrm{0}}$ is a constant, and $\\textit{n}(n>4)$ is also a constant.  Derive the expression for the temperature $T(h)$ of the martian atmosphere as a function of the height $h$.  Express the result using the following physical quantities: the mass of Mars $M_{m}$, radius $R_{m}$, molar mass of the atmosphere $\\mu$, constant $n$, gravitational constant $G$, and ideal gas constant $R$.", "solutions": "(1) Basic Assumptions and Ideal Gas Law  In the atmosphere at a certain height \\( h \\) on Mars, a thin horizontally placed box-shaped region is defined. The volume of this region is \\( V \\), the mass of the atmosphere inside is \\( M \\), the pressure is \\( P(h) \\), and the temperature is \\( T(h) \\). Because the box is very thin, the density, pressure, and temperature of the gas can be considered constant.  According to the ideal gas law:  $$ P(h)V = n R T(h)  $$  The volume of the atmosphere inside the box is:  $$ V = \\frac{M}{\\rho(h)}  $$  The number of moles of the Mars atmosphere inside the box is:  $$ n = \\frac{M}{\\mu}  $$  By combining equations (1), (2), and (3), we get:  $$ T(h) = \\frac{P(h) \\mu}{\\rho(h) R}  $$  (2) Determine the Pressure \\( P(h) \\)  Consider a thin spherical cap-shaped atmospheric layer from height \\( x \\) to \\( x + dx \\), subtending a solid angle \\( \\Delta \\Omega \\). Let \\( \\Delta \\Omega \\) be very small, so that the radial lines on the side of the spherical cap can be considered parallel to each other.  From the force analysis, we know:  $$ [P(x + dx) - P(x)] \\cdot \\Delta \\Omega (R_m + x)^2 + \\rho(x) g(x) \\cdot \\Delta \\Omega (R_m + x)^2 dx = 0 $$  That is:  $$ \\frac{dP}{dx} = - \\rho(x) g(x)  $$  Where the gravitational acceleration from the surface of Mars to height \\( x \\) is:  $$ g(x) = \\frac{G M_m}{(R_m + x)^2} $$  Substituting into equation (6) and integrating, we obtain:  $$ P(h) = G M_m \\int_h^{\\infty} \\frac{\\rho(x)}{(R_m + x)^2} dx  $$  (3) Substitute and Determine the Temperature Expression  Substitute equation (7′) into equation (4), and use the density distribution expression provided in the problem:  $$ \\rho(x) = \\rho_0 \\left(1 + \\frac{x}{R_m}\\right)^{1 - n} $$  Finally, we get:  $$ T(h) = \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R (R_m + h)}  $$  Final Result (Temperature Distribution of Martian Atmosphere)  $$ \\boxed{T(h) = \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R (R_m + h)}} $$  This result indicates that the temperature of Mars' atmosphere decreases inversely with height \\( h \\).", "final_answers": "$$T(h) = \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R (R_m + h)}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThe problem asks for the temperature distribution $T(h)$ of the Martian atmosphere as a function of height $h$ above the surface. The atmosphere is treated as an ideal gas in equilibrium.\n\nThe given physical quantities and variables are:\n-   $h$: height above the surface of Mars.\n-   $M_m$: mass of Mars.\n-   $R_m$: radius of Mars.\n-   $\\mu$: molar mass of the Martian atmosphere (CO₂).\n-   $G$: the universal gravitational constant.\n-   $R$: the ideal gas constant.\n-   $n$: a dimensionless constant, with the condition $n > 4$.\n-   $\\rho_0$: a constant related to the atmospheric density at the surface.\n-   $\\rho(h)$: the mass density of the atmosphere at height $h$, given by the relation:\n    $$ \\rho(h)=\\rho_{\\mathrm{o}}\\left(1+\\frac{h}{R_{m}}\\right)^{1-n} $$\n\nWe assume the following:\n1.  The atmosphere is in hydrostatic equilibrium.\n2.  The atmosphere behaves as an ideal gas.\n3.  The total mass of the atmosphere is negligible compared to the mass of Mars ($M_m$), so the gravitational field is determined solely by $M_m$.\n4.  The atmosphere extends to a great height, and the pressure approaches zero as height approaches infinity.\n\nThe goal is to derive an expression for $T(h)$ in terms of $M_m, R_m, \\mu, n, G,$ and $R$.\n\n### Step 1: Temperature, Pressure, and Density Relation from the Ideal Gas Law\nFor an ideal gas, the relationship between pressure $P$, volume $V$, number of moles $n_{\\text{mol}}$, and temperature $T$ is given by the ideal gas law. We can express this law in terms of mass density $\\rho$.\n\\[\\boxed{PV = n_{\\text{mol}}RT}\\]\nThe number of moles $n_{\\text{mol}}$ can be expressed as the total mass $m$ of the gas divided by its molar mass $\\mu$. The density $\\rho$ is the mass per unit volume, $m/V$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn_{\\text{mol}} &= \\frac{m}{\\mu} \\label{eq:moles} \\tag{1} \\\\\n\\rho &= \\frac{m}{V} \\label{eq:density} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting these into the ideal gas law:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nP V &= \\left(\\frac{m}{\\mu}\\right) R T \\nonumber \\\\\nP &= \\left(\\frac{m}{V}\\right) \\frac{R T}{\\mu} \\nonumber \\\\\nP(h) &= \\frac{\\rho(h)}{\\mu} R T(h) \\label{eq:ideal_gas_density} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nHere, we have explicitly written the pressure, density, and temperature as functions of height $h$. We can rearrange this equation to express the temperature $T(h)$ in terms of pressure $P(h)$ and density $\\rho(h)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nT(h) = \\frac{\\mu P(h)}{R \\rho(h)} \\label{eq:temp_expression} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Hydrostatic Equilibrium and Gravitational Field\nTo find the pressure $P(h)$, we consider the condition of hydrostatic equilibrium for a small element of the atmosphere. Let's analyze the forces on a thin, horizontal slab of atmosphere of area $A$ and thickness $dh$ at a height $h$ above the surface. The condition for static equilibrium is that the net force on the slab is zero.\n\\[\\boxed{\\sum \\vec{F} = 0}\\]\nThe forces acting on the slab in the vertical direction are:\n1.  The upward force from the pressure below the slab: $F_{\\text{up}} = P(h)A$.\n2.  The downward force from the pressure above the slab: $F_{\\text{down,P}} = P(h+dh)A$.\n3.  The downward gravitational force on the slab: $dF_g = dm \\cdot g(h)$, where $dm$ is the mass of the slab and $g(h)$ is the gravitational acceleration at height $h$.\n\nThe mass of the slab is $dm = \\rho(h) dV = \\rho(h) A dh$. The gravitational acceleration at a distance $r = R_m + h$ from the center of Mars is given by Newton's law of universal gravitation.\n\\[\\boxed{g(h) = \\frac{G M_m}{(R_m + h)^2}}\\]\nFor equilibrium, the net force is zero:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nF_{\\text{up}} - F_{\\text{down,P}} - dF_g &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\nP(h)A - P(h+dh)A - \\rho(h) A dh \\cdot g(h) &= 0 \\label{eq:force_balance} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nDividing by the area $A$ and rearranging gives:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nP(h) - P(h+dh) &= \\rho(h) g(h) dh \\nonumber \\\\\n-\\frac{P(h+dh) - P(h)}{dh} &= \\rho(h) g(h) \\nonumber\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTaking the limit as $dh \\to 0$, we obtain the differential equation for hydrostatic equilibrium:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dP}{dh} = -\\rho(h) g(h) = -\\rho(h) \\frac{G M_m}{(R_m + h)^2} \\label{eq:hydrostatic} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Calculation of Pressure by Integration\nTo find the pressure $P(h)$, we integrate the hydrostatic equilibrium equation from height $h$ to infinity. This is based on the fundamental theorem of calculus.\n\\[\\boxed{P(h_2) - P(h_1) = \\int_{h_1}^{h_2} \\frac{dP}{dh'} dh'}\\]\nWe apply the boundary condition that the pressure at infinite height is zero.\n\\[\\boxed{P(h \\to \\infty) = 0}\\]\nLet's integrate Eq. \\eqref{eq:hydrostatic} from $h$ to $\\infty$. We use a dummy variable of integration $x$ to avoid confusion.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_{P(h)}^{P(\\infty)} dP &= \\int_h^{\\infty} -\\rho(x) \\frac{G M_m}{(R_m + x)^2} dx \\nonumber \\\\\nP(\\infty) - P(h) &= -G M_m \\int_h^{\\infty} \\frac{\\rho(x)}{(R_m + x)^2} dx \\nonumber \\\\\n0 - P(h) &= -G M_m \\int_h^{\\infty} \\frac{\\rho(x)}{(R_m + x)^2} dx \\nonumber \\\\\nP(h) &= G M_m \\int_h^{\\infty} \\frac{\\rho(x)}{(R_m + x)^2} dx \\label{eq:pressure_integral} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we substitute the given expression for density $\\rho(x) = \\rho_0 (1 + \\frac{x}{R_m})^{1-n} = \\rho_0 (\\frac{R_m+x}{R_m})^{1-n}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nP(h) &= G M_m \\int_h^{\\infty} \\frac{\\rho_0 \\left(\\frac{R_m+x}{R_m}\\right)^{1-n}}{(R_m + x)^2} dx \\nonumber \\\\\n&= G M_m \\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} \\int_h^{\\infty} \\frac{(R_m+x)^{1-n}}{(R_m + x)^2} dx \\nonumber \\\\\n&= G M_m \\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} \\int_h^{\\infty} (R_m+x)^{-n-1} dx \\label{eq:integral_to_solve} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe evaluate the integral. Since $n>4$, the exponent $-n$ is negative, so the term $(R_m+x)^{-n}$ approaches zero as $x \\to \\infty$, ensuring the integral converges.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_h^{\\infty} (R_m+x)^{-n-1} dx &= \\left[ \\frac{(R_m+x)^{-n}}{-n} \\right]_h^{\\infty} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\lim_{x \\to \\infty} \\left( \\frac{(R_m+x)^{-n}}{-n} \\right) - \\frac{(R_m+h)^{-n}}{-n} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 0 + \\frac{(R_m+h)^{-n}}{n} = \\frac{1}{n(R_m+h)^n} \\label{eq:integral_result} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting this result back into the expression for $P(h)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nP(h) = G M_m \\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} \\left( \\frac{1}{n(R_m+h)^n} \\right) \\label{eq:pressure_final} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Derivation of the Temperature Expression\nFinally, we substitute the expressions for pressure $P(h)$ (Eq. \\eqref{eq:pressure_final}) and density $\\rho(h)$ into our equation for temperature $T(h)$ from Step 1.\n\\[\\boxed{T(h) = \\frac{\\mu P(h)}{R \\rho(h)}}\\]\nThe density at height $h$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\rho(h) = \\rho_0 \\left(1+\\frac{h}{R_m}\\right)^{1-n} = \\rho_0 \\left(\\frac{R_m+h}{R_m}\\right)^{1-n} = \\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} (R_m+h)^{1-n} \\label{eq:density_h} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we perform the substitution using Eq. \\eqref{eq:temp_expression}, Eq. \\eqref{eq:pressure_final}, and Eq. \\eqref{eq:density_h}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nT(h) &= \\frac{\\mu}{R} \\frac{P(h)}{\\rho(h)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu}{R} \\frac{G M_m \\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} \\left( \\frac{1}{n(R_m+h)^n} \\right)}{\\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} (R_m+h)^{1-n}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R} \\frac{\\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} (R_m+h)^{-n}}{\\rho_0 R_m^{n-1} (R_m+h)^{1-n}} \\label{eq:temp_substitute} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe terms $\\rho_0$ and $R_m^{n-1}$ cancel out. We simplify the remaining expression:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nT(h) &= \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R} \\frac{(R_m+h)^{-n}}{(R_m+h)^{1-n}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R} (R_m+h)^{-n - (1-n)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R} (R_m+h)^{-n - 1 + n} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R} (R_m+h)^{-1} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R (R_m+h)} \\label{eq:temp_final} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe expression for the temperature $T(h)$ of the Martian atmosphere as a function of height $h$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{T(h) = \\frac{\\mu G M_m}{n R (R_m + h)}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MODERN/211", "tag": "MODERN", "questions": "In the ground frame S, two trains with an intrinsic length of $L_{0}$ are stationary along the $x$ axis, with the left side of train A located at $x=0$. The gap between the left side of train B and the right side of train A is $D$. At time $t=0$ in the ground frame S, both trains A and B synchronize their carriage times to $t_{A}=t_{B}=0$, and the clocks are located on the left side of each train. At this moment, the two trains start moving with constant accelerations relative to themselves, $a_{A}$ and $a_{B}$.\n\nLet the distance between train carriages AB in frame S be $D(t)$. Express the value of $a_{B}$ when $D(t)\\equiv D$ in terms of $L_{0}$, $a_{A}$, and the speed of light $c$.", "solutions": "Since the left end of the train is aligned with the ground clock, the left end of the train can be regarded as a point mass, and thus we can study uniform accelerated motion.\n\nLet the velocity of the left end at time $t$ in the ground frame be $v(t)$, at time $t+d t$, first perform a Lorentz transformation to the rest frame with velocity $v(t)$. In the rest frame, obtain an infinitesimal velocity $adτ$:\n\nUsing the proper time formula:\n\n$$\nv+dv={\\frac{v+adτ}{1+{\\frac{v\\times adτ}{c^{2}}}}}\\rightarrow dv=adτ\\left(1-{\\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}}\\right)\n$$\n\n$$\ndτ={\\sqrt{1-{\\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}}}}dt \\to dv=a{\\sqrt{1-{\\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}}^{3}}}dt\n$$ \n\nSeparate variables on both sides, yielding:\n\n$$\nat=\\int_{0}^{v}{\\frac{dV}{1-{V}^{2}/{c}^{2}}}={\\frac{v}{1-{v}^{2}/{c}^{2}}}\n$$\n\nSolving for the velocity function:\n\n$$\nv(t)={\\frac{at}{\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{at}{c}}\\right)^{2}}}}\\to x(t)=x_{0}+\\int_{0}^{t}v(t)dt=x_{0}+{\\frac{c^{2}}{a}}\\left({\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{at}{c}}\\right)^{2}}}-1\\right)\n$$\n\nSelect special cases A, B to write the displacement function:\n\n$$\n\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{\\displaystyle x_{l A}=\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{A}}\\left(\\sqrt{1+\\left(\\frac{a_{A}t}{c}\\right)^{2}}-1\\right)}\\ {\\displaystyle x_{l B}=L_{0}+D+\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{B}}\\left(\\sqrt{1+\\left(\\frac{a_{B}t}{c}\\right)^{2}}-1\\right)}\\end{array}\\right.\n$$\n\nUsing the motion on the left side, we can calculate the proper time:\n\n$$\nτ=\\int_{0}^{t}{\\sqrt{1-\\left({\\frac{v}{c}}\\right)^{2}}}dt=\\int_{0}^{t}{\\frac{dt}{\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{at}{c}}\\right)^{2}}}}={\\frac{c}{a}}\\mathrm{arcsinh}{\\frac{at}{c}}\n$$\n\nApply to special cases A, B:\n\n$$\n\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l l}{{\\displaystyleτ_{A}=\\frac{c}{a_{A}}\\mathrm{arcsinh}\\frac{a_{A}t}{c}}}\\ {{\\displaystyleτ_{B}=\\frac{c}{a_{B}}\\mathrm{arcsinh}\\frac{a_{B}t}{c}}}\\end{array}\\right.\n$$\n\nTaking train A as an example, given the proper time $τ_{A}$, the speed of A at this time is:\n\n$$\nv_{A}(τ)={\\frac{a_{A}t}{\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{a_{A}t}{c}}\\right)^{2}}}}=c\\operatorname{tanh}{\\frac{a_{A}τ}{c}}\n$$\n\nThe left side of the train system $(0,τ)$ and the ground frame $(x_{l A},t)$ are aligned, allowing for easy writing of the Lorentz transformation for the right end time and coordinates in the ground frame:\n\n$$\nt_{r,A}=t+{\\frac{v_{A}L_{0}/c^{2}}{1-v_{A}^{2}/c^{2}}}=t+\\cosh{\\frac{a_{A}τ}{c}}\\left({\\frac{L_{0}}{c}}\\operatorname{tanh}{\\frac{a_{A}τ}{c}}\\right)=t+{\\frac{L_{0}}{c}}\\sinh{\\frac{a_{A}τ}{c}}=\\left(1+{\\frac{a_{A}L_{0}}{c^{2}}}\\right)t\n$$\n\n$$\nx_{r,A}=x_{l,A}+\\frac{L_{0}}{1-v_{A}^{2}/c^{2}}=\\left(\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{A}}+L_{0}\\right)\\sqrt{1+\\left(\\frac{a_{A}t}{c}\\right)^{2}}-\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{A}}\n$$\n\nSince $x_{r,A}$ occurs at event S frame $t=t_{r,A}$, the correct $x_{r,A}(t)$ function should replace $t$:\n\n$$\nx_{r,A}={\\frac{c^{2}}{{\\frac{a_{A}}{1+{\\frac{a_{A}L_{0}}{c^{2}}}}}}}{\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{a_{A}t/c}{1+{\\frac{a_{A}L_{0}}{c^{2}}}}}\\right)^{2}}}-{\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{A}}\n$$\n\nAt this moment, the distance between the right side of A and the left side of B is:\n\n$$\n=x_{l,B}-x_{r,A}=L_{0}+D+{\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{B}}}\\left(\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{a_{B}t}{c}}\\right)^{2}}-1\\right)+{\\frac{c^{2}}{a_{A}}}-{\\frac{c^{2}}{{\\frac{a_{A}}{1+{\\frac{a_{A}L_{0}}{c^{2}}}}}}}\\sqrt{1+\\left({\\frac{a_{A}t/c}{1+{\\frac{a_{A}L_{0}}{c^{2}}}}}\\right)^{2}}\n$$\n\nIf the distance is constant, then naturally:\n\n$$\na_{B}={\\frac{a_{A}}{1+{\\frac{a_{A}L_{0}}{c^{2}}}}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\frac{a_A}{1+\\frac{a_A L_0}{c^2}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem describes the relativistic motion of two trains, A and B, in one dimension. We are given their initial state in a stationary ground frame S and their subsequent motion, and we need to find a condition on their proper accelerations such that the distance between them in frame S remains constant.\n\n**Given Information:**\n*   **Frame of Reference**: The ground frame S, which is an inertial frame with a spatial coordinate $x$ and time coordinate $t$.\n*   **Trains**: Two trains, designated A and B.\n*   **Proper Length**: Both trains have the same proper (or intrinsic) length, $L_0$.\n*   **Initial State (at $t=0$ in frame S)**:\n    *   Both trains are at rest, so their initial velocities are $v_A(0) = v_B(0) = 0$.\n    *   The left end of train A is at position $x_{l,A}(0) = 0$. Since the train is at rest, its length in S is its proper length, so its right end is at $x_{r,A}(0) = L_0$.\n    *   There is a gap of length $D$ between the trains. The left end of train B is at $x_{l,B}(0) = x_{r,A}(0) + D = L_0 + D$.\n    *   Clocks located at the left end of each train are synchronized to zero in frame S: $t_A=t_B=0$.\n*   **Motion (for $t>0$ in frame S)**:\n    *   The trains begin to move with constant proper accelerations. The phrase \"constant accelerations relative to themselves\" is interpreted as constant proper acceleration.\n    *   The proper acceleration of the left end of train A is $a_A$.\n    *   The proper acceleration of the left end of train B is $a_B$.\n*   **Constraint**: The distance between the right end of train A and the left end of train B, as measured in the ground frame S, remains constant for all time $t \\ge 0$. This distance is $D(t) = x_{l,B}(t) - x_{r,A}(t)$, so the condition is $D(t) = D$.\n*   **Objective**: Determine the value of the proper acceleration $a_B$ in terms of $L_0$, $a_A$, and the speed of light $c$.\n\n**Assumptions:**\n*   The motion is purely one-dimensional along the $x$-axis.\n*   For an extended object like a train to accelerate while maintaining its proper length $L_0$, it must behave as a Born-rigid body. This means the proper distance between any two points on the train remains constant throughout the motion.\n\n### Step 1: Equation of Motion for Constant Proper Acceleration\nWe first establish the equations for velocity $v(t)$ and position $x(t)$ in the ground frame S for a particle that starts from rest at $x_0$ and moves with a constant proper acceleration $a$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe definition of proper acceleration $a$ relates the velocity change $dv'$ in the instantaneous co-moving inertial frame to the proper time interval $d\\tau$:\n\\[\\boxed{\na = \\frac{dv'}{d\\tau}\n}\\]\nThe relativistic velocity addition formula for collinear motion relates the velocity in the lab frame $v$, the infinitesimal relative velocity $dv'$, and the new velocity in the lab frame $v+dv$:\n\\[\\boxed{\nv+dv = \\frac{v + dv'}{1 + \\frac{v \\, dv'}{c^2}}\n}\\]\nThe time dilation formula relates the proper time interval $d\\tau$ to the coordinate time interval $dt$ in the lab frame:\n\\[\\boxed{\nd\\tau = \\frac{dt}{\\gamma(v)} = \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}} \\, dt\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nFrom the velocity addition formula, for an infinitesimal velocity change $dv'$, we can perform a first-order Taylor expansion:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nv+dv &\\approx (v + dv') \\left(1 - \\frac{v \\, dv'}{c^2}\\right) = v - \\frac{v^2 dv'}{c^2} + dv' - \\frac{v(dv')^2}{c^2} \\nonumber \\\\\ndv &\\approx \\left(1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}\\right) dv' \\quad (\\text{neglecting terms of order } (dv')^2) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{dv}{dv'} &= 1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2} \\label{eq:dv_dvprime}\n\\end{align}\\]\nUsing the definition of proper acceleration, $dv' = a \\, d\\tau$. Substituting this into Eq. \\eqref{eq:dv_dvprime} gives:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dv}{d\\tau} = a\\left(1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}\\right) \\label{eq:dv_dtau}\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo find the rate of change of velocity with respect to the lab frame time $t$, we use the chain rule and the time dilation formula:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dv}{dt} = \\frac{dv}{d\\tau} \\frac{d\\tau}{dt} = a\\left(1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}\\right) \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}} = a\\left(1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}\\right)^{3/2} \\label{eq:dv_dt}\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo find $v(t)$, we separate variables and integrate from the initial condition $v(0)=0$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^v \\frac{dV}{\\left(1 - V^2/c^2\\right)^{3/2}} &= \\int_0^t a \\, dt' \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left[ \\frac{V}{\\sqrt{1-V^2/c^2}} \\right]_0^v &= at \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{v(t)}{\\sqrt{1-v(t)^2/c^2}} &= at \\label{eq:v_integrated}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSolving for $v(t)$ yields the velocity as a function of time:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nv(t) = \\frac{at}{\\sqrt{1 + (at/c)^2}} \\label{eq:v_t}\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo find the position $x(t)$, we integrate $v(t) = dx/dt$ from the initial position $x(0)=x_0$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nx(t) - x_0 &= \\int_0^t v(t') \\, dt' = \\int_0^t \\frac{at'}{\\sqrt{1 + (at'/c)^2}} \\, dt' \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left[ \\frac{c^2}{a} \\sqrt{1 + (at'/c)^2} \\right]_0^t \\nonumber \\\\\nx(t) &= x_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{at}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\label{eq:x_t}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis equation describes the worldline of a particle undergoing hyperbolic motion.\n\n### Step 2: Worldline of a Born-Rigid Accelerating Train\nFor train A to maintain its proper length $L_0$, it must be Born-rigid. This imposes a specific structure on the worldlines of all points constituting the train.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n\\[\\boxed{\n\\text{Born Rigidity: The proper distance between any two infinitesimally close points of an accelerating body remains constant in their co-moving frame.}\n}\\]\nFor a body undergoing constant proper acceleration, Born rigidity implies that all points on the body follow hyperbolic worldlines in spacetime that share a common center of asymptotes. The general form of such a family of hyperbolas in the $(x, ct)$ plane is:\n\\[\\boxed{\n(x - x_c)^2 - (ct)^2 = R^2\n}\\]\nwhere $x_c$ is the common center and $R$ is the \"radius\" of a specific hyperbola, which is different for each point on the body.\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe worldline of the left end of train A starts at $x_{l,A}(0)=0$ with proper acceleration $a_A$. Using Eq. \\eqref{eq:x_t}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nx_{l,A}(t) = \\frac{c^2}{a_A} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_A t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\label{eq:xlA}\n\\end{align}\\]\nWe can rewrite this in the standard hyperbolic form to identify its geometric properties:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nx_{l,A}(t) + \\frac{c^2}{a_A} &= \\frac{c^2}{a_A} \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_A t}{c}\\right)^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(x_{l,A} + \\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 &= \\left(\\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 \\left(1 + \\left(\\frac{a_A t}{c}\\right)^2\\right) = \\left(\\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 + (ct)^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(x_{l,A} + \\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 - (ct)^2 &= \\left(\\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 \\label{eq:wl_lA}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis is a hyperbola with its center of asymptotes at $x_c = -c^2/a_A$. For Born rigidity, the worldline of the right end of train A, $x_{r,A}(t)$, must be a hyperbola with the same center $x_c$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\left(x_{r,A} + \\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 - (ct)^2 = R_{r,A}^2 \\label{eq:wl_rA_general}\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo find the radius $R_{r,A}$ for the right end, we use its initial condition $x_{r,A}(0) = L_0$ at $t=0$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\left(L_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 - (c \\cdot 0)^2 = R_{r,A}^2 \\implies R_{r,A} = L_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a_A} \\label{eq:R_val}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThus, the worldline of the right end of train A is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\left(x_{r,A} + \\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 - (ct)^2 = \\left(L_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a_A}\\right)^2 \\label{eq:wl_rA}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 3: Proper Acceleration of the Right End of Train A\nEach hyperbolic worldline corresponds to a motion with a constant proper acceleration. We can find the proper acceleration of the right end of train A, denoted $a_{r,A}$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe proper acceleration $a$ for a hyperbolic worldline of the form $(x - x_c)^2 - (ct)^2 = R^2$ is related to its radius $R$ by:\n\\[\\boxed{\na = \\frac{c^2}{R}\n}\\]\nThis relation is a direct consequence of comparing the general hyperbolic equation with the derived worldline equation Eq. \\eqref{eq:x_t}, as shown by rearranging it into the form of Eq. \\eqref{eq:wl_lA}.\n\n**Derivation**:\nFrom Eq. \\eqref{eq:wl_rA}, the radius of the hyperbola for the right end of train A is $R_{r,A} = L_0 + c^2/a_A$. Using the principle above, the proper acceleration of the right end of train A is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\na_{r,A} = \\frac{c^2}{R_{r,A}} = \\frac{c^2}{L_0 + c^2/a_A} \\label{eq:a_rA_calc}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSimplifying this expression gives:\n\\[\\begin{align}\na_{r,A} = \\frac{c^2 a_A}{a_A L_0 + c^2} = \\frac{a_A}{1 + \\frac{a_A L_0}{c^2}} \\label{eq:a_rA}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis result shows that for a Born-rigid rod, the front end ($a_{r,A}$) must have a smaller proper acceleration than the rear end ($a_A$) to maintain its structure.\n\n### Step 4: Setting up the Constant Distance Condition\nWe now write the expressions for the positions of the right end of train A and the left end of train B and apply the condition that the distance between them is always $D$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe position of a particle undergoing hyperbolic motion is given by Eq. \\eqref{eq:x_t}:\n\\[\\boxed{\nx(t) = x_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{at}{c}\\right)^{2}} - 1 \\right)\n}\\]\nThe problem states that the distance between the trains is constant:\n\\[\\boxed{\nx_{l,B}(t) - x_{r,A}(t) = D \\quad \\text{for all } t \\ge 0\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe right end of train A starts at $x_{r,A}(0) = L_0$ and has proper acceleration $a_{r,A}$. Its position at time $t$ is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nx_{r,A}(t) = L_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a_{r,A}} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_{r,A} t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\label{eq:xrA_t}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe left end of train B starts at $x_{l,B}(0) = L_0 + D$ and has proper acceleration $a_B$. Its position at time $t$ is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nx_{l,B}(t) = (L_0 + D) + \\frac{c^2}{a_B} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_B t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\label{eq:xlB_t}\n\\end{align}\\]\nApplying the constant distance condition:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nx_{l,B}(t) - x_{r,A}(t) &= D \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left[ (L_0 + D) + \\frac{c^2}{a_B} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_B t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\right] - \\left[ L_0 + \\frac{c^2}{a_{r,A}} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_{r,A} t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\right] &= D \\nonumber \\\\\nD + \\frac{c^2}{a_B} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_B t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) - \\frac{c^2}{a_{r,A}} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_{r,A} t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) &= D \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{c^2}{a_B} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_B t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) &= \\frac{c^2}{a_{r,A}} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{a_{r,A} t}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right) \\label{eq:condition}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 5: Solving for $a_B$\nThe condition derived in the previous step must hold for all $t \\ge 0$. This powerful constraint allows us to determine $a_B$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\n\\[\\boxed{\n\\text{If a function } f(x) \\text{ is strictly monotonic over its domain, then the equality } f(x_1) = f(x_2) \\text{ implies that } x_1 = x_2.\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nThe equation derived in Step 4, Eq. \\eqref{eq:condition}, must hold for all $t \\ge 0$. Let's define a function $f(a, t) = \\frac{c^2}{a} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\left(\\frac{at}{c}\\right)^2} - 1 \\right)$. The condition is $f(a_B, t) = f(a_{r,A}, t)$.\nFor any fixed time $t > 0$, we can show that the function $f(a,t)$ is strictly increasing with respect to the acceleration $a$ (for $a>0$). The partial derivative with respect to $a$ is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial a} &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial a} \\left[ \\frac{c^2}{a} \\left( \\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}} - 1 \\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{c^2}{a^2}\\left(\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}} - 1\\right) + \\frac{c^2}{a} \\left( \\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}}} \\cdot \\frac{2at^2}{c^2} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{c^2}{a^2}\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}} + \\frac{c^2}{a^2} + \\frac{t^2}{\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{a^2\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}}} \\left[ -c^2\\left(1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}\\right) + c^2\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}} + a^2t^2 \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{c^2}{a^2\\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}}} \\left[ -\\left(1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}\\right) + \\sqrt{1 + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2}} + \\frac{a^2t^2}{c^2} \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{c^2}{a^2\\sqrt{1 + (at/c)^2}} \\left[ \\sqrt{1 + (at/c)^2} - 1 \\right]\n\\end{align}\\]\nFor $a>0$ and $t>0$, the term $\\sqrt{1 + (at/c)^2}$ is strictly greater than 1. Therefore, $\\frac{\\partial f}{\\partial a} > 0$, and the function $f(a,t)$ is strictly monotonic in $a$.\nSince the equality $f(a_B, t) = f(a_{r,A}, t)$ must be true for all $t>0$, and the function is one-to-one in its first argument, the arguments must be equal.\n\\[\\begin{align}\na_B = a_{r,A} \\label{eq:aB_eq_arA}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThis means that for the gap between the trains to remain constant, the proper acceleration of the front of the trailing train (left end of B) must be identical to the proper acceleration of the back of the leading train (right end of A).\nSubstituting the expression for $a_{r,A}$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:a_rA}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\na_B = \\frac{a_A}{1 + \\frac{a_A L_0}{c^2}} \\label{eq:final_result}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe value of $a_B$ for which the distance $D(t)$ between the trains remains constant is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{a_B = \\frac{a_A}{1 + \\frac{a_A L_0}{c^2}}}\n\\end{align}\\]"}
