{"id": "MECHANICS/106", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "Two thin rods, each with mass $m$ and length $l$, are centrally connected by a thin string (with negligible mass). The upper ends are also connected by a very short flexible string (with negligible length). The other end of each rod is free to slide across a horizontal table without friction. The plane formed by the rods and strings is perpendicular to the tabletop, with gravitational acceleration $g$. Initially, the rods are stationary, forming an angle $\\theta_{0}$ with the tabletop. When the thin string at the center is cut, the rods fall vertically until they hit the table. What is the magnitude of the velocity $v$ of the rods just before the ends connected at the table touch the tabletop?", "solutions": "Solution: Using the conservation of energy:\nInitial mechanical energy: $\\frac{1}{2}mgl\\sin\\theta_{0}$ \nMechanical energy while in motion (angular velocity is $\\dot{\\theta}$): translational kinetic energy $^{+}$ rotational kinetic energy $^+$ gravitational potential energy:\n$$\n{\\frac{1}{2}}m{\\dot{\\theta}}^{2}{\\frac{l^{2}}{4}}+{\\frac{1}{2}}{\\frac{1}{12}}m l^{2}{\\dot{\\theta}}^{2}+{\\frac{1}{2}}m g l \\sin\\theta={\\frac{1}{6}}m l^{2}{\\dot{\\theta}}^{2}+{\\frac{1}{2}}m g l \\sin\\theta\n$$\nWe obtain the angular velocity $\\dot{\\theta}: \\dot{\\theta} = \\sqrt{3g/l(\\sin\\theta_{0} - \\sin\\theta)}$. The terminal velocity is: $v=-\\sqrt{3gl\\sin\\theta_{0}}$", "final_answers": "$$v = \\sqrt{3 g l \\sin \\theta_0}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThe problem describes a mechanical system consisting of two identical thin rods, each with mass $m$ and length $l$. The rods are arranged symmetrically in a vertical plane, forming an A-frame structure. Their upper ends are connected by a short, flexible, massless string, which acts as a hinge. Their lower ends are free to slide without friction on a horizontal tabletop. The system is subject to a uniform gravitational field with acceleration $g$.\n\nInitially, the system is held stationary by a thin, massless string connecting the centers of the two rods. In this initial configuration, the rods form an angle $\\theta_0$ with the horizontal tabletop.\n\nThe process begins when the central string is cut, allowing the A-frame to collapse under gravity. The rods fall until they lie flat on the table. The phrase \"the rods fall vertically\" is interpreted to mean that the center of mass of the entire two-rod system moves purely in the vertical direction, which is consistent with the symmetry of the setup for any initial angle $\\theta_0$.\n\nThe question asks for the magnitude of the velocity $v$ of the rods just before they hit the table. The phrase \"velocity of the rods\" is ambiguous, as different points on the rods have different velocities. We will interpret this as the velocity of the top hinge, as it is a unique and important point in the system whose motion characterizes the collapse. The final moment is when the rods are horizontal, i.e., the angle they make with the table is $\\theta=0$.\n\nThe variables involved are:\n*   $m$: mass of each rod.\n*   $l$: length of each rod.\n*   $g$: acceleration due to gravity.\n*   $\\theta_0$: the initial angle each rod makes with the horizontal table.\n*   $\\theta$: the instantaneous angle a rod makes with the horizontal table.\n*   $v$: the magnitude of the velocity of the top hinge when the rods hit the table (i.e., when $\\theta=0$).\n\nWe assume the rods are rigid and uniform, the strings are massless, the hinge is ideal (frictionless), and the tabletop is frictionless.\n\n### Step 1: Kinematics of the System\nWe establish a Cartesian coordinate system to describe the motion. Let the horizontal tabletop be the x-axis and the vertical axis of symmetry be the y-axis. The origin $(0,0)$ is on the table, directly below the top hinge.\n\nThe velocity of a point is the time derivative of its position vector.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{v} = \\frac{d\\vec{r}}{dt}}\\]\nThe position of the top hinge, P, is always on the y-axis. Its height is determined by the rod's length $l$ and the angle $\\theta$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{r}_P = (0, l\\sin\\theta)\n\\label{eq:pos_P} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe center of mass (CM) of the right rod is at its geometric center. Its coordinates are:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{r}_{CM} = \\left(\\frac{l}{2}\\cos\\theta, \\frac{l}{2}\\sin\\theta\\right)\n\\label{eq:pos_CM} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe velocity of the top hinge $\\vec{v}_P$ is found by differentiating its position with respect to time, using the chain rule where $\\dot{\\theta} = d\\theta/dt$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{v}_P = \\frac{d\\vec{r}_P}{dt} = (0, l\\cos\\theta \\dot{\\theta})\n\\label{eq:vel_P} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSimilarly, the velocity of the CM of the right rod is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{v}_{CM} = \\frac{d\\vec{r}_{CM}}{dt} = \\left(-\\frac{l}{2}\\sin\\theta \\dot{\\theta}, \\frac{l}{2}\\cos\\theta \\dot{\\theta}\\right)\n\\label{eq:vel_CM} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Total Mechanical Energy of the System\nThe system consists of the two rods. The forces acting on the system are gravity, the normal forces from the table, and internal forces at the hinge. Gravity is a conservative force. The normal forces act perpendicular to the horizontal motion of the lower ends of the rods, so they do no work. There is no friction. Therefore, the total mechanical energy of the system is conserved.\n\\[\n\\boxed{E = K + U = \\text{constant}}\n\\]\nHere, $K$ is the total kinetic energy and $U$ is the total gravitational potential energy.\n\n**Potential Energy (U):**\nThe gravitational potential energy of a body is determined by the height of its center of mass. We set the potential energy reference $U=0$ at the tabletop ($y=0$).\n\\[\n\\boxed{U_g = mgy_{CM}}\n\\]\nThe height of the CM of each rod is $y_{CM} = \\frac{l}{2}\\sin\\theta$. Since there are two identical rods, the total potential energy is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU = 2 \\times \\left(mg y_{CM}\\right) = 2 \\left(mg \\frac{l}{2}\\sin\\theta\\right) = mgl\\sin\\theta\n\\label{eq:PE} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n**Kinetic Energy (K):**\nThe kinetic energy of a rigid body in planar motion is the sum of the translational kinetic energy of its center of mass and the rotational kinetic energy about its center of mass.\n\\[\n\\boxed{K_{\\text{rod}} = \\frac{1}{2}mv_{CM}^2 + \\frac{1}{2}I_{CM}\\omega^2}\n\\]\nThe moment of inertia of a thin rod of mass $m$ and length $l$ about its center is:\n\\[\n\\boxed{I_{CM} = \\frac{1}{12}ml^2}\n\\]\nThe squared speed of the CM of one rod is found from Eq. \\eqref{eq:vel_CM}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_{CM}^2 = \\left(-\\frac{l}{2}\\sin\\theta \\dot{\\theta}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{l}{2}\\cos\\theta \\dot{\\theta}\\right)^2 = \\frac{l^2\\dot{\\theta}^2}{4}(\\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta) = \\frac{l^2\\dot{\\theta}^2}{4}\n\\label{eq:v_CM_sq} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe angular speed of the rod is $\\omega = |\\dot{\\theta}|$, so $\\omega^2 = \\dot{\\theta}^2$. The kinetic energy of one rod is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nK_{\\text{one rod}} &= \\frac{1}{2}m\\left(\\frac{l^2\\dot{\\theta}^2}{4}\\right) + \\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{1}{12}ml^2\\right)\\dot{\\theta}^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{1}{8}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}^2 + \\frac{1}{24}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left(\\frac{3+1}{24}\\right)ml^2\\dot{\\theta}^2 = \\frac{1}{6}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}^2\n\\label{eq:KE_one} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe total kinetic energy of the system of two identical rods is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nK = 2 \\times K_{\\text{one rod}} = 2 \\left(\\frac{1}{6}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}^2\\right) = \\frac{1}{3}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}^2\n\\label{eq:KE_total} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Application of Energy Conservation\nThe total mechanical energy $E = K+U$ is conserved throughout the motion. We equate the total energy of the initial state to the total energy of the final state.\n\\[\n\\boxed{K_f + U_f = K_i + U_i}\n\\]\n**Initial State:** The rods are at rest at an angle $\\theta_i = \\theta_0$.\nThe initial kinetic energy is zero because the system is stationary.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nK_i = 0\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe initial potential energy is calculated using Eq. \\eqref{eq:PE} at $\\theta = \\theta_0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU_i = mgl\\sin(\\theta_0)\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSo, the total initial energy is $E_i = K_i + U_i = mgl\\sin(\\theta_0)$.\n\n**Final State:** The rods have hit the table, so their final angle is $\\theta_f = 0$. Let the angular velocity at this instant be $\\dot{\\theta}_f$.\nThe final kinetic energy is given by Eq. \\eqref{eq:KE_total} at the final instant.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nK_f = \\frac{1}{3}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}_f^2\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe final potential energy is calculated using Eq. \\eqref{eq:PE} at $\\theta = 0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU_f = mgl\\sin(0) = 0\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSo, the total final energy is $E_f = K_f + U_f = \\frac{1}{3}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}_f^2$.\n\nBy conservation of energy, $E_f = E_i$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{1}{3}ml^2\\dot{\\theta}_f^2 &= mgl\\sin(\\theta_0) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\dot{\\theta}_f^2 &= \\frac{3mgl\\sin(\\theta_0)}{ml^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\dot{\\theta}_f^2 &= \\frac{3g\\sin(\\theta_0)}{l}\n\\label{eq:theta_dot_final} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculation of the Final Velocity\nWe want to find the magnitude of the velocity of the top hinge, $v$, when the rods hit the table. This corresponds to the final state where $\\theta_f=0$. The magnitude of the hinge's velocity is given by $v_P = |l\\cos\\theta \\dot{\\theta}|$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:vel_P}.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv = v_P(\\theta=0) &= |l\\cos(0) \\dot{\\theta}_f| \\nonumber \\\\\n&= l |\\dot{\\theta}_f| \\nonumber \\\\\n&= l \\sqrt{\\dot{\\theta}_f^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= l \\sqrt{\\frac{3g\\sin(\\theta_0)}{l}} \\quad (\\text{using eq. \\ref{eq:theta_dot_final}}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\sqrt{l^2 \\cdot \\frac{3g\\sin(\\theta_0)}{l}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\sqrt{3gl\\sin(\\theta_0)}\n\\label{eq:final_v} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe magnitude of the velocity $v$ of the top hinge of the rods just before they touch the tabletop is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{v = \\sqrt{3gl\\sin(\\theta_0)}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/58", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "An arbitrary multi-terminal resistor network structure, for example with $N+1$ terminals, sets one specific terminal (0 terminal) as the reference for electric potential, setting its potential at 0. The potentials for other terminals (numbered 1, 2, ..., N) are $v_{1}, v_{2}, \\ldots, v_{N}$, and the current flowing into the network through these corresponding terminals (negative when flowing out) are $I_{1}, I_2, \\ldots, I_n$. Therefore, we have:\n\n$$\n\\left\\{\n\\begin{array}{l}\nV_{1} = a_{11} I_{1} + a_{12} I_{2} + \\cdots + a_{1N} I_{N} \\\\\nV_{2} = a_{21} I_{1} + a_{22} I_{2} + \\cdots + a_{2N} I_{N} \\\\\n\\vdots \\\\\nV_{i} = a_{i1} I_{1} + a_{i2} I_{2} + \\cdots + a_{iN} I_{N} \\\\\n\\vdots \\\\\nV_{N} = a_{N1} I_{1} + a_{N2} I_{2} + \\cdots + a_{NN} I_{N} \n\\end{array}\n\\right.\n$$\n\nDue to symmetry, we know that $a_{ij} = a_{ji}$.\n\nThis means that the properties of the $N+1$ terminal network can be determined by $\\frac{N(N+1)}{2}$ independent parameters: $a_{11}, a_{12}, \\ldots , a_{ij}, \\ldots , a_{NN} (i<j)$. These parameters are only determined by the resistor network itself and are unrelated to the potential at the terminals or the magnitude of the current flowing in.\n\nConsider a square uniform conductive thin plate as a four-terminal resistor network. The four vertices are sequentially numbered clockwise as 0, 1, 2, 3. If the equivalent resistance between adjacent vertices is ${R}_{1}$ and the equivalent resistance between opposite vertices is ${{R}}_{2}$, use the method of finding the coefficients $a_{i j} (i,j=1,2,3)$ to solve: what is the equivalent resistance between the other two vertices if a pair of adjacent vertices is short-circuited?", "solutions": "For this situation, label the 4 endpoints sequentially as 0, 1, 2, 3. If current flows into endpoint 1 with current I (flowing out from endpoint 0), then:   \n\n$$\nV_{1}=a_{11}I=I R_{1}\n$$  \n\nThus, we obtain: $a_{11}=R_{1}$  \n\nSimilarly, if current flows into endpoints 2 or 3 with current I, we can respectively obtain: $a_{22}=R_{2}$ $a_{33}=R_{1}$. If current flows into endpoint 1 with current I and flows out from endpoint 2:  \n\n$$\nV_{1}^{\\prime}=a_{11}I-a_{12}I,V_{2}^{\\prime}=a_{21}I-a_{22}I\n$$  \n\nAt this moment, the potential difference between endpoints 1 and 2 is:  \n\n$$\nV_{1}^{\\prime}-V_{2}^{\\prime}=(a_{11}-2a_{12}+a_{22})I\n$$  \n\nDue to symmetry, at this moment, the potential difference between endpoints 1 and 2 should be equal to the potential at endpoint 1 (between 1 and 0) when current flows only into endpoint 1 (out from endpoint 0), thus:  \n\n$$\n(a_{11}-2a_{12}+a_{22})I=a_{11}I\n$$  \n\nWe obtain:  \n\n$$\na_{12}=\\frac{1}{2}a_{22}=\\frac{1}{2}R_{2}\n$$  \n\n[This can also be directly obtained by the condition of current input into endpoint 2, where the potential at endpoint 1 is half of that at endpoint 2 due to symmetry.] Similarly, we obtain:  \n\n$$\na_{23}=\\frac{1}{2}R_{2}\n$$  \n\nReturning again to the situation with current flowing only into endpoint 1 (flowing out from endpoint 0), at this moment, the potentials at endpoints 2 and 3 are respectively:  \n\n$$\nV_{2}=a_{21}I,V_{3}=a_{31}I\n$$  \n\nDue to symmetry, the potential difference between endpoints 1 and 2 should be equal to the potential difference between endpoints 3 and 0, thus:  \n\n$$\nV_{1}-V_{2}=V_{3}\n$$  \n\nTherefore:  \n\n$$\na_{11}I-a_{21}I=a_{31}I\n$$  \n\nWe obtain:  \n\n$$\na_{13}=a_{31}=a_{11}-a_{12}=R_{1}-{\\frac{1}{2}}R_{2}\n$$  \n\nNow returning to the required situation of the problem, without loss of generality, we can assume endpoints 3 and 0 are short-circuited and calculate the equivalent resistance between endpoints 1 and 2. In this case, if current flows into endpoint 1 with current I and out from endpoint 2, since endpoints 3 and 0 are short-circuited, there must be current flowing from 0 through the short-circuit wire into endpoint 3. Let the current flowing through the short-circuit wire be $I^{\\prime}$, then it can be considered as the original four-terminal situation with current flowing into endpoint 1, out from endpoint 2, and into endpoint 3 with $I^{\\prime}$. At this moment, the potential at endpoint 3 is:  \n\n$$\nV_{3}=a_{31}I-a_{32}I+a_{33}I^{\\prime}\n$$  \n\nBecause 3 and 0 are practically short-circuited, $V_{3}$ should be 0. Thus we can compute:  \n\n$$\nI^{\\prime}=\\frac{a_{32}-a_{31}}{a_{33}}I=\\frac{R_{2}-R_{1}}{R_{1}}I\n$$  \n\nWe can then compute the potentials at endpoints 1 and 2:  \n\nThe potential difference between endpoints 1 and 2:  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{c}{{V_{1}=a_{11}I-a_{12}I+a_{13}I^{\\prime}=(R_{1}-\\displaystyle{\\frac{1}{2}}R_{2})\\displaystyle{\\frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}}}I}}\\ {{V_{2}=a_{21}I-a_{22}I+a_{23}I^{\\prime}=\\displaystyle{\\frac{R_{2}}{2}}\\displaystyle{\\frac{R_{2}-2R_{1}}{R_{1}}}I}}\\end{array}\n$$  \n\n$$\nV_{1}-V_{2}=\\frac{(2R_{1}-R_{2})R_{2}}{2R_{1}}I\n$$  \n\nThus, the equivalent resistance between endpoints 1 and 2 is:  \n\n$$\nR={\\frac{V_{1}-V_{2}}{I}}={\\frac{(2R_{1}-R_{2})R_{2}}{2R_{1}}}=(2-{\\frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}}})R_{2}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\\left(2-\\frac{R_2}{R_1}\\right)R_2$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem analyzes a four-terminal resistor network, which is physically realized as a square uniform conductive thin plate. The four vertices of the square serve as the terminals and are numbered sequentially in a clockwise manner as 0, 1, 2, and 3.\n\nThe electrical behavior of this network is described by a set of linear equations relating the potentials at terminals 1, 2, and 3 to the currents flowing into them. Terminal 0 is designated as the reference terminal, meaning its potential is held at zero, i.e., $V_0 = 0$. The potentials at the other terminals are denoted by $V_1, V_2, V_3$, and the currents flowing into the network at these terminals are $I_1, I_2, I_3$.\n\nThe relationship between the potentials and currents for terminals $i, j \\in \\{1, 2, 3\\}$ is given by the matrix equation:\n$V_i = \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{ij} I_j$.\nThe coefficients $a_{ij}$ form the resistance matrix, which is symmetric ($a_{ij} = a_{ji}$) due to reciprocity. The values of these coefficients are determined by the intrinsic properties of the conductive plate.\n\nWe are provided with the following information based on the geometry of the square plate:\n1.  The equivalent resistance between any two adjacent vertices is $R_1$. The adjacent pairs are (0,1), (1,2), (2,3), and (3,0).\n2.  The equivalent resistance between any two opposite (diagonal) vertices is $R_2$. The opposite pairs are (0,2) and (1,3).\n\nThe problem asks for the equivalent resistance between terminals 1 and 2, under the condition that terminals 0 and 3, which form an adjacent pair, are short-circuited.\n\n### Step 1: Determine the diagonal coefficients of the resistance matrix ($a_{ii}$)\nWe first determine the diagonal elements of the resistance matrix, $a_{11}$, $a_{22}$, and $a_{33}$. This is done by considering the two-terminal resistance between each terminal $k \\in \\{1, 2, 3\\}$ and the reference terminal 0.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nThe general relationship between terminal potentials and currents for this 3-port network is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nV_i = \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{ij} I_j\n}\\]\nThe definition of the two-terminal equivalent resistance between terminals $k$ and $l$ is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nR_{k,l} = \\frac{V_k - V_l}{I}\n}\\]\nwhere a current $I$ is injected at terminal $k$ and extracted at terminal $l$, with all other terminals left open (i.e., their currents are zero).\n\n**Derivation**\nTo find the coefficient $a_{kk}$, we consider a setup where a current $I$ is injected into terminal $k$ (so $I_k = I$) and extracted from the reference terminal 0. All other currents into terminals $j \\in \\{1, 2, 3\\}$ with $j \\neq k$ are zero ($I_j = 0$).\nThe potential at terminal $k$ is given by the general relation:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_k = a_{k1}I_1 + a_{k2}I_2 + a_{k3}I_3\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWith our specific current setup ($I_k=I, I_j=0$ for $j\\neq k$), this simplifies to:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_k = a_{kk}I_k = a_{kk}I\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSince terminal 0 is the reference, its potential is $V_0 = 0$. The equivalent resistance between terminals $k$ and 0 is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nR_{k0} = \\frac{V_k - V_0}{I} = \\frac{a_{kk}I - 0}{I} = a_{kk} \\label{eq:akk}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe use this result and the given resistances to find the diagonal coefficients:\n*   For $k=1$: Terminals 1 and 0 are adjacent, so their equivalent resistance is $R_{10} = R_1$. Therefore, $a_{11} = R_1$.\n*   For $k=2$: Terminals 2 and 0 are opposite, so their equivalent resistance is $R_{20} = R_2$. Therefore, $a_{22} = R_2$.\n*   For $k=3$: Terminals 3 and 0 are adjacent, so their equivalent resistance is $R_{30} = R_1$. Therefore, $a_{33} = R_1$.\n\n### Step 2: Determine the off-diagonal coefficients of the resistance matrix ($a_{ij}$ for $i \\neq j$)\nNext, we determine the off-diagonal elements $a_{12}$, $a_{23}$, and $a_{13}$ by considering the resistances between pairs of non-reference terminals.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nThe relationship between terminal potentials and currents is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nV_i = \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{ij} I_j\n}\\]\nThe definition of two-terminal equivalent resistance is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nR_{k,l} = \\frac{V_k - V_l}{I}\n}\\]\nThe resistance matrix is symmetric:\n\\[\\boxed{\na_{ij} = a_{ji}\n}\\]\nThe problem states that due to the square's geometry, the resistance between any adjacent pair of vertices is $R_1$ and between any opposite pair is $R_2$.\n\n**Derivation**\nTo find the coefficient $a_{kl}$ where $k, l \\in \\{1, 2, 3\\}$ and $k \\neq l$, we consider injecting a current $I$ at terminal $k$ ($I_k = I$) and extracting it at terminal $l$ ($I_l = -I$). The other terminal current, $I_m$ (where $m \\neq k, l$), is zero. The potentials at terminals $k$ and $l$ are:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_k &= \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{kj} I_j = a_{kk}I_k + a_{kl}I_l + a_{km}I_m = a_{kk}I - a_{kl}I \\\\\nV_l &= \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{lj} I_j = a_{lk}I_k + a_{ll}I_l + a_{lm}I_m = a_{lk}I - a_{ll}I\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe potential difference between terminals $k$ and $l$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_k - V_l &= (a_{kk}I - a_{kl}I) - (a_{lk}I - a_{ll}I) \\\\\n&= (a_{kk} + a_{ll} - a_{kl} - a_{lk})I\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nUsing the symmetry property $a_{kl} = a_{lk}$, this becomes:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_k - V_l = (a_{kk} + a_{ll} - 2a_{kl})I\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThus, the equivalent resistance is $R_{kl} = \\frac{V_k - V_l}{I} = a_{kk} + a_{ll} - 2a_{kl}$. We can now solve for $a_{kl}$:\n*   **To find $a_{12}$**: Terminals 1 and 2 are adjacent, so $R_{12} = R_1$.\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    R_{12} &= a_{11} + a_{22} - 2a_{12} \\\\\n    R_1 &= R_1 + R_2 - 2a_{12} \\\\\n    0 &= R_2 - 2a_{12} \\implies a_{12} = \\frac{R_2}{2}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n*   **To find $a_{23}$**: Terminals 2 and 3 are adjacent, so $R_{23} = R_1$.\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    R_{23} &= a_{22} + a_{33} - 2a_{23} \\\\\n    R_1 &= R_2 + R_1 - 2a_{23} \\\\\n    0 &= R_2 - 2a_{23} \\implies a_{23} = \\frac{R_2}{2}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n*   **To find $a_{13}$**: Terminals 1 and 3 are opposite, so $R_{13} = R_2$.\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    R_{13} &= a_{11} + a_{33} - 2a_{13} \\\\\n    R_2 &= R_1 + R_1 - 2a_{13} \\\\\n    R_2 &= 2R_1 - 2a_{13} \\implies a_{13} = R_1 - \\frac{R_2}{2}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n\n### Step 3: Analyze the circuit with the shorted terminals\nWe now analyze the circuit under the specified condition: terminals 0 and 3 are short-circuited. We want to find the equivalent resistance between terminals 1 and 2. To do this, we inject a current $I$ at terminal 1 and extract it at terminal 2.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nA short circuit between two terminals means they are at the same electric potential. Since $V_0=0$ is the reference potential, the short-circuit condition is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nV_3 = V_0 = 0\n}\\]\nThe relationship between terminal potentials and currents remains valid:\n\\[\\boxed{\nV_i = \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{ij} I_j\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**\nThe experimental setup to measure the required resistance is as follows:\n*   Current $I$ is injected at terminal 1: $I_1 = I$.\n*   Current $I$ is extracted from terminal 2: $I_2 = -I$.\n*   Terminals 0 and 3 are short-circuited, which implies $V_3 = 0$. This condition will determine the current $I_3$ that flows into terminal 3.\n\nWe use the condition $V_3=0$ to find $I_3$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_3 &= a_{31}I_1 + a_{32}I_2 + a_{33}I_3 \\\\\n0 &= a_{31}(I) + a_{32}(-I) + a_{33}I_3 \\\\\n0 &= (a_{31} - a_{32})I + a_{33}I_3\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSolving for $I_3$ in terms of $I$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nI_3 = -\\frac{a_{31} - a_{32}}{a_{33}}I = \\frac{a_{32} - a_{31}}{a_{33}}I \\label{eq:I3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the coefficient values we found (using symmetry $a_{31}=a_{13}$ and $a_{32}=a_{23}$):\n$a_{13} = R_1 - R_2/2$, $a_{23} = R_2/2$, $a_{33} = R_1$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nI_3 = \\frac{R_2/2 - (R_1 - R_2/2)}{R_1}I = \\frac{R_2 - R_1}{R_1}I \\label{eq:I3_val}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the potential difference and equivalent resistance\nWith all currents ($I_1, I_2, I_3$) expressed in terms of $I$, we can calculate the potential difference $V_1 - V_2$ and subsequently the equivalent resistance $R_{eq}$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nThe definition of the required equivalent resistance is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nR_{eq} = \\frac{V_1 - V_2}{I}\n}\\]\nThe relationship between terminal potentials and currents is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nV_i = \\sum_{j=1}^{3} a_{ij} I_j\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**\nWe express the potentials $V_1$ and $V_2$ using the known currents $I_1=I$, $I_2=-I$, and $I_3$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_1 &= a_{11}I_1 + a_{12}I_2 + a_{13}I_3 = a_{11}I - a_{12}I + a_{13}I_3 \\\\\nV_2 &= a_{21}I_1 + a_{22}I_2 + a_{23}I_3 = a_{21}I - a_{22}I + a_{23}I_3\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe potential difference is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_1 - V_2 &= (a_{11}I - a_{12}I + a_{13}I_3) - (a_{21}I - a_{22}I + a_{23}I_3) \\\\\n&= (a_{11} - a_{21})I - (a_{12} - a_{22})I + (a_{13} - a_{23})I_3 \\\\\n&= (a_{11} - 2a_{12} + a_{22})I + (a_{13} - a_{23})I_3 \\quad (\\text{using } a_{12}=a_{21}) \\label{eq:V1V2_general}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we substitute the values of the coefficients and the expression for $I_3$ from eq. \\eqref{eq:I3_val}:\n*   $a_{11} - 2a_{12} + a_{22} = R_1 - 2(R_2/2) + R_2 = R_1$.\n*   $a_{13} - a_{23} = (R_1 - R_2/2) - (R_2/2) = R_1 - R_2$.\n*   $I_3 = \\frac{R_2 - R_1}{R_1}I$.\n\nSubstituting these into eq. \\eqref{eq:V1V2_general}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV_1 - V_2 &= (R_1)I + (R_1 - R_2)\\left(\\frac{R_2 - R_1}{R_1}\\right)I \\\\\n&= R_1 I - \\frac{(R_1 - R_2)^2}{R_1}I \\\\\n&= \\left( \\frac{R_1^2 - (R_1^2 - 2R_1R_2 + R_2^2)}{R_1} \\right)I \\\\\n&= \\left( \\frac{R_1^2 - R_1^2 + 2R_1R_2 - R_2^2}{R_1} \\right)I \\\\\n&= \\frac{2R_1R_2 - R_2^2}{R_1}I \\\\\n&= \\frac{R_2(2R_1 - R_2)}{R_1}I \\label{eq:V1V2_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe equivalent resistance $R_{eq}$ is therefore:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nR_{eq} = \\frac{V_1 - V_2}{I} = \\frac{R_2(2R_1 - R_2)}{R_1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe equivalent resistance between the other two vertices (1 and 2) when a pair of adjacent vertices (0 and 3) is short-circuited is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{R_{eq} = \\frac{R_2(2R_1 - R_2)}{R_1}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/412", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "Consider a semi-infinite solenoid with radius $R$, turns per unit length $n$, connected to a constant current source with current $I$. To facilitate subsequent calculations, we establish a cylindrical coordinate system such that the $z$-axis coincides with the symmetry axis of the solenoid. The solenoid extends from the origin along the negative $z$-axis to infinity, and the current is viewed as rotating counterclockwise when observed from above the $z$-axis, meaning the direction of the current is in the positive $\\hat{\\theta}$ direction. Now, a superconducting metal ring is placed such that some constraint keeps the symmetry axis of the current loop always coinciding with the $z$-axis, allowing it to move freely up and down in this state. It is known that at the instant the metal ring transitions from normal to superconducting state, a current $I_{0}$ flows within the ring, and there is no other external magnetic field at a sufficiently far distance from the solenoid. $I_{0}$ flows in the positive $\\hat{\\theta}$ direction. Subsequently, the metal ring remains in the superconducting state. Assume the gravitational acceleration is $\\overrightarrow{g}=-g\\widehat{z}$, the mass of the metal ring is $m$, and it is of uniform density. Let $z_{0}>0$ be known. If the equilibrium is stable, find the vibration period $T$ near the equilibrium position (expressed in terms of $n$, $I_{0}$, $r$, $R$, $L$, $m$), and the answer may include $z_{0}$. It is known that the radius of the metal ring is $r \\ll R$, and the self-inductance is $L$.", "solutions": "The equilibrium condition is\n\n$$\nF(z)=m g\n$$\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\mu_{0}n I R^{2}r^{2}\\frac{1}{(z^{2}+R^{2})^{3/2}}(\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}(1-\\frac{z}{\\sqrt{z^{2}+R^{2}}})-I_{0})=m g\n$$\n\nConsider the stability of the equilibrium. If $\\frac{d F}{d z}$ is negative, then the equilibrium is stable; otherwise, it is unstable.\n\n$$\n\\left.{\\frac{d F}{d z}}\\right|_{z_{0}}={\\frac{\\pi}{2}}\\mu_{0}n I R^{2}r^{2}\\cdot[({\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}}-I_{0}){\\frac{-3z_{0}}{(z_{0}^{2}+R^{2})^{5/2}}}+{\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}}{\\frac{3z_{0}^{2}-R^{2}}{(z_{0}^{2}+R^{2})^{3}}}]\n$$\n\nTherefore, the requirement for stability is\n\n$$\n\\frac{3z_{0}^{2}-R^{2}}{3z_{0}\\sqrt{z_{0}^{2}+R^{2}}}<1-\\frac{2I_{0}L}{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}\n$$\n\nIf the equilibrium is stable, then\n\n$$\nT=2\\pi\\sqrt{\\frac{m}{\\left.\\displaystyle-\\frac{d F}{d z}\\right|_{z_{0}}}}\n$$\n\n$$\nT=2\\pi\\sqrt{\\frac{m}{\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\mu_{0}n I R^{2}r^{2}\\cdot[(\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}-I_{0})\\frac{3z_{0}}{(z_{0}^{2}+R^{2})^{5/2}}-\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}\\frac{3z_{0}^{2}-R^{2}}{(z_{0}^{2}+R^{2})^{3}}]}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nT=2\\pi\\sqrt{\\frac{\\frac{1}{(z_0^{2}+R^{2})^{3/2}}(\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}(1-\\frac{z_0}{\\sqrt{z_0^{2}+R^{2}}})-I_{0})}{g\\left[(\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}-I_{0})\\frac{3z_{0}}{(z_{0}^{2}+R^{2})^{5/2}}-\\frac{\\mu_{0}n I\\pi r^{2}}{2L}\\frac{3z_{0}^{2}-R^{2}}{(z_{0}^{2}+R^{2})^{3}}\\right]}}\n$$\n\n", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem investigates the dynamics of a superconducting metal ring moving along the axis of a semi-infinite solenoid under the influence of both magnetic and gravitational forces. We are asked to determine the period of small vertical oscillations of the ring around a stable equilibrium position.\n\n**System Parameters and Geometry:**\n*   **Solenoid:** A semi-infinite solenoid with radius $R$ and $n$ turns per unit length. It is connected to a constant current source, carrying a current $I$.\n*   **Coordinate System:** A cylindrical coordinate system $(\\rho, \\theta, z)$ is used. The solenoid's axis of symmetry coincides with the $z$-axis, and the solenoid occupies the region $z \\le 0$. The current $I$ flows in the positive azimuthal direction ($+\\hat{\\theta}$), which is counter-clockwise when viewed from the positive $z$-axis.\n*   **Superconducting Ring:** A metal ring of mass $m$, radius $r$, and self-inductance $L$. It is constrained to move along the $z$-axis, with its center at position $z$. A key geometric assumption is that the ring's radius is much smaller than the solenoid's radius, i.e., $r \\ll R$.\n*   **Gravitational Field:** A uniform gravitational field is present, described by the gravitational acceleration vector $\\vec{g} = -g\\hat{z}$.\n\n**Initial and Boundary Conditions:**\n*   The ring is initially at a position very far from the solenoid ($z \\to \\infty$), where the magnetic field from the solenoid is negligible.\n*   At this distant location, the ring transitions into a superconducting state, carrying a persistent initial current $I_0$ which flows in the positive $\\hat{\\theta}$ direction.\n*   The ring remains in the superconducting state throughout its subsequent motion.\n\n**Objective:**\nThe problem asks for the period, $T$, of small oscillations of the ring around an equilibrium position $z_0 > 0$, given that this equilibrium is stable. For levitation at $z_0 > 0$, the magnetic force must be repulsive, pointing upwards to counteract the downward gravitational force. This imposes conditions on the direction of the current in the ring, which will be analyzed. The final expression for $T$ can be in terms of the given parameters: $n, I, I_0, r, R, L, m, g$, and the equilibrium position $z_0$.\n\n### Step 1: Magnetic Field of the Semi-Infinite Solenoid\nTo find the force on the ring, we first need the magnetic field produced by the solenoid. We calculate the magnetic field component along the axis of symmetry, $B_z(z)$, for any point $z>0$. We model the solenoid as a continuous distribution of circular current loops. The on-axis magnetic field of a single circular current loop of radius $R$ at an axial distance $d$ from its center, carrying current $I_{\\text{loop}}$, is given by the Biot-Savart law:\n\\[\n\\boxed{B_z = \\frac{\\mu_0 I_{\\text{loop}} R^2}{2(d^2 + R^2)^{3/2}}}\n\\]\nA differential segment of the solenoid of length $dz'$ at position $z' \\le 0$ acts as a current loop with an effective current $I_{\\text{loop}} = nI dz'$. The axial distance from this loop to a point $z>0$ on the axis is $d = z-z'$. To find the total field at $z$, we integrate the contributions from all such loops from $z'=-\\infty$ to $z'=0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nB_z(z) &= \\int_{-\\infty}^{0} \\frac{\\mu_0 (nI dz') R^2}{2((z-z')^2 + R^2)^{3/2}} \\label{eq:B_integral} \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I R^2}{2} \\int_{-\\infty}^{0} \\frac{dz'}{((z-z')^2 + R^2)^{3/2}} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Let } u = z' - z, \\text{ so } du = dz'. \\text{ The integration limits for } u \\text{ are } -\\infty \\text{ and } -z. \\nonumber \\\\\nB_z(z) &= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I R^2}{2} \\int_{-\\infty}^{-z} \\frac{du}{(u^2 + R^2)^{3/2}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I R^2}{2} \\left[ \\frac{u}{R^2 \\sqrt{u^2 + R^2}} \\right]_{-\\infty}^{-z} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\left( \\frac{-z}{\\sqrt{(-z)^2 + R^2}} - \\lim_{u \\to -\\infty} \\frac{u}{\\sqrt{u^2 + R^2}} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\left( \\frac{-z}{\\sqrt{z^2 + R^2}} - (-1) \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\left( 1 - \\frac{z}{\\sqrt{z^2 + R^2}} \\right) \\label{eq:B_field}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is the magnetic field component along the $z$-axis at a position $z>0$. Since $I>0$, $B_z(z)$ is positive for all $z>0$.\n\n### Step 2: Current in the Superconducting Ring\nA fundamental property of a perfect superconductor is that the total magnetic flux passing through it remains constant over time.\n\\[\\boxed{\\Phi_{\\text{total}} = \\Phi_{\\text{ext}}(z) + \\Phi_{\\text{self}}(z) = \\text{constant}}\\]\nThe total flux is the sum of the flux from the external magnetic field (from the solenoid), $\\Phi_{\\text{ext}}(z)$, and the flux from the ring's own current (self-flux), $\\Phi_{\\text{self}}(z)$. The self-flux is defined by the ring's self-inductance $L$ and its current $I_{\\text{ring}}(z)$.\n\\[\\boxed{\\Phi_{\\text{self}}(z) = L I_{\\text{ring}}(z)}\\]\nThe external flux is the integral of the solenoid's magnetic field over the area of the ring.\n\\[\\boxed{\\Phi_{\\text{ext}}(z) = \\int_{\\text{ring}} \\vec{B}_{\\text{solenoid}} \\cdot d\\vec{A}}\\]\nGiven the condition $r \\ll R$, the magnetic field $B_z(z)$ from the solenoid can be considered uniform over the ring's area $A = \\pi r^2$. The area vector is $d\\vec{A} = dA \\hat{z}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Phi_{\\text{ext}}(z) \\approx B_z(z) A = \\pi r^2 B_z(z) \\label{eq:flux_ext}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe constant total flux is determined by the initial conditions. At $z \\to \\infty$, the solenoid's field $B_z(\\infty) = \\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2}(1-1) = 0$, so the external flux $\\Phi_{\\text{ext}}(\\infty) = 0$. The initial current in the ring is given as $I_{\\text{ring}}(\\infty) = I_0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Phi_{\\text{total}} &= \\Phi_{\\text{ext}}(\\infty) + \\Phi_{\\text{self}}(\\infty) = 0 + L I_0 = L I_0 \\label{eq:flux_const}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nBy flux conservation, for any position $z$, we have $\\pi r^2 B_z(z) + L I_{\\text{ring}}(z) = L I_0$. We can solve for the current in the ring at any position $z$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nI_{\\text{ring}}(z) &= \\frac{L I_0 - \\pi r^2 B_z(z)}{L} = I_0 - \\frac{\\pi r^2}{L} B_z(z) \\label{eq:I_ring}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe term $-\\frac{\\pi r^2}{L} B_z(z)$ represents the induced current. According to Lenz's law, as the ring approaches the solenoid, the external flux (in the $+\\hat{z}$ direction) increases, so an opposing current is induced to create a flux in the $-\\hat{z}$ direction. This corresponds to a current in the $-\\hat{\\theta}$ direction.\n\n### Step 3: Magnetic Force on the Ring\nThe magnetic force on the current-carrying ring is given by the integral of the Lorentz force over the closed loop of the ring.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{F}_{\\text{mag}} = \\oint I_{\\text{ring}} d\\vec{l} \\times \\vec{B}_{\\text{solenoid}}}\\]\nTo evaluate this, we need the magnetic field $\\vec{B}_{\\text{solenoid}}$ at the location of the ring wire $(\\rho=r)$. For an axisymmetric field, Gauss's law for magnetism, $\\nabla \\cdot \\vec{B} = 0$, provides a relationship between the radial and axial components of the field.\n\\[\\boxed{\\nabla \\cdot \\vec{B} = 0 \\implies \\frac{1}{\\rho}\\frac{\\partial(\\rho B_\\rho)}{\\partial \\rho} + \\frac{\\partial B_z}{\\partial z} = 0}\\]\nFor small $\\rho$ near the axis, we can approximate $\\frac{\\partial B_z(\\rho,z)}{\\partial z} \\approx \\frac{dB_z(0,z)}{dz} \\equiv \\frac{dB_z}{dz}$. Integrating with respect to $\\rho$ gives $\\rho B_\\rho \\approx -\\int_0^\\rho \\rho' \\frac{dB_z}{dz} d\\rho' = -\\frac{\\rho^2}{2}\\frac{dB_z}{dz}$. Thus, the radial component is approximately:\n\\[\\boxed{B_\\rho(\\rho, z) \\approx -\\frac{\\rho}{2} \\frac{dB_z(z)}{dz}}\\]\nThe current element on the ring is $d\\vec{l} = r d\\theta \\hat{\\theta}$. The magnetic field at the ring is $\\vec{B}(r,z) \\approx B_z(z)\\hat{z} + B_\\rho(r,z)\\hat{\\rho}$. Substituting into the Lorentz force integral:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{F}_{\\text{mag}} &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} I_{\\text{ring}}(z) (r d\\theta \\hat{\\theta}) \\times \\left( B_z(z) \\hat{z} + B_\\rho(r, z) \\hat{\\rho} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= I_{\\text{ring}}(z) r \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left( B_z(z) (\\hat{\\theta} \\times \\hat{z}) + B_\\rho(r, z) (\\hat{\\theta} \\times \\hat{\\rho}) \\right) d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= I_{\\text{ring}}(z) r \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left( B_z(z) \\hat{\\rho} - B_\\rho(r, z) \\hat{z} \\right) d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{The radial unit vector } \\hat{\\rho} = \\cos\\theta\\hat{x} + \\sin\\theta\\hat{y} \\text{ integrates to zero over } [0, 2\\pi]. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\vec{F}_{\\text{mag}} &= -I_{\\text{ring}}(z) r \\hat{z} \\int_0^{2\\pi} B_\\rho(r, z) d\\theta = -I_{\\text{ring}}(z) r \\hat{z} \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left(-\\frac{r}{2} \\frac{dB_z(z)}{dz}\\right) d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= I_{\\text{ring}}(z) \\frac{r^2}{2} \\frac{dB_z}{dz} \\hat{z} (2\\pi) = I_{\\text{ring}}(z) (\\pi r^2) \\frac{dB_z}{dz} \\hat{z} \\label{eq:Force_formula}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe force is purely in the $z$-direction, $F_z(z) = I_{\\text{ring}}(z) (\\pi r^2) \\frac{dB_z}{dz}$. We need the derivative of $B_z(z)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dB_z}{dz} &= \\frac{d}{dz} \\left[ \\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\left( 1 - \\frac{z}{\\sqrt{z^2 + R^2}} \\right) \\right] = -\\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\frac{d}{dz} \\left( \\frac{z}{(z^2+R^2)^{1/2}} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\left( \\frac{(z^2+R^2)^{1/2}(1) - z \\cdot \\frac{1}{2}(z^2+R^2)^{-1/2}(2z)}{z^2+R^2} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{\\mu_0 n I}{2} \\left( \\frac{(z^2+R^2) - z^2}{(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}} \\right) = -\\frac{\\mu_0 n I R^2}{2(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}} \\label{eq:dB_dz}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSince all parameters are positive, $\\frac{dB_z}{dz} < 0$. For the magnetic force $F_z$ to be positive (repulsive, pointing upwards), we must have $I_{\\text{ring}}(z) < 0$. This means the current in the ring must flow in the direction opposite to the solenoid current, which is consistent with a repulsive force.\n\n### Step 4: Equilibrium and Stability Analysis\nThe total vertical force on the ring is the sum of the magnetic force $F_z(z)$ and the gravitational force $F_g = -mg$.\n\\[\\boxed{F_{\\text{net}}(z) = F_z(z) + F_g = F_z(z) - mg}\\]\nAt an equilibrium position $z_0$, the net force is zero. The upward magnetic force must balance the downward gravitational force.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nF_{\\text{net}}(z_0) = 0 \\quad \\implies \\quad F_z(z_0) = mg \\label{eq:Equilibrium}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor the equilibrium to be stable, any small displacement from $z_0$ must result in a restoring force. This corresponds to a local minimum of the potential energy, which requires the derivative of the net force with respect to position to be negative at the equilibrium point.\n\\[\\boxed{\\left.\\frac{dF_{\\text{net}}}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} < 0}\\]\nSince the gravitational force is constant, this condition simplifies to $\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} < 0$. As shown in Step 3, equilibrium requires $I_{ring}(z_0) < 0$. The second derivative of the magnetic field is $\\frac{d^2B_z}{dz^2} = \\frac{3\\mu_0 n I R^2 z}{2(z^2+R^2)^{5/2}} > 0$ for $z>0$. Differentiating the force gives $\\frac{dF_z}{dz} = \\frac{dI_{ring}}{dz}(\\pi r^2 \\frac{dB_z}{dz}) + I_{ring}(\\pi r^2 \\frac{d^2B_z}{dz^2}) = -\\frac{(\\pi r^2)^2}{L}(\\frac{dB_z}{dz})^2 + I_{ring}(\\pi r^2 \\frac{d^2B_z}{dz^2})$. At $z_0$, the first term is negative. The second term is a product of $I_{ring}(z_0)<0$ and other positive terms, so it is also negative. Thus, $\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0}$ is always negative, and any equilibrium point is stable.\n\n### Step 5: Period of Small Oscillations\nFor small oscillations around the stable equilibrium position $z_0$, we consider a small displacement $\\delta z$, such that $z = z_0 + \\delta z$. The net force can be approximated by a first-order Taylor expansion.\n\\[\\boxed{F_{\\text{net}}(z_0+\\delta z) \\approx F_{\\text{net}}(z_0) + \\left.\\frac{dF_{\\text{net}}}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} \\delta z}\\]\nUsing Newton's second law, $m\\ddot{\\delta z} = F_{\\text{net}}$, and the equilibrium condition $F_{\\text{net}}(z_0)=0$, the equation of motion for the displacement becomes that of a simple harmonic oscillator:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm\\ddot{\\delta z} = \\left(\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0}\\right) \\delta z = -k \\delta z\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe effective spring constant is $k = -\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0}$. The period of oscillation $T$ is given by:\n\\[\\boxed{T = 2\\pi\\sqrt{\\frac{m}{k}}}\\]\nTo calculate $k$, we differentiate $F_z(z) = \\left(I_0 - \\frac{\\pi r^2}{L}B_z(z)\\right) \\left(\\pi r^2 \\frac{dB_z}{dz}\\right)$. For convenience, let's define two functions based on the structure of the force expression:\n$H(z) = \\frac{\\pi r^2 B_z(z)}{L} - I_0$ and $G(z) = -\\pi r^2 \\frac{dB_z}{dz}$.\nWith these definitions, the force is $F_z(z) = -I_{ring}(z) G(z) = -(-H(z)) G(z) = H(z)G(z)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dF_z}{dz} &= \\frac{d}{dz}(H(z)G(z)) = \\frac{dH}{dz}G(z) + H(z)\\frac{dG}{dz} \\label{eq:dFdz_rule}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe find the derivatives of $H(z)$ and $G(z)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dH}{dz} &= \\frac{d}{dz}\\left(\\frac{\\pi r^2}{L} B_z(z) - I_0\\right) = \\frac{\\pi r^2}{L} \\frac{dB_z}{dz} = \\frac{\\pi r^2}{L} \\left(-\\frac{G(z)}{\\pi r^2}\\right) = -\\frac{G(z)}{L} \\label{eq:dHdz_clean} \\\\\n\\frac{dG}{dz} &= \\frac{d}{dz}\\left(-\\pi r^2 \\frac{dB_z}{dz}\\right) = \\frac{d}{dz}\\left(\\frac{\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2 R^2}{2}(z^2+R^2)^{-3/2}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2 R^2}{2} \\left(-\\frac{3}{2}(z^2+R^2)^{-5/2}(2z)\\right) = -\\frac{3z}{z^2+R^2} \\left(\\frac{\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2 R^2}{2(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}}\\right) = -\\frac{3z}{z^2+R^2} G(z) \\label{eq:dGdz_clean}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow substitute these derivatives into the expression for $\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0}$. At equilibrium, $F_z(z_0) = H(z_0)G(z_0) = mg$, so $H(z_0) = mg/G(z_0)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} &= \\left.\\frac{dH}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} G(z_0) + H(z_0)\\left.\\frac{dG}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left(-\\frac{G(z_0)}{L}\\right) G(z_0) + \\frac{mg}{G(z_0)} \\left(-\\frac{3z_0}{z_0^2+R^2} G(z_0)\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{G(z_0)^2}{L} - \\frac{3mg z_0}{z_0^2+R^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{where } G(z_0) &= -\\pi r^2 \\left.\\frac{dB_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} = \\frac{\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2 R^2}{2(z_0^2+R^2)^{3/2}}. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} &= -\\frac{1}{L}\\left(\\frac{\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2 R^2}{2(z_0^2+R^2)^{3/2}}\\right)^2 - \\frac{3mg z_0}{z_0^2+R^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\left( \\frac{(\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2)^2 R^4}{4L(z_0^2+R^2)^3} + \\frac{3mg z_0}{z_0^2+R^2} \\right) \\label{eq:dF_dz_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe spring constant $k$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nk = -\\left.\\frac{dF_z}{dz}\\right|_{z_0} = \\frac{3mg z_0}{z_0^2+R^2} + \\frac{(\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2)^2 R^4}{4L(z_0^2+R^2)^3} \\label{eq:k_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFinally, the period of oscillation is $T = 2\\pi\\sqrt{m/k}$.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe period of small oscillations $T$ near the stable equilibrium position $z_0$ is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{T = 2\\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{m}{\\frac{3mg z_0}{z_0^2+R^2} + \\frac{(\\mu_0 n I \\pi r^2)^2 R^4}{4L(z_0^2+R^2)^3}}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/43", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "Two dielectric materials with base areas both equal to $\\pmb{A}$, thicknesses of $h_{1}$ and $h_{2}$ respectively, dielectric constants of $\\varepsilon_{1}$ and $\\varepsilon_{2}$ respectively, and conductivities of $\\sigma_{1}$ and $\\sigma_{2}$ respectively, are placed tightly between two highly conductive flat plates with the same area $\\pmb{A}$ and a separation distance of $(h_{1}+h_{2})$, forming a capacitor. The system is connected into a circuit , with a power source of electromotive force $U_{0}$. Initially, the capacitor is uncharged, and at $\\scriptstyle t=0$, the switch is turned on. Determine the time-dependent relationship of the current $I(t)$ flowing through the switch for $t > 0$.", "solutions": "Let the magnitudes of the electric field intensity in the two media be $E_{1}, E_{2}$ respectively, and according to the relationship between the electric potentials, we have  \n\n$$\nE_{1}h_{1} + E_{2}h_{2} = U_{0}\n$$  \n\nThe magnitudes of the current density in the two media are  \n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n    j_1 &= \\sigma_1 E_1, \\\\\n    j_2 &= \\sigma_2 E_2.\n\\end{aligned}\n$$  \n\nLet the free charge surface density at the contact of the two media be $\\sigma_{\\bullet}$, then  \n\nFrom this, we obtain  \n\n$$\n\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l l}{\\displaystyle{\\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\sigma_{\\circ}}{\\mathrm{d}t}}=j_{1}-j_{2}}\\ {\\sigma_{\\circ}=\\varepsilon_{2}E_{2}-\\varepsilon_{1}E_{1}}\\end{array}\\right.\n$$  \n\n$$\nU_{0} = \\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\sigma_{0}}{\\mathrm{d}t}\\cdot\\left(\\frac{h_{1}\\varepsilon_{2} + h_{2}\\varepsilon_{1}}{\\sigma_{1}\\varepsilon_{2} - \\sigma_{2}\\varepsilon_{1}}\\right) + \\sigma_{0}\\cdot\\left(\\frac{\\sigma_{1}h_{2} + \\sigma_{2}h_{1}}{\\sigma_{1}\\varepsilon_{2} - \\sigma_{2}\\varepsilon_{1}}\\right)\n$$  \n\nThat is  \n\n$$\n\\sigma_{0} = \\frac{U_{0}\\left(\\sigma_{1}\\varepsilon_{2} - \\sigma_{2}\\varepsilon_{1}\\right)}{\\sigma_{1}h_{2} + \\sigma_{2}h_{1}}\\cdot\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{t}{\\tau}}\\right)\n$$  \n\nWhere the time constant is  \n\n$$\n\\tau = \\frac{h_{1}\\varepsilon_{2} + h_{2}\\varepsilon_{1}}{h_{1}\\sigma_{2} + h_{2}\\sigma_{1}}\n$$  \n\nThe current in the circuit can be obtained as  \n\n$$\nI = A{\\left(\\sigma_{1}E_{1} + \\varepsilon_{1}{\\frac{\\mathrm{d}E_{1}}{\\mathrm{d}t}}\\right)} = A{\\left(\\sigma_{2}E_{2} + \\varepsilon_{2}{\\frac{\\mathrm{d}E_{2}}{\\mathrm{d}t}}\\right)}\n$$  \n\nSubstitute in to get  \n\n$$\nI = A U_{0}\\cdot\\left[\\frac{\\sigma_{1}\\sigma_{2}}{\\sigma_{1}h_{2}+\\sigma_{2}h_{1}} + \\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{\\sigma_{1}h_{2}+\\sigma_{2}h_{1}}{\\varepsilon_{1}h_{2}+\\varepsilon_{2}h_{1}}t}\\cdot\\left(\\frac{\\varepsilon_{2}\\sigma_{1}+\\varepsilon_{1}\\sigma_{2}}{\\varepsilon_{1}h_{2}+\\varepsilon_{2}h_{1}} - \\frac{\\sigma_{1}\\sigma_{2}}{\\sigma_{1}h_{2}+\\sigma_{2}h_{1}} - \\frac{\\varepsilon_{1}\\varepsilon_{2}\\left(\\sigma_{1}h_{2}+\\sigma_{2}h_{1}\\right)}{\\left(\\varepsilon_{1}h_{2}+\\varepsilon_{2}h_{1}\\right)^{2}}\\right)\\right]\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nI = A U_0 \\left[\\frac{\\sigma_1 \\sigma_2}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} + e^{-\\frac{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1}{\\varepsilon_1 h_2 + \\varepsilon_2 h_1} t} \\left(\\frac{\\varepsilon_2 \\sigma_1 + \\varepsilon_1 \\sigma_2}{\\varepsilon_1 h_2 + \\varepsilon_2 h_1} - \\frac{\\sigma_1 \\sigma_2}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} - \\frac{\\varepsilon_1 \\varepsilon_2 (\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)}{(\\varepsilon_1 h_2 + \\varepsilon_2 h_1)^2} \\right)\\right]\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem analyzes the transient behavior of a composite capacitor connected to a DC voltage source. The capacitor is constructed from two parallel, highly conductive plates, each with area $A$. The plates are separated by a total distance of $(h_1 + h_2)$. The space between the plates is filled by two different dielectric materials stacked in series.\n\nThe properties of the two dielectric materials are:\n*   **Material 1**: Thickness $h_1$, dielectric constant $\\varepsilon_1$, and conductivity $\\sigma_1$.\n*   **Material 2**: Thickness $h_2$, dielectric constant $\\varepsilon_2$, and conductivity $\\sigma_2$.\n\nThe capacitor is connected in a circuit with a power source providing a constant electromotive force (EMF) $U_0$. At time $t=0$, a switch is closed, connecting the power source to the capacitor, which is initially uncharged. The goal is to determine the total current $I(t)$ flowing through the circuit for all times $t > 0$.\n\nWe will use the following variables in our analysis:\n*   $E_1(t)$, $E_2(t)$: The magnitudes of the electric fields in material 1 and 2, respectively.\n*   $j_1(t)$, $j_2(t)$: The magnitudes of the conduction current densities in material 1 and 2.\n*   $\\sigma_f(t)$: The free surface charge density that accumulates at the interface between the two dielectrics.\n*   $I(t)$: The total current flowing through the switch.\n\nWe make the following assumptions:\n1.  The electric field and current density are uniform within each dielectric layer and are directed perpendicular to the capacitor plates.\n2.  The conductivity of the plates is infinite, so there is no potential drop across them.\n3.  Fringing effects at the edges of the capacitor are negligible.\n\nThis physical system can be modeled as an equivalent electrical circuit. Each dielectric layer acts as a resistor ($R_i = h_i / (\\sigma_i A)$) in parallel with a capacitor ($C_i = \\varepsilon_i A / h_i$). The two resulting R-C parallel blocks are connected in series across the voltage source $U_0$. While we will solve the problem using fundamental electromagnetic field equations, this circuit model provides a useful physical intuition for the initial and final states of the system.\n\n### Step 1: Fundamental Physical Laws\nWe establish the fundamental equations governing the electromagnetic fields and charges within the capacitor. These equations are derived from Maxwell's equations and material relations.\n\n1.  **Voltage Relation**: The total potential drop across the two dielectrics is equal to the applied voltage $U_0$. This is an application of Kirchhoff's voltage law for a closed loop including the source.\n    \\[\\boxed{U_0 = \\int_0^{h_1+h_2} \\vec{E} \\cdot d\\vec{l}}\\]\n    Given our assumption of uniform fields, this simplifies to:\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    E_1(t) h_1 + E_2(t) h_2 = U_0 \\label{eq:volt} \\tag{1}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n2.  **Gauss's Law at the Interface**: The discontinuity in the electric displacement field ($\\vec{D} = \\varepsilon \\vec{E}$) at the interface is equal to the free surface charge density $\\sigma_f$.\n    \\[\\boxed{\\hat{n} \\cdot (\\vec{D}_2 - \\vec{D}_1) = \\sigma_f}\\]\n    With fields perpendicular to the interface (let the direction from material 1 to 2 be positive), this becomes:\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    \\varepsilon_2 E_2(t) - \\varepsilon_1 E_1(t) = \\sigma_f(t) \\label{eq:gauss} \\tag{2}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n3.  **Charge Conservation at the Interface**: The rate of accumulation of charge at the interface equals the net conduction current flowing into it. This is derived from the continuity equation.\n    \\[\\boxed{\\frac{d\\sigma_f}{dt} = \\hat{n} \\cdot (\\vec{j}_1 - \\vec{j}_2)}\\]\n    For our one-dimensional case, this is:\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    \\frac{d\\sigma_f(t)}{dt} = j_1(t) - j_2(t) \\label{eq:continuity} \\tag{3}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n4.  **Ohm's Law**: The conduction current density in each material is proportional to the electric field.\n    \\[\\boxed{\\vec{j} = \\sigma \\vec{E}}\\]\n    This gives us the relations for each material:\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    j_1(t) = \\sigma_1 E_1(t) \\quad \\text{and} \\quad j_2(t) = \\sigma_2 E_2(t) \\label{eq:ohm} \\tag{4}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n\n### Step 2: Deriving the Differential Equation for Interface Charge\nWe combine the equations from Step 1 to obtain a single differential equation for the interface charge density $\\sigma_f(t)$. First, we express the electric fields $E_1$ and $E_2$ in terms of $\\sigma_f$ and $U_0$ by solving the linear system formed by Eq. \\eqref{eq:volt} and \\eqref{eq:gauss}.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\text{From \\eqref{eq:volt}:} \\quad E_2 &= \\frac{U_0 - E_1 h_1}{h_2} \\nonumber \\\\\n    \\text{Substitute into \\eqref{eq:gauss}:} \\quad \\varepsilon_2 \\left(\\frac{U_0 - E_1 h_1}{h_2}\\right) - \\varepsilon_1 E_1 &= \\sigma_f \\nonumber \\\\\n    \\varepsilon_2 U_0 - \\varepsilon_2 h_1 E_1 - \\varepsilon_1 h_2 E_1 &= h_2 \\sigma_f \\nonumber \\\\\n    (\\varepsilon_1 h_2 + \\varepsilon_2 h_1) E_1 &= \\varepsilon_2 U_0 - h_2 \\sigma_f \\nonumber \\\\\n    E_1(t) &= \\frac{\\varepsilon_2 U_0 - h_2 \\sigma_f(t)}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\label{eq:E1} \\tag{5} \\\\\n    \\text{Similarly, solving for } E_2(t): \\quad E_2(t) &= \\frac{\\varepsilon_1 U_0 + h_1 \\sigma_f(t)}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\label{eq:E2} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNext, we substitute these expressions for $E_1$ and $E_2$ into the charge conservation equation \\eqref{eq:continuity}, using Ohm's law \\eqref{eq:ohm}.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\frac{d\\sigma_f}{dt} &= \\sigma_1 E_1 - \\sigma_2 E_2 \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\sigma_1 \\left(\\frac{\\varepsilon_2 U_0 - h_2 \\sigma_f}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1}\\right) - \\sigma_2 \\left(\\frac{\\varepsilon_1 U_0 + h_1 \\sigma_f}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)U_0 - (\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)\\sigma_f}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\label{eq:pre_de} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nRearranging this expression yields a first-order linear ordinary differential equation for $\\sigma_f(t)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\frac{d\\sigma_f}{dt} + \\left(\\frac{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1}\\right) \\sigma_f = \\frac{\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} U_0 \\label{eq:de_sigma} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Solving for the Interface Charge Density $\\sigma_f(t)$\nThe differential equation \\eqref{eq:de_sigma} is of the standard form $\\frac{dy}{dt} + P y = Q$, where $P$ and $Q$ are constants.\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{For } \\frac{dy}{dt} + Py = Q, \\text{ the general solution is } y(t) = \\frac{Q}{P} + C e^{-Pt}}\\]\nThe initial condition is that the capacitor is uncharged at $t=0$, which implies there is no initial charge at the interface.\n\\[\\boxed{\\sigma_f(t=0) = 0}\\]\nFrom Eq. \\eqref{eq:de_sigma}, we identify the relaxation time constant $\\tau = 1/P$ and the steady-state charge density $\\sigma_{f,\\infty} = Q/P$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\tau &= \\frac{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\label{eq:tau} \\tag{9} \\\\\n    \\sigma_{f,\\infty} &= \\lim_{t\\to\\infty} \\sigma_f(t) = \\frac{(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)U_0 / (h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)}{(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1) / (h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)} = \\frac{(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)U_0}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\label{eq:sigma_inf} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe general solution for the interface charge density is $\\sigma_f(t) = \\sigma_{f,\\infty} + C e^{-t/\\tau}$. We apply the initial condition $\\sigma_f(0)=0$ to find the integration constant $C$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\sigma_f(0) = \\sigma_{f,\\infty} + C e^{0} = 0 \\implies C = -\\sigma_{f,\\infty} \\nonumber\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTherefore, the time-dependent interface charge density is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\sigma_f(t) = \\sigma_{f,\\infty} (1 - e^{-t/\\tau}) = \\frac{(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)U_0}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\left(1 - e^{-t/\\tau}\\right) \\label{eq:sigma_t} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Derivation of the Total Current I(t)\nThe total current density, $\\vec{j}_{\\text{total}}$, is the sum of the conduction current density and the displacement current density. It must be uniform throughout the device due to charge conservation.\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{j}_{\\text{total}} = \\vec{j}_{\\text{cond}} + \\frac{\\partial \\vec{D}}{\\partial t} = \\sigma \\vec{E} + \\varepsilon \\frac{\\partial \\vec{E}}{\\partial t}}\\]\nThe total current $I(t)$ is the total current density multiplied by the area $A$. We can calculate it using the fields in either material. Let's use material 1.\n\\[\\boxed{I(t) = A j_{\\text{total},1} = A \\left(\\sigma_1 E_1(t) + \\varepsilon_1 \\frac{dE_1(t)}{dt}\\right)}\\]\nSince $\\sigma_f(t)$ relaxes to its final value exponentially with time constant $\\tau$, so does $E_1(t)$. We can write $E_1(t) = E_{1,\\infty} + (E_{1,0} - E_{1,\\infty})e^{-t/\\tau}$. Substituting this into the current equation gives $I(t) = I_\\infty + I_{\\text{transient}}(t)$, where $I_\\infty$ is the steady-state current and $I_{\\text{transient}}(t)$ decays with time constant $\\tau$.\n\nFirst, we find the steady-state current $I_\\infty$. As $t \\to \\infty$, all time derivatives vanish, so $I_\\infty = A \\sigma_1 E_{1,\\infty}$. We find $E_{1,\\infty}$ by substituting $\\sigma_{f,\\infty}$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:sigma_inf} into Eq. \\eqref{eq:E1}.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    E_{1,\\infty} &= \\frac{\\varepsilon_2 U_0 - h_2 \\sigma_{f,\\infty}}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} = \\frac{1}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\left( \\varepsilon_2 U_0 - h_2 \\frac{(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)U_0}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{U_0}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\left[ \\varepsilon_2(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1) - h_2(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{U_0}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\left[ \\varepsilon_2 \\sigma_1 h_2 + \\varepsilon_2 \\sigma_2 h_1 - h_2 \\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1 \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{U_0}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\left[ \\sigma_2(\\varepsilon_2 h_1 + \\varepsilon_1 h_2) \\right] = \\frac{\\sigma_2 U_0}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\label{eq:E1_inf} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe steady-state current is therefore:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    I_\\infty = A \\sigma_1 E_{1,\\infty} = A \\sigma_1 \\left(\\frac{\\sigma_2 U_0}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1}\\right) = \\frac{A U_0 \\sigma_1 \\sigma_2}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\label{eq:I_inf} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNext, we find the transient part of the current, which can be written as $I_{\\text{transient}}(t) = I_{\\text{transient},0} e^{-t/\\tau}$. The amplitude $I_{\\text{transient},0}$ is given by $A (\\sigma_1 - \\varepsilon_1/\\tau) (E_{1,0} - E_{1,\\infty})$. We calculate the terms in this expression.\nAt $t=0$, $\\sigma_f(0)=0$. From Eq. \\eqref{eq:E1}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    E_{1,0} = E_1(0) = \\frac{\\varepsilon_2 U_0}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\label{eq:E1_0} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe difference between initial and final electric field is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    E_{1,0} - E_{1,\\infty} &= \\frac{\\varepsilon_2 U_0}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} - \\frac{\\sigma_2 U_0}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{U_0 \\left[ \\varepsilon_2(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1) - \\sigma_2(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1) \\right]}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{U_0 \\left[ \\varepsilon_2 \\sigma_1 h_2 + \\varepsilon_2 \\sigma_2 h_1 - \\sigma_2 h_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 h_2 \\varepsilon_1 \\right]}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= U_0 \\frac{h_2(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\label{eq:factor2} \\tag{15}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe other factor in the transient amplitude is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    \\sigma_1 - \\frac{\\varepsilon_1}{\\tau} &= \\sigma_1 - \\varepsilon_1 \\frac{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} = \\frac{\\sigma_1(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1) - \\varepsilon_1(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{\\sigma_1 h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + \\sigma_1 h_2 \\varepsilon_1 - \\varepsilon_1 \\sigma_1 h_2 - \\varepsilon_1 \\sigma_2 h_1}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} = \\frac{h_1(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\label{eq:factor1} \\tag{16}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe amplitude of the transient current is $A$ times the product of \\eqref{eq:factor1} and \\eqref{eq:factor2}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n    I_{\\text{transient},0} &= A \\left( \\frac{h_1(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} \\right) \\left( U_0 \\frac{h_2(\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)(\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n    &= \\frac{A U_0 h_1 h_2 (\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)^2}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)^2 (\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\label{eq:I_trans_amp} \\tag{17}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nCombining the steady-state current \\eqref{eq:I_inf} and the transient current gives the total current $I(t) = I_\\infty + I_{\\text{transient},0} e^{-t/\\tau}$.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe time-dependent relationship of the current $I(t)$ flowing through the switch for $t > 0$ is the sum of a constant steady-state current and an exponentially decaying transient current:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{I(t) = \\frac{A U_0 \\sigma_1 \\sigma_2}{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1} + \\frac{A U_0 h_1 h_2 (\\sigma_1 \\varepsilon_2 - \\sigma_2 \\varepsilon_1)^2}{(h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1)^2 (\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1)} \\exp\\left(-\\frac{\\sigma_1 h_2 + \\sigma_2 h_1}{h_1 \\varepsilon_2 + h_2 \\varepsilon_1} t\\right)}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/117", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "There is an available cycloidal valley, which can be described using a cycloid (downward along the $y$-axis): \n$$\n\\left\\{{\\begin{array}{l}{x=R(\\theta-\\sin\\theta)}\\\\ {y=R(1-\\cos\\theta)}\\end{array}}\\right.\n$$\n Someone wants to release a cube with a mass of $M$ and with equal length, width, and height of $r$ at rest from one end of the valley at $\\theta = 0$. It is released facing the slope. A layer of snow with a surface density of $\\sigma$ is attached to the valley. The snow is in contact with the ground but does not interact, remaining stationary until it touches the object, at which point it adheres to its surface without altering the object's shape. Assuming gravitational acceleration $g$, there are the approximate conditions $\\sigma r R \\ll M, r \\ll R$ (results are retained up to the first order of $r$). Determine the highest position the cube can reach at the other end (considering no rolling occurs).\n", "solutions": "In this sub-question, energy is not conserved, but analyzing its motion still presents certain difficulties. Considering that the problem only requires accuracy to the first-order term, the loss of ascent quotient can be divided into two parts for correction, with zero-order motion considered during the correction process.  For the collision process between the square block and the snow, consider the conservation of momentum:  $$ M v = (M + \\sigma\\gamma u{\\mathrm{d}}t)(v - {\\mathrm{d}}v) $$  This results in:  $$ \\mathrm{d}\\upsilon = -\\frac{\\sigma r v^{2}}{M}\\mathrm{d}t $$  The energy loss during the process is:  $$ d E = \\frac{1}{2}(M + \\mathrm{d}M)(\\upsilon + \\mathrm{d}\\upsilon)^{2} - \\frac{1}{2}(M)\\upsilon^{2} = -\\frac{1}{2}\\sigma r\\upsilon^{2}\\upsilon\\mathrm{d}t = -\\frac{1}{2}\\sigma r\\upsilon^{2}\\mathrm{d}s $$  In this case, it can be treated as linear motion, and the equation is not influenced by acceleration. Therefore, it can be corrected independently, with the zero-order velocity expression as:  $$ \\upsilon_{0} = \\sqrt{2g R(1-\\cos\\theta)} $$  Substituting into the integral:  $$ \\delta W = \\int f\\mathrm{d}s = \\int_{0}^{2\\pi} -g R(1-\\cos\\theta)\\sigma\\boldsymbol{r}\\cdot2R\\sin\\frac{\\theta}{2}\\mathrm{d}\\theta = -\\frac{32}{3}g R^{2}r\\sigma $$  This gives the energy loss caused by collisions, which we convert into a height correction, then combine it with the correction for the gravitational component of the snow from the first question, resulting in the total reached height:  $$ \\begin{array}{l} {{\\delta y_{f} = \\displaystyle\\frac{32}{3}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sigma R^{2}r}{M}}}{{}}\\\\ {{\\delta y_{g} = \\displaystyle\\frac{32}{3}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sigma R^{2}r}{M}}}{{}}\\\\ {{\\delta y = \\displaystyle\\frac{64}{3}\\displaystyle\\frac{\\sigma R^{2}r}{M}}} \\end{array} $$  The two combined terms are both first-order and do not interfere with each other.\n", "final_answers": "$$\n\\delta y=\\frac{64}{3}\\frac{\\sigma R^2 r}{M}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the highest position a cube reaches when sliding in a cycloidal valley covered with snow. The cube starts from rest and accumulates snow as it moves.\n\nThe physical situation is defined by the following elements:\n*   **The Cube:** An object of mass `M` and side length `r`.\n*   **The Valley:** A cycloidal path, with the y-axis pointing downwards. The path of the cube's center of mass is described by the parametric equations:\n    $$\n    \\left\\{{\\begin{array}{l}{x=R(\\theta-\\sin\\theta)}\\\\ {y=R(1-\\cos\\theta)}\\end{array}}\\right.\n    $$\n    *   `R` is the radius of the generating circle of the cycloid.\n    *   `\\theta` is the parameter describing the position along the path.\n    *   `y` represents the vertical drop from the starting height. The initial position is at `\\theta=0`, corresponding to `(x,y)=(0,0)`.\n*   **The Snow:** A layer of snow with a uniform surface density `\\sigma` (mass per unit area) covers the valley. As the cube slides, it collects a strip of snow of width `r`.\n*   **The Process:** The cube is released from rest at `\\theta=0`. It slides down into the valley and up the other side, continuously accumulating mass through perfectly inelastic collisions with the stationary snow. We need to find the final vertical position `y_f` where the cube momentarily stops.\n*   **Assumptions and Approximations:**\n    1.  The cube slides without rolling.\n    2.  The accumulated snow adheres to the cube but does not alter its effective shape or size `r` for the purpose of collecting more snow.\n    3.  The total mass of the collected snow is much smaller than the cube's mass. This is formally stated by the condition `\\sigma r R \\ll M`, which implies that `\\epsilon = (\\sigma r R)/M` is a small dimensionless parameter. All results will be calculated to the first order in this parameter.\n    4.  The cube's size is much smaller than the valley's characteristic dimension, `r \\ll R`. This justifies treating the cube as a point mass for its trajectory and kinematics.\n    5.  The gravitational acceleration `g` is constant.\n\n### Step 1: Arc Length of the Cycloidal Path\nTo determine the mass of snow collected, we need the arc length `s` of the path. The differential arc length `ds` for a curve defined by parametric equations `x(\\theta)` and `y(\\theta)` is given by:\n\\[\n\\boxed{ds = \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{dx}{d\\theta}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{dy}{d\\theta}\\right)^2} d\\theta}\n\\]\n**Derivation:**\nFirst, we compute the derivatives of the parametric coordinates with respect to `\\theta`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dx}{d\\theta} &= \\frac{d}{d\\theta} [R(\\theta - \\sin\\theta)] = R(1 - \\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:dxdtheta} \\\\\n\\frac{dy}{d\\theta} &= \\frac{d}{d\\theta} [R(1 - \\cos\\theta)] = R\\sin\\theta \\label{eq:dydtheta}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting these into the arc length formula:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nds &= \\sqrt{[R(1 - \\cos\\theta)]^2 + [R\\sin\\theta]^2} \\, d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= R \\sqrt{(1 - 2\\cos\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta) + \\sin^2\\theta} \\, d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= R \\sqrt{2 - 2\\cos\\theta} \\, d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nUsing the half-angle trigonometric identity `1 - \\cos\\theta = 2\\sin^2(\\theta/2)`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nds &= R \\sqrt{4\\sin^2(\\theta/2)} \\, d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2R\\sin(\\theta/2) \\, d\\theta \\quad (\\text{since } \\sin(\\theta/2) \\ge 0 \\text{ for } \\theta \\in [0, 2\\pi])\n\\label{eq:ds}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Zeroth-Order Velocity Approximation\nWe perform a first-order perturbation analysis based on the small parameter `(\\sigma r R)/M`. As a first step, we find the velocity of the cube in the absence of snow (the zeroth-order solution). In this idealized case, mechanical energy is conserved.\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\Delta E_k + \\Delta U_g = 0}\n\\]\n**Derivation:**\nThe cube starts from rest (`E_{k,i}=0`) at `y=0`. We define the initial potential energy as `U_{g,i}=0`. At a vertical drop `y`, the kinetic energy is `E_k = \\frac{1}{2}Mv_0^2` and the potential energy is `U_g = -Mgy` (since the y-axis points downwards).\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n(\\frac{1}{2}Mv_0^2 - 0) + (-Mgy - 0) &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{1}{2}Mv_0^2 &= Mgy \\nonumber \\\\\nv_0^2 &= 2gy\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the expression for `y` from the problem statement, `y = R(1-\\cos\\theta)`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv_0^2 = 2gR(1-\\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:v0_sq}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis unperturbed velocity `v_0` will be used to approximate the true velocity `v` when calculating first-order energy loss terms.\n\n### Step 3: Overall Energy Balance for the System\nWe consider the system to be the cube plus all the snow it collects along its entire path. This choice is advantageous because the non-conservative forces associated with the inelastic collisions (the adhesion of snow) are internal to the system. We can then apply the generalized work-energy theorem, which relates the work done by external forces to the change in the total energy of the system.\n\\[\n\\boxed{W_{\\text{ext}} = \\Delta E_k + \\Delta E_p + \\Delta E_{\\text{th}}}\n\\]\n**Derivation:**\nIn this problem:\n*   The external forces are gravity and the normal force. The work done by gravity is accounted for by the change in potential energy `\\Delta E_p`. The normal force is always perpendicular to the displacement, so it does no work. Thus, `W_{\\text{ext}} = 0`.\n*   The system starts from rest and ends at rest, so the net change in kinetic energy is `\\Delta E_k = 0`.\n*   `\\Delta E_p` is the total change in gravitational potential energy of the cube and all the collected snow.\n*   `\\Delta E_{\\text{th}}` is the thermal energy generated due to the perfectly inelastic collisions between the cube and the snow.\n\nThe energy balance equation for the entire process from the initial state (rest at `y=0`) to the final state (rest at `y=y_f`) simplifies to:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n0 = 0 + \\Delta E_p + \\Delta E_{\\text{th}} \\implies \\Delta E_p + \\Delta E_{\\text{th}} = 0 \\label{eq:energy_balance}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Change in Gravitational Potential Energy (`\\Delta E_p`)\nThe total change in potential energy is the sum of the changes for the cube and for the snow. The gravitational potential energy of a mass `m` at a vertical position `y` (with the y-axis pointing downwards) is:\n\\[\n\\boxed{U_g = -mgy}\n\\]\n**Derivation:**\nThe total change in potential energy is `\\Delta E_p = \\Delta E_{p, \\text{cube}} + \\Delta E_{p, \\text{snow}}`.\nFor the cube:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta E_{p, \\text{cube}} &= U_{g, \\text{cube, final}} - U_{g, \\text{cube, initial}} = -Mgy_f - (-Mg \\cdot 0) = -Mgy_f \\label{eq:dEp_cube}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor the snow, an infinitesimal mass element `dm = \\sigma r ds` is initially at rest at position `y(s)`. At the end of the process, this mass is part of the cube-snow conglomerate at the final height `y_f`. The change in its potential energy is `d(\\Delta E_{p, \\text{snow}}) = -gy_f dm - (-gy(s) dm)`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta E_{p, \\text{snow}} &= \\int_0^{s_f} g(y(s) - y_f) dm = g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds - g y_f \\int_0^{s_f} \\sigma r ds \\nonumber \\\\\n&= g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds - g y_f m_{\\text{snow, total}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe are solving for `y_f` to first order in the small parameter `\\epsilon = (\\sigma r R)/M`. The term `g\\sigma r \\int y ds` is of order `g \\sigma r R^2`. The term `g y_f m_{\\text{snow, total}}` is of order `g y_f (\\sigma r R)`. Since the energy loss is a first-order effect, `y_f` will be proportional to `\\epsilon`. Thus, the term `g y_f m_{\\text{snow, total}}` is of order `g ((\\sigma r R^2)/M) (\\sigma r R) = g(\\sigma r)^2 R^3/M`. This is smaller than the `g \\sigma r R^2` term by a factor of `\\epsilon`, making it a second-order correction. We can therefore neglect it.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta E_{p, \\text{snow}} \\approx g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds \\label{eq:dEp_snow}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nCombining the terms for the cube and snow:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta E_p \\approx -Mgy_f + g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds \\label{eq:dEp_total}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Dissipated Thermal Energy (`\\Delta E_{\\text{th}}`)\nThermal energy is generated during the continuous series of perfectly inelastic collisions. The energy dissipated in a perfectly inelastic collision between a moving mass `m_1` and a stationary mass `m_2` is equal to the loss of kinetic energy in the center-of-mass frame, which is given by:\n\\[\n\\boxed{dE_{\\text{th}} = \\frac{1}{2}\\mu v_{\\text{rel}}^2}\n\\]\nwhere `\\mu = \\frac{m_1 m_2}{m_1+m_2}` is the reduced mass and `v_{\\text{rel}}` is the relative velocity.\n**Derivation:**\nHere, `m_1 = m(s)` is the current mass of the cube plus snow, `m_2 = dm = \\sigma r ds` is the infinitesimal mass of the snow element being collected, and `v_{\\text{rel}} = v(s)` is the velocity of the cube relative to the stationary snow.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ndE_{\\text{th}} = \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{m(s) \\cdot dm}{m(s)+dm}v(s)^2 = \\frac{1}{2} dm \\, v(s)^2 \\left( \\frac{m(s)}{m(s)+dm} \\right)\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSince `dm \\ll m(s) \\approx M`, the correction factor `\\frac{m(s)}{m(s)+dm} = \\frac{1}{1+dm/m(s)} \\approx 1 - \\frac{dm}{m(s)}`. The error introduced by approximating this factor as 1 is of order `dm/M`. This leads to a second-order correction in the total dissipated energy, which can be neglected in a first-order calculation.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ndE_{\\text{th}} \\approx \\frac{1}{2} dm \\, v(s)^2 = \\frac{1}{2} (\\sigma r ds) v(s)^2\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe total thermal energy dissipated over the entire path from the start to the final position `s_f` is the integral of this expression.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Delta E_{\\text{th}} = \\int_0^{s_f} dE_{\\text{th}} = \\frac{1}{2} \\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} v(s)^2 ds \\label{eq:dEth_total}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 6: Combining Terms and Solving for the Final Height\nWe now substitute the expressions for `\\Delta E_p` (Eq. \\ref{eq:dEp_total}) and `\\Delta E_{\\text{th}}` (Eq. \\ref{eq:dEth_total}) into the energy balance equation from Step 3.\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\Delta E_p + \\Delta E_{\\text{th}} = 0}\n\\]\n**Derivation:**\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(-Mgy_f + g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds\\right) + \\left(\\frac{1}{2} \\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} v(s)^2 ds\\right) \\approx 0\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSolving for `Mgy_f`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nMgy_f \\approx g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds + \\frac{1}{2} \\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} v(s)^2 ds \\label{eq:mgyf_s}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe integrals are already multiplied by the small quantity `\\sigma r`, so to obtain a first-order result for `y_f`, we can use the zeroth-order approximation for the integrands. The true velocity squared `v(s)^2` can be replaced by the unperturbed velocity squared `v_0(s)^2 = 2gy(s)`. The error introduced, `v_0^2 - v^2`, is of first order in `\\sigma r`, so its contribution to the integral results in a second-order error in `y_f`, which is negligible.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nMgy_f &\\approx g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds + \\frac{1}{2} \\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} (2gy(s)) ds \\nonumber \\\\\n&= g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds + g\\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2 g \\sigma r \\int_0^{s_f} y(s) ds\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSince the energy loss is small, the cube almost reaches the same height on the other side, so the final parameter `\\theta_f` is close to `2\\pi`. We can approximate the upper limit of the integral `s_f` by the path length of a full arch, `s(2\\pi)`. This is valid because the integrand is already of first order in `\\sigma r`, so corrections to the integration limit only introduce second-order errors to `y_f`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nMgy_f &\\approx 2 g \\sigma r \\int_0^{2\\pi} y(\\theta) \\frac{ds}{d\\theta} d\\theta\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFinally, solving for `y_f`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ny_f \\approx \\frac{2 \\sigma r}{M} \\int_0^{2\\pi} y(\\theta) \\frac{ds}{d\\theta} d\\theta \\label{eq:yf_integral_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 7: Evaluating the Path Integral\nThe final step is to compute the definite integral `\\int_0^{2\\pi} y(\\theta) \\frac{ds}{d\\theta} d\\theta`.\n**Derivation:**\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^{2\\pi} y(\\theta) \\frac{ds}{d\\theta} d\\theta &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} [R(1-\\cos\\theta)] [2R\\sin(\\theta/2)] d\\theta \\quad (\\text{using Eq. \\ref{eq:ds}}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2R^2 \\int_0^{2\\pi} (1-\\cos\\theta)\\sin(\\theta/2) d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2R^2 \\int_0^{2\\pi} [2\\sin^2(\\theta/2)]\\sin(\\theta/2) d\\theta \\quad (\\text{using } 1-\\cos\\theta = 2\\sin^2(\\theta/2)) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 4R^2 \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\sin^3(\\theta/2) d\\theta\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nLet `u = \\theta/2`, so `d\\theta = 2du`. The integration limits for `u` are from `0` to `\\pi`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n4R^2 \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\sin^3(\\theta/2) d\\theta &= 4R^2 \\int_0^{\\pi} \\sin^3(u) (2du) = 8R^2 \\int_0^{\\pi} \\sin^3(u) du \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 8R^2 \\int_0^{\\pi} (1-\\cos^2u)\\sin u \\, du \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 8R^2 \\left[-\\cos u + \\frac{\\cos^3 u}{3}\\right]_0^{\\pi} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 8R^2 \\left[ \\left(-\\cos\\pi + \\frac{\\cos^3\\pi}{3}\\right) - \\left(-\\cos 0 + \\frac{\\cos^3 0}{3}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 8R^2 \\left[ \\left(-(-1) + \\frac{(-1)^3}{3}\\right) - \\left(-1 + \\frac{1^3}{3}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 8R^2 \\left[ \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{3}\\right) - \\left(-1 + \\frac{1}{3}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 8R^2 \\left[ \\frac{2}{3} - \\left(-\\frac{2}{3}\\right) \\right] = 8R^2 \\left(\\frac{4}{3}\\right) = \\frac{32}{3}R^2\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting this result into our expression for `y_f` (Eq. \\ref{eq:yf_integral_final}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ny_f \\approx \\frac{2 \\sigma r}{M} \\left(\\frac{32}{3}R^2\\right) = \\frac{64}{3}\\frac{\\sigma r R^2}{M}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe highest position the cube can reach at the other end, measured as the vertical drop `y_f` from the starting level, is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{y_f = \\frac{64}{3}\\frac{\\sigma r R^2}{M}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "OPTICS/42", "tag": "OPTICS", "questions": "We consider a special rotationally symmetric refractive index distribution $n=n(r)$, such that the light trajectory is $r=a\\cos q\\theta$ (although it is not very realistic for the refractive index to diverge at $r=0$). In the space where $r<a$, find the refractive index $n(r)$ (since proportionally changing the refractive index does not affect the light's path, your answer should contain a dimensionless coefficient $n_{0}$).", "solutions": "Conservation of Angular Momentum\n\n$$\nL=m r^{2}{\\dot{\\theta}}\n$$  \n\nTherefore\n\n$$\n{\\frac{d}{d t}}={\\frac{L}{m r^{2}}}{\\frac{d}{d\\theta}}\n$$  \n\nConservation of Mechanical Energy\n\n$$\nE=V+{\\frac{1}{2}}m\\left({\\dot{r}}^{2}+r^{2}{\\dot{\\theta}}^{2}\\right)=V+{\\frac{L^{2}}{2m r^{4}}}\\left(r^{2}+a^{2}q^{2}\\sin^{2}q\\theta\\right)\n$$  \n\nThus\n\n$$\nV={\\frac{L^{2}}{2m}}\\left({\\frac{q^{2}-1}{r^{2}}}-{\\frac{a^{2}q^{2}}{r^{4}}}\\right)\n$$  \n\nAnd\n\n$$\nE=0\n$$  \n\n$$\nA={\\frac{L^{2}}{2m}}\\left(q^{2}-1\\right)\n$$  \n\nUsing $B$ as a known quantity, we have\n\nSince\n\nGiven the magnitude of the velocity\n\n$$\nv={\\sqrt{{\\frac{2}{m}}{\\frac{B}{l^{2}}}\\left({\\frac{1}{l^{2}}}-{\\frac{q^{2}-1}{a^{2}q^{2}}}\\right)}}\n$$  \n\nAnd because\n\n$$\nB=\\frac{L^{2}}{2m}a^{2}q^{2}\n$$  \n\nLet the angle between the velocity direction and the polar axis be $\\varphi$, substituting in\n\n$$\nL=m v l\\sin\\varphi\n$$  \n\nSolving\n\n$$\n\\varphi=\\pm\\arcsin{\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\left({\\frac{a^{2}}{l^{2}}}-1\\right)q^{2}+1}}}\n$$  \n\nIt's obvious that we also require\n\n$$\nl\\leq a\n$$  \n\n(2) The condition $E=0$ was previously mentioned, so in the analogy of light, there is no need to match the refractive index to satisfy $E=0$, simply let\n\n$$\nV=-{\\frac{1}{2}}n^{2}\n$$  \n\nThis is feasible, such that\n\n$$\nn(r)={\\sqrt{{\\frac{L^{2}}{m}}\\left({\\frac{a^{2}q^{2}}{r^{4}}}-{\\frac{q^{2}-1}{r^{2}}}\\right)}}\n$$  \n\nTaking into account the problem of dimensional analysis, proportional changes, and range, finally we get:\n\n$$\nn(r)=n_{0}a{\\sqrt{\\left({\\frac{a^{2}q^{2}}{r^{4}}}-{\\frac{q^{2}-1}{r^{2}}}\\right)}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\nn_0 a \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2 q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2 - 1}{r^2}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem requires us to determine the refractive index profile, $n(r)$, for a medium that is rotationally symmetric. This symmetry implies that the refractive index $n$ is a function only of the radial distance $r$ from the origin. We are given that a light ray propagating in this medium follows a specific trajectory described in polar coordinates $(r, \\theta)$ by the equation $r = a\\cos(q\\theta)$. This trajectory is defined for the region where the radial distance $r$ is less than or equal to a constant $a$. The problem asks for the functional form of $n(r)$.\n\nThe variables and constants involved are:\n*   $r, \\theta$: The polar coordinates describing the position of the light ray.\n*   $n(r)$: The refractive index of the medium, which is a function of $r$.\n*   $a$: A positive constant with dimensions of length, representing the maximum radial extent of the trajectory.\n*   $q$: A dimensionless constant that characterizes the shape of the trajectory.\n\nWe are also informed that scaling the refractive index by a constant factor does not alter the light's path. Consequently, the solution for $n(r)$ is unique only up to a multiplicative constant. This ambiguity should be resolved by including a dimensionless coefficient, denoted as $n_0$, in the final expression. The problem statement anticipates that the resulting $n(r)$ might exhibit non-physical behavior, such as a divergence at the origin ($r=0$), which is acceptable for this theoretical problem.\n\n### Step 1: The Optical-Mechanical Analogy\nTo determine the refractive index from the given trajectory, we utilize the optical-mechanical analogy. This analogy stems from the formal equivalence between the principle governing light propagation (Fermat's Principle) and a principle of classical mechanics (Maupertuis' Principle). This allows us to translate the optical problem of finding a refractive index for a given light path into the mechanical problem of finding a potential field for a particle following an equivalent trajectory.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nThe path of a light ray is determined by Fermat's Principle, which states that the optical path length between two points is an extremum.\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\delta \\int n \\, ds = 0}\n\\]\nHere, $n$ is the refractive index and $ds$ is an element of arc length along the path.\n\nThe trajectory of a classical particle with a fixed total energy is governed by Maupertuis' Principle (a form of the Principle of Least Action), which states that the abbreviated action is an extremum.\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\delta \\int p \\, ds = 0}\n\\]\nHere, $p$ is the magnitude of the particle's momentum.\n\n**Derivation**\nComparing the mathematical forms of Fermat's Principle and Maupertuis' Principle reveals a direct analogy. The two variational principles become identical if we identify the refractive index $n(r)$ as being proportional to the momentum $p(r)$ of an analogous particle. For a non-relativistic particle of mass $m$ and total energy $E$ moving in a potential $V(r)$, the momentum is given by $p = \\sqrt{2m(E - V(r))}$. This leads to the central relationship of the optical-mechanical analogy:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn(r) = C \\sqrt{E - V(r)} \\label{eq:analogy} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nwhere $C$ is a constant of proportionality. Our strategy is to first find the potential energy function $V(r)$ that would cause a classical particle to follow the given trajectory $r = a\\cos(q\\theta)$, and then use Eq. \\eqref{eq:analogy} to determine the refractive index $n(r)$.\n\n### Step 2: Deriving the Equivalent Potential Energy\nWe now determine the potential energy function $V(r)$ for a particle of mass $m$ that results in the trajectory $r(\\theta) = a\\cos(q\\theta)$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nFor a particle moving in a central potential $V(r)$, its total energy $E$ and angular momentum $L$ are conserved quantities.\nThe total energy is the sum of kinetic and potential energies, expressed in polar coordinates as:\n\\[\n\\boxed{E = T + V(r) = \\frac{1}{2}m(\\dot{r}^2 + r^2\\dot{\\theta}^2) + V(r)}\n\\]\nThe magnitude of the angular momentum is given by:\n\\[\n\\boxed{L = mr^2\\dot{\\theta}}\n\\]\n\n**Derivation**\nFirst, we express the kinetic energy $T$ as a function of the radial coordinate $r$. From the conservation of angular momentum, we have $\\dot{\\theta} = L/(mr^2)$. Using the chain rule, the radial velocity is $\\dot{r} = \\frac{dr}{d\\theta}\\dot{\\theta} = \\frac{dr}{d\\theta}\\frac{L}{mr^2}$. Substituting these into the expression for kinetic energy:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nT &= \\frac{1}{2}m\\left[ \\left(\\frac{dr}{d\\theta}\\frac{L}{mr^2}\\right)^2 + r^2\\left(\\frac{L}{mr^2}\\right)^2 \\right] = \\frac{1}{2}m \\frac{L^2}{m^2r^4} \\left[ \\left(\\frac{dr}{d\\theta}\\right)^2 + r^2 \\right] = \\frac{L^2}{2mr^4} \\left[ \\left(\\frac{dr}{d\\theta}\\right)^2 + r^2 \\right] \\label{eq:T_polar} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor the given trajectory $r(\\theta) = a\\cos(q\\theta)$, the derivative with respect to $\\theta$ is $\\frac{dr}{d\\theta} = -aq\\sin(q\\theta)$. We can express this purely in terms of $r$ by using $\\cos(q\\theta) = r/a$ and the trigonometric identity $\\sin^2(q\\theta) = 1 - \\cos^2(q\\theta) = 1 - (r/a)^2$.\nSubstituting these into Eq. \\eqref{eq:T_polar}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nT(r) &= \\frac{L^2}{2mr^4} \\left[ (-aq\\sin(q\\theta))^2 + r^2 \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{L^2}{2mr^4} \\left[ a^2q^2\\sin^2(q\\theta) + r^2 \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{L^2}{2mr^4} \\left[ a^2q^2\\left(1 - \\frac{r^2}{a^2}\\right) + r^2 \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{L^2}{2mr^4} \\left[ a^2q^2 - q^2r^2 + r^2 \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{L^2}{2m} \\left( \\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2} \\right) \\label{eq:T_r} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFrom the optical-mechanical analogy, $n(r) \\propto \\sqrt{E-V(r)}$. Since $T(r) = E-V(r)$, it follows that $n(r) \\propto \\sqrt{T(r)}$. This shows that the refractive index profile is determined by the kinetic energy function $T(r)$, which in turn is uniquely determined by the trajectory. The total energy $E$ of the analogous mechanical system is an arbitrary constant, as its value only shifts the potential $V(r)$ by a constant amount but does not change the physics. For algebraic simplicity, we can set $E=0$. This choice defines the potential energy to be $V(r) = -T(r)$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nV(r) = -T(r) = - \\frac{L^2}{2m} \\left( \\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2} \\right) = \\frac{L^2}{2m} \\left( \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2} - \\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} \\right) \\label{eq:V_r} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Calculating the Refractive Index\nHaving found the kinetic energy function $T(r)$ corresponding to the trajectory, we can now determine the refractive index profile $n(r)$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**\nWe use the relationship from the optical-mechanical analogy, which states that the refractive index is proportional to the square root of the kinetic energy of the analogous particle.\n\\[\n\\boxed{n(r) \\propto \\sqrt{T(r)}}\n\\]\nThis is equivalent to $n(r) = C \\sqrt{E - V(r)}$ from Step 1, with $E-V(r)=T(r)$.\n\n**Derivation**\nLet the proportionality constant be $K'$, so $n(r) = K' \\sqrt{T(r)}$. Substituting the expression for $T(r)$ from Eq. \\eqref{eq:T_r}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn(r) &= K' \\sqrt{\\frac{L^2}{2m} \\left( \\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2} \\right)} = \\left(K' \\frac{L}{\\sqrt{2m}}\\right) \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2}} \\label{eq:n_intermediate} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe constants $K'$, $L$, and $m$ are parameters of the analogous mechanical system. We can combine them into a single constant $K = K' \\frac{L}{\\sqrt{2m}}$. The term under the square root has dimensions of $[L]^{-2}$, so its square root has dimensions of $[L]^{-1}$. Since $n(r)$ must be dimensionless, the constant $K$ must have dimensions of length, $[L]$.\n\nTo satisfy the problem's requirement for a dimensionless constant $n_0$, we define $K$ in terms of the characteristic length $a$ and $n_0$ by setting $K = n_0 a$. This definition allows us to give $n_0$ a clear physical interpretation. Let's evaluate $n(r)$ at the boundary $r=a$:\n$n(a) = n_0 a \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2q^2}{a^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{a^2}} = n_0 a \\sqrt{\\frac{q^2 - (q^2-1)}{a^2}} = n_0 a \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{a^2}} = n_0$.\nThus, our choice of constant implies that $n_0$ is the refractive index at the radial distance $r=a$. Substituting $K = n_0 a$ into our expression for $n(r)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn(r) = n_0 a \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2}} \\label{eq:n_final_derivation} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor the refractive index $n(r)$ to be a real number, the argument of the square root (the radicand) must be non-negative for all $r$ on the trajectory ($0 < r \\le a$). The radicand is $\\frac{a^2q^2 - (q^2-1)r^2}{r^4}$. We must check if $a^2q^2 - (q^2-1)r^2 \\ge 0$.\n*   **Case 1: $q^2 - 1 \\ge 0$ (i.e., $|q| \\ge 1$)**. In this case, $q^2-1$ is non-negative. Since $r^2 \\le a^2$, we have $(q^2-1)r^2 \\le (q^2-1)a^2$. Therefore, $a^2q^2 - (q^2-1)r^2 \\ge a^2q^2 - (q^2-1)a^2 = a^2(q^2 - q^2 + 1) = a^2$. Since $a^2 > 0$, the radicand is always positive.\n*   **Case 2: $q^2 - 1 < 0$ (i.e., $|q| < 1$)**. In this case, $q^2-1$ is negative. Let $q^2-1 = -k$ where $k>0$. The expression becomes $a^2q^2 - (-k)r^2 = a^2q^2 + kr^2$. Since $a^2q^2 \\ge 0$ and $kr^2 > 0$ for $r>0$, their sum is positive.\nIn both cases, the condition is satisfied, so the expression for $n(r)$ is real-valued for all points on the trajectory where $r>0$.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe refractive index distribution $n(r)$ that produces the light trajectory $r=a\\cos(q\\theta)$ in the region $r \\le a$ is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{n(r) = n_0 a \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2q^2}{r^4} - \\frac{q^2-1}{r^2}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nwhere $n_0$ is a dimensionless constant representing the refractive index at the boundary $r=a$."}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/45", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "Calculate the wave speed of longitudinal waves in a one-dimensional gas. Consider a section of the gas column with cross-sectional area $S$, assume its displacement along the $x$ direction is $\\xi = \\xi(x)$, the gas pressure distribution is $p = p(x)$, and the density of the gas when uncompressed is $\\rho_{0}$. Consider the case of small amplitude and long wavelength, i.e. $\\xi \\ll x, \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\ll 1, (p-p_0)\\ll p_0, (\\rho-\\rho_0)\\ll\\rho_0$. Calculate the wave speed of longitudinal waves in a van der Waals gas. The state equation of one mole of the gas is given as:\n\n$$\n\\left( p + \\frac{a}{V^{2}} \\right)(V - b) = RT\\ \n$$\n\nThe molar heat capacity at constant volume is $c_{v}$, and the molar mass of the gas is $\\mu$. Solve for the wave speed under adiabatic conditions, expressed in terms of $p, \\rho, a, b,\\mu, \\gamma = \\frac{c_{v} + R}{c_{v}}$.  \nHint: You can use the formulas:\n\n$$dU = c_{v}dT + \\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T}dV$$\n\nand\n\n$$\\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T} = T\\left( \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T} \\right)_{V} - p$$\n\nto calculate the adiabatic equation.", "solutions": "Consider the air column from $x \\rightarrow x + dx$. From the dynamics equation, we obtain:\n\n$$\n\\rho_{0}Sdx\\frac{\\partial^{2}\\xi}{\\partial t^{2}} = - \\frac{dp}{dS}(1)\n$$\n\nAfter simplification, we get\n\n$$\n\\rho_{0}\\frac{\\partial^{2}\\xi}{\\partial t^{2}} = - \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x}(2)\n$$\n\nConsider the air column originally located at $x\\rightarrow x+\\mathrm d x$, now located at $x+\\xi\\rightarrow x+dx+\\xi +d\\xi$. By mass conservation:\n\n$$\n\\rho(d\\xi + dx) = \\rho_{0}dx(3)\n$$\n\nHence, we get\n\n$$\n\\rho = \\rho_{0}\\left( 1 - \\frac{\\partial\\xi}{\\partial x} \\right)(4)\n$$\n\nUsing\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} = \\left( \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial\\rho} \\right)_{c} \\cdot \\frac{\\partial\\rho}{\\partial x}(5)\n$$\n\nwe obtain\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\partial^{2}\\xi}{\\partial t^{2}} = \\left( \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial\\rho} \\right)_{c}\\frac{\\partial^{2}\\xi}{\\partial x^{2}}(6)\n$$\n\nThe wave speed is\n\n$$\nv = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}}\n$$\n\nUsing the formula from the hint, we obtain\n\n$$\n\\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T} = T\\left( \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T} \\right)_{V} - p = \\frac{a}{V^{2}}(7)\n$$\n\nFirst Law of Thermodynamics\n\n$$\ndQ = dU + dW(8)\n$$\n\n$$\n0 = c_{v}dT + \\frac{a}{V^{2}}dV + pdV = c_{v}dT + \\frac{RT}{V - b}dV(9)\n$$\n\nIntegrating and substituting into the state equation, we obtain\n\n$$\n\\left( p + \\frac{a}{V^{2}} \\right)(V - b)^{\\frac{c_{v} + R}{C_{v}}} = C(10)\n$$\n\nUsing\n\n$$\nV = \\frac{\\mu}{\\rho}(11)\n$$\n\nTaking the logarithm of equation (10) and then differentiating, we obtain:\n\n$$\nv = \\sqrt{\\left. \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial\\rho} \\right. \\right)_{s}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma\\mu}{\\mu\\rho - b\\rho^{2}}\\left( p + \\frac{a}{\\mu^{2}}\\rho^{2} \\right) - \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^{2}}}(12)\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma\\mu}{\\mu\\rho - b\\rho^2}\\left(p + \\frac{a}{\\mu^2}\\rho^2\\right) - \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2}}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the derivation of the wave speed for longitudinal waves propagating through a one-dimensional van der Waals gas. The process is assumed to be adiabatic.\n\nThe physical system is a gas confined to a column with a constant cross-sectional area $S$. The state of the gas is described by several variables:\n*   **Equilibrium State:** The gas is initially in a uniform equilibrium state with pressure $p$, density $\\rho$, and temperature $T$. Note that the problem statement uses $p_0, \\rho_0$ in the setup and $p, \\rho$ in the final expression; we will use $p, \\rho$ to denote the equilibrium quantities in the final result, which is standard convention.\n*   **Wave Perturbation:** The longitudinal wave causes small displacements $\\xi(x, t)$ of gas elements from their equilibrium position $x$. This leads to small perturbations in pressure and density.\n*   **Approximations:** The analysis is performed under the small amplitude and long wavelength approximation, meaning that the displacement $\\xi$ and its derivatives are small: $\\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x} \\ll 1$.\n\nThe gas is a van der Waals gas, and its properties are given by:\n*   **Equation of State:** For one mole of the gas, the equation of state is $\\left( p_{inst} + \\frac{a}{V^{2}} \\right)(V - b) = RT$, where $p_{inst}$ is the instantaneous pressure, $V$ is the molar volume, $T$ is the temperature, $R$ is the universal gas constant, and $a, b$ are the van der Waals constants.\n*   **Molar Mass:** The molar mass of the gas is $\\mu$. The molar volume $V$ and density $\\rho_{inst}$ are related by $V = \\mu/\\rho_{inst}$.\n*   **Thermal Properties:** The molar heat capacity at constant volume is $c_v$, and the heat capacity ratio is $\\gamma = \\frac{c_v + R}{c_v}$.\n\nThe problem provides two thermodynamic relations to help derive the adiabatic equation for the gas:\n1.  $dU = c_{v}dT + \\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T}dV$\n2.  $\\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T} = T\\left( \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T} \\right)_{V} - p$\n\nThe final goal is to express the wave speed $v$ in terms of the equilibrium properties $p, \\rho$ and the gas constants $a, b, \\mu, \\gamma$.\n\n### Step 1: Derive the Equation of Motion for a Gas Element\nWe consider a small cylindrical element of the gas, initially at rest between positions $x$ and $x+dx$. We apply Newton's Second Law to this element.\n\n\\[\\boxed{F_{\\text{net}} = ma}\\]\n\nThe mass of the element is determined by its equilibrium density $\\rho$ and initial volume $S\\,dx$. The acceleration is the second time derivative of its displacement $\\xi$. The net force is due to the pressure difference on its two faces.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Mass of the element: } dm &= \\rho S dx \\label{eq:mass} \\\\\n\\text{Acceleration of the element: } a_x &= \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial t^2} \\label{eq:accel} \\\\\n\\text{Force on the left face at } x \\text{: } F_{\\text{left}} &= p(x,t) S \\\\\n\\text{Force on the right face at } x+dx \\text{: } F_{\\text{right}} &= -p(x+dx,t) S \\\\\n\\text{Net force on the element: } F_{\\text{net}} &= S [p(x,t) - p(x+dx,t)] \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Using Taylor expansion } p(x+dx,t) \\approx p(x,t) + \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x}dx \\text{, we get:} \\nonumber \\\\\nF_{\\text{net}} &\\approx S \\left[ -\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} dx \\right] \\label{eq:force}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting these into Newton's Second Law:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n(\\rho S dx) \\left( \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial t^2} \\right) &= -S \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} dx \\nonumber \\\\\n\\rho \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial t^2} &= - \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} \\label{eq:motion}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Derive the Relation between Density and Displacement\nWe apply the principle of mass conservation to the same gas element. The mass of the fluid in a material volume is constant.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Mass Conservation: } m = \\rho_{\\text{initial}} V_{\\text{initial}} = \\rho_{\\text{final}} V_{\\text{final}}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Binomial Approximation: } (1+u)^{-1} \\approx 1-u \\text{ for } |u| \\ll 1}\\]\n\nThe volume of the element changes due to the displacement of its boundaries.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Initial volume: } dV_0 &= S dx \\\\\n\\text{Mass of the element: } dm &= \\rho dV_0 = \\rho S dx \\label{eq:mass_cons} \\\\\n\\text{At time } t \\text{, the left face is at } x' &= x + \\xi(x,t) \\\\\n\\text{At time } t \\text{, the right face is at } (x+dx)' &= x+dx + \\xi(x+dx,t) \\\\\n\\text{The new length of the element is } dx' &= (x+dx)' - x' = dx + \\xi(x+dx,t) - \\xi(x,t) \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx dx + \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x} dx = \\left(1 + \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\right) dx \\\\\n\\text{The new volume is } dV &= S dx' = S \\left(1 + \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\right) dx \\label{eq:new_vol} \\\\\n\\text{The new density is } \\rho(x,t)\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nApplying mass conservation, $dm = \\rho(x,t) dV$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\rho S dx &= \\rho(x,t) \\left[ S \\left(1 + \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\right) dx \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n\\rho &= \\rho(x,t) \\left(1 + \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\rho(x,t) &= \\frac{\\rho}{1 + \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Using the binomial approximation for small } \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\rho(x,t) &\\approx \\rho \\left(1 - \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\right) \\label{eq:continuity}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Formulate the Wave Equation\nWe combine the equation of motion \\eqref{eq:motion} and the continuity relation \\eqref{eq:continuity}. The pressure $p$ is a function of density $\\rho$ for an adiabatic process. We use the chain rule to relate the pressure gradient to the displacement.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Chain Rule: } \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} = \\frac{dp}{d\\rho} \\frac{\\partial \\rho}{\\partial x}}\\]\n\nThe pressure variations in a sound wave are rapid, and heat conduction in a gas is generally slow. Thus, there is negligible heat exchange, and the process can be treated as adiabatic (constant entropy). The derivative $\\frac{dp}{d\\rho}$ is therefore the adiabatic derivative, evaluated at the equilibrium state.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{From the continuity equation \\eqref{eq:continuity}, we differentiate } \\rho(x,t) \\text{ with respect to } x: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{\\partial \\rho(x,t)}{\\partial x} &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial x} \\left[ \\rho \\left(1 - \\frac{\\partial \\xi}{\\partial x}\\right) \\right] = -\\rho \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial x^2} \\label{eq:rho_deriv} \\\\\n\\text{Substitute this into the chain rule expression for the pressure gradient:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial x} &= \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s \\left(-\\rho \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial x^2}\\right) \\label{eq:p_deriv} \\\\\n\\text{Now substitute \\eqref{eq:p_deriv} into the equation of motion \\eqref{eq:motion}:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\rho \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial t^2} &= - \\left[ \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s \\left(-\\rho \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial x^2}\\right) \\right] \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial t^2} &= \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s \\frac{\\partial^2 \\xi}{\\partial x^2} \\label{eq:wave_eq}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Identify the Wave Speed\nThe derived equation \\eqref{eq:wave_eq} is in the standard form of the one-dimensional wave equation.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Standard 1D Wave Equation: } \\frac{\\partial^2 y}{\\partial t^2} = v^2 \\frac{\\partial^2 y}{\\partial x^2}}\\]\n\nBy comparing our derived equation for the displacement $\\xi$ with the standard form, we identify the square of the wave speed, $v^2$.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv^2 &= \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s \\label{eq:v_squared} \\\\\nv &= \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s} \\label{eq:v_speed}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe derivative is evaluated at the equilibrium state. The next task is to calculate this derivative for a van der Waals gas.\n\n### Step 5: Derive the Adiabatic Equation for a van der Waals Gas\nWe use the given thermodynamic relations to find the relationship between pressure and volume for an adiabatic process ($dQ=0$).\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{First Law of Thermodynamics: } dQ = dU + p dV}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Internal Energy Change: } dU = c_{v}dT + \\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T}dV}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Thermodynamic Identity: } \\left( \\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V} \\right)_{T} = T\\left( \\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T} \\right)_{V} - p}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Van der Waals Equation: } \\left( p + \\frac{a}{V^{2}} \\right)(V - b) = RT}\\]\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{From the van der Waals equation, we express } p \\text{ and find } \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T}\\right)_V: \\nonumber \\\\\np = \\frac{RT}{V-b} - \\frac{a}{V^2} \\implies \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T}\\right)_V = \\frac{R}{V-b}. \\\\\n\\text{Substitute this into the identity for } \\left(\\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V}\\right)_T: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V}\\right)_T &= T\\left(\\frac{R}{V-b}\\right) - \\left(\\frac{RT}{V-b} - \\frac{a}{V^2}\\right) = \\frac{a}{V^2}. \\label{eq:dUdV} \\\\\n\\text{For an adiabatic process, } dQ=0 \\text{, so from the First Law, } 0 = dU + p dV. \\nonumber \\\\\n0 &= \\left(c_v dT + \\left(\\frac{\\partial U}{\\partial V}\\right)_T dV\\right) + p dV = c_v dT + \\left(p + \\frac{a}{V^2}\\right) dV. \\label{eq:adiabatic_diff} \\\\\n\\text{From the state equation, } p + \\frac{a}{V^2} = \\frac{RT}{V-b}. \\text{ Substituting this into \\eqref{eq:adiabatic_diff}:} \\nonumber \\\\\n0 &= c_v dT + \\frac{RT}{V-b} dV \\implies \\frac{c_v}{T} dT = - \\frac{R}{V-b} dV. \\\\\n\\text{Integrating both sides: } \\int \\frac{c_v}{T} dT = - \\int \\frac{R}{V-b} dV \\implies c_v \\ln T = -R \\ln(V-b) + \\text{const}. \\nonumber \\\\\n\\ln(T^{c_v}) + \\ln((V-b)^R) = \\text{const} \\implies T^{c_v}(V-b)^R = C_1. \\\\\n\\text{Substitute } T = \\frac{1}{R}\\left(p+\\frac{a}{V^2}\\right)(V-b): \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left[\\frac{1}{R}\\left(p+\\frac{a}{V^2}\\right)(V-b)\\right]^{c_v} (V-b)^R &= C_1 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(p+\\frac{a}{V^2}\\right)^{c_v} (V-b)^{c_v+R} &= C_2. \\\\\n\\text{Using } \\gamma = \\frac{c_v+R}{c_v} \\text{ and raising to the power of } 1/c_v: \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(p+\\frac{a}{V^2}\\right)(V-b)^{\\gamma} &= C \\quad (\\text{constant}). \\label{eq:adiabatic_relation}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 6: Calculate the Adiabatic Derivative $(\\partial p / \\partial \\rho)_s$\nWe now differentiate the adiabatic relation \\eqref{eq:adiabatic_relation} to find $(\\partial p / \\partial \\rho)_s$. We first express the relation in terms of density $\\rho$.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Molar Volume: } V = \\frac{\\mu}{\\rho}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\text{Adiabatic Relation: } \\left(p+\\frac{a}{V^2}\\right)(V-b)^{\\gamma} = C}\\]\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\text{Substitute } V=\\mu/\\rho \\text{ into the adiabatic relation:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left(p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}\\right) \\left(\\frac{\\mu}{\\rho} - b\\right)^\\gamma &= C \\label{eq:adiabatic_rho} \\\\\n\\text{Take the natural logarithm for easier differentiation:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\ln\\left(p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}\\right) + \\gamma \\ln\\left(\\frac{\\mu}{\\rho} - b\\right) &= \\ln C \\\\\n\\text{Differentiate with respect to } \\rho \\text{ at constant entropy:} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{1}{p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}}\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho} + \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2}\\right) + \\gamma \\frac{1}{\\frac{\\mu}{\\rho}-b}\\left(-\\frac{\\mu}{\\rho^2}\\right) &= 0 \\\\\n\\frac{1}{p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}}\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho} + \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2}\\right) &= \\gamma \\frac{\\mu/\\rho^2}{(\\mu-b\\rho)/\\rho} = \\frac{\\gamma\\mu}{\\rho(\\mu-b\\rho)} \\\\\n\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho} + \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2} &= \\frac{\\gamma\\mu\\left(p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}\\right)}{\\rho(\\mu-b\\rho)} \\\\\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s &= \\frac{\\gamma\\mu\\left(p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}\\right)}{\\mu\\rho - b\\rho^2} - \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2} \\label{eq:dpdrho}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis derivative is evaluated at the equilibrium state, so $p$ and $\\rho$ in this expression represent the equilibrium pressure and density.\n\n### Step 7: Final Expression for the Wave Speed\nFinally, we substitute the expression for $(\\partial p / \\partial \\rho)_s$ from \\eqref{eq:dpdrho} into the formula for the wave speed \\eqref{eq:v_speed}.\n\n\\[\\boxed{v = \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial \\rho}\\right)_s}}\\]\n\nThe derivation is a direct substitution of the result from Step 6.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nv^2 &= \\frac{\\gamma\\mu\\left(p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}\\right)}{\\mu\\rho - b\\rho^2} - \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2} \\nonumber \\\\\nv &= \\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma\\mu\\left(p + \\frac{a\\rho^2}{\\mu^2}\\right)}{\\mu\\rho - b\\rho^2} - \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^2}} \\label{eq:final_v}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe wave speed of longitudinal waves in a van der Waals gas under adiabatic conditions is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{v = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\gamma\\mu}{\\mu\\rho - b\\rho^{2}}\\left( p + \\frac{a\\rho^{2}}{\\mu^{2}} \\right) - \\frac{2a\\rho}{\\mu^{2}}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/37", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "The curling can be approximated as a solid homogeneous cylinder with mass $m$, bottom surface radius $r$, and height $h$. Only the outer edge of the bottom is in contact with the ice surface, which has a friction coefficient $\\mu$. The support force of the ice surface on the curling stone is $N=\\int_{0}^{2\\pi}n(\\theta)\\mathrm{d}\\theta$,\nwhere $n(\\theta)$ is the distribution of the support force according to the polar coordinate $\\theta$. When the curling is stationary on the horizontal ice surface, $n(\\theta)=mg/2\\pi$. Assume that the deformation of the outer edge of the curling is very small, and the elastic force satisfies Hooke's law. Therefore, it can be proven that the support force distribution has the form $n(\\theta)=n_0+n_1\\cos(\\theta-\\theta_0)$ (where $n_0$, $n_1$, and $\\theta_0$ are unknown quantities). If the curling has a velocity $v$ in the positive direction along the x-axis, and also has an angular velocity $\\omega$ in the clockwise direction (viewed from above), the curling will generate a lateral acceleration $a$ in the y-direction. It is through this that the athlete can achieve the curling's turn. Find the expression for $a_y$ in the limit case where $v\\gg\\omega r$.", "solutions": "The deformation at a particular point $\\pmb{d}$ is a linear function of its projection distance $\\boldsymbol{\\mathbf{\\rho}}_{x}$ in the direction of maximum deformation:  \n\n$$\nd = d_{0} + x \\tan\\alpha\n$$  \n\nAssuming the direction of maximum deformation is $\\theta_{0}$, we have:  \n\n$$\nx = r \\cos{\\left(\\theta - \\theta_{0}\\right)}\n$$  \n\nAccording to Hooke's law:  \n\n$$\nn = k d = k d_{0} + k r \\tan\\alpha \\cos\\left(\\theta - \\theta_{0}\\right) = n_{0} + n_{1} \\cos\\left(\\theta - \\theta_{0}\\right)\n$$  \n\nThe curling stone is in vertical force equilibrium, so:  \n\n$$\nN = \\int_{0}^{2\\pi} n\\big(\\theta\\big)d\\theta = m g\n$$  \n\nSolving, we obtain $n_{0} = m g / 2\\pi$.  \n\nThe friction force acting on the curling stone is proportional to the normal pressure:  \n\n$$\nf(\\theta) = \\mu n(\\theta)\n$$  \n\nIts direction is along the negative $\\mathbf{x}$ axis.  \n\nDuring the motion of the curling stone, the overall torque is balanced:  \n\n$$\nM_{x} = \\int_{0}^{2\\pi}\\boldsymbol{n}(\\theta) r \\sin\\theta d\\theta + \\frac{1}{2} \\int_{0}^{2\\pi} f_{y}\\left(\\theta\\right) h d\\theta = 0\n$$  \n\n$$\nM_{y} = -\\int_{0}^{2\\pi} \\eta \\left(\\theta\\right) r \\cos\\theta d\\theta - \\frac{1}{2} \\int_{0}^{2\\pi} f_{x}\\left(\\theta\\right) h d\\theta = 0\n$$  \n\nWhen $\\nu \\gg \\omega r$, the components of the friction force retain only the first-order approximations:  \n\n$$\nf_{x} = -\\frac{\\nu + \\omega r \\sin\\theta}{\\sqrt{\\left(\\nu + \\omega r \\sin\\theta\\right)^{2} + \\omega^{2} r^{2} \\cos^{2}\\theta}} \\mu n(\\theta) \\approx -\\mu n(\\theta)\n$$  \n\n$$\nf_{y} = \\frac{\\omega r \\cos{\\theta}}{\\sqrt{\\left(\\nu + \\omega r \\sin{\\theta}\\right)^{2} + \\omega^{2} r^{2} \\cos^{2}{\\theta}}} \\mu n(\\theta) \\approx \\frac{\\omega r \\cos{\\theta}}{\\nu} \\mu n(\\theta)\n$$  \n\nFor convenience in solving, let $n\\left(\\theta\\right) = n_{0} + a \\cos\\theta + b \\sin\\theta$. Substituting into equations (6) and (7) and solving simultaneously, we obtain:  \n\n$$\nn\\left(\\theta\\right) = \\frac{m g}{2\\pi} \\left(1 + \\frac{\\mu h}{r} \\cos\\theta - \\frac{\\mu^{2} h^{2} \\omega}{2 \\nu r} \\sin\\theta\\right)\n$$  \n\nThe final transverse acceleration is:  \n\n$$\na_{y} = \\frac{1}{m} \\int_{0}^{2\\pi} f_{y} d\\theta = \\frac{\\mu^{2} \\omega h g}{2 \\nu}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\\frac{\\mu^2\\omega hg}{2v}$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem analyzes the motion of a curling stone to determine its lateral acceleration. The stone is modeled as a solid homogeneous cylinder with mass $m$, height $h$, and a bottom radius $r$. It moves on a horizontal ice surface with a coefficient of kinetic friction $\\mu$.\n\nThe key physical parameters and conditions are:\n*   **Object Geometry**: A solid homogeneous cylinder. Its center of mass (CM) is located at a height $h/2$ from the base.\n*   **Contact with Ice**: The stone is supported only by the thin outer circular edge (rim) of its bottom surface, which has a radius $r$.\n*   **Coordinate System**: We establish a right-handed Cartesian coordinate system $(x, y, z)$. The origin $(0,0,0)$ is at the center of the stone's bottom circular rim. The xy-plane represents the ice surface, and the z-axis points vertically upwards. A polar coordinate $\\theta$ is used to denote position on the rim, measured from the positive x-axis.\n*   **Motion**:\n    *   The stone's center of mass has a translational velocity $\\vec{v} = v \\hat{i}$ along the positive x-axis.\n    *   The stone rotates with an angular velocity $\\vec{\\omega} = -\\omega \\hat{k}$, corresponding to a clockwise rotation when viewed from above.\n*   **Forces**:\n    *   **Gravitational Force**: $\\vec{F}_g = -mg\\hat{k}$, acting downwards through the CM.\n    *   **Normal Force**: The ice exerts an upward support force on the bottom rim. This force is distributed along the rim and is described by a linear density $n(\\theta)$ (force per unit angle). The total normal force is $N = \\int_{0}^{2\\pi} n(\\theta) d\\theta$.\n    *   **Frictional Force**: A kinetic friction force acts on each point of the rim, opposing the local velocity of the rim relative to the ice.\n*   **Given Distribution Form**: The problem states that the normal force distribution takes the form $n(\\theta) = n_0 + n_1\\cos(\\theta - \\theta_0)$. This non-uniform distribution arises from the slight tilting of the stone due to the torque from friction, which causes a non-uniform elastic deformation of the rim. The parameters $n_0$, $n_1$, and $\\theta_0$ are determined by the dynamics of the motion.\n*   **Objective**: Find the expression for the stone's lateral acceleration, $a_y$, in the y-direction.\n*   **Limiting Condition**: The calculation is to be performed in the limit where the translational speed is much greater than the rotational speed at the rim, i.e., $v \\gg \\omega r$.\n*   **Assumption**: The stone slides without tumbling. This implies that the net torque about the center of mass in the horizontal (x and y) directions is zero, which maintains the stone's orientation in a quasi-static equilibrium.\n\n### Step 1: Kinematics of a Point on the Rim\nTo calculate the friction force, we first need the velocity of any point on the rim relative to the stationary ice. The velocity of a point on a rigid body is the sum of the translational velocity of a reference point and the velocity due to rotation about that reference point. We choose the center of the bottom rim (the origin) as our reference point.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\vec{v}_{P} = \\vec{v}_{\\text{ref}} + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{P/\\text{ref}}}\n\\]\nHere, $\\vec{v}_{P}$ is the velocity of a point $P$ on the rim, $\\vec{v}_{\\text{ref}}$ is the velocity of our reference point (the origin), which is the translational velocity of the stone, $\\vec{v} = v\\hat{i}$. The vector $\\vec{p} = \\vec{r}_{P/\\text{ref}}$ is the position vector of point $P$ relative to the origin. The velocity of point $P$ relative to the ice is $\\vec{v}_{rel} = \\vec{v}_P$.\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{p} &= r\\cos\\theta \\hat{i} + r\\sin\\theta \\hat{j} \\label{eq:pos_p} \\\\\n\\vec{v}_{rel}(\\theta) &= \\vec{v} + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{p} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= v\\hat{i} + (-\\omega\\hat{k}) \\times (r\\cos\\theta \\hat{i} + r\\sin\\theta \\hat{j}) \\label{eq:v_rel_start} \\\\\n&= v\\hat{i} - \\omega r \\cos\\theta (\\hat{k} \\times \\hat{i}) - \\omega r \\sin\\theta (\\hat{k} \\times \\hat{j}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= v\\hat{i} - \\omega r \\cos\\theta (\\hat{j}) - \\omega r \\sin\\theta (-\\hat{i}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (v + \\omega r \\sin\\theta)\\hat{i} - (\\omega r \\cos\\theta)\\hat{j} \\label{eq:v_rel_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Frictional Force Analysis\nThe kinetic friction force $d\\vec{f}$ on a small segment of the rim of angular width $d\\theta$ opposes the relative velocity $\\vec{v}_{rel}$ and its magnitude is proportional to the elemental normal force $dN = n(\\theta)d\\theta$.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{d\\vec{f} = -\\mu \\, dN \\, \\frac{\\vec{v}_{rel}}{|\\vec{v}_{rel}|} = -\\mu n(\\theta) d\\theta \\, \\frac{\\vec{v}_{rel}}{|\\vec{v}_{rel}|}}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{(1+x)^k \\approx 1+kx \\text{ for } |x| \\ll 1 \\quad (\\text{Binomial Approximation})}\n\\]\nFirst, we find the magnitude of the relative velocity and approximate it for the limit $v \\gg \\omega r$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n|\\vec{v}_{rel}| &= \\sqrt{(v + \\omega r \\sin\\theta)^2 + (-\\omega r \\cos\\theta)^2} = \\sqrt{v^2 + 2v\\omega r \\sin\\theta + \\omega^2 r^2 \\sin^2\\theta + \\omega^2 r^2 \\cos^2\\theta} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\sqrt{v^2 + 2v\\omega r \\sin\\theta + \\omega^2 r^2} \\label{eq:v_rel_mag} \\\\\n&= v \\sqrt{1 + \\frac{2\\omega r}{v}\\sin\\theta + \\left(\\frac{\\omega r}{v}\\right)^2} \\nonumber\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nIn the limit $v \\gg \\omega r$, the term $\\epsilon = \\frac{\\omega r}{v}$ is small. Using the binomial approximation $(1+x)^{1/2} \\approx 1+x/2$ and keeping only terms up to the first order in $\\epsilon$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n|\\vec{v}_{rel}| \\approx v \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{2\\omega r}{v}\\sin\\theta\\right)\\right) = v + \\omega r \\sin\\theta \\label{eq:v_rel_mag_approx}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow we find the components of the friction force per unit angle, $\\vec{f}(\\theta) = d\\vec{f}/d\\theta$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nf_x(\\theta) &= -\\mu n(\\theta) \\frac{v_{rel,x}}{|\\vec{v}_{rel}|} \\approx -\\mu n(\\theta) \\frac{v + \\omega r \\sin\\theta}{v + \\omega r \\sin\\theta} = -\\mu n(\\theta) \\label{eq:fx_approx} \\\\\nf_y(\\theta) &= -\\mu n(\\theta) \\frac{v_{rel,y}}{|\\vec{v}_{rel}|} \\approx -\\mu n(\\theta) \\frac{-\\omega r \\cos\\theta}{v + \\omega r \\sin\\theta} = \\frac{\\mu \\omega r \\cos\\theta \\, n(\\theta)}{v(1 + \\frac{\\omega r}{v}\\sin\\theta)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx \\frac{\\mu \\omega r \\cos\\theta \\, n(\\theta)}{v} \\left(1 - \\frac{\\omega r}{v}\\sin\\theta\\right) \\quad (\\text{using } (1+x)^{-1} \\approx 1-x) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta - \\mathcal{O}\\left(\\left(\\frac{\\omega r}{v}\\right)^2\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&\\approx \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta \\label{eq:fy_approx}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nIn the last step for $f_y(\\theta)$, we kept only the leading term, which is of order $\\omega r/v$.\n\n### Step 3: Torque Balance about the Center of Mass\nThe assumption of no tumbling means the net torque about the stone's center of mass (CM), located at $(0, 0, h/2)$, must be zero in the horizontal directions. The forces creating torques are the distributed normal force and the distributed friction force, both acting on the bottom rim ($z=0$).\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\vec{\\tau} = \\vec{r} \\times \\vec{F}}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\vec{\\tau}_{net, CM} = \\int_0^{2\\pi} (\\vec{r}_{app} \\times d\\vec{N} + \\vec{r}_{app} \\times d\\vec{f}) = \\vec{0}}\n\\]\nThe lever arm from the CM to a point $P$ on the rim is $\\vec{r}_{app} = \\vec{p} - (h/2)\\hat{k} = r\\cos\\theta\\hat{i} + r\\sin\\theta\\hat{j} - (h/2)\\hat{k}$.\nThe torque from the normal force element $d\\vec{N} = n(\\theta)d\\theta \\hat{k}$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nd\\vec{\\tau}_N &= \\vec{r}_{app} \\times d\\vec{N} = (r\\cos\\theta\\hat{i} + r\\sin\\theta\\hat{j} - \\frac{h}{2}\\hat{k}) \\times (n(\\theta)d\\theta \\hat{k}) \\\\\n&= (r n(\\theta) \\sin\\theta d\\theta) \\hat{i} - (r n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta d\\theta) \\hat{j}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe torque from the friction force element $d\\vec{f} = (f_x(\\theta)\\hat{i} + f_y(\\theta)\\hat{j})d\\theta$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nd\\vec{\\tau}_f &= \\vec{r}_{app} \\times d\\vec{f} = (r\\cos\\theta\\hat{i} + r\\sin\\theta\\hat{j} - \\frac{h}{2}\\hat{k}) \\times (f_x(\\theta)\\hat{i} + f_y(\\theta)\\hat{j})d\\theta \\\\\n&= \\left(\\frac{h}{2}f_y(\\theta)d\\theta\\right)\\hat{i} - \\left(\\frac{h}{2}f_x(\\theta)d\\theta\\right)\\hat{j} + (r\\cos\\theta f_y(\\theta) - r\\sin\\theta f_x(\\theta))d\\theta \\hat{k}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSetting the x and y components of the total torque to zero gives two balance equations:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\tau_x &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left(r n(\\theta) \\sin\\theta + \\frac{h}{2}f_y(\\theta)\\right) d\\theta = 0 \\label{eq:torque_x} \\\\\n\\tau_y &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left(-r n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta - \\frac{h}{2}f_x(\\theta)\\right) d\\theta = 0 \\label{eq:torque_y}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Determining the Normal Force Distribution\nWe use the given form $n(\\theta) = n_0 + n_1\\cos(\\theta-\\theta_0)$. For easier integration, we expand it as $n(\\theta) = n_0 + a\\cos\\theta + b\\sin\\theta$, where $a=n_1\\cos\\theta_0$ and $b=n_1\\sin\\theta_0$. We determine the coefficients $n_0, a, b$ using the force and torque balance equations.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\int_0^{2\\pi} n(\\theta) d\\theta = mg}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{n(\\theta) = n_0 + a\\cos\\theta + b\\sin\\theta}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\int_0^{2\\pi} \\cos^2\\theta \\, d\\theta = \\pi, \\quad \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\sin^2\\theta \\, d\\theta = \\pi, \\quad \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta \\, d\\theta = 0}\n\\]\nFirst, vertical force balance (total normal force equals gravity) gives $n_0$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^{2\\pi} (n_0 + a\\cos\\theta + b\\sin\\theta) d\\theta = n_0 \\int_0^{2\\pi} d\\theta + a \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\cos\\theta d\\theta + b \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\sin\\theta d\\theta = 2\\pi n_0 = mg\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThus, $n_0 = \\frac{mg}{2\\pi}$. Now we use the torque equations. From $\\tau_y=0$ and $f_x(\\theta) \\approx -\\mu n(\\theta)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left(-r n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta - \\frac{h}{2}(-\\mu n(\\theta))\\right) d\\theta &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} n(\\theta) \\left(\\frac{\\mu h}{2} - r\\cos\\theta\\right) d\\theta = 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\int_0^{2\\pi} (n_0 + a\\cos\\theta + b\\sin\\theta) \\left(\\frac{\\mu h}{2} - r\\cos\\theta\\right) d\\theta &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\nn_0 \\frac{\\mu h}{2} (2\\pi) - a r (\\pi) &= 0 \\implies a = \\frac{2\\pi n_0 \\mu h}{2\\pi r} = \\frac{n_0 \\mu h}{r} \\label{eq:a_solved}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFrom $\\tau_x=0$ and $f_y(\\theta) \\approx \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^{2\\pi} \\left(r n(\\theta) \\sin\\theta + \\frac{h}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta\\right)\\right) d\\theta &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} n(\\theta) \\left(r\\sin\\theta + \\frac{\\mu h \\omega r}{2v}\\cos\\theta\\right) d\\theta = 0 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\int_0^{2\\pi} (n_0 + a\\cos\\theta + b\\sin\\theta) \\left(r\\sin\\theta + \\frac{\\mu h \\omega r}{2v}\\cos\\theta\\right) d\\theta &= 0 \\nonumber \\\\\nb r (\\pi) + a \\frac{\\mu h \\omega r}{2v} (\\pi) &= 0 \\implies b = -a \\frac{\\mu h \\omega}{2v} \\label{eq:b_solved}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Calculating the Net Transverse Force and Acceleration\nThe net force in the y-direction, $F_y$, is the integral of the y-component of the friction force density over the entire rim. The acceleration is then found using Newton's second law.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{F_y = \\int_0^{2\\pi} f_y(\\theta) d\\theta}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\boxed{F_y = m a_y}\n\\]\nUsing our approximated expression for $f_y(\\theta)$ from Eq. (\\ref{eq:fy_approx}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nF_y &= \\int_0^{2\\pi} f_y(\\theta) d\\theta \\approx \\int_0^{2\\pi} \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} n(\\theta) \\cos\\theta d\\theta \\label{eq:Fy_integral} \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} \\int_0^{2\\pi} (n_0 + a\\cos\\theta + b\\sin\\theta) \\cos\\theta d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} \\left(n_0 \\int_0^{2\\pi}\\cos\\theta d\\theta + a \\int_0^{2\\pi}\\cos^2\\theta d\\theta + b \\int_0^{2\\pi}\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta d\\theta\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu \\omega r}{v} (0 + a\\pi + 0) = \\frac{\\mu \\omega r \\pi a}{v} \\label{eq:Fy_solved}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstitute the expression for $a$ from Eq. (\\ref{eq:a_solved}) and $n_0 = mg/2\\pi$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nF_y &= \\frac{\\mu \\omega r \\pi}{v} \\left(\\frac{n_0 \\mu h}{r}\\right) = \\frac{\\mu^2 \\omega \\pi n_0 h}{v} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{\\mu^2 \\omega \\pi h}{v} \\left(\\frac{mg}{2\\pi}\\right) = \\frac{\\mu^2 \\omega h m g}{2v}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFinally, the lateral acceleration $a_y$ is obtained from Newton's second law:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\na_y = \\frac{F_y}{m} = \\frac{1}{m} \\left(\\frac{\\mu^2 \\omega h m g}{2v}\\right) = \\frac{\\mu^2 \\omega h g}{2v} \\label{eq:ay_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe expression for the lateral acceleration $a_y$ in the limit $v \\gg \\omega r$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{a_y = \\frac{\\mu^2 \\omega h g}{2v}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/654", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "The forty-second batch of Trisolarian immigrants arrived on Earth aboard a spaceship propelled by photons. The spaceship has a rest mass of $M$, and it uses the method of annihilating matter and antimatter to produce photons, which are then emitted directly backward to provide thrust. In the reference frame of the spaceship, the frequency of the photons emitted backward is $ u _{0}$. For simplicity, we assume that the \\\"windward side\\\" of the Trisolarian spaceship is a flat surface with an area $S$. During flight, dust floating in the universe may collide with it. We assume that the cosmic dust is composed of particles with rest mass $m$. For an observer on Earth: the spaceship moves at a constant speed of $v _1$, the particles in the cosmic dust have a speed of $v_2$ and move in the same direction as the spaceship, and the particles in the dust are uniformly distributed with a density of $n$. If, according to the Trisolarian beings on the spaceship, the cosmic dust undergoes a \\\"perfectly elastic collision\\\" upon impact with the spaceship, what is the number $N^{'}$ of photons that need to be emitted backward per unit time in the reference frame of the spaceship to maintain its constant speed? Given are Planck's constant $h$, the speed of light in vacuum $c$, and relativistic effects need to be considered.\n", "solutions": "There are two reference frames; let's set up the agreements first. The reference frame of the Earth observer is called the $\\Sigma$ frame, and the reference frame of the spaceship is called the $\\Sigma$ frame.  We agree that: $$\\beta_{1}=\\frac{v_{1}}{c},\\gamma_{1}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{1}^{2}}},\\beta_{2}=\\frac{v_{2}}{c},\\gamma_{2}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{2}^{2}}},\\beta_{21}=\\frac{v_{21}}{c},\\gamma_{21}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{21}^{2}}}$$ $$\\beta_{2}^{'}=\\frac{v_{2}^{'}}{c},\\gamma_{2}^{'}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{2}^{'2}}},\\beta_{21}^{'}=\\frac{v_{21}^{'}}{c},\\gamma_{21}^{'}=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-\\beta_{21}^{'2}}}$$    The resistance of the spaceship is equal to the impulse given to the spaceship by cosmic dust particles per unit time. In the reference frame of the spaceship, we have:    $$ F^{'}=n^{'}S\\left|v_{2}^{'}\\right|\\times\\left|p_{2}^{'}-p_{21}^{'}\\right|=n^{'}S\\left|v_{2}^{'}\\right|\\times\\left|2p_{2}^{'}\\right|=2n^{'}S m \\gamma_{2}^{'}v_{2}^{'2} $$    The calculation of $n'$ needs to take into account the length contraction effect. If the particle density is $n_{0}$ in the rest frame of the cosmic dust itself, we have:  $$ n=n_{0}\\gamma_{2}, n^{'}=n_{0}\\gamma_{2}^{'} $$  Therefore, we can obtain $n^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\gamma_{2}^{'}}{\\gamma_{2}}n_{0}$.    Since $S$ is perpendicular to the direction of velocity, it is identical in both reference frames.  By relativistic velocity transformation:  $$ v_{2}^{'}=\\frac{v_{2}-v_{1}}{1-\\frac{v_{2}v_{1}}{c^{2}}} $$    Substituting into the expression for $F$ yields:  $$ F^{'}=2\\frac{\\gamma_{2}^{'}}{\\gamma_{2}}n S m\\gamma_{2}^{'} v_{2}^{'2}=2n S m\\gamma_{1}^{2}\\gamma_{2}(v_{1}-v_{2})^{2} $$    From momentum conservation in the spaceship reference frame, we can obtain:  $$ \\boldsymbol{F}^{'}=\\frac{N^{'} h  u_{0}}{c} $$    $$ N^{'}=\\frac{2n S m c\\gamma_{1}^{2}\\gamma_{2}(v_{1}-v_{2})^{2}}{h  u_{0}} $$\n", "final_answers": "$$\n\\frac{2nSmc(v_{1}-v_{2})^{2}}{(1-\\left(\\frac{v_1}{c}\\right)^2)\\sqrt{1-\\left(\\frac{v_2}{c}\\right)^2}h\\nu_{0}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem requires us to find the rate of photon emission, denoted as $N'$, necessary for a spaceship to maintain a constant velocity while traveling through a region of cosmic dust. The analysis will be conducted by balancing the forces in the spaceship's own inertial reference frame.\n\nWe are given two inertial reference frames:\n1.  The Earth's frame, which we will denote as $\\Sigma$.\n2.  The spaceship's rest frame, which we will denote as $\\Sigma'$.\n\nThe physical quantities, constants, and variables are defined as follows:\n*   **In the Earth frame ($\\Sigma$):**\n    *   The spaceship moves at a constant velocity $v_1$.\n    *   The cosmic dust particles move in the same direction as the spaceship with a velocity $v_2$.\n    *   The number density of dust particles (number of particles per unit volume) is $n$.\n*   **In the spaceship frame ($\\Sigma'$):**\n    *   The spaceship is stationary.\n    *   Photons are emitted backward with a frequency $u_0$.\n    *   The collision between a dust particle and the spaceship is described as \"perfectly elastic\". Since the spaceship's velocity is maintained by the photon drive, it acts as a fixed object of infinite effective mass in the collision. In a one-dimensional collision, this means the dust particle's kinetic energy and speed are conserved, and its velocity is reversed.\n    *   The number of photons emitted backward per unit time is $N'$, which is the quantity we need to determine.\n*   **Properties of the spaceship and dust:**\n    *   Rest mass of the spaceship: $M$. (This information is not required for the final calculation as we are maintaining constant velocity, not accelerating).\n    *   Rest mass of a dust particle: $m$.\n    *   Area of the spaceship's front surface: $S$.\n*   **Physical constants:**\n    *   Planck's constant: $h$.\n    *   Speed of light in vacuum: $c$.\n\nWe will use the standard relativistic notation:\n*   $\\beta_1 = v_1/c$ and the corresponding Lorentz factor $\\gamma_1 = (1 - \\beta_1^2)^{-1/2}$.\n*   $\\beta_2 = v_2/c$ and the corresponding Lorentz factor $\\gamma_2 = (1 - \\beta_2^2)^{-1/2}$.\n*   Quantities measured in the spaceship frame $\\Sigma'$ are denoted with a prime (e.g., $v_2'$, $n'$).\n\nThe problem will be solved by calculating the drag force exerted by the dust on the spaceship and equating it to the thrust provided by the photon emission, thereby ensuring the net force on the spaceship is zero in its own frame.\n\n### Step 1: Determine Dust Properties in the Spaceship's Frame\nTo analyze the collisions in the spaceship's frame $\\Sigma'$, we must first determine the velocity ($v_2'$) and number density ($n'$) of the cosmic dust as measured by an observer on the spaceship.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nFor two frames $\\Sigma$ and $\\Sigma'$ where $\\Sigma'$ moves with velocity $u$ relative to $\\Sigma$ along a common x-axis, the velocity $v$ of an object in $\\Sigma$ transforms to $v'$ in $\\Sigma'$ according to the relativistic velocity transformation formula:\n\\[\\boxed{\nv' = \\frac{v-u}{1 - \\frac{vu}{c^2}}\n}\\]\nThe number density $n$ of a group of particles moving with velocity $v$ is related to their proper number density $n_0$ (the density in their own rest frame) by the Lorentz contraction effect:\n\\[\\boxed{\nn = \\gamma n_0 \\quad \\text{where} \\quad \\gamma = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1-(v/c)^2}}\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nFirst, we find the velocity of a dust particle, $v_2'$, in the spaceship's frame $\\Sigma'$. The spaceship frame $\\Sigma'$ moves with velocity $u=v_1$ relative to the Earth frame $\\Sigma$. The dust particles have velocity $v=v_2$ in $\\Sigma$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nv_2' = \\frac{v_2 - v_1}{1 - \\frac{v_1 v_2}{c^2}}\n\\label{eq:v2_prime} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\\]\nNext, we find the number density $n'$ of the dust in the $\\Sigma'$ frame. Let $n_0$ be the proper number density of the dust particles. In the Earth frame $\\Sigma$, the dust moves at velocity $v_2$, so its observed density is related to its proper density by:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nn = \\gamma_2 n_0 \\implies n_0 = \\frac{n}{\\gamma_2}\n\\label{eq:n_earth} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\\]\nIn the spaceship frame $\\Sigma'$, the dust moves at velocity $v_2'$, so its density is given by:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nn' = \\gamma_2' n_0\n\\label{eq:n_ship_proper} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\\]\nwhere $\\gamma_2' = (1 - (v_2'/c)^2)^{-1/2}$. Substituting eq. \\eqref{eq:n_earth} into eq. \\eqref{eq:n_ship_proper}, we relate the density in the spaceship frame to the density in the Earth frame:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nn' = \\frac{\\gamma_2'}{\\gamma_2} n\n\\label{eq:n_prime} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 2: Calculate the Resistive Force from Cosmic Dust\nThe resistive force (drag) on the spaceship is the total momentum transferred from the colliding dust particles per unit time, as measured in the spaceship's frame $\\Sigma'$.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe relativistic momentum of a particle with rest mass $m$ and velocity $v$ is:\n\\[\\boxed{\np = \\gamma m v\n}\\]\nThe force exerted by a stream of particles is the rate of momentum they transfer, which can be calculated as the product of the particle flux and the momentum change per particle:\n\\[\\boxed{\nF = \\frac{dP}{dt} = (\\text{Number of particles colliding per unit time}) \\times (\\text{Momentum change per particle})\n}\\]\nFor a perfectly elastic collision with a stationary object of effectively infinite mass, the incoming particle's kinetic energy is conserved. For a 1D collision, this means its speed is unchanged, and its velocity is reversed.\n\n**Derivation**:\nIn frame $\\Sigma'$, the number of dust particles colliding with the spaceship's front surface $S$ per unit time is the particle flux multiplied by the area:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dN_{\\text{coll}}}{dt'} = n' |v_2'| S\n\\label{eq:flux} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe momentum of a single dust particle before collision in $\\Sigma'$ is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\np_{2, \\text{before}}' = m \\gamma_2' v_2'\n\\label{eq:p_before} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\\]\nAs the collision is perfectly elastic in $\\Sigma'$ and the spaceship is held stationary, the particle's kinetic energy is conserved. This implies its speed $|v_2'|$ is unchanged. The particle's velocity is reversed: $v_{2, \\text{after}}' = -v_2'$. The momentum after collision is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\np_{2, \\text{after}}' = m \\gamma_2' (-v_2') = -p_{2, \\text{before}}'\n\\label{eq:p_after} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe change in momentum of one particle is $\\Delta p_2' = p_{2, \\text{after}}' - p_{2, \\text{before}}' = -2p_{2, \\text{before}}'$. By Newton's third law, the momentum transferred to the spaceship is the negative of this, $\\Delta p_{\\text{ship}}' = -\\Delta p_2' = 2p_{2, \\text{before}}'$. The magnitude of momentum transferred to the ship per collision is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\n|\\Delta p_{\\text{ship}}'| = |2p_{2, \\text{before}}'| = 2 m \\gamma_2' |v_2'|\n\\label{eq:dp_ship} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\\]\nThe total resistive force $F'_{\\text{drag}}$ is the product of the particle collision rate and the magnitude of momentum transferred per particle. This force acts as a drag, opposing the spaceship's motion.\n\\[\\begin{align}\nF'_{\\text{drag}} &= \\left(\\frac{dN_{\\text{coll}}}{dt'}\\right) |\\Delta p_{\\text{ship}}'| = (n' |v_2'| S) (2 m \\gamma_2' |v_2'|) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2 n' S m \\gamma_2' (v_2')^2\n\\label{eq:F_drag_prime} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 3: Express the Resistive Force in Terms of Earth Frame Quantities\nThe final answer should be in terms of the initial given quantities ($n, v_1, v_2$, etc.), which are defined in the Earth frame $\\Sigma$. We now substitute the expressions for $n'$ and $v_2'$ into the force equation and simplify.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nFrom the relativistic velocity transformation, one can derive the following identity for the Lorentz factor $\\gamma'$ corresponding to the relative velocity $v'$ between an object (velocity $v$) and a frame (velocity $u$):\n\\[\\boxed{\n\\gamma' = \\gamma_u \\gamma_v (1 - \\beta_u \\beta_v)\n}\\]\nHere, $\\gamma'$ corresponds to $v'$, $\\gamma_u$ to the frame velocity $u$, and $\\gamma_v$ to the object velocity $v$.\n\n**Derivation**:\nWe start with the expression for the drag force from eq. \\eqref{eq:F_drag_prime} and substitute $n'$ from eq. \\eqref{eq:n_prime}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nF'_{\\text{drag}} = 2 \\left(n \\frac{\\gamma_2'}{\\gamma_2}\\right) S m \\gamma_2' (v_2')^2 = \\frac{2nSm}{\\gamma_2} (\\gamma_2')^2 (v_2')^2\n\\label{eq:F_drag_sub} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\\]\nNow we express the term $(\\gamma_2')^2 (v_2')^2$ using Earth frame quantities. The Lorentz factor for the relative velocity $v_2'$ is $\\gamma_2' = \\gamma_1 \\gamma_2 (1 - \\beta_1 \\beta_2)$.\n\\[\\begin{align}\n(\\gamma_2')^2 (v_2')^2 &= \\left( \\gamma_1 \\gamma_2 (1 - \\beta_1 \\beta_2) \\right)^2 \\left( \\frac{v_2 - v_1}{1 - \\frac{v_1 v_2}{c^2}} \\right)^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left( \\gamma_1 \\gamma_2 (1 - \\beta_1 \\beta_2) \\right)^2 \\left( \\frac{c(\\beta_2 - \\beta_1)}{1 - \\beta_1 \\beta_2} \\right)^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2^2 (1 - \\beta_1 \\beta_2)^2 \\frac{c^2(\\beta_2 - \\beta_1)^2}{(1 - \\beta_1 \\beta_2)^2} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2^2 c^2 (\\beta_2 - \\beta_1)^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2^2 (v_2 - v_1)^2\n\\label{eq:gamma_v_sq} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSubstituting eq. \\eqref{eq:gamma_v_sq} into eq. \\eqref{eq:F_drag_sub}:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nF'_{\\text{drag}} &= \\frac{2nSm}{\\gamma_2} \\left( \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2^2 (v_2 - v_1)^2 \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= 2nSm \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2 (v_1 - v_2)^2\n\\label{eq:F_drag_final} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\\]\nNote that we used $(v_2 - v_1)^2 = (v_1 - v_2)^2$ in the final expression.\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the Propulsive Force and Find N'\nTo maintain a constant velocity, the net force on the spaceship in its own frame $\\Sigma'$ must be zero. The forward propulsive thrust from the emitted photons must exactly balance the backward drag force from the dust.\n\n**Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions**:\nThe energy of a photon with frequency $\\nu$ is given by the Planck-Einstein relation:\n\\[\\boxed{\nE = h \\nu\n}\\]\nThe energy-momentum relation for a massless particle (like a photon) is:\n\\[\\boxed{\nE = pc\n}\\]\nFor an object to maintain a constant velocity, the net force acting on it must be zero (Newton's First Law):\n\\[\\boxed{\n\\vec{F}_{\\text{net}} = 0\n}\\]\n\n**Derivation**:\nIn the spaceship frame $\\Sigma'$, each photon is emitted with frequency $u_0$. The energy of one photon is $E' = h u_0$. From the energy-momentum relation, its momentum is $p'_{\\text{photon}} = E'/c = h u_0 / c$.\nThe photons are emitted backward. By conservation of momentum, each photon provides a forward thrust of magnitude $p'_{\\text{photon}}$ to the spaceship. If $N'$ photons are emitted per unit time, the total propulsive force (thrust) is:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nF'_{\\text{thrust}} = N' p'_{\\text{photon}} = N' \\frac{h u_0}{c}\n\\label{eq:F_thrust} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\\]\nTo maintain a constant velocity, the magnitude of the thrust must equal the magnitude of the drag force:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nF'_{\\text{thrust}} &= F'_{\\text{drag}} \\nonumber \\\\\nN' \\frac{h u_0}{c} &= 2nSm \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2 (v_1 - v_2)^2\n\\label{eq:force_balance} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\\]\nSolving for the photon emission rate $N'$:\n\\[\\begin{align}\nN' = \\frac{2nSmc \\gamma_1^2 \\gamma_2 (v_1 - v_2)^2}{h u_0}\n\\label{eq:N_final} \\tag{15}\n\\end{align}\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe number $N'$ of photons that need to be emitted backward per unit time in the reference frame of the spaceship to maintain its constant speed is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{N' = \\frac{2n S m c\\gamma_{1}^{2}\\gamma_{2}(v_{1}-v_{2})^{2}}{h u_{0}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "THERMODYNAMICS/244", "tag": "THERMODYNAMICS", "questions": "Consider a non-ideal gas system. Without worrying about the internal composition and interaction details, we find that its macroscopic equation of state is:\n\n$$\np = k V^{-4/5}T^{3/2}\n$$\n\nwhere $k$ is a constant coefficient.\n\nConsider a very special case. If for this non-ideal gas, its specific heat ratio:\n\n$$\n\\gamma = \\frac{C_{p}}{C_{V}}\n$$\n\nis exactly a constant that is independent of temperature and volume. Calculate the value of $\\gamma$.", "solutions": "Combine the formula for the difference in heat capacities with the heat capacity relation:\n\n$$\nC_{p}=\\gamma C_{V}\n$$\n\nThis directly solves for the heat capacity:\n\n$$\nC_{V}=\\frac{45}{16}\\frac{k V^{1/5}T^{1/2}}{\\gamma-1}\n$$\n\nAnd at this point, it must satisfy\n\n$$\n\\frac{\\partial C_{V}}{\\partial V}=g=\\frac{3}{4}k V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}\n$$\n\nSubstituting gives the only possible value for $\\gamma$:\n\n$$\n\\gamma=\\frac{7}{4}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\gamma = \\frac{7}{4}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem considers a non-ideal gas whose thermodynamic state is described by the equation of state:\n$$p = k V^{-4/5}T^{3/2}$$\nwhere $p$ is the pressure, $V$ is the volume, and $T$ is the absolute temperature. The coefficient $k$ is a constant.\n\nA key property of this gas is that its specific heat ratio, $\\gamma$, is a constant, independent of temperature and volume. The specific heat ratio is defined as the ratio of the heat capacity at constant pressure, $C_p$, to the heat capacity at constant volume, $C_V$:\n$$\\gamma = \\frac{C_p}{C_V} = \\text{constant}$$\n\nThe objective is to determine the numerical value of this constant $\\gamma$. We assume the system is in thermodynamic equilibrium and that the principles of thermodynamics are applicable.\n\n### Step 1: Derive an expression for the difference in heat capacities $C_p - C_V$\nWe begin with the general thermodynamic relation for the difference between the heat capacities, which is valid for any simple compressible system.\n\\[\\boxed{C_p - C_V = T \\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T}\\right)_V \\left(\\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial T}\\right)_p}\\]\nTo use this formula, we must compute the two partial derivatives from the given equation of state.\n\nFirst, we calculate $\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T}\\right)_V$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T}\\right)_V &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T} \\left(k V^{-4/5}T^{3/2}\\right)_V \\nonumber \\\\\n&= k V^{-4/5} \\left(\\frac{3}{2}T^{1/2}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left(\\frac{p}{T^{3/2}}\\right) \\left(\\frac{3}{2}T^{1/2}\\right) \\quad \\left(\\text{using } k V^{-4/5} = \\frac{p}{T^{3/2}}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{3}{2} \\frac{p}{T}\n\\label{eq:dpdT} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNext, to calculate $\\left(\\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial T}\\right)_p$, we first express $V$ as a function of $p$ and $T$ from the equation of state:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\np = k V^{-4/5}T^{3/2} \\implies V^{-4/5} = p k^{-1} T^{-3/2} \\implies V = \\left(p k^{-1} T^{-3/2}\\right)^{-5/4} = p^{-5/4} k^{5/4} T^{15/8}\n\\label{eq:V_of_pT} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we compute the partial derivative of $V$ with respect to $T$ at constant $p$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial V}{\\partial T}\\right)_p &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T} \\left(p^{-5/4} k^{5/4} T^{15/8}\\right)_p \\nonumber \\\\\n&= p^{-5/4} k^{5/4} \\left(\\frac{15}{8}T^{7/8}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\left(\\frac{V}{T^{15/8}}\\right) \\left(\\frac{15}{8}T^{7/8}\\right) \\quad \\left(\\text{using eq. \\ref{eq:V_of_pT}}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{15}{8} \\frac{V}{T}\n\\label{eq:dVdT} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the expressions for the partial derivatives from eq. \\eqref{eq:dpdT} and eq. \\eqref{eq:dVdT} into the formula for $C_p - C_V$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nC_p - C_V &= T \\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\frac{p}{T}\\right) \\left(\\frac{15}{8}\\frac{V}{T}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{45}{16} \\frac{pV}{T}\n\\label{eq:CpCv_final} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Express $C_V$ in terms of V, T, and $\\gamma$\nWe use the definition of the specific heat ratio, $\\gamma$, which is given as a constant.\n\\[\\boxed{\\gamma = \\frac{C_p}{C_V}}\\]\nFrom this definition, we can write $C_p = \\gamma C_V$. Substituting this into our result for the difference in heat capacities (eq. \\eqref{eq:CpCv_final}) allows us to solve for $C_V$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nC_p - C_V &= \\gamma C_V - C_V = (\\gamma - 1)C_V \\label{eq:CpCv_gamma} \\tag{5} \\\\\n\\text{Equating with eq. \\ref{eq:CpCv_final}: } \\quad (\\gamma - 1)C_V &= \\frac{45}{16} \\frac{pV}{T} \\nonumber \\\\\nC_V &= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\frac{45}{16} \\frac{pV}{T} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\text{Substituting } p = k V^{-4/5}T^{3/2}: \\quad C_V &= \\frac{1}{\\gamma-1} \\frac{45}{16} \\frac{(k V^{-4/5}T^{3/2})V}{T} \\nonumber \\\\\nC_V &= \\frac{45k}{16(\\gamma-1)} V^{1/5}T^{1/2}\n\\label{eq:Cv_expr1} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis expression gives $C_V$ as a function of $V$ and $T$, with $\\gamma$ as a parameter.\n\n### Step 3: Derive a second thermodynamic relation involving $C_V$\nTo determine the value of $\\gamma$, we need a second, independent constraint on the thermodynamic properties of the gas. Such a constraint is provided by the following thermodynamic identity, which follows from the fact that entropy is a state function (i.e., from Maxwell relations):\n\\[\\boxed{\\left(\\frac{\\partial C_V}{\\partial V}\\right)_T = T \\left(\\frac{\\partial^2 p}{\\partial T^2}\\right)_V}\\]\nWe first compute the second partial derivative of $p$ with respect to $T$ at constant $V$. From Step 1, we have $\\left(\\frac{\\partial p}{\\partial T}\\right)_V = \\frac{3}{2} k V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial^2 p}{\\partial T^2}\\right)_V &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial T} \\left(\\frac{3}{2} k V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}\\right)_V \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{3}{2} k V^{-4/5} \\left(\\frac{1}{2}T^{-1/2}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{3}{4} k V^{-4/5}T^{-1/2}\n\\label{eq:d2pdT2} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting this result into the thermodynamic identity:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial C_V}{\\partial V}\\right)_T = T \\left(\\frac{3}{4} k V^{-4/5}T^{-1/2}\\right) = \\frac{3}{4} k V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}\n\\label{eq:dCvDV_expr2} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Calculate the value of $\\gamma$\nWe now have two independent ways to determine the partial derivative $\\left(\\frac{\\partial C_V}{\\partial V}\\right)_T$. The first is from the general thermodynamic identity (eq. \\eqref{eq:dCvDV_expr2}). The second is by directly differentiating our derived expression for $C_V$ (eq. \\eqref{eq:Cv_expr1}). The consistency between these two results will determine the value of $\\gamma$.\n\nThe problem states that $\\gamma$ is a constant, which is a crucial assumption for the following step.\n\\[\\boxed{\\gamma = \\text{constant}}\\]\nWe differentiate the expression for $C_V$ from eq. \\eqref{eq:Cv_expr1} with respect to $V$ at constant $T$, treating $\\gamma$ as a constant.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\left(\\frac{\\partial C_V}{\\partial V}\\right)_T &= \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial V} \\left(\\frac{45k}{16(\\gamma-1)} V^{1/5}T^{1/2}\\right)_T \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{45k T^{1/2}}{16(\\gamma-1)} \\frac{\\partial}{\\partial V}(V^{1/5}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{45k T^{1/2}}{16(\\gamma-1)} \\left(\\frac{1}{5}V^{-4/5}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= \\frac{9k}{16(\\gamma-1)} V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}\n\\label{eq:dCvDV_expr1} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nFor the thermodynamic model to be consistent, the two expressions for $\\left(\\frac{\\partial C_V}{\\partial V}\\right)_T$, eq. \\eqref{eq:dCvDV_expr2} and eq. \\eqref{eq:dCvDV_expr1}, must be equal.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{9k}{16(\\gamma-1)} V^{-4/5}T^{1/2} &= \\frac{3}{4} k V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe terms $k V^{-4/5}T^{1/2}$ are non-zero, so they can be cancelled from both sides, leaving an equation solely for $\\gamma$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{9}{16(\\gamma-1)} &= \\frac{3}{4} \\nonumber \\\\\n9 \\times 4 &= 3 \\times 16(\\gamma-1) \\nonumber \\\\\n36 &= 48(\\gamma-1) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma-1 &= \\frac{36}{48} = \\frac{3}{4} \\nonumber \\\\\n\\gamma &= 1 + \\frac{3}{4} = \\frac{7}{4}\n\\label{eq:gamma_final} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe value of the specific heat ratio $\\gamma$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\gamma = \\frac{7}{4}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/25", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "On an infinitely large horizontal plane, establish polar coordinates ($r, \\theta$) .On the plane there is a stationary magnetic field of magnitude $\\frac{mv}{q\\sqrt{ar}}$ directed vertically upwards. A particle with a charge-to-mass ratio of $\\frac{3q}{2\\sqrt{2}m}$ is projected along the polar axis direction($\\theta=0$) from the origin with an initial velocity of $v_0$. Find the polar coordinate trajectory equation $r(\\theta)$ for this particle.", "solutions": "Solution:\nThe dynamic equations are\n$$\n\\left\\{{\\begin{array}{l}{m({\\ddot{r}}-r{\\dot{\\theta}^{2}})=q B r{\\dot{\\theta}}}\\\\ {m{\\frac{d\\left(r^{2}{\\dot{\\theta}}\\right)}{r d t}}=-q B{\\dot{r}}}\\end{array}}\\right.\n$$\n\nRearranging and integrating equation (21) yields:\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{l}{{d(r^{2}\\dot{\\theta})={\\frac{3v_{0}\\sqrt{r}}{2\\sqrt{2a}}}d r}}\\\\ {{d(r^{2}\\dot{\\theta})=-d{\\frac{v_{0}r^{\\frac{3}{2}}}{\\sqrt{2a}}}}}\\\\ {{~\\therefore~r^{2}\\dot{\\theta}+{\\frac{v_{0}r^{\\frac{3}{2}}}{\\sqrt{2a}}}=0}}\\\\ {{\\dot{\\theta}=-{\\frac{v_{0}}{\\sqrt{2a r}}}}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nLorentz force does no work, energy conservation:\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{r}{\\therefore\\dot{r}=\\sqrt{v_{0}^{2}-\\frac{v_{0}^{2}r}{2a}}}\\\\ {\\frac{d r}{d\\theta}=-\\sqrt{2a r-r^{2}}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\therefore r=a(1-\\cos\\theta)\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\na(1-\\cos\\theta)\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the trajectory, expressed by the polar coordinate equation $r(\\theta)$, of a charged particle moving on a two-dimensional horizontal plane. The particle is subject to a static, non-uniform magnetic field that is perpendicular to the plane.\n\nThe given information is organized as follows:\n*   **Particle Properties**:\n    *   Let the particle's mass be $m_p$ and its charge be $q_p$.\n    *   The charge-to-mass ratio is given as $\\frac{q_p}{m_p} = \\frac{3q}{2\\sqrt{2}m}$, where $q$ and $m$ are positive constants.\n\n*   **Magnetic Field**:\n    *   The magnetic field is directed vertically upwards, perpendicular to the plane of motion. We can write it as $\\vec{B} = B(r)\\hat{z}$, where $\\hat{z}$ is the unit vector normal to the plane.\n    *   The magnitude of the field depends on the radial distance $r$ from the origin: $B(r) = \\frac{mv}{q\\sqrt{ar}}$. Here, $a$, $m$, $q$, and $v$ are positive constants.\n\n*   **Initial Conditions**:\n    *   At time $t=0$, the particle is at the origin, so its initial position is $r(0)=0$.\n    *   It is projected with an initial speed $v_0$ along the polar axis, which is the direction $\\theta=0$.\n    *   This means the initial velocity vector is $\\vec{v}(0) = v_0 \\hat{r}$. In terms of polar velocity components, this implies the initial radial velocity is $\\dot{r}(0) = v_0$ and the initial tangential velocity is $v_\\theta(0) = r(0)\\dot{\\theta}(0) = 0$.\n\n*   **Assumptions**:\n    *   The magnetic force is the only force acting on the particle. Other forces like gravity are considered negligible.\n    *   The Lorentz force does no work, so the particle's kinetic energy and speed are constant. We assume that the parameter $v$ in the magnetic field's definition is equal to this constant speed, i.e., $v = v_0$. This is a common convention in such problems to ensure a self-consistent formulation. Thus, the magnetic field magnitude is $B(r) = \\frac{mv_0}{q\\sqrt{ar}}$.\n\n*   **Objective**:\n    *   To find the function $r(\\theta)$ that describes the particle's path.\n\n### Step 1: Equations of Motion in Polar Coordinates\nThe motion of the particle is governed by Newton's Second Law, where the net force is the Lorentz force due to the magnetic field.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{F}_{\\text{net}} = m_p \\vec{a}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{F}_{\\text{Lorentz}} = q_p (\\vec{v} \\times \\vec{B})}\\]\nIn polar coordinates $(r, \\theta)$, the velocity and acceleration vectors are expressed as:\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{v} = \\dot{r}\\hat{r} + r\\dot{\\theta}\\hat{\\theta}}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{\\vec{a} = (\\ddot{r} - r\\dot{\\theta}^2)\\hat{r} + (r\\ddot{\\theta} + 2\\dot{r}\\dot{\\theta})\\hat{\\theta}}\\]\nThe magnetic field is $\\vec{B} = B(r)\\hat{z}$. The Lorentz force is calculated by taking the cross product with the velocity vector. We use a right-handed coordinate system where $\\hat{r} \\times \\hat{\\theta} = \\hat{z}$, which implies $\\hat{r} \\times \\hat{z} = -\\hat{\\theta}$ and $\\hat{\\theta} \\times \\hat{z} = \\hat{r}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\vec{F} &= q_p ((\\dot{r}\\hat{r} + r\\dot{\\theta}\\hat{\\theta}) \\times B(r)\\hat{z}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= q_p B(r) (\\dot{r}(\\hat{r} \\times \\hat{z}) + r\\dot{\\theta}(\\hat{\\theta} \\times \\hat{z})) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= q_p B(r) (-\\dot{r}\\hat{\\theta} + r\\dot{\\theta}\\hat{r}) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= q_p B(r) r\\dot{\\theta} \\hat{r} - q_p B(r) \\dot{r} \\hat{\\theta}\n\\label{eq:force} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nBy equating the components of $m_p\\vec{a} = \\vec{F}$, we obtain the equations of motion:\n*   **Radial component ($\\hat{r}$)**:\n    \\[\\begin{align} m_p(\\ddot{r} - r\\dot{\\theta}^2) = q_p B(r) r\\dot{\\theta} \\label{eq:radial_eom} \\tag{2} \\end{align}\\]\n*   **Tangential component ($\\hat{\\theta}$)**:\n    \\[\\begin{align} m_p(r\\ddot{\\theta} + 2\\dot{r}\\dot{\\theta}) = -q_p B(r) \\dot{r} \\label{eq:tangential_eom} \\tag{3} \\end{align}\\]\n\n### Step 2: Derivation of the Angular Velocity\nWe use the tangential equation of motion (Eq. \\ref{eq:tangential_eom}) to find the angular velocity $\\dot{\\theta}$. The left side of the equation is related to the time derivative of the specific angular momentum.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{d}{dt}(r^2\\dot{\\theta}) = 2r\\dot{r}\\dot{\\theta} + r^2\\ddot{\\theta} = r(2\\dot{r}\\dot{\\theta} + r\\ddot{\\theta})}\\]\nUsing this identity, we can rewrite Eq. \\ref{eq:tangential_eom} as:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{m_p}{r} \\frac{d(r^2\\dot{\\theta})}{dt} &= -q_p B(r) \\frac{dr}{dt} \\nonumber \\\\\nm_p \\, d(r^2\\dot{\\theta}) &= -q_p B(r) r \\, dr \\nonumber \\\\\nd(r^2\\dot{\\theta}) &= -\\frac{q_p}{m_p} B(r) r \\, dr \\label{eq:diff_ang_mom} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the given expressions for the charge-to-mass ratio $\\frac{q_p}{m_p} = \\frac{3q}{2\\sqrt{2}m}$ and the magnetic field $B(r) = \\frac{mv_0}{q\\sqrt{ar}}$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nd(r^2\\dot{\\theta}) &= -\\left(\\frac{3q}{2\\sqrt{2}m}\\right) \\left(\\frac{mv_0}{q\\sqrt{ar}}\\right) r \\, dr \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{3v_0}{2\\sqrt{2}\\sqrt{a}} \\frac{r}{\\sqrt{r}} \\, dr \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\frac{3v_0}{2\\sqrt{2a}} r^{1/2} \\, dr \\label{eq:diff_explicit} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe integrate this equation from the initial state ($t=0$, where $r=0$ and the angular momentum $m_p r^2\\dot{\\theta}=0$) to a general state $(r, \\dot{\\theta})$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_{0}^{r^2\\dot{\\theta}} d(r'^2\\dot{\\theta}') &= \\int_{0}^{r} -\\frac{3v_0}{2\\sqrt{2a}} r'^{1/2} dr' \\nonumber \\\\\nr^2\\dot{\\theta} - 0 &= -\\frac{3v_0}{2\\sqrt{2a}} \\left[\\frac{r'^{3/2}}{3/2}\\right]_0^r \\nonumber \\\\\nr^2\\dot{\\theta} &= -\\frac{3v_0}{2\\sqrt{2a}} \\frac{2}{3} r^{3/2} = -\\frac{v_0}{\\sqrt{2a}} r^{3/2} \\label{eq:integrated_ang_mom} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSolving for the angular velocity $\\dot{\\theta}$ yields:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\dot{\\theta} = -\\frac{v_0}{\\sqrt{2a}} \\frac{r^{3/2}}{r^2} = -\\frac{v_0}{\\sqrt{2ar}} \\label{eq:theta_dot} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Derivation of the Radial Velocity\nThe Lorentz force is always perpendicular to the velocity of the particle, so it does no work. According to the work-energy theorem, the kinetic energy of the particle must be conserved.\n\n\\[\\boxed{W_{\\text{net}} = \\Delta E_k}\\]\n\\[\\boxed{W_{\\text{Lorentz}} = \\int \\vec{F}_{\\text{Lorentz}} \\cdot d\\vec{l} = \\int q_p(\\vec{v} \\times \\vec{B}) \\cdot \\vec{v} dt = 0}\\]\nSince the net work is zero, the kinetic energy is constant. This implies the particle's speed remains constant and equal to its initial value, $v_0$.\n\\[\\boxed{v^2 = v_0^2}\\]\nThe speed squared in polar coordinates is given by:\n\\[\\boxed{v^2 = \\dot{r}^2 + (r\\dot{\\theta})^2}\\]\nCombining these principles, we have:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\dot{r}^2 + (r\\dot{\\theta})^2 = v_0^2 \\label{eq:energy_cons} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we substitute the expression for $\\dot{\\theta}$ from Eq. \\ref{eq:theta_dot}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\dot{r}^2 + \\left(r \\left(-\\frac{v_0}{\\sqrt{2ar}}\\right)\\right)^2 &= v_0^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\dot{r}^2 + \\left(-\\frac{v_0\\sqrt{r}}{\\sqrt{2a}}\\right)^2 &= v_0^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\dot{r}^2 + \\frac{v_0^2 r}{2a} &= v_0^2 \\nonumber \\\\\n\\dot{r}^2 &= v_0^2 \\left(1 - \\frac{r}{2a}\\right) \\label{eq:r_dot_sq} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTaking the square root gives the radial velocity. We choose the positive root because the particle is projected outwards from the origin, so its radial velocity must be initially positive ($\\dot{r}(0)=v_0$).\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\dot{r} = v_0 \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{r}{2a}} \\label{eq:r_dot} \\tag{10}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Derivation and Solution of the Trajectory Equation\nTo find the trajectory $r(\\theta)$, we eliminate the time variable by relating $dr$ and $d\\theta$ using the chain rule.\n\n\\[\\boxed{\\frac{dr}{d\\theta} = \\frac{dr/dt}{d\\theta/dt} = \\frac{\\dot{r}}{\\dot{\\theta}}}\\]\nSubstituting the expressions for $\\dot{r}$ (Eq. \\ref{eq:r_dot}) and $\\dot{\\theta}$ (Eq. \\ref{eq:theta_dot}):\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dr}{d\\theta} &= \\frac{v_0 \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{r}{2a}}}{-v_0 / \\sqrt{2ar}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\sqrt{2ar} \\sqrt{1 - \\frac{r}{2a}} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\sqrt{2ar \\left(\\frac{2a-r}{2a}\\right)} \\nonumber \\\\\n&= -\\sqrt{r(2a-r)} = -\\sqrt{2ar - r^2} \\label{eq:traj_de} \\tag{11}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is a separable ordinary differential equation. We rearrange the terms and integrate from the initial condition ($r=0$ at $\\theta=0$) to a general point $(r, \\theta)$ on the trajectory.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dr}{\\sqrt{2ar - r^2}} &= -d\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\int_0^r \\frac{dr'}{\\sqrt{2ar' - r'^2}} &= \\int_0^\\theta -d\\theta' \\label{eq:integral_form} \\tag{12}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo evaluate the integral on the left, we complete the square in the denominator: $2ar - r^2 = a^2 - a^2 + 2ar - r^2 = a^2 - (r^2 - 2ar + a^2) = a^2 - (r-a)^2$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^r \\frac{dr'}{\\sqrt{a^2 - (r'-a)^2}} &= -\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\left[ \\arcsin\\left(\\frac{r'-a}{a}\\right) \\right]_0^r &= -\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{r-a}{a}\\right) - \\arcsin\\left(\\frac{0-a}{a}\\right) &= -\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{r-a}{a}\\right) - \\arcsin(-1) &= -\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{r-a}{a}\\right) - \\left(-\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right) &= -\\theta \\nonumber \\\\\n\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{r-a}{a}\\right) &= -\\theta - \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\label{eq:arcsin_result} \\tag{13}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo find $r(\\theta)$, we take the sine of both sides and solve for $r$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{r-a}{a} &= \\sin\\left(-\\theta - \\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right) = -\\sin\\left(\\theta + \\frac{\\pi}{2}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n\\frac{r-a}{a} &= -\\cos(\\theta) \\quad (\\text{using the identity } \\sin(x+\\pi/2)=\\cos(x)) \\nonumber \\\\\nr-a &= -a\\cos(\\theta) \\nonumber \\\\\nr(\\theta) &= a - a\\cos(\\theta) = a(1-\\cos\\theta) \\label{eq:final_trajectory} \\tag{14}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is the polar equation of a cardioid.\n\n### Final Answer\nThe polar coordinate trajectory equation for the particle is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{r(\\theta) = a(1-\\cos\\theta)}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "MECHANICS/100", "tag": "MECHANICS", "questions": "Consider a metal beam with a width of $a$, thickness of $h$, and Young's modulus of $E$. The beam is placed on supports spaced at a distance $l$, and it is assumed that the length of the metal beam is slightly greater than $l$. A weight with a mass of $m$ is placed in the middle of the beam. Assume the angle between the beam and the horizontal line is very small, neglect friction and the weight of the beam, and take the gravitational acceleration as $g$.\n\nHint: Since the beam has thickness, it develops a situation where the inner side is compressed and the outer side is stretched when in equilibrium. Although the net force at the interface is zero, a torque is generated. This also causes every part of the beam to experience compression/stretch, thereby storing potential energy.\n\nAfter the weight reaches equilibrium, apply a small horizontal perturbation along the rod’s direction to the weight and determine the vibration angular frequency of the system.", "solutions": "(1) Using the point where the heavy object is suspended as the origin, and the horizontal direction as the $\\pmb{\\mathscr{x}}$ axis, and the vertical direction as the $\\textit{\\textbf{y}}$ axis, establish a coordinate system.\n\nFirst, consider a small curved metal beam segment with a central angle of $\\theta$ and radius of $\\scriptstyle{\\mathcal{R}}$, then the strain at $z$ is:  \n\n$$\n\\epsilon = \\frac{(R+z)\\theta - R\\theta}{R\\theta} = \\frac{z}{R}\n$$\n\nResulting moment:  \n\n$$\nM = \\int_{-\\frac{h}{2}}^{\\frac{h}{2}}\\frac{E a}{R}z^{2}d z = \\frac{E a h^{3}}{12R}\n$$\n\nGiven the approximation condition ${y}^{\\prime}\\ll1$:  \n\n$$\nR = {\\frac{(1+y^{\\prime2})^{\\frac{3}{2}}}{|y^{\\prime\\prime}|}} \\approx {\\frac{1}{|y^{\\prime\\prime}|}}\n$$\n\nSubstitute into the previous equation:  \n\n$$\nM = {\\frac{E a h^{3}|y^{\\prime\\prime}|}{12}}\n$$\n\nFor the part of the metal beam with $\\mathfrak{x}(\\mathfrak{x}>0)$ and above, set up the moment equilibrium at the $\\pmb{x}$ position:  \n\n$$\nM = \\frac{m g}{2}(\\frac{l}{2}-x)\n$$\n\nSubstitute into the previous equation:  \n\n$$\ny^{\\prime\\prime} = \\frac{6m g}{E a h^{3}}(\\frac{l}{2}-x)\n$$\n\nInitial conditions:  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{r}{y(0)=0}\\ {y^{\\prime}(0)=0}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nIntegrating yields:  \n\n$$\ny = {\\frac{3m g l}{2E a h^{3}}}x^{2} - {\\frac{m g}{E a h^{3}}}x^{3}\n$$\n\nSubstitute $\\begin{array}{r}{x=\\frac{1}{2}}\\end{array}$ to obtain:  \n\n$$\n\\lambda = \\frac{m g l^{3}}{4E a h^{3}}\n$$\n\nBy the results of question (1), the metal beam can be equated to a spring with a stiffness coefficient of:  \n\n$$\nk = \\frac{4E a h^{3}}{l^{3}}\n$$\n\nThis gives the angular frequency of vertical vibration:  \n\n$$\n\\omega_{1} = {\\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}}} = {\\sqrt{\\frac{4E a h^{3}}{m l^{3}}}}\n$$\n\nAs shown in the diagram, let the heavy object deviate from the center by $\\delta l$, denote $\\begin{array}{r}{\\varepsilon=\\frac{\\delta\\ell}{\\ l}}\\end{array}$\n\nFrom mechanical equilibrium:  \n\n$$\nN_{1} = \\frac{m g}{2}(1-2\\varepsilon)\n$$\n\n$$\nN_{2} = \\frac{m g}{2}(1+2\\varepsilon)\n$$\n\nFor the part above the horizontal axis, establish the moment equilibrium equation at (2 >0):  \n\n$$\nM_{1} = {{N}_{2}}\\left[\\frac{l}{2}\\left(1-2\\varepsilon\\right)-x\\right]\n$$\n\nSimilarly, for ${\\mathfrak{x}}<{\\mathfrak{0}}$:  \n\n$$\nM_{2} = N_{1}\\left[\\frac{l}{2}\\left(1+2\\varepsilon\\right)+x\\right]\n$$\n\nInitial conditions:  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{c}{y\\left(0\\right)=0}\\ {y^{\\prime}\\left(0\\right)=k_{0}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nSubstitute into equation (2) and solve using initial conditions:  \n\nSubstitute boundary conditions:  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{c}{{y_{1}=k_{0}x+\\displaystyle\\frac{3m g l}{2E a h^{3}}\\left(1-4\\varepsilon^{2}\\right)x^{2}-\\displaystyle\\frac{m g}{E a h^{3}}\\left(1+2\\varepsilon\\right)x^{3}(x>0)}} \\\\ {{y_{2}=k_{0}x+\\displaystyle\\frac{3m g l}{2E a h^{3}}\\left(1-4\\varepsilon^{2}\\right)x^{2}+\\displaystyle\\frac{m g}{E a h^{3}}\\left(1-2\\varepsilon\\right)x^{3}(x<0)}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\n$$\ny_{1}\\left(\\frac{l}{2}\\left(1-2\\varepsilon\\right)\\right) = y_{2}\\left(-\\frac{l}{2}\\left(1+2\\varepsilon\\right)\\right) = \\lambda^{\\prime}\n$$\n\nSolve to obtain:  \n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{l}{{k_{0}=\\displaystyle\\frac{2m g l^{2}}{E a h^{3}}\\left(1-4\\varepsilon^{2}\\right)\\varepsilon}} \\\\ {{\\lambda^{\\prime}=\\displaystyle\\frac{m g l^{3}}{4E a h^{3}}\\left(1-4\\varepsilon^{2}\\right)^{2}}}\\end{array}\n$$\n\nWhen $\\varepsilon\\ll1$, we have:  \n\n$$\n\\lambda^{\\prime} \\approx \\frac{m g l^{3}}{4E a h^{3}}\\left(1-8\\varepsilon^{2}\\right)\n$$\n\nTherefore, the gravitational potential energy of the heavy object is:  \n\n$$\nE_{p1} = \\frac{2m^{2}g^{2}l^{3}}{E a h^{3}}\\varepsilon^{2}\n$$\n\nConsider a small segment of the metal beam and its elastic potential energy:  \n\n$$\nd E_{p2} = \\int{\\frac{1}{2}}E\\epsilon^{2}d V = \\int_{-{\\frac{h}{2}}}^{{\\frac{h}{2}}}{\\frac{{\\cal E}a y^{\\prime\\prime2}d x}{2}}z^{2}d z = {\\frac{{\\cal E}a h^{3}}{24}}y^{\\prime\\prime2}d x\n$$\n\nIntegrating yields:  \n\n$$\nE_{p2} = \\int_{-\\frac{1}{2}(1+2\\varepsilon)}^{0}\\frac{E a h^{3}}{24}y_{2}^{\\prime\\prime}d x + \\int_{0}^{\\frac{1}{2}(1-2\\varepsilon)}\\frac{E a h^{3}}{24}{y_{1}^{\\prime\\prime}}^{2}d x = \\frac{m^{2}g^{2}l^{3}(1-4\\varepsilon^{2})^{2}}{8E a h^{3}} \\approx \\frac{m^{2}g^{2}l^{3}(1-8\\varepsilon^{2})}{8E a h^{3}}\n$$\n\nThe kinetic energy of the ball is:  \n\n$$\nE_{k} = {\\frac{1}{2}}m l^{2}{\\dot{\\varepsilon}}^{2}\n$$\n\nTotal energy of the system:  \n\n$$\nE = E_{k} + E_{p1} + E_{p2} = {\\frac{1}{2}}m l^{2}{\\dot{\\varepsilon}}^{2} + {\\frac{m^{2}g^{2}l^{3}}{E a h^{3}}}\\varepsilon^{2} + E_{0} = {\\frac{1}{2}}M{\\dot{\\varepsilon}}^{2} + {\\frac{1}{2}}K\\varepsilon^{2} + E_{0}\n$$\n\nGiving the angular frequency of horizontal vibration:\n\n$$\n\\omega_{2} = {\\sqrt{\\frac{K}{M}}} = {\\sqrt{\\frac{2m g^{2}l}{E a h^{3}}}}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$\n\\sqrt{\\frac{2m g^2 l}{E a h^3}}\n$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the angular frequency of small horizontal oscillations of a mass `m` placed on a metal beam. The beam has a rectangular cross-section, rests on two supports, and deflects under the weight of the mass.\n\nThe given physical quantities are:\n*   `a`: width of the beam's cross-section.\n*   `h`: thickness of the beam's cross-section.\n*   `E`: Young's modulus of the beam's material.\n*   `l`: distance between the two supports.\n*   `m`: mass of the weight placed on the beam.\n*   `g`: acceleration due to gravity.\n\nThe goal is to find the angular frequency `ω` of the horizontal vibration when the mass is given a small perturbation from its central equilibrium position.\n\nWe establish a coordinate system where the origin `(0,0)` is at the center of the span on the axis of the undeflected beam. The x-axis is horizontal along the beam's length, and the y-axis is vertical, pointing downwards. The supports are located at `x = -l/2` and `x = l/2`.\n\nThe following assumptions are made based on the problem statement:\n1.  The beam is treated as \"simply supported\" at the two ends of the span `l`.\n2.  The deflection of the beam is small, allowing the use of Euler-Bernoulli beam theory.\n3.  The weight of the beam itself is negligible compared to the weight of the mass `m`.\n4.  Friction and air resistance are negligible.\n\nThe physical approach is to determine the total potential energy of the system (gravitational and elastic) as a function of the mass's horizontal position `x`. The system will oscillate around the position of minimum potential energy. By approximating the potential energy function as a parabola near this minimum, we can find an effective spring constant for the horizontal motion and subsequently the angular frequency of oscillation.\n\n### Step 1: Vertical Deflection of the Beam\nFirst, we determine the vertical deflection of the beam, `y_m(x)`, at the point where the mass `m` is located, as a function of its horizontal position `x`. We use standard formulas from Euler-Bernoulli beam theory.\n\nFor a simply supported beam of length `l` subjected to a point load `F` at distances `b` and `c` from the two supports, the vertical deflection under the load is given by:\n\\[\\boxed{ y_{\\text{load}} = \\frac{F b^2 c^2}{3EIl} }\\]\nThe term `I` is the second moment of area of the beam's cross-section. For a rectangular cross-section of width `a` and thickness `h`, it is:\n\\[\\boxed{ I = \\frac{ah^3}{12} }\\]\nIn our case, the load is the weight of the mass, `F = mg`. The mass is at a horizontal position `x` measured from the center. The distances to the supports at `x = -l/2` and `x = l/2` are `c = x - (-l/2) = l/2 + x` and `b = l/2 - x`, respectively.\nSubstituting these into the deflection formula:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ny_m(x) &= \\frac{mg \\left(\\frac{l}{2} - x\\right)^2 \\left(\\frac{l}{2} + x\\right)^2}{3EIl} \\\\\n&= \\frac{mg \\left[\\left(\\frac{l}{2} - x\\right)\\left(\\frac{l}{2} + x\\right)\\right]^2}{3EIl} = \\frac{mg \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right)^2}{3EIl} \\label{eq:deflection_I} \\tag{1}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nNow, we substitute the expression for `I`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\ny_m(x) &= \\frac{mg \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right)^2}{3E\\left(\\frac{ah^3}{12}\\right)l} = \\frac{12mg \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right)^2}{3Eah^3l} \\\\\n&= \\frac{4mg}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right)^2 \\label{eq:deflection_x} \\tag{2}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Total Potential Energy of the System\nThe total potential energy `U` of the system is the sum of the mass's gravitational potential energy `U_g` and the beam's elastic potential energy `U_e`.\n\nThe gravitational potential energy of the mass `m` at a vertical displacement `y` (downwards) is:\n\\[\\boxed{ U_g = -mgy }\\]\nThe elastic potential energy stored in a linearly elastic beam due to a gradually applied point load `F` that causes a deflection `y` is:\n\\[\\boxed{ U_e = \\frac{1}{2} F y }\\]\nThe total potential energy `U(x)` as a function of the mass's horizontal position `x` is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU(x) &= U_g(x) + U_e(x) \\\\\n&= -mg y_m(x) + \\frac{1}{2} (mg) y_m(x) \\\\\n&= -\\frac{1}{2} mg y_m(x) \\label{eq:U_total_1} \\tag{3}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the expression for `y_m(x)` from Eq. \\eqref{eq:deflection_x}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nU(x) = -\\frac{1}{2} mg \\left[ \\frac{4mg}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right)^2 \\right] = -\\frac{2m^2g^2}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right)^2 \\label{eq:U_total_2} \\tag{4}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Effective Spring Constant for Small Horizontal Oscillations\nFor small horizontal oscillations, the mass moves about its stable equilibrium position. The potential energy function `U(x)` can be approximated by a quadratic function near this point. The effective spring constant `k` of this harmonic potential determines the restoring force.\n\nThe potential energy of a system oscillating about a stable equilibrium point `x_0` can be approximated using a Taylor series expansion:\n\\[\\boxed{ U(x) \\approx U(x_0) + \\left.\\frac{dU}{dx}\\right|_{x=x_0}(x-x_0) + \\frac{1}{2}\\left.\\frac{d^2U}{dx^2}\\right|_{x=x_0}(x-x_0)^2 }\\]\nFor a simple harmonic oscillator, this simplifies to `U_{osc} = \\frac{1}{2}k(x-x_0)^2`, where the effective spring constant is `k = \\left.\\frac{d^2U}{dx^2}\\right|_{x=x_0}`.\n\nFirst, we find the equilibrium position `x_0` by finding where the force `F_x = -dU/dx` is zero.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dU}{dx} &= -\\frac{2m^2g^2}{Eah^3l} \\cdot 2\\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right) \\cdot (-2x) = \\frac{8m^2g^2x}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - x^2\\right) \\label{eq:dUdx} \\tag{5}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSetting `dU/dx = 0` gives `x=0` as the equilibrium position (the center of the beam). Next, we find the second derivative to determine the effective spring constant `k`.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{d^2U}{dx^2} &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\left[ \\frac{8m^2g^2}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2x}{4} - x^3\\right) \\right] \\\\\n&= \\frac{8m^2g^2}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - 3x^2\\right) \\label{eq:d2Udx2} \\tag{6}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nEvaluating the second derivative at the equilibrium position `x=0`:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nk = \\left.\\frac{d^2U}{dx^2}\\right|_{x=0} = \\frac{8m^2g^2}{Eah^3l} \\left(\\frac{l^2}{4} - 0\\right) = \\frac{2m^2g^2l}{Eah^3} \\label{eq:k_eff} \\tag{7}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 4: Angular Frequency of Oscillation\nThe system can be modeled as a simple harmonic oscillator with mass `m` and the effective spring constant `k` found in Step 3.\n\nThe kinetic energy of the oscillating mass is:\n\\[\\boxed{ E_k = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 }\\]\nFor small horizontal oscillations, the path of the mass is nearly horizontal. The vertical component of velocity `v_y` is much smaller than the horizontal component `v_x = \\dot{x}`. Thus, we can approximate the kinetic energy by considering only the horizontal motion: `E_k \\approx \\frac{1}{2}m\\dot{x}^2`.\n\nThe angular frequency `ω` of a simple harmonic oscillator is given by the relation:\n\\[\\boxed{ \\omega = \\sqrt{\\frac{k}{m}} }\\]\nUsing the mass `m` and the effective spring constant `k` from Eq. \\eqref{eq:k_eff}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\omega^2 &= \\frac{k}{m} = \\frac{1}{m} \\left( \\frac{2m^2g^2l}{Eah^3} \\right) \\\\\n&= \\frac{2mg^2l}{Eah^3} \\label{eq:omega_sq} \\tag{8}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTaking the square root gives the angular frequency of the small horizontal vibrations.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\omega = \\sqrt{\\frac{2mg^2l}{Eah^3}} \\label{eq:omega} \\tag{9}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe angular frequency of the small horizontal vibration of the system is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\\omega = \\sqrt{\\frac{2mg^2l}{Eah^3}}}\n\\end{align}\n\\]"}
{"id": "ELECTRICITY/89", "tag": "ELECTRICITY", "questions": "A typhoon is a vortex-like weather system, and as it passes, it is often accompanied by lightning. When the electric field strength in the air reaches a certain value, the air breaks down, generating lightning. The breakdown field strength of air is denoted as $E_{m}$. The typhoon system is modeled as an isothermal atmospheric ideal gas with a temperature denoted as ${T}_{0}$. Under strong ionization conditions, it can be considered as consisting of neutral monoatomic gas (with mass $m_{tot}=m_{N}+m_{e}$) and free electrons (with mass $m_{e}$) released through ionization. It is known that each atom can ionize to release at most one electron, with the total number of monoatomic gas particles being $N$.\n\nThe rotation speed of the typhoon is ${\\overrightarrow{\\omega}}=\\omega{\\hat{z}}$. In this problem, we consider a cylindrical typhoon system with radius ${R}$ and height $H(H \\gg R)$. Both the electrons and the positive ions are confined within this cylindrical volume and do not escape. Interactions between free electrons and free electrons, free electrons and positive ions, and positive ions and positive ions are ignored. Additionally, the effects of internal potential distributions within the typhoon on the distribution of free electrons and positive ions are not considered (calculated results can be simplified using $k=\\frac{\\omega^2}{2k_BT_0}$). The permittivity of free space is $\\varepsilon_0$. \n\nAfter the typhoon has stabilized, researchers need to deploy unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) to gather data within the typhoon system. The UAV has a volume of $V(V^{\\frac{1}{3}} \\ll R)$ and mass ${m}$. To ensure stable operation during data collection, the UAV must remain at a radius ${r_{0}}$ while orbiting the typhoon center with the same angular velocity $\\omega$. It is known that the UAV can only exert thrust in the vertical direction. At time $t=0$, the UAV in stable operation experiences a small radial perturbation and acquires an initial radial velocity $\\overrightarrow{v_{0}}$ with $v_{0} \\ll \\omega r_{0}$. Observations show that the UAV exhibits periodic precession. Solve for its precession angular frequency $\\Omega$ (the answer can be expressed in terms of $q_{0}$ and $r_{0}$).", "solutions": "According to the problem statement, a single ideal gas under the isothermal model can satisfy the Boltzmann distribution in any continuous potential energy field distribution. By entering the rotating reference frame of the typhoon, centrifugal potential energy is introduced:\n\n$$\nV_{\\text{eff}} = -\\frac{1}{2}m\\omega^2r^2\n$$\n\nThus, the mass density of free electrons and positive ions satisfies:\n\n$$\n\\rho_{-}(r) = \\rho_{-0}e^{m_{\\text{e}}kr^2}, \\rho_{+}(r) = \\rho_{+0}e^{m_{N}kr^2}\n$$\n\nConsider that the total number of electrons and positive ions satisfies the normalization condition:\n\nSolving yields:\n\n$$\nN = \\frac{\\int_{0}^{R}2\\pi r H\\times\\rho_{-}(r)dr}{m_e}, N = \\frac{\\int_{0}^{R}2\\pi r H\\times\\rho_{+}(r)dr}{m_N}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\rho_{-}(r) = \\rho_{-0}e^{-m_{e}kr^2} = \\frac{k m_{e}^2N}{\\pi H(e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1)}e^{m_{e}kr^2}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\rho_{+}(r) = \\rho_{+0}e^{-m_{N}kr^2} = \\frac{k m_{N}^2N}{\\pi H(e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1)}e^{m_{N}kr^2}\n$$\n\nFrom\n\n$$\nPV = nRT\n$$\n\nIt follows that\n\n$$\nP(r) = \\left(\\frac{\\rho_{+}}{m_{N}} + \\frac{\\rho_{-}}{m_{e}}\\right)k_{B}T_{0}\n$$\n\n$$\nP(r) = \\left(\\frac{k m_{e}N}{\\pi H(e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1)}e^{m_{e}kr^2} + \\frac{k m_{N}N}{\\pi H(e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1)}e^{m_{N}kr^2}\\right)k_{B}T_{0}\n$$\n\nWe prioritize considering the electric field intensity at the maximum electric field, analyzing symmetry $\\vec{E} = E(r)\\hat{r}$\n\n$$\nE(r) = \\frac{\\int_{0}^{r}(e\\rho_{+} - e\\rho_{-})(2\\pi r \\, dr)}{2\\pi r\\varepsilon_{0}H} = \\frac{N e}{2\\pi r H\\varepsilon_{0}}\\left[\\frac{e^{m_{N}kr^2}-1}{e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1} - \\frac{e^{m_{e}kr^2}-1}{e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1}\\right]\n$$\n\nConsidering when $\\pmb{E}$ reaches maximum value, it satisfies:\n\n$$\n\\frac{dE(r)}{dr} = 0\n$$\n\nSimplifying, the $r_{\\text{max}}$ at maximum electric field satisfies the equation when $r = r_{\\text{max}}$:\n\n$$\n\\left[\\frac{e^{m_{N}kr^2}-1}{e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1} - \\frac{e^{m_{e}kr^2}-1}{e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1}\\right] - 2kr^2\\left[m_{N}\\frac{e^{m_{N}kr^2}}{e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1} - m_{e}\\frac{e^{m_{e}kr^2}}{e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1}\\right] = 0\n$$\n\nSubstituting the data, solving yields:\n\n$$\nr_{\\text{max}} = 719.96 \\, \\mathrm{m}\n$$\n\nAt this time:\n\n$$\nE_{\\text{max}} = \\frac{N e}{2\\pi r_{\\text{max}}H\\varepsilon_{0}}\\left[\\frac{e^{m_{N}kr_{\\text{max}}^2}-1}{e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1} - \\frac{e^{m_{e}kr_{\\text{max}}^2}-1}{e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1}\\right] = -9.83 \\times 10^{18} \\, \\mathrm{V/m}\n$$\n\nSince:\n\n$$\n\\left|E_{\\text{max}}\\right| > E_m\n$$\n\nIt can break down air.\n\nFor analyzing the forces on the drone in the ground reference frame, the buoyancy it experiences satisfies:\n\n$$\n\\vec{F}' = (\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}))V g\\hat{z} + (\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}))V\\omega^2r_{0}(-\\hat{r})\n$$\n\nIn the $\\hat{r}$ direction, list the force balance equation:\n\n$$\nE(r_{0})q_{0} - (\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}))V\\omega^2r_{0} = -m\\omega^2r_{0}\n$$\n\nSubstituting specific values, solving gives:\n\n$$\nq_{0} = \\frac{-m\\omega^2r_{0} + \\left(\\frac{k m_{\\circ}^2N}{\\pi H(\\circ^{m_{\\circ}kr_{0}^2}-1)}e^{m_{\\circ}kr_{0}^2} + \\frac{k m_{N}^2N}{\\pi H(\\circ^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}-1)}e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}\\right)V\\omega^2r_{\\circ}}{\\frac{N e}{2\\pi r_{0}H\\varepsilon_{0}}\\left[\\frac{e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}-1}{e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}-1} - \\frac{e^{m_{e}kr_{0}^2}-1}{e^{m_{\\circ}kr_{0}^2}-1}\\right]}\n$$\n\nFurther consider the force balance equation in the $\\hat{z}$ direction:\n\n$$\nF_{0} + (\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}))V g - m g = 0\n$$\n\nSubstitute specific values, solving yields:\n\n$$\nF_{0} = -(\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}))V g + m g\n$$\n\n$$\nF_{0} = m g - \\left(\\frac{k m_{e}^2N}{\\pi H(e^{m_{e}k R^2}-1)}e^{m_{e}kr_{0}^2} + \\frac{k m_{N}^2N}{\\pi H(e^{m_{N}k R^2}-1)}e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}\\right)V g\n$$\n\nWith conservation of angular momentum:\n\n$$\nL_{0} = m r_{0}^2\\omega\n$$\n\nAssume a relative stable position $\\boldsymbol{r}_{0}$ with a perturbation distance $\\delta r$, and write out the dynamic equation:\n\n$$\nm\\ddot{\\delta r} = \\frac{L_{0}^2}{m(r_{0}+\\delta r)^3} + E(r_{0}+\\delta r)q_{0} - [\\rho_{-}(r_{0}+\\delta r) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}+\\delta r)]V\\omega^2(r_{0}+\\delta r)\n$$\n\nAnalyze and calculate the results in each term:\n\nEffective centrifugal force term:\n\n$$\n\\frac{L_{0}^2}{m(r+\\delta r)^3} = \\frac{L_{0}^2}{m r_{0}^3} + \\frac{\\partial\\frac{L_{0}^2}{m r^3}}{\\partial r}\\delta r = \\frac{L_{0}^2}{m r_{0}^3} - 3m\\omega^2\\delta r\n$$\n\nRadial electric field term:\n\n$$\nE(r_{0}+\\delta r)q_{0} = E(r_{0})q + \\frac{N e q_{0}}{2\\pi H\\varepsilon_{0}r_{0}^2}\\left[\\frac{(2k m_{N}r_{0}^2 - 1)e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2} + 1}{e^{m_{N}k R^2} - 1} - \\frac{(2k m_{e}r_{0}^2 - 1)e^{m_{e}kr_{0}^2} + 1}{e^{m_{e}k R^2} - 1}\\right]\\delta r\n$$\n\nRadial component of buoyancy term:\n\n$$\n\\begin{array}{rl}\n-[\\rho_{-}(r_{0}+\\delta r) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0}+\\delta r)]V\\omega^2(r_{0}+\\delta r) =& -[\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0})]V\\omega^2r_{0} - \\ldots\n\\end{array}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\ldots \\frac{k N V\\omega^2}{\\pi H}\\left[\\frac{(2k m_{N}r_{0}^2 + 1)e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}}{e^{m_{N}k R^2} - 1}m_{N}^2 + \\frac{(2k m_{e}r_{0}^2 + 1)e^{m_{e}kr_{0}^2}}{e^{m_{e}k R^2} - 1}m_{e}^2\\right]\\delta r\n$$\n\nSince\n\n$$\n\\frac{L_{0}^2}{m r_{0}^3} + E(r_{0})q_{0} - [\\rho_{-}(r_{0}) + \\rho_{+}(r_{0})]V\\omega^2r_{0} = 0\n$$\n\nZero-order term sum is zero, thus only considering the first-order terms, we obtain the precession angular frequency:\n\n$$\n\\boxed{\\Omega^2 = 3\\omega^2 - \\frac{N e q_{0}}{2\\pi m H\\varepsilon_{0}r_{0}^2}\\left[\\frac{(2k m_{N}r_{0}^2 - 1)e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2} + 1}{e^{m_{N}k R^2} - 1} - \\frac{(2k m_{\\text{e}}r_{0}^2 - 1)e^{m_{\\text{e}}kr_{0}^2} + 1}{e^{m_{\\text{e}}k R^2} - 1}\\right] + \\frac{k N V\\omega^2}{\\pi m H}\\left[\\frac{(2k m_{N}r_{0}^2 + 1)e^{m_{N}kr_{0}^2}}{e^{m_{N}k R^2} - 1}m_{N}^2 + \\frac{(2k m_{e}r_{0}^2 + 1)e^{m_{e}kr_{0}^2}}{e^{m_{e}k R^2} - 1}m_{e}^2\\right]}\n$$", "final_answers": "$$3\\omega^2 - \\frac{Ne q_0}{2\\pi m H \\varepsilon_0 r_0^2} \\left( \\frac{(2k m_N r_0^2 - 1)e^{m_N k r_0^2} + 1}{e^{m_N k R^2} - 1} - \\frac{(2k m_e r_0^2 - 1)e^{m_e k r_0^2} + 1}{e^{m_e k R^2} - 1} \\right) + \\frac{k N V \\omega^2}{\\pi m H} \\left( \\frac{(2k m_N r_0^2 + 1)e^{m_N k r_0^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2} - 1} m_N^2 + \\frac{(2k m_c r_0^2 + 1)e^{m_c k r_0^2}}{e^{m_c k R^2} - 1} m_c^2 \\right)$$", "improved_solutions": "# Refined Solution\n### Problem Statement Explanation\nThis problem asks for the precession angular frequency, $\\Omega$, of a small Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) that is slightly perturbed from a stable circular orbit within a rotating typhoon.\n\n**Typhoon Model:**\n*   **Geometry and Motion:** The typhoon is modeled as a cylinder of radius $R$ and height $H$ (with $H \\gg R$), rotating with a constant angular velocity $\\vec{\\omega} = \\omega \\hat{z}$ about its central axis.\n*   **Thermodynamics:** The system is an isothermal ideal gas at a constant temperature $T_0$.\n*   **Composition and Ionization:** The gas consists of particles of a single type of monoatomic gas. We assume a state of full ionization, where all $N$ initial atoms have separated into $N$ positive ions (mass $m_N$, charge $+e$) and $N$ free electrons (mass $m_e$, charge $-e$). The neutral particles are ignored in the density calculation.\n*   **Particle Distribution Assumptions:**\n    *   The spatial distribution of ions and electrons is determined by thermal equilibrium in the rotating frame, following a Boltzmann distribution under an effective potential from the centrifugal force.\n    *   Electrostatic interactions between charged particles are ignored when calculating their number densities, but the resulting macroscopic electric field is calculated from these densities.\n    *   All charged particles are confined within the cylindrical volume.\n*   **Constants and Parameters:**\n    *   $k_B$: Boltzmann constant.\n    *   $\\varepsilon_0$: Permittivity of free space.\n    *   $k = \\frac{\\omega^2}{2k_B T_0}$: A given parameter for simplification.\n\n**UAV Model:**\n*   **Physical Properties:** The UAV has mass $m$, a small volume $V$ (such that $V^{1/3} \\ll R$), and carries an electric charge $q_0$.\n*   **Initial State:** It is initially in a stable circular orbit at a radius $r_0$, co-rotating with the typhoon at the same angular velocity $\\omega$.\n*   **Dynamics:** The UAV can only generate vertical thrust, which is irrelevant for the radial motion. At time $t=0$, it receives a small radial velocity perturbation $\\vec{v}_{0}$ ($v_{0} \\ll \\omega r_{0}$), causing it to undergo small radial oscillations.\n\n**Objective:**\nCalculate the angular frequency $\\Omega$ of the UAV's periodic radial oscillations.\n\n### Step 1: Particle Density Distributions in the Rotating Frame\nIn the reference frame rotating with the typhoon at angular velocity $\\omega$, a particle of mass $m_{\\text{particle}}$ experiences a centrifugal force, which can be described by an effective potential energy. The particles are in thermal equilibrium at temperature $T_0$, so their number density $n(r)$ follows the Boltzmann distribution.\n\n\\[\\boxed{ V_{\\text{eff}}(r) = -\\frac{1}{2} m_{\\text{particle}} \\omega^2 r^2 }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ n(r) = n_0 e^{-\\frac{V_{\\text{eff}}(r)}{k_B T_0}} }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\int_{\\text{Volume}} n(r) dV = N_{\\text{total}} }\\]\n\n**Derivation:**\nThe number density $n(r)$ for a particle species at a radial distance $r$ is given by:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn(r) &= n_0 \\exp\\left(-\\frac{-\\frac{1}{2}m_{\\text{particle}}\\omega^2r^2}{k_B T_0}\\right) = n_0 \\exp\\left(\\frac{m_{\\text{particle}}\\omega^2r^2}{2k_B T_0}\\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= n_0 e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kr^2} \\label{eq:density_form}\n\\end{align}\nwhere $n_0$ is a normalization constant and $k = \\frac{\\omega^2}{2k_B T_0}$. The total number of positive ions and free electrons is each $N$. We find $n_0$ for each species by integrating its number density over the cylindrical volume and setting it equal to $N$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nN &= \\int_0^H dz \\int_0^R (2\\pi r dr) \\, n(r) = 2\\pi H \\int_0^R n_0 e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kr^2} r dr \\label{eq:norm_integral}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nTo solve the integral, we use the substitution $u = m_{\\text{particle}}kr^2$, which gives $du = 2m_{\\text{particle}}kr dr$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^R r e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kr^2} dr = \\frac{1}{2m_{\\text{particle}}k} \\int_0^{m_{\\text{particle}}kR^2} e^u du = \\frac{1}{2m_{\\text{particle}}k} \\left(e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kR^2} - 1\\right)\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting this back into Eq. \\eqref{eq:norm_integral} and solving for the normalization constant $n_0$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nN &= 2\\pi H n_0 \\left[ \\frac{1}{2m_{\\text{particle}}k} (e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kR^2} - 1) \\right] \\implies n_0 = \\frac{N m_{\\text{particle}}k}{\\pi H (e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kR^2} - 1)}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nApplying this general result to the positive ions (mass $m_N$) and electrons (mass $m_e$), we obtain their respective number densities:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nn_+(r) &= \\frac{N m_N k}{\\pi H (e^{m_N k R^2} - 1)} e^{m_N kr^2} \\label{eq:n_plus} \\\\\nn_-(r) &= \\frac{N m_e k}{\\pi H (e^{m_e k R^2} - 1)} e^{m_e kr^2} \\label{eq:n_minus}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Charge Density and Electric Field\nThe difference in mass between ions and electrons ($m_N \\gg m_e$) causes a radial separation of charge. The heavier positive ions are pushed further outwards by the centrifugal force than the lighter electrons. This creates a net charge density $\\rho_q(r)$ and a radial electric field $E(r)$.\n\n\\[\\boxed{ \\rho_q(r) = e(n_+(r) - n_-(r)) }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\oint_S \\vec{E} \\cdot d\\vec{A} = \\frac{Q_{\\text{enc}}}{\\varepsilon_0} \\quad (\\text{Gauss's Law}) }\\]\n\n**Derivation:**\nThe net charge density at radius $r$ is the difference between the positive and negative charge densities.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\rho_q(r) = e n_+(r) - e n_-(r) = e(n_+(r) - n_-(r))\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nDue to cylindrical symmetry, the electric field must be purely radial, $\\vec{E}(r) = E(r)\\hat{r}$. We apply Gauss's Law to a cylindrical surface of radius $r$ and height $H$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nE(r) \\cdot (2\\pi r H) &= \\frac{1}{\\varepsilon_0} Q_{\\text{enc}} = \\frac{1}{\\varepsilon_0} \\int_0^H dz \\int_0^r (2\\pi r' dr') \\, \\rho_q(r') \\\\\nE(r) &= \\frac{e}{\\varepsilon_0 r} \\int_0^r (n_+(r') - n_-(r')) r' dr'\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe integral of $n_{\\text{particle}}(r')r'$ was effectively solved in Step 1. The total number of particles of a species inside radius $r$ is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\int_0^H dz \\int_0^r (2\\pi r' dr') n_{\\text{particle}}(r') = 2\\pi H \\int_0^r n_0 e^{m_{\\text{particle}}kr'^2} r' dr' = N \\frac{e^{m_{\\text{particle}} kr^2} - 1}{e^{m_{\\text{particle}} k R^2} - 1}\n\\end{align}\nThus, the integral $\\int_0^r n_{\\text{particle}}(r') r' dr'$ is $\\frac{N}{2\\pi H} \\frac{e^{m_{\\text{particle}} kr^2} - 1}{e^{m_{\\text{particle}} k R^2} - 1}$. Substituting this into the expression for $E(r)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nE(r) = \\frac{Ne}{2\\pi \\varepsilon_0 H r} \\left[ \\frac{e^{m_N kr^2} - 1}{e^{m_N k R^2} - 1} - \\frac{e^{m_e kr^2} - 1}{e^{m_e k R^2} - 1} \\right] \\label{eq:Efield}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Fluid Hydrostatic Equilibrium\nIn the rotating frame, the plasma is in hydrostatic equilibrium. The outward pressure gradient force is balanced by the inward body forces acting on the fluid.\n\n\\[\\boxed{ \\nabla P = \\vec{f}_{\\text{body}} }\\]\n\n**Derivation:**\nThe body forces per unit volume acting on the plasma are the centrifugal force density, $\\vec{f}_{cf} = \\rho_m(r) \\omega^2 r \\hat{r}$, and the electric force density, $\\vec{f}_{E} = \\rho_q(r) \\vec{E}(r)$. The total mass density of the plasma is $\\rho_m(r) = m_N n_+(r) + m_e n_-(r)$. The equilibrium condition in the radial direction is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dP}{dr} = f_{cf} + f_E = \\rho_m(r) \\omega^2 r + \\rho_q(r) E(r) \\label{eq:pressure_gradient}\n\\end{align}\nThis equation gives the pressure gradient required to maintain the solid-body rotation of the plasma.\n\n### Step 4: Forces on the UAV\nThe UAV is subject to physical forces from the surrounding plasma and the electric field. We analyze these forces in the inertial (lab) frame.\n\n\\[\\boxed{ \\vec{F}_{\\text{buoyancy}} = -\\int_V \\nabla P \\, dV' }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\vec{F}_{\\text{electric}} = q_0 \\vec{E} }\\]\n\n**Derivation:**\nThe total physical radial force, $F_{r, \\text{phys}}$, on the UAV is the sum of the electric force and the buoyancy force.\n1.  **Electric Force:** The force on the UAV's charge $q_0$ is $F_{E, UAV}(r) = q_0 E(r)$.\n2.  **Buoyancy Force:** Since the UAV has a small volume $V$ ($V^{1/3} \\ll R$), the pressure gradient $\\nabla P$ is approximately constant over its volume. The buoyancy force is $\\vec{F}_B \\approx -V \\nabla P$. The radial component is:\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    F_B(r) = -V \\frac{dP}{dr}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\n    Using the pressure gradient from Eq. \\eqref{eq:pressure_gradient}:\n    \\[\n    \\begin{align}\n    F_B(r) = -V \\left( \\rho_m(r) \\omega^2 r + \\rho_q(r) E(r) \\right) \\label{eq:buoyancy}\n    \\end{align}\n    \\]\nThe total physical radial force on the UAV is the sum of these two forces:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nF_{r, \\text{phys}}(r) &= F_{E, UAV}(r) + F_B(r) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= q_0 E(r) - V \\left( \\rho_m(r) \\omega^2 r + \\rho_q(r) E(r) \\right) \\nonumber \\\\\n&= (q_0 - V\\rho_q(r))E(r) - V\\rho_m(r)\\omega^2 r \\label{eq:radial_force}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Equilibrium Condition for UAV Orbit\nFor the UAV to maintain a stable circular orbit at radius $r_0$ with angular velocity $\\omega$, the net physical radial force must provide the necessary centripetal force.\n\n\\[\\boxed{ \\vec{F}_{\\text{net}} = m\\vec{a} }\\]\n\n**Derivation:**\nIn the inertial frame, the acceleration for a circular orbit of radius $r_0$ at angular velocity $\\omega$ is the centripetal acceleration, $a_r = -\\omega^2 r_0$. Applying Newton's second law in the radial direction:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nF_{r, \\text{phys}}(r_0) = m a_r = -m \\omega^2 r_0\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nSubstituting the force expression from Eq. \\eqref{eq:radial_force} gives the equilibrium condition that determines the stable radius $r_0$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n(q_0 - V\\rho_q(r_0))E(r_0) - V\\rho_m(r_0)\\omega^2 r_0 = -m \\omega^2 r_0 \\label{eq:equilibrium}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Step 6: Perturbation Analysis and Oscillation Frequency\nWe analyze small radial oscillations around the equilibrium radius $r_0$. The motion is governed by the radial equation of motion in the inertial frame, accounting for the conservation of angular momentum.\n\n\\[\\boxed{ m\\ddot{r} = F_r(r) + \\frac{L_z^2}{mr^3} }\\]\n\\[\\boxed{ \\Omega = \\sqrt{\\frac{k_{\\text{eff}}}{m_{\\text{object}}}} \\quad (\\text{for SHM } m\\ddot{x} = -k_{\\text{eff}}x) }\\]\n\n**Derivation:**\nThe radial equation of motion for the UAV is $m(\\ddot{r} - r\\dot{\\theta}^2) = F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r)$. Since there are no tangential forces on the UAV, its angular momentum $L_z = mr^2\\dot{\\theta}$ is conserved. From the initial condition ($r=r_0, \\dot{\\theta}=\\omega$), we have $L_z = mr_0^2\\omega$. Thus, $\\dot{\\theta} = \\frac{r_0^2\\omega}{r^2}$. The equation becomes:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm\\ddot{r} = F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r) + mr\\left(\\frac{r_0^2\\omega}{r^2}\\right)^2 = F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r) + \\frac{m r_0^4 \\omega^2}{r^3}\n\\end{align}\nLet $G(r) = F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r) + \\frac{m r_0^4 \\omega^2}{r^3}$ be the total effective radial force. For a small perturbation $r(t) = r_0 + \\delta r(t)$, we expand $G(r)$ in a Taylor series around $r_0$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm\\ddot{\\delta r} \\approx G(r_0) + \\left.\\frac{dG}{dr}\\right|_{r=r_0} \\delta r\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nAt the equilibrium radius $r_0$, $G(r_0) = F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r_0) + \\frac{m r_0^4 \\omega^2}{r_0^3} = F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r_0) + m r_0 \\omega^2$. Using the equilibrium condition from Eq. \\eqref{eq:equilibrium}, $F_{r, \\text{phys}}(r_0) = -m r_0 \\omega^2$, we find that $G(r_0) = 0$. The equation for the perturbation simplifies to:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\nm\\ddot{\\delta r} = \\left(\\left.\\frac{dG}{dr}\\right|_{r_0}\\right) \\delta r\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThis is the equation for simple harmonic motion, $m\\ddot{\\delta r} = -k_{\\text{eff}}\\delta r$, with an effective spring constant $k_{\\text{eff}} = -\\left.\\frac{dG}{dr}\\right|_{r_0}$. The angular frequency of this oscillation is $\\Omega = \\sqrt{k_{\\text{eff}}/m}$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Omega^2 = \\frac{k_{\\text{eff}}}{m} = -\\frac{1}{m}\\left.\\frac{dG}{dr}\\right|_{r_0}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nWe now compute the derivative of $G(r)$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dG}{dr} = \\frac{dF_{r, \\text{phys}}}{dr} + m r_0^4 \\omega^2 \\left(-\\frac{3}{r^4}\\right) \\implies \\left.\\frac{dG}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} = \\left.\\frac{dF_{r, \\text{phys}}}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} - 3m\\omega^2\n\\end{align}\nSubstituting this into the expression for $\\Omega^2$:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Omega^2 = -\\frac{1}{m}\\left( \\left.\\frac{dF_{r, \\text{phys}}}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} - 3m\\omega^2 \\right) = 3\\omega^2 - \\frac{1}{m}\\left.\\frac{dF_{r, \\text{phys}}}{dr}\\right|_{r_0}\n\\end{align}\nDifferentiating the physical force from Eq. \\eqref{eq:radial_force}:\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\frac{dF_{r, \\text{phys}}}{dr} &= \\frac{d}{dr}\\left[ (q_0 - V\\rho_q(r))E(r) - V\\rho_m(r)\\omega^2 r \\right] \\\\\n&= (q_0 - V\\rho_q(r))\\frac{dE}{dr} - V E(r) \\frac{d\\rho_q}{dr} - V\\omega^2 \\frac{d}{dr}(r\\rho_m(r))\n\\end{align}\nEvaluating at $r=r_0$ and substituting into the expression for $\\Omega^2$ gives the final result.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\Omega^2 = 3\\omega^2 - \\frac{1}{m} \\left[ (q_0 - V\\rho_q(r_0))\\left.\\frac{dE}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} - V E(r_0)\\left.\\frac{d\\rho_q}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} - V\\omega^2 \\left.\\frac{d(r\\rho_m)}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} \\right] \\label{eq:omega_sq_final}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer\nThe precession angular frequency $\\Omega$ of the UAV's radial oscillations is given by the square root of the following expression. The expression depends on the UAV's properties ($m, V, q_0$), the typhoon's parameters ($\\omega, T_0, N, R, H$), and the equilibrium radius $r_0$. The required functions and their derivatives must be evaluated at $r=r_0$.\n\\[\n\\begin{align}\n\\boxed{\n\\Omega^2 = 3\\omega^2 - \\frac{1}{m} \\left[ (q_0 - V\\rho_q(r_0))\\left.\\frac{dE}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} - V E(r_0)\\left.\\frac{d\\rho_q}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} - V\\omega^2 \\left.\\frac{d(r\\rho_m)}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} \\right]\n}\n\\end{align}\n\\]\nThe terms in this expression are defined as follows, with $k = \\frac{\\omega^2}{2k_B T_0}$:\n*   Charge and mass densities at $r_0$:\n    *   $\\rho_q(r_0) = e(n_+(r_0) - n_-(r_0))$\n    *   $\\rho_m(r_0) = m_N n_+(r_0) + m_e n_-(r_0)$\n*   Electric field $E(r_0)$ is given by Eq. \\eqref{eq:Efield}.\n*   Derivatives evaluated at $r_0$:\n    *   $\\left.\\frac{dE}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} = \\frac{Ne}{2\\pi \\varepsilon_0 H r_0^2} \\left[ \\frac{(2km_N r_0^2 - 1)e^{m_N kr_0^2} + 1}{e^{m_N k R^2} - 1} - \\frac{(2km_e r_0^2 - 1)e^{m_e kr_0^2} + 1}{e^{m_e k R^2} - 1} \\right]$\n    *   $\\left.\\frac{d\\rho_q}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} = 2ker_0(m_N n_+(r_0) - m_e n_-(r_0))$\n    *   $\\left.\\frac{d(r\\rho_m)}{dr}\\right|_{r_0} = \\rho_m(r_0) + 2kr_0^2(m_N^2 n_+(r_0) + m_e^2 n_-(r_0))$"}
